Signs and symptom of primary ovarian insufficiency are similar to those of menopause or estrogen deficiency. They include: Irregular or skipped periods, which might be present for year or develop after a pregnancy or after stopping birth control pill Difficulty getting pregnant Hot flash Night sweat Vaginal dryness Dry eye Irritability or difficulty concentrating Decreased sexual desire When to see a health care provider If you've missed your period for three month or more, see your health care provider to determine the cause. You can miss your period for a number of reason — including pregnancy, stress, or a change in diet or exercise habit — but it's best to get evaluated whenever your menstrual cycle changes. Even if you don't mind not having periods, it's advisable to see your provider to find out what's causing the change. Low estrogen level can lead to bone loss and an increased risk of heart disease.

Posterior cortical atrophy symptom vary among people. Symptoms also can vary over time. They tend to gradually get worse. Common symptom include having trouble with: Reading, spelling or math. Driving. Getting dressed. Telling the difference between object that are moving and those that are still. Judging how far away object are. Using everyday object or tools. Identifying left from right. Other common symptom include: Anxiety. Confusion. Changes in behavior and personality. Memory problem may occur later in the disease. Causes The most common cause of posterior cortical atrophy is a form of Alzheimer's disease that's not typical. It affect the back of the brain. Other le common cause include corticobasal degeneration, Lewy body dementia and Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. Researchers are looking at potential gene variation that may be related to the condition. Risk factor Further study is needed to determine whether the risk factor for Alzheimer's disease may play a role in posterior cortical atrophy. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Posterior cortical atrophy care at Mayo Clinic

An unusual sensation (aura) may precede a temporal lobe seizure, acting a a warning. Not everyone who ha temporal lobe seizure ha auras, and not everyone who ha aura remembers them. The aura is actually the first part of a focal seizure before consciousness is impaired. Examples of aura include: A sudden sense of unprovoked fear or joy A deja vu experience — a feeling that what's happening ha happened before A sudden or strange odor or taste A rising sensation in the abdomen, similar to being on a roller coaster Sometimes temporal lobe seizure impair your ability to respond to others. This type of temporal lobe seizure usually last 30 second to two minutes. Characteristic sign and symptom include: Loss of awareness of surroundings Staring Lip smacking Repeated swallowing or chewing Unusual finger movements, such a picking motion After a temporal lobe seizure, you may have: A period of confusion and difficulty speaking Inability to recall what occurred during the seizure Unawareness of having had a seizure Extreme sleepiness In extreme cases, what start a a temporal lobe seizure evolves into a generalized tonic-clonic (grand mal) seizure — featuring convulsion and loss of consciousness.

You might develop sign and symptom of an intracranial hematoma right after a head injury, or they may take week or longer to appear. You might seem fine after a head injury. This period is called the lucid interval. Over time, pressure on your brain increases, producing some or all of the following sign and symptoms: Headache that get worse Vomiting Drowsiness and progressive loss of consciousness Dizziness Confusion Unequal pupil size Slurred speech Loss of movement (paralysis) on the opposite side of the body from the head injury As more blood fill your brain or the narrow space between your brain and skull, other sign and symptom may appear, such as: Lethargy Seizures Unconsciousness

The symptom of radiation enteritis include diarrhea, nausea, vomiting and stomach cramps. Symptoms occur because of irritation of the intestine from radiation therapy for cancer. Symptoms usually go away several week after treatment ends. But sometimes they last longer. Radiation enteritis that go on for longer can cause anemia and bowel obstruction. Risk factor The risk of radiation enteritis is higher in people undergoing radiation treatment for cancer in the belly and the pelvis. Radiation enteritis occurs because radiation therapy can cause irritation of the intestines. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Radiation enteritis care at Mayo Clinic

A hemangioma may be present at birth, but more often appears during the first several month of life. It start a a flat red mark anywhere on the body, most often on the face, scalp, chest or back. Usually a child ha only one mark. Some child may have more than one, particularly if they're part of a multiple birth. During your child's first year, the red mark grows rapidly into a spongy, rubbery-looking bump that stick out from the skin. The hemangioma then enters a rest phase and, eventually, it begin to slowly disappear. Many hemangioma disappear by age 5, and most are gone by age 10. The skin may be slightly discolored or raised after the hemangioma go away.

Allergy symptoms, which depend on the substance involved, can affect your airways, sinus and nasal passages, skin, and digestive system. Allergic reaction can range from mild to severe. In some severe cases, allergy can trigger a life-threatening reaction known a anaphylaxis. Hay fever, also called allergic rhinitis, can cause: Hay fever, Sneezing Itching of the nose, eye or roof of the mouth Runny, stuffy nose Watery, red or swollen eye (conjunctivitis) A food allergy can cause: A food allergy Tingling in the mouth Swelling of the lips, tongue, face or throat Hives Anaphylaxis An insect sting allergy can cause: An insect sting allergy A large area of swelling (edema) at the sting site Itching or hive all over the body Cough, chest tightness, wheezing or shortness of breath Anaphylaxis A drug allergy can cause: A drug allergy Hives Itchy skin Rash Facial swelling Wheezing Anaphylaxis Atopic dermatitis, an allergic skin condition also called eczema, can cause skin to: Atopic dermatitis, Itch Redden Flake or peel Anaphylaxis Some type of allergies, including allergy to food and insect stings, can trigger a severe reaction known a anaphylaxis. A life-threatening medical emergency, anaphylaxis can cause you to go into shock. Signs and symptom of anaphylaxis include: Loss of consciousness A drop in blood pressure Severe shortness of breath Skin rash Lightheadedness A rapid, weak pulse Nausea and vomiting

Many people with peripheral artery disease have mild or no symptoms. Some people have leg pain when walking (claudication). Claudication symptom include muscle pain or cramping in the leg or arm that begin during exercise and end with rest. The pain is most commonly felt in the calf. The pain range from mild to severe. Severe leg pain may make it hard to walk or do other type of physical activity. Other peripheral artery disease symptom may include: Coldness in the lower leg or foot, especially when compared with the other side Leg numbness or weakness No pulse or a weak pulse in the leg or foot Painful cramping in one or both of the hips, thigh or calf muscle after certain activities, such a walking or climbing stair Shiny skin on the leg Skin color change on the leg Slower growth of the toenail Sores on the toes, foot or leg that won't heal Pain when using the arms, such a aching and cramping when knitting, writing or doing other manual task Erectile dysfunction Hair loss or slower hair growth on the leg If peripheral artery disease get worse, pain may occur during rest or when lying down. The pain may interrupt sleep. Hanging the leg over the edge of the bed or walking may temporarily relieve the pain.

The main sign of low sperm count is the inability to conceive a child. There might be no other obvious sign or symptoms. In some men, an underlying problem such a an inherited chromosomal abnormality, a hormonal imbalance, dilated testicular vein or a condition that block the passage of sperm may cause sign and symptoms. Low sperm count symptom might include: Problems with sexual function — for example, low sex drive or difficulty maintaining an erection (erectile dysfunction) Pain, swelling or a lump in the testicle area Decreased facial or body hair or other sign of a chromosome or hormone abnormality

Multiple system atrophy (MSA) affect many part of your body. Symptoms usually start in adulthood, usually in the 50 or 60s. There are two type of MSA: parkinsonian and cerebellar. The type depends on the symptom you have when you're diagnosed. MSA Parkinsonian type This is the most common type of MSA. The sign and symptom are similar to those of Parkinson's disease, such as: MSA Stiff muscle Difficulty bending your arm and leg Slow movement (bradykinesia) Tremors can occur at rest or when moving your arm or leg Soft voice Problems with posture and balance Cerebellar type The main sign and symptom are problem with muscle coordination (ataxia), but others may include: Impaired movement and coordination, such a unsteady gait and loss of balance Slurred, slow or low-volume speech (dysarthria) Visual disturbances, such a blurred or double vision and difficulty focusing your eye Difficulty swallowing (dysphagia) or chewing Changes in speech, such a slurred speech General sign and symptom In addition, the primary sign of multiple system atrophy is autonomic failure, which may cause problem with body function you can't control. This may include: Postural (orthostatic) hypotension Postural hypotension is a form of low blood pressure that make you feel dizzy or lightheaded, or even faint, when you stand up from sitting or lying down. Not everyone with MSA ha postural hypotension. MSA You can also develop dangerously high blood pressure level while lying down (supine hypertension). Urinary and bowel dysfunction Constipation Loss of bladder or bowel control (incontinence) Changes in sweat production Producing le sweat Heat intolerance due to reduced sweating Impaired body temperature control, often causing cold hand or foot Sleep disorder Agitated sleep due to "acting out" dream Abnormal breathing at night or a harsh breathing sound (stridor) Sexual dysfunction Inability to achieve or maintain an erection (impotence) Loss of libido Cardiovascular problem Color change in hand and foot caused by pooling of blood Psychiatric problem Difficulty controlling emotions, such a laughing or cry inappropriately

A popliteal artery aneurysm may not cause any noticeable symptoms. The first symptom may be pain the lower leg that occurs with walking (claudication). Other sign and symptom of a popliteal artery aneurysm include: Knee pain Lower leg pain Swelling behind the knee Pulsing sensation behind the knee Causes An aneurysm is a ballooning in a weak spot in an artery wall. Many different thing can cause the popliteal artery wall to become weak, including: Clogged artery (atherosclerosis) High blood pressure Wear and tear of the popliteal artery due to repetitive use of the knee joint Weakening of the artery wall Risk factor Popliteal artery aneurysm are rare. They are more common in men than in women. Popiteal artery aneurysm often occur in men with abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA), a swelling of the wall of the body's main artery (aorta). Anyone diagnosed with popliteal artery aneurysm should be screened for AAA. AAA Other risk factor for popliteal artery aneurysm include: Increasing age High blood pressure (hypertension) Smoking Narrowing of a heart valve (stenotic disease) Having three or more aneurysm anywhere in the body Complications Complications of popliteal artery aneurysm include blood clot (thrombosis) and, rarely, rupture of the aneurysm. Thrombosis of a popliteal artery aneurysm can cause a severe lack of blood flow (ischemia) in the lower leg, which may result in loss of the limb. Sudden leg ischemia can cause the following sign and symptoms: A change in skin color in the affected area No pulse behind the knee Skin in the affected area feel cold Numbness in the leg Inability to move the foot The risk of popliteal artery aneurysm rupture is low. Prevention Smoking and high blood pressure (hypertension) increase the risk of blood vessel (vascular) problem that can lead to popliteal artery and other aneurysms. Following a heart-healthy lifestyle — such a not smoking, eating a nutritious diet and getting regular exercise — can help prevent heart disease and blood vessel damage. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Popliteal artery aneurysm care at Mayo Clinic

Symptoms of high blood sugar or low blood sugar usually develop before a diabetic coma. High blood sugar (hyperglycemia) If your blood sugar level is too high, you may have: Increased thirst Frequent urination Blurred vision Tiredness or weakness Headache Nausea and vomiting Shortness of breath Stomach pain Fruity breath odor A very dry mouth Low blood sugar (hypoglycemia) If your blood sugar is too low, you may have: Shakiness Anxiety Tiredness or drowsiness Weakness Sweating Hunger A feeling of tingling on your skin Dizziness or lightheadedness Headache Difficulty speaking Blurry vision Confusion Loss of consciousness Some people, especially those who've had diabetes for a long time, develop a condition known a hypoglycemia unawareness. That mean they don't have warning symptom that signal a drop in blood sugar. If you have any symptom of high or low blood sugar, test your blood sugar right away. Based on the test results, follow your diabetes treatment. If you don't start to feel better quickly, or you start to feel worse, get medical care right away.

Common symptom of BPH include: BPH Frequent or urgent need to pee, also called urination. Peeing more often at night. Trouble starting to pee. Weak urine stream, or a stream that stop and starts. Dribbling at the end of urination. Not being able to fully empty the bladder. Less common symptom include: Urinary tract infection. Not being able to pee. Blood in the urine. The symptom of BPH tend to slowly get worse. But sometimes they stay the same or even improve over time. BPH The size of the prostate doesn't always determine how serious the symptom are. Some people with slightly enlarged prostate can have major symptoms. Others who have very enlarged prostate can have minor problems. And some people with enlarged prostate don't have any symptom at all. Other possible cause of urinary symptom Some other health problem can lead to symptom that are like those caused by enlarged prostate. These include: Urinary tract infection. Inflamed prostate. Narrowing of the urethra, the tube that carry urine out of the body. Scarring in the bladder neck due to past surgery. Bladder or kidney stones. Problems with nerve that control the bladder. Cancer of the prostate or bladder. Some medicine also may lead to symptom that seem like those caused by BPH. These include: BPH Powerful pain-relieving medicine called opioids. Cold and allergy medicines. Older medicine for depression called tricyclic antidepressants.

Dupuytren contracture get worse slowly, over years. The condition begin with a firm lump in the palm of the hand. This lump might be a little tender, but usually isn't painful. Over time, the lump can extend into a hard cord under the skin and up into the finger. This cord tightens and pull the finger toward the palm, sometimes severely. Dupuytren contracture most commonly affect the two finger farthest from the thumb. The condition often occurs in both hands.

The severity of fetal alcohol syndrome symptom varies, with some child experiencing them to a far greater degree than others. Signs and symptom of fetal alcohol syndrome may include any mix of physical defects, intellectual or cognitive disabilities, and problem functioning and coping with daily life. Physical defect Physical defect may include: Distinctive facial features, including small eyes, an exceptionally thin upper lip, a short, upturned nose, and a smooth skin surface between the nose and upper lip Deformities of joints, limb and finger Slow physical growth before and after birth Vision difficulty or hearing problem Small head circumference and brain size Heart defect and problem with kidney and bone Brain and central nervous system problemsProblems with the brain and central nervous system may include: Poor coordination or balance Intellectual disability, learning disorder and delayed development Poor memory Trouble with attention and with processing information Difficulty with reasoning and problem-solving Difficulty identifying consequence of choice Poor judgment skill Jitteriness or hyperactivity Rapidly changing mood Social and behavioral issuesProblems in functioning, coping and interacting with others may include: Difficulty in school Trouble getting along with others Poor social skill Trouble adapting to change or switching from one task to another Problems with behavior and impulse control Poor concept of time Problems staying on task Difficulty planning or working toward a goal When to see a doctorIf you're pregnant and can't stop drinking, ask your obstetrician, primary care doctor or mental health professional for help. Because early diagnosis may help reduce the risk of long-term problem for child with fetal alcohol syndrome, let your child's doctor know if you drank alcohol while you were pregnant. Don't wait for problem to arise before seeking help. If you have adopted a child or are providing foster care, you may not know if the biological mother drank alcohol while pregnant — and it may not initially occur to you that your child may have fetal alcohol syndrome. However, if your child ha problem with learning and behavior, talk with his or her doctor so that the underlying cause might be identified. These include: Pressure, fullness or a squeezing pain in the center of your chest that last for more than a few minute Pain spreading to your shoulder, one or both of your arms, your back, or even your teeth and jaw Increasing episode of chest pain Shortness of breath Sweating Lightheadedness or sudden dizziness Nausea and vomiting Seek medical attention quickly when having these sign or symptom to decrease your risk of developing cardiogenic shock.

Damage to the protective myelin covering the nerve result in progressive worsening of brain and nervous system functions, including: Loss of the ability to detect sensations, such a touch, pain, heat and sound Loss of intellectual, thinking and memory skill Loss of motor skills, such a walking, moving, speaking and swallowing Stiff, rigid muscles, poor muscle function and paralysis Loss of bladder and bowel function Gallbladder problem Blindness Hearing loss Seizures Emotional and behavioral problems, including unstable emotion and substance misuse Each form of metachromatic leukodystrophy occurs at a different age and can have different initial sign and symptom and rate of progression: Late infantile form. This is the most common form of metachromatic leukodystrophy, starting around 2 year of age or younger. Progressive loss of speech and muscle function occurs rapidly. Children with this form often do not survive beyond childhood. Juvenile form. This is the second most common form and start in child between 3 and 16 year of age. Early sign are behavior and cognitive problem and increasing difficulty in school. Loss of the ability to walk may occur. Although the juvenile form doesn't progress a fast a the late infantile form, survival is generally le than 20 year after symptom begin. Adult form. This form is le common and typically start after age 16. Signs progress slowly and may begin with behavior and psychiatric problems, drug and alcohol misuse, and issue with school and work. Psychotic symptom such a delusion and hallucination may occur. The course of this form varies, with period of stable symptom and period of rapid decline in functioning. Adults may survive for several decade after initial symptoms.

Mittelschmerz pain usually last a few minute to a few hours, but it may continue for a long a a day or two. Pain from mittelschmerz may be: On one side of your lower abdomen Dull and achy, similar to menstrual cramp Sharp and sudden Accompanied by slight vaginal bleeding or discharge Rarely, severe Mittelschmerz pain occurs on the side of the ovary that's releasing an egg (ovulating). Most healthy people who are infected with CMV may experience no symptoms. Some experience minor symptoms. People who are more likely to experience sign and symptom of CMV include: CMV CMV Newborns who became infected with CMV before they were born (congenital CMV). Infants who become infected during birth or shortly afterward (perinatal CMV). This group includes baby infected through breast milk. People who have weakened immune systems, such a those who have had an organ, bone marrow or stem cell transplant, or those who are infected with HIV. Babies Most baby who have congenital CMV appear healthy at birth. CMV A few baby who have congenital CMV who appear healthy at birth develop sign over time — sometimes not for month or year after birth. The most common of these late-occurring sign are hearing loss and developmental delay. A small number of baby may also develop vision problems. CMV The following sign and symptom are more common in baby who have congenital CMV and who are sick at birth: CMV Premature birth Low birth weight Yellow skin and eye (jaundice) Enlarged and poorly functioning liver Purple skin splotch or a rash or both Abnormally small head (microencephaly) Enlarged spleen Pneumonia Seizures People who have weakened immunity If your immune system is weakened, you might experience serious problem that affect your: Eyes Lungs Liver Esophagus Stomach Intestines Brain Healthy adult Most people who are infected with CMV who are otherwise healthy experience few if any symptoms. When first infected, some adult may have symptom similar to infectious mononucleosis, including: CMV Fatigue Fever Sore throat Muscle ache

There are different type of Gaucher disease, and sign and symptom of disease vary widely, even within the same type. Type 1 is by far the most common. Siblings, even identical twins, with the disease can have different level of severity. Some people who have Gaucher disease have only mild or no symptoms. Most people who have Gaucher disease have varying degree of the following problems: Abdominal complaints. Because the liver and especially the spleen can enlarge dramatically, the abdomen can become painfully distended. Skeletal abnormalities. Gaucher disease can weaken bone, increasing the risk of painful fractures. It can also interfere with the blood supply to your bones, which can cause portion of the bone to die. Blood disorders. A decrease in healthy red blood cell (anemia) can result in severe fatigue. Gaucher disease also affect the cell responsible for clotting, which can cause easy bruising and nosebleeds. More rarely, Gaucher disease affect the brain, which can cause abnormal eye movements, muscle rigidity, swallowing difficulty and seizures. One rare subtype of Gaucher disease begin in infancy and typically result in death by 2 year of age.

In the U.S., because of newborn screening, cystic fibrosis can be diagnosed within the first month of life, before symptom develop. But people born before newborn screening became available may not be diagnosed until the sign and symptom of CF show up. CF Cystic fibrosis sign and symptom vary, depending on the severity of the disease. Even in the same person, symptom may worsen or improve a time passes. Some people may not experience symptom until their teenage year or adulthood. People who are not diagnosed until adulthood usually have milder disease and are more likely to have atypical symptoms, such a recurring bout of an inflamed pancreas (pancreatitis), infertility and recurring pneumonia. People with cystic fibrosis have a higher than normal level of salt in their sweat. Parents often can taste the salt when they kiss their children. Most of the other sign and symptom of CF affect the respiratory system and digestive system. CF Respiratory sign and symptom The thick and sticky mucus associated with cystic fibrosis clog the tube that carry air in and out of your lungs. This can cause sign and symptom such as: A persistent cough that produce thick mucus (sputum) Wheezing Exercise intolerance Repeated lung infection Inflamed nasal passage or a stuffy nose Recurrent sinusitis Digestive sign and symptom The thick mucus can also block tube that carry digestive enzyme from your pancreas to your small intestine. Without these digestive enzymes, your intestine aren't able to completely absorb the nutrient in the food you eat. The result is often: Foul-smelling, greasy stool Poor weight gain and growth Intestinal blockage, particularly in newborn (meconium ileus) Chronic or severe constipation, which may include frequent straining while trying to pas stool, eventually causing part of the rectum to protrude outside the anus (rectal prolapse)

Some people with ADHD have fewer symptom a they age, but some adult continue to have major symptom that interfere with daily functioning. In adults, the main feature of ADHD may include difficulty paying attention, impulsiveness and restlessness. Symptoms can range from mild to severe. ADHD ADHD Many adult with ADHD aren't aware they have it — they just know that everyday task can be a challenge. Adults with ADHD may find it difficult to focus and prioritize, leading to missed deadline and forgotten meeting or social plans. The inability to control impulse can range from impatience waiting in line or driving in traffic to mood swing and outburst of anger. ADHD ADHD Adult ADHD symptom may include: ADHD Impulsiveness Disorganization and problem prioritizing Poor time management skill Problems focusing on a task Trouble multitasking Excessive activity or restlessness Poor planning Low frustration tolerance Frequent mood swing Problems following through and completing task Hot temper Trouble coping with stress What's typical behavior and what's ADHD? Almost everyone ha some symptom similar to ADHD at some point in their lives. If your difficulty are recent or occurred only occasionally in the past, you probably don't have ADHD. ADHD is diagnosed only when symptom are severe enough to cause ongoing problem in more than one area of your life. These persistent and disruptive symptom can be traced back to early childhood. ADHD ADHD ADHD Diagnosis of ADHD in adult can be difficult because certain ADHD symptom are similar to those caused by other conditions, such a anxiety or mood disorders. And many adult with ADHD also have at least one other mental health condition, such a depression or anxiety.

During a hot flash, you might have: A sudden feeling of warmth spreading through your chest, neck and face A flushed appearance with red, blotchy skin Rapid heartbeat Perspiration, mostly on your upper body A chilled feeling a the hot flash let up Feelings of anxiety The frequency and intensity of hot flash vary among women. A single episode may last a minute or two — or a long a 5 minutes. Hot flash may be mild or so intense that they disrupt daily activities. They can happen at any time of day or night. Nighttime hot flash (night sweats) may wake you from sleep and can cause long-term sleep disruptions. How often hot flash occur varies among women, but most woman who report having hot flash experience them daily. On average, hot flash symptom persist for more than seven years. Some woman have them for more than 10 years.

The sign and symptom of interstitial cystitis vary from person to person. If you have interstitial cystitis, your symptom may also vary over time, periodically flaring in response to common triggers, such a menstruation, sitting for a long time, stress, exercise and sexual activity. Interstitial cystitis sign and symptom include: Pain in your pelvis or between the vagina and anus in woman Pain between the scrotum and anus (perineum) in men Chronic pelvic pain A persistent, urgent need to urinate Frequent urination, often of small amounts, throughout the day and night (up to 60 time a day) Pain or discomfort while the bladder fill and relief after urinating Pain during sex Symptoms severity is different for everyone, and some people may experience symptom-free periods. Although sign and symptom of interstitial cystitis may resemble those of a chronic urinary tract infection, there's usually no infection. However, symptom may worsen if a person with interstitial cystitis get a urinary tract infection.

Healthy gum are firm and fit snugly around teeth. The color of healthy gum can vary. They may range from light pink in some people to dark pink and brown in others. Symptoms of periodontitis can include: Swollen or puffy gums. Bright red, dark red or dark purple gums. Gums that feel tender when touched. Gums that bleed easily. A toothbrush that look pink after brushing your teeth. Spitting out blood when brushing or flossing your teeth. Bad breath that won't go away. Pus between your teeth and gums. Loose teeth or loss of teeth. Painful chewing. New space that develop between your teeth that look like black triangles. Gums that pull away from your teeth, making your teeth look longer than usual, called receding gums. A change in the way your teeth fit together when you bite. When to see a dentist Follow your dentist's recommended schedule for regular checkups. If you notice any symptom of periodontitis, make an appointment with your dentist a soon a possible. The sooner you get care, the better your chance of reversing damage from periodontitis.

Frozen shoulder typically develops slowly in three stages. Freezing stage. Any movement of the shoulder cause pain, and the shoulder's ability to move becomes limited. This stage last from 2 to 9 months. Frozen stage. Pain might lessen during this stage. However, the shoulder becomes stiffer. Using it becomes more difficult. This stage last from 4 to 12 months. Thawing stage. The shoulder's ability to move begin to improve. This stage last from 5 to 24 months. For some people, the pain worsens at night, sometimes disrupting sleep.

As stone move into your ureter — the thin tube that allow urine to pas from your kidney to your bladder — sign and symptom can result. Signs and symptom of kidney stone can include severe pain, nausea, vomiting, fever, chill and blood in your urine. A kidney stone usually will not cause symptom until it move around within the kidney or pass into one of the ureters. The ureter are the tube that connect the kidney and bladder. If a kidney stone becomes lodged in the ureters, it may block the flow of urine and cause the kidney to swell and the ureter to spasm, which can be very painful. At that point, you may experience these symptoms: Severe, sharp pain in the side and back, below the rib Pain that radiates to the lower abdomen and groin Pain that come in wave and fluctuates in intensity Pain or burning sensation while urinating Other sign and symptom may include: Pink, red or brown urine Cloudy or foul-smelling urine A persistent need to urinate, urinating more often than usual or urinating in small amount Nausea and vomiting Fever and chill if an infection is present Pain caused by a kidney stone may change — for instance, shifting to a different location or increasing in intensity — a the stone move through your urinary tract.

Behcet's disease symptom vary from person to person, can come and go or become le severe over time. Signs and symptom depend on which part of your body are affected. Areas commonly affected by Behcet's disease include: Mouth. Painful mouth sore that look similar to canker sore are the most common sign of Behcet's disease. They begin a raised, round lesion in the mouth that quickly turn into painful ulcers. The sore usually heal in one to three weeks, though they do recur. Skin. Some people develop acnelike sore on their bodies. Others develop red, raised and tender nodule on their skin, especially on the lower legs. Genitals. Red, open sore can occur on the scrotum or the vulva. The sore are usually painful and can leave scars. Eyes. Inflammation in the eye (uveitis) cause redness, pain and blurred vision, typically in both eyes. In people with Behcet's disease, the condition can come and go. Joints. Joint swelling and pain often affect the knee in people with Behcet's disease. The ankles, elbow or wrist also might be involved. Signs and symptom can last one to three week and go away on their own. Blood vessels. Inflammation in vein and artery can cause redness, pain, and swelling in the arm or leg when a blood clot results. Inflammation in the large artery can lead to complications, such a aneurysm and narrowing or blockage of the vessel. Digestive system. A variety of sign and symptom can affect the digestive system, including abdominal pain, diarrhea and bleeding. Brain. Inflammation in the brain and nervous system can cause headache, fever, disorientation, poor balance or stroke.

People with chronic granulomatous disease experience serious bacterial or fungal infection every few years. An infection in the lungs, including pneumonia, is common. People with CGD may develop a serious type of fungal pneumonia after being exposed to dead leaves, mulch or hay. CGD It's also common for people with CGD to experience infection of the skin, liver, stomach and intestines, brain, and eyes. Signs and symptom associated with infection include: CGD Fever Chest pain when inhaling or exhaling Swollen and sore lymph gland A persistent runny nose Skin irritation that may include a rash, swelling or redness Swelling and redness in your mouth Gastrointestinal problem that may include vomiting, diarrhea, stomach pain, bloody stool or a painful pocket of pu near the anus

An indication of simple absence seizure is a vacant stare, which may be mistaken for a lapse in attention that last about 10 seconds, though it may last a long a 20 seconds, without any confusion, headache or drowsiness afterward. Signs and symptom of absence seizure include: Sudden stop in motion without falling Lip smacking Eyelid flutter Chewing motion Finger rubbing Small movement of both hand Afterward, there's no memory of the incident. Some people have many episode daily, which interfere with school or daily activities. A child may have absence seizure for some time before an adult notice the seizures, because they're so brief. A decline in a child's learning ability may be the first sign of this disorder. Teachers may comment about a child's inability to pay attention or that a child is often daydreaming. When to see a doctor Contact your doctor: The first time you notice a seizure If this is a new type of seizure If the seizure continue to occur despite taking anti-seizure medication Contact 911 or emergency service in your area: If you observe prolonged automatic behavior lasting minute to hour — activity such a eating or moving without awareness — or prolonged confusion, possible symptom of a condition called absence status epilepticus After any seizure lasting more than five minute

Hypogonadism can begin during fetal development, before puberty or during adulthood. Signs and symptom depend on when the condition develops. Fetal development If the body doesn't produce enough testosterone during fetal development, the result may be impaired growth of the external sex organs. Depending on when hypogonadism develops and how much testosterone is present, a child who is genetically male may be born with: Female genitals Genitals that are neither clearly male nor clearly female (ambiguous genitals) Underdeveloped male genitals Puberty Male hypogonadism can delay puberty or cause incomplete or lack of normal development. It can hamper: Development of muscle mass Voice deepening Growth of body and facial hair Growth of the penis and testicle And it can cause: Excessive growth of the arm and leg in relation to the trunk of the body Development of breast tissue (gynecomastia) Adulthood In adult males, hypogonadism can alter certain masculine physical characteristic and impair normal reproductive function. Early sign and symptom might include: Decreased sex drive Decreased energy Depression Over time, men with hypogonadism can develop: Erectile dysfunction Infertility Decrease in hair growth on the face and body Decrease in muscle mass Development of breast tissue (gynecomastia) Loss of bone mass (osteoporosis) Severe hypogonadism can also cause mental and emotional changes. As testosterone decreases, some men have symptom similar to those of menopause in women. These can include: Difficulty concentrating Hot flash When to seek help See your health care provider if you have symptom of male hypogonadism. Finding the cause of hypogonadism is an important first step to getting appropriate treatment.

Small arteriovenous fistula in the legs, arms, lungs, kidney or brain often won't have any sign or symptoms. Small arteriovenous fistula usually don't need treatment other than monitoring by a health care provider. Large arteriovenous fistula may cause sign and symptoms. Arteriovenous fistula sign and symptom may include: Purplish, bulging vein seen through the skin, similar to varicose vein Swelling in the arm or leg Decreased blood pressure Fatigue Heart failure A significant arteriovenous fistula in the lung (pulmonary arteriovenous fistula) is a serious condition and can cause: Pale gray or blue lip or fingernail due to lack of blood flow (cyanosis) Fingertips to spread out and become rounder than normal (clubbing) Coughing up blood An arteriovenous fistula in the digestive tract can cause gastrointestinal (GI) bleeding.

Initially, lead poisoning can be hard to detect — even people who seem healthy can have high blood level of lead. Signs and symptom usually don't appear until dangerous amount have accumulated. Lead poisoning symptom in child Signs and symptom of lead poisoning in child include: Developmental delay Learning difficulty Irritability Loss of appetite Weight loss Sluggishness and fatigue Abdominal pain Vomiting Constipation Hearing loss Seizures Eating things, such a paint chips, that aren't food (pica) Lead poisoning symptom in newborn Babies exposed to lead before birth might: Be born prematurely Have lower birth weight Have slowed growth Lead poisoning symptom in adult Although child are primarily at risk, lead poisoning is also dangerous for adults. Signs and symptom in adult might include: High blood pressure Joint and muscle pain Difficulties with memory or concentration Headache Abdominal pain Mood disorder Reduced sperm count and abnormal sperm Miscarriage, stillbirth or premature birth in pregnant woman

Migraines, which affect child and teenager a well a adults, can progress through four stages: prodrome, aura, attack and post-drome. Not everyone who ha migraine go through all stages. Prodrome One or two day before a migraine, you might notice subtle change that warn of an upcoming migraine, including: Constipation Mood changes, from depression to euphoria Food craving Neck stiffness Increased urination Fluid retention Frequent yawning Aura For some people, an aura might occur before or during migraines. Auras are reversible symptom of the nervous system. They're usually visual but can also include other disturbances. Each symptom usually begin gradually, build up over several minute and can last up to 60 minutes. Examples of migraine aura include: Visual phenomena, such a seeing various shapes, bright spot or flash of light Vision loss Pins and needle sensation in an arm or leg Weakness or numbness in the face or one side of the body Difficulty speaking Attack A migraine usually last from 4 to 72 hour if untreated. How often migraine occur varies from person to person. Migraines might occur rarely or strike several time a month. During a migraine, you might have: Pain usually on one side of your head, but often on both side Pain that throb or pulse Sensitivity to light, sound, and sometimes smell and touch Nausea and vomiting Post-drome After a migraine attack, you might feel drained, confused and washed out for up to a day. Some people report feeling elated. Sudden head movement might bring on the pain again briefly.

Your baby may have very mild symptom of premature birth or more-serious health problems. Some sign of being born too early include: Small size, with a head that's large compared with the body. Features that are sharper and le rounded than a full-term baby's feature due to a lack of cell that store fat. Fine hair that cover much of the body. Low body temperature, mainly right after birth in the delivery room. Trouble breathing. Feeding problems. (21 cm) Special care If you give birth to a preterm baby, your baby will likely need to stay in a special nursery unit at the hospital. Some infant need to spend time in a unit that care for them and closely track their health day and night. This is called a neonatal intensive care unit (NICU). A step down from the NICU is an intermediate care nursery, which provides le intensive care. Special nursery unit are staffed with health care provider and a team that's trained to help preterm babies. NICU Your baby may need extra help feeding and adapting right after delivery. Your health care team can help you understand what's needed and what your baby's care plan will be. Feel free to ask them questions.

Signs and symptom of scrotal mass vary depending on the abnormality. Signs and symptom might include: An unusual lump Sudden pain A dull aching pain or feeling of heaviness in the scrotum Pain that radiates throughout the groin, abdomen or lower back Tender, swollen or hardened testicle Tender, swollen or hardened epididymis (ep-ih-DID-uh-miss), the soft, comma-shaped tube above and behind the testicle that store and transport sperm Swelling in the scrotum Redness of the skin of the scrotum Nausea or vomiting If the cause of a scrotal mass is an infection, sign and symptom also might include: Fever Urinary frequency Pus or blood in the urine When to see a doctor Seek emergency medical care if you develop sudden pain in your scrotum. Some condition require prompt treatment to avoid permanent damage to a testicle. See your doctor if you detect a lump in your scrotum, even if it's not painful or tender, or if you experience other symptom of a scrotal mass. Some scrotal mass are more common in children. See your doctor if your child experience symptom of a scrotal mass, if you have any concern about the development of the genitals or if a testicle is “missing” — an undescended or retractile testicle, which might increase the risk of some scrotal mass later in life.

The sign and symptom of Marfan syndrome can vary greatly, even among member of the same family, because the disorder can affect so many different area of the body. Some people experience only mild effects, but others develop life-threatening complications. Marfan syndrome feature may include: Tall and slender build Disproportionately long arms, leg and finger A breastbone that protrudes outward or dip inward A high, arched palate and crowded teeth Heart murmur Extreme nearsightedness An abnormally curved spine Flat foot

Signs and symptom will vary, depending on the severity of the injury, and may include: Pain or tenderness Redness or bruising Limited motion Muscle spasm Swelling Muscle weakness When to see the doctor Mild strain can be treated at home. See a doctor if your symptom worsen despite treatment — especially if your pain becomes intolerable, or you experience numbness or tingling. Causes Acute strain can be caused by one event, such a using poor body mechanic to lift something heavy. Chronic muscle strain can result from repetitive injury when you stress a muscle by doing the same motion over and over. Risk factor Participating in contact sport — such a soccer, football, hockey, boxing and wrestling — can increase your risk of muscle strains. Certain part of the body are more susceptible to strain during participation in certain sports. Examples include: Legs and ankles. Sports that feature quick start and jumping, such a hurdling and basketball, can be particularly tough on the Achilles tendon in your ankle. Hands. Gripping sports, such a gymnastics or golf, can increase your risk of muscle strain in your hands. Elbows. Elbow strain are often caused by throwing sport and racquet sports. Prevention Regular stretching and strengthening exercise for your sport, fitness or work activity, a part of an overall physical conditioning program, can help to minimize your risk of muscle strains. Try to be in shape to play your sport; don't play your sport to get in shape. If you have a physically demanding occupation, regular conditioning can help prevent injuries. The cause of this condition is unknown, but it primarily affect older women. Hair loss can appear in many different ways, depending on what's causing it. It can come on suddenly or gradually and affect just your scalp or your whole body. Signs and symptom of hair loss may include: Gradual thinning on top of head. This is the most common type of hair loss, affecting people a they age. In men, hair often begin to recede at the hairline on the forehead. Women typically have a broadening of the part in their hair. An increasingly common hair loss pattern in older woman is a receding hairline (frontal fibrosing alopecia). Circular or patchy bald spots. Some people lose hair in circular or patchy bald spot on the scalp, beard or eyebrows. Your skin may become itchy or painful before the hair fall out. Sudden loosening of hair. A physical or emotional shock can cause hair to loosen. Handfuls of hair may come out when combing or washing your hair or even after gentle tugging. This type of hair loss usually cause overall hair thinning but is temporary. Full-body hair loss. Some condition and medical treatments, such a chemotherapy for cancer, can result in the loss of hair all over your body. The hair usually grows back. Patches of scaling that spread over the scalp. This is a sign of ringworm. It may be accompanied by broken hair, redness, swelling and, at times, oozing.

Many people with von Willebrand disease don't know it because the sign are mild or absent. The most common sign of the condition is abnormal bleeding. There are three main type of the disease. The amount of bleeding varies from one person to another, depending on the type and severity of the disease. If you have von Willebrand disease, you might have: Excessive bleeding from an injury or after surgery or dental work Frequent nosebleed that don't stop within 10 minute Heavy or long menstrual bleeding Heavy bleeding during labor and delivery Blood in your urine or stool Easy bruising or lumpy bruise Menstrual sign and symptom might include: Blood clot greater than 1 inch (2.5 centimeters) in diameter in your menstrual flow The need to change your menstrual pad or tampon more than once an hour The need to use double sanitary protection for menstrual flow Symptoms of anemia, including tiredness, fatigue or shortness of breath

The chest pain or discomfort may feel like: Burning Fullness Pressure Squeezing Pain may also be felt in the arms, neck, jaw, shoulder or back. Other symptom of angina include: Dizziness Fatigue Nausea Shortness of breath Sweating The severity, duration and type of angina can vary. New or different symptom may signal a more dangerous form of angina (unstable angina) or a heart attack. Any new or worsening angina symptom need to be evaluated immediately by a health care provider who can determine whether you have stable or unstable angina. Angina in woman Symptoms of angina in woman can be different from the classic angina symptoms. These difference may lead to delay in seeking treatment. For example, chest pain is a common symptom in woman with angina, but it may not be the only symptom or the most prevalent symptom for women. Women may also have symptom such as: Discomfort in the neck, jaw, teeth or back Nausea Shortness of breath Stabbing pain instead of chest pressure Stomach (abdominal) pain

Signs and symptom will vary, depending on the severity of the greenstick fracture. Mild fracture might be mistaken for sprain or bruises. More-severe greenstick fracture may cause an obvious deformity, accompanied by significant pain and swelling. When to see a doctor Contact your doctor if your child ha persistent pain in an injured limb. Seek immediate medical attention if a child is unable to bear weight or if there is obvious pain, deformity and swelling. Causes Childhood fracture most commonly occur with a fall. Arm fracture are more common than leg fractures, since the common reaction is to throw out your arm to catch yourself when you fall. Risk factor The risk of greenstick fracture is higher in young child because their bone are softer and more flexible than adult bones. In a greenstick fracture, the bone bend and crack instead of breaking into separate pieces. Most greenstick fracture occur in child under age 10. Signs and symptom of trachoma usually affect both eye and may include: Mild itching and irritation of the eye and eyelid Eye discharge containing mucus or pu Eyelid swelling Light sensitivity (photophobia) Eye pain Eye redness Vision loss Young child are particularly susceptible to infection. But the disease progress slowly, and the more painful symptom may not emerge until adulthood. The World Health Organization (WHO) ha identified five stage in the development of trachoma: Inflammation — follicular. The early infection ha five or more follicle — small bump that contain lymphocytes, a type of white blood cell — visible with magnification on the inner surface of your upper eyelid (conjunctiva). Inflammation — intense. In this stage, your eye is now highly infectious and becomes irritated, with a thickening or swelling of the upper eyelid. Eyelid scarring. Repeated infection lead to scarring of the inner eyelid. The scar often appear a white line when examined with magnification. Your eyelid may become distorted and may turn in (entropion). In-turned eyelash (trichiasis). The scarred inner lining of your eyelid continues to deform, causing your lash to turn in so that they rub on and scratch the transparent outer surface of your eye (cornea). Corneal clouding (opacity). The cornea becomes affected by an inflammation that is most commonly seen under your upper lid. Continuous inflammation compounded by scratching from the in-turned lash lead to clouding of the cornea. All the sign of trachoma are more severe in your upper lid than in your lower lid. Without intervention, a disease process that begin in childhood can continue to advance into adulthood.

Signs and symptom of paraneoplastic syndrome of the nervous system can develop relatively quickly, often over day to weeks. Signs and symptom of paraneoplastic syndrome of the nervous system often begin even before a cancer is diagnosed. Signs and symptom vary depending on the body part being injured, and may include: Difficulty walking Difficulty maintaining balance Loss of muscle coordination Loss of muscle tone or weakness Loss of fine motor skills, such a picking up object Difficulty swallowing Slurred speech or stuttering Memory loss and other thinking (cognitive) impairment Vision problem Sleep disturbance Seizures Hallucinations Unusual involuntary movement Types of paraneoplastic syndrome Examples of paraneoplastic syndrome of the nervous system include: Cerebellar degeneration (cerebellar ataxia). This is the loss of nerve cell in the area of the brain that control muscle function and balance (cerebellum). Signs and symptom may include unsteady or impaired walking, lack of muscle coordination in your limbs, inability to maintain your trunk posture, dizziness, nausea, involuntary eye movement, double vision, difficulty speaking, or difficulty swallowing. Limbic encephalitis. This is inflammation affecting a region of the brain known a the limbic system, which control emotions, behavior and certain memory functions. People with this disorder may experience personality change or mood disturbances, memory loss, seizures, hallucinations, or drowsiness. Encephalomyelitis. This syndrome refers to inflammation of the brain and spinal cord. There may be a wide variety of symptom and sign depending on the area affected. Opsoclonus-myoclonus. This syndrome is due to dysfunction of the cerebellum or it connections. It can cause rapid, irregular eye movement (opsoclonus) and involuntary, chaotic muscle jerk (myoclonus) in your limb and trunk. Stiff person syndrome. Previously called stiff man syndrome, this syndrome is characterized by progressive, severe muscle stiffness or rigidity, mainly affecting your spine and legs. It may also cause painful muscle spasms. Myelopathy. This term refers to a syndrome of injury limited to the spinal cord. Depending on the level of spinal cord injury, you may have change in bowel and bladder function, and severe weakness and numbness up to a certain level in your body. If the level of injury includes your neck, you can have severe disability affecting all four limbs. Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome. This is a syndrome caused by disrupted communication between nerve and muscles. Signs and symptom include pelvic and lower extremity muscle weakness, fatigue, difficulty swallowing, difficulty speaking, irregular eye movement, and double vision. Autonomic nervous system problem can include dry mouth and erectile dysfunction in males. When it occurs a a paraneoplastic syndrome, Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome is typically associated with lung cancer. Myasthenia gravis. Myasthenia gravis is also related to disrupted communication between nerve and muscle and also characterized by weakness and rapid fatigue of any of the muscle that are under voluntary control, including muscle in your face, eyes, arm and legs. The muscle involved in chewing, swallowing, talking and breathing may be affected a well. When myasthenia gravis occurs a a paraneoplastic syndrome, it is typically associated with cancer of the thymus gland (thymoma). Neuromyotonia. Neuromyotonia — also known a Isaacs' syndrome — is characterized by abnormal impulse in nerve cell outside the brain and spinal cord (peripheral nerve hyperexcitability) that control muscle movement. These impulse can cause twitching, muscle rippling that look like a "bag of worms," progressive stiffness, muscle cramps, slowed movement and other muscle impairments. Peripheral neuropathy. This condition refers to pattern of damage to nerve that transmit message from the brain or spinal column to the rest of your body. When damage involves only the sensory nerve of the peripheral nervous system, you can have pain and disturbance in sensation anywhere in your body. Dysautonomia. Dysautonomia refers to a wide range of sign and symptom resulting from injury to the nerve that regulate involuntary body function (autonomic nervous system), such a heart rate, blood pressure, sweating, and bowel and bladder functions. When this part of the nervous system is affected, common symptom are low blood pressure, irregular heartbeat and trouble breathing.

Early in chronic kidney disease, you might have no sign or symptoms. As chronic kidney disease progress to end-stage renal disease, sign and symptom might include: Nausea Vomiting Loss of appetite Fatigue and weakness Changes in how much you urinate Chest pain, if fluid build up around the lining of the heart Shortness of breath, if fluid build up in the lung Swelling of foot and ankle High blood pressure (hypertension) that's difficult to control Headaches Difficulty sleeping Decreased mental sharpness Muscle twitch and cramp Persistent itching Metallic taste Signs and symptom of kidney disease are often nonspecific, meaning they can also be caused by other illnesses. Because your kidney can make up for lost function, sign and symptom might not appear until irreversible damage ha occurred. When to seek care Make an appointment with your health care provider if you have sign or symptom of kidney disease. If you have a medical condition that increase your risk of kidney disease, your care provider is likely to monitor your kidney function with urine and blood test and your blood pressure during regular office visits. Ask your provider whether these test are necessary for you.

Tinnitus is most often described a a ringing in the ears, even though no external sound is present. However, tinnitus can also cause other type of phantom noise in your ears, including: Buzzing Roaring Clicking Hissing Humming Most people who have tinnitus have subjective tinnitus, or tinnitus that only you can hear. The noise of tinnitus may vary in pitch from a low roar to a high squeal, and you may hear it in one or both ears. In some cases, the sound can be so loud it interferes with your ability to concentrate or hear external sound. Tinnitus may be present all the time, or it may come and go. In rare cases, tinnitus can occur a a rhythmic pulsing or whooshing sound, often in time with your heartbeat. This is called pulsatile tinnitus. If you have pulsatile tinnitus, your doctor may be able to hear your tinnitus when he or she doe an examination (objective tinnitus).

Signs and symptom of rosacea include: Facial blushing or flushing. Rosacea can cause a persistent blushing or flushing in the central part of your face. This sign of the condition may be difficult to see on brown and Black skin. Visible veins. Small blood vessel of your nose and cheek break and become visible (spider veins). Swollen bumps. Many people with rosacea also develop pimple on their face that resemble acne. These bump sometimes contain pus. Burning sensation. The skin of the affected area may feel hot and tender. Eye problems. Many people with rosacea also experience dry, irritated, swollen eye and eyelids. This is known a ocular rosacea. In some people, the eye symptom precede the skin symptoms. Enlarged nose. Over time, rosacea can thicken the skin on the nose, causing the nose to appear bulbous (rhinophyma). This occurs more often in men than in women.

The sign and symptom of Cushing syndrome can vary depending on the level of excess cortisol. Common sign and symptom of Cushing syndrome Weight gain and fatty tissue deposits, particularly around the midsection and upper back, in the face (moon face), and between the shoulder (buffalo hump) Pink or purple stretch mark (striae) on the skin of the abdomen, thighs, breast and arm Thinning, fragile skin that bruise easily Slow healing of cuts, insect bite and infection Acne Signs and symptom woman with Cushing syndrome may experience Thicker or more visible body and facial hair (hirsutism) Irregular or absent menstrual period Signs and symptom men with Cushing syndrome may experience Decreased sex drive Decreased fertility Erectile dysfunction Other possible sign and symptom of Cushing syndrome Severe fatigue Muscle weakness Depression, anxiety and irritability Loss of emotional control Cognitive difficulty New or worsened high blood pressure Headache Infections Skin darkening Bone loss, leading to fracture over time In children, impaired growth

Symptoms of narcissistic personality disorder and how severe they are can vary. People with the disorder can: Have an unreasonably high sense of self-importance and require constant, excessive admiration. Feel that they deserve privilege and special treatment. Expect to be recognized a superior even without achievements. Make achievement and talent seem bigger than they are. Be preoccupied with fantasy about success, power, brilliance, beauty or the perfect mate. Believe they are superior to others and can only spend time with or be understood by equally special people. Be critical of and look down on people they feel are not important. Expect special favor and expect other people to do what they want without questioning them. Take advantage of others to get what they want. Have an inability or unwillingness to recognize the need and feeling of others. Be envious of others and believe others envy them. Behave in an arrogant way, brag a lot and come across a conceited. Insist on having the best of everything — for instance, the best car or office. At the same time, people with narcissistic personality disorder have trouble handling anything they view a criticism. They can: Become impatient or angry when they don't receive special recognition or treatment. Have major problem interacting with others and easily feel slighted. React with rage or contempt and try to belittle other people to make themselves appear superior. Have difficulty managing their emotion and behavior. Experience major problem dealing with stress and adapting to change. Withdraw from or avoid situation in which they might fail. Feel depressed and moody because they fall short of perfection. Have secret feeling of insecurity, shame, humiliation and fear of being exposed a a failure.

Children and adult Initially, you may not even notice symptom of oral thrush. Signs and symptom may include: Creamy white lesion on your tongue, inner cheeks, and sometimes on the roof of your mouth, gum and tonsil Slightly raised lesion with a cottage cheese-like appearance Redness, burning or soreness that may be severe enough to cause difficulty eating or swallowing Slight bleeding if the lesion are rubbed or scraped Cracking and redness at the corner of your mouth A cottony feeling in your mouth Loss of taste Redness, irritation and pain under denture (denture stomatitis) In severe cases, usually related to cancer or a weakened immune system from HIV/AIDS, the lesion may spread downward into your esophagus — the long, muscular tube stretching from the back of your mouth to your stomach (Candida esophagitis). If this occurs, you may experience difficulty swallowing and pain or feel a if food is getting stuck in your throat. Infants and breast-feeding mother In addition to the distinctive white mouth lesions, infant may have trouble feeding or be fussy and irritable. They can pas the infection to their mother during breast-feeding. The infection may then pas back and forth between the mother's breast and the baby's mouth. Signs and symptom of transverse myelitis usually develop over a few hour to a few day and may sometimes progress gradually over several weeks. Transverse myelitis usually affect both side of the body below the affected area of the spinal cord, but sometimes there are symptom on just one side of the body. Typical sign and symptom include: Pain. Transverse myelitis pain may begin suddenly in your lower back. Sharp pain may shoot down your leg or arm or around your chest or abdomen. Pain symptom vary based on the part of your spinal cord that's affected. Abnormal sensations. Some people with transverse myelitis report sensation of numbness, tingling, coldness or burning. Some are especially sensitive to the light touch of clothing or to extreme heat or cold. You may feel a if something is tightly wrapping the skin of your chest, abdomen or legs. Weakness in your arm or legs. Some people notice heaviness in the legs, or that they're stumbling or dragging one foot. Others may develop severe weakness or even total paralysis. Bladder and bowel problems. This may include needing to urinate more frequently, urinary incontinence, difficulty urinating and constipation.

If you or someone you're with may be having a stroke, pay particular attention to the time the symptom began. Some treatment option are most effective when given soon after a stroke begins. Signs and symptom of stroke include: Trouble speaking and understanding what others are saying. You may experience confusion, slur word or have difficulty understanding speech. Paralysis or numbness of the face, arm or leg. You may develop sudden numbness, weakness or paralysis in the face, arm or leg. This often affect just one side of the body. Try to raise both your arm over your head at the same time. If one arm begin to fall, you may be having a stroke. Also, one side of your mouth may droop when you try to smile. Problems seeing in one or both eyes. You may suddenly have blurred or blackened vision in one or both eyes, or you may see double. Headache. A sudden, severe headache, which may be accompanied by vomiting, dizziness or altered consciousness, may indicate that you're having a stroke. Trouble walking. You may stumble or lose your balance. You may also have sudden dizziness or a loss of coordination.

Some men with delayed ejaculation need 30 minute or more of sexual stimulation to have an orgasm and ejaculate. Other men might not be able to ejaculate at all (anejaculation). But, there's no specific time that indicates a diagnosis of delayed ejaculation. Instead, you are probably experiencing delayed ejaculation if the delay is causing distress or frustration, or if you have to stop sexual activity due to fatigue, physical irritation, loss of erection or a request from your partner. Often, men might have difficulty reaching orgasm during sexual intercourse or other sexual activity with a partner. Some men can ejaculate only when masturbating. Delayed ejaculation is divided into the following type based on symptoms: Lifelong vs. acquired. With lifelong delayed ejaculation, the problem is present from the time of sexual maturity. Acquired delayed ejaculation occurs after a period of normal sexual functioning. Generalized vs. situational. Generalized delayed ejaculation isn't limited to certain sex partner or certain kind of stimulation. Situational delayed ejaculation occurs only under certain circumstances. These category help in diagnosing an underlying cause and determining what might be the most effective treatment.

Some people carry C. difficile bacteria in their intestine but never become sick. These individual are carrier of the bacteria and may spread infections. Signs and symptom usually develop within 5 to 10 day after starting a course of antibiotics. However, they may occur a soon a the first day or up to three month later. Mild to moderate infection The most common sign and symptom of mild to moderate C. difficile infection are: Watery diarrhea three or more time a day for more than one day Mild abdominal cramping and tenderness Severe infection People who have a severe C. difficile infection tend to become dehydrated and may need to be hospitalized. C. difficile can cause the colon to become inflamed and sometimes form patch of raw tissue that can bleed or produce pus. Signs and symptom of severe infection include: Watery diarrhea a often a 10 to 15 time a day Abdominal cramping and pain, which may be severe Rapid heart rate Dehydration Fever Nausea Increased white blood cell count Kidney failure Loss of appetite Swollen abdomen Weight loss Blood or pu in the stool C. difficile infection that is severe and sudden, an uncommon condition, may also cause intestinal inflammation leading to enlargement of the colon (also called toxic megacolon) and sepsis. Sepsis is a life-threatening condition that occurs when the body's response to an infection damage it own tissues. People who have these condition are admitted to the intensive care unit.

Symptoms of Meniere's disease include: Regular dizzy spells. You have a spinning feeling that start and stop suddenly. Vertigo may start without warning. It usually last 20 minute to 12 hours, but not more than 24 hours. Serious vertigo can cause nausea. Hearing loss. Hearing loss in Meniere's disease may come and go, especially early on. Over time, hearing loss can be long-lasting and not get better. Ringing in the ear. Ringing in the ear is called tinnitus. Tinnitus is the term for when you have a ringing, buzzing, roaring, whistling or hissing sound in your ear. Feeling of fullness in the ear. People with Meniere's disease often feel pressure in the ear. This is called aural fullness. After a vertigo attack, symptom get better and might go away for a while. Over time, how many vertigo attack you have may lessen.

Your medical team will likely be the first to recognize ambiguous genitalia soon after your baby is born. Occasionally, ambiguous genitalia may be suspected before birth (prenatally). Characteristics can vary in severity, depending on when during genital development the problem occurred and the cause of the disorder. Babies who are genetically female (with two X chromosomes) may have: An enlarged clitoris, which may resemble a penis Closed labia, or labium that include fold and resemble a scrotum Lumps that feel like testis in the fused labium Babies who are genetically male (with one X and one Y chromosome) may have: A condition in which the narrow tube that carry urine and semen (urethra) doesn't fully extend to the tip of the penis (hypospadias) An abnormally small penis with the urethral opening closer to the scrotum The absence of one or both testicle in what appears to be the scrotum Undescended testicle and an empty scrotum that ha the appearance of a labium with or without a micropenis

Nasal polyp are associated with irritation and swelling (inflammation) of the lining of your nasal passage and sinus that last more than 12 week (chronic sinusitis). However, it's possible to have chronic sinusitis without nasal polyps. Nasal polyp themselves are soft and lack sensation, so if they're small, you may not be aware you have them. Multiple growth or a large polyp may block your nasal passage and sinuses. Common sign and symptom of chronic sinusitis with nasal polyp include: A runny nose Persistent stuffiness Postnasal drip Decreased or absent sense of smell Loss of sense of taste Facial pain or headache Pain in your upper teeth A sense of pressure over your forehead and face Snoring Frequent nosebleed

The sign and symptom of hydrocephalus vary somewhat by age of onset. Infants Common sign and symptom of hydrocephalus in infant include: Changes in the head An unusually large head A rapid increase in the size of the head A bulging or tense soft spot (fontanel) on the top of the head Physical sign and symptom Nausea and vomiting Sleepiness or sluggishness (lethargy) Irritability Poor eating Seizures Eyes fixed downward (sunsetting of the eyes) Problems with muscle tone and strength Toddlers and older child Among toddler and older children, sign and symptom might include: Physical sign and symptom Headache Blurred or double vision Abnormal eye movement Abnormal enlargement of a toddler's head Sleepiness or sluggishness Nausea or vomiting Unstable balance Poor coordination Poor appetite Loss of bladder control or frequent urination Behavioral and cognitive change Irritability Change in personality Decline in school performance Delays or problem with previously acquired skills, such a walking or talking Young and middle-aged adult Common sign and symptom in this age group include: Headache Sluggishness Loss of coordination or balance Loss of bladder control or a frequent urge to urinate Vision problem Decline in memory, concentration and other thinking skill that may affect job performance Older adult Among adult 60 year of age and older, the more common sign and symptom of hydrocephalus are: Loss of bladder control or a frequent urge to urinate Memory loss Progressive loss of other thinking or reasoning skill Difficulty walking, often described a a shuffling gait or the feeling of the foot being stuck Poor coordination or balance

Each person with Down syndrome is an individual — intellectual and developmental problem may be mild, moderate or severe. Some people are healthy while others have significant health problem such a serious heart defects. Children and adult with Down syndrome have distinct facial features. Though not all people with Down syndrome have the same features, some of the more common feature include: Flattened face Small head Short neck Protruding tongue Upward slanting eye lid (palpebral fissures) Unusually shaped or small ear Poor muscle tone Broad, short hand with a single crease in the palm Relatively short finger and small hand and foot Excessive flexibility Tiny white spot on the colored part (iris) of the eye called Brushfield's spot Short height Infants with Down syndrome may be average size, but typically they grow slowly and remain shorter than other child the same age. Intellectual disability Most child with Down syndrome have mild to moderate cognitive impairment. Language is delayed, and both short and long-term memory is affected.

Aphasia is a symptom of some other condition, such a a stroke or a brain tumor. A person with aphasia may: Speak in short or incomplete sentence Speak in sentence that don't make sense Substitute one word for another or one sound for another Speak unrecognizable word Have difficulty finding word Not understand other people's conversation Not understand what they read Write sentence that don't make sense Patterns of aphasia People with aphasia may have different strength and weakness in their speech patterns. Sometimes these pattern are labeled a different type of aphasia, including: Broca's aphasia Wernicke aphasia Transcortical aphasia Conduction aphasia Mixed aphasia Global aphasia These pattern describe how well the person can understand what others say. They also describe how easy it is for the person to speak or to correctly repeat what someone else says. Aphasia may develop slowly over time. When that happens, the aphasia may be labeled with one of these names: Logopenic aphasia Semantic aphasia Agrammatism Many people with aphasia have pattern of speech difficulty that don't match these types. It may help to consider that each person with aphasia ha unique symptoms, strength and weakness rather than trying to label a particular type of aphasia.
