A brain arteriovenous malformation may not cause any sign or symptom until the AVM ruptures, resulting in hemorrhage. In about half of all brain AVMs, hemorrhage is the first sign. AVM AVM But some people with brain AVM may experience sign and symptom other than bleeding, such as: AVM Seizures Headache or pain in one area of the head Muscle weakness or numbness in one part of the body Some people may experience more-serious neurological sign and symptoms, depending on the location of the AVM, including: AVM Severe headache Weakness, numbness or paralysis Vision loss Difficulty speaking Confusion or inability to understand others Severe unsteadiness Signs and symptom of a brain AVM may begin at any age but usually emerge between age 10 and 40. Brain AVMs can damage brain tissue over time. The effect slowly build and often cause symptom in early adulthood. AVM AVM By middle age, however, brain AVMs tend to remain stable and are le likely to cause symptoms. AVM Research hasn't found that pregnancy increase the risk of hemorrhage for people with a brain AVM. However, more research need to be done. AVM One severe type of brain AVM involves the vein of Galen. It cause sign and symptom that emerge soon or immediately after birth. The major blood vessel involved in this type of brain AVM can cause fluid to build up in the brain and the head to swell. It can also cause swollen vein that are visible on the scalp, seizures, failure to thrive and congestive heart failure.

If your child ha clubfoot, here's what it might look like: The top of the foot is usually twisted downward and inward, increasing the arch and turning the heel inward. The foot may be turned so severely that it actually look a if it's upside down. The affected leg or foot may be slightly shorter. The calf muscle in the affected leg are usually underdeveloped. Despite it look, clubfoot itself doesn't cause any discomfort or pain.

Babies with Rett syndrome usually are born after an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. Most infant with Rett syndrome seem to grow and behave a expected for the first six months. After that, sign and symptom start to appear. The most pronounced change generally occur at 12 to 18 month of age, over a period of week or months. Symptoms and their severity vary greatly from child to child. The main sign and symptom include: Slowed growth. Brain growth slows after birth. Smaller than usual head size (microcephaly) is sometimes the first sign that a child ha Rett syndrome. As child get older, there is delayed growth in other part of the body. Loss of movement and coordination abilities. The first sign often include reduced hand control and a decreasing ability to crawl or walk. At first, this loss of ability occurs rapidly, and then it continues more gradually. Eventually muscle become weak or stiff, with unusual movement and positioning. Loss of communication abilities. Children with Rett syndrome typically begin to lose the ability to speak, to make eye contact and to communicate in other ways. They may become disinterested in other people, toy and their surroundings. Some child have rapid changes, such a a sudden loss of language. Over time, child may gradually regain eye contact and develop nonverbal communication skills. Unusual hand movements. Children with Rett syndrome usually develop repetitive, purposeless hand movements, which differ from child to child. Hand movement may include hand-wringing, squeezing, clapping, tapping or rubbing. Other sign and symptom can include: Unusual eye movements. Children with Rett syndrome tend to have unusual eye movements, such a intense staring, blinking, crossed eye or closing one eye at a time. Breathing problems. These include breath holding, rapid breathing (hyperventilation), forcefully blowing out air or saliva, and swallowing air. These problem tend to occur during waking hours. Other breathing disturbance such a shallow breathing or short period of stopping breathing (apnea) can occur during sleep. Irritability and crying. Children with Rett syndrome may become increasingly agitated and irritable a they get older. Periods of cry or screaming may begin suddenly, for no apparent reason, and last for hours. Some child may experience fear and anxiety. Other unusual behaviors. These may include, for example, sudden, odd facial expression and long bout of laughter, hand licking, and grasping of hair or clothing. Intellectual disabilities. Loss of skill may be connected to losing the ability to think, understand and learn. Seizures. Most people who have Rett syndrome experience seizure at some time during their lives. Multiple seizure type may occur and are associated with change on an electroencephalogram (EEG). Sideways curvature of the spine (scoliosis). Scoliosis is common with Rett syndrome. It typically begin between 8 and 11 year of age and progress with age. Surgery may be required if the curvature is severe. Irregular heartbeat. This is a life-threatening problem for many child and adult with Rett syndrome and can result in sudden death. Sleep disturbances. Problems with sleep pattern can include irregular sleep times, falling asleep during the day and being awake at night, or waking in the night with cry or screaming. Other symptoms. A variety of other symptom can occur, such a a decreased response to pain; small hand and foot that are usually cold; problem with chewing and swallowing; problem with bowel function; and teeth grinding. Stages of Rett syndrome Rett syndrome is commonly divided into four stages: Stage 1: Early onset. Signs and symptom are subtle and easily overlooked during the first stage, which start between 6 and 18 month of age. Stage 1 can last for a few month or a year. Babies in this stage may show le eye contact and start to lose interest in toys. They may also have delay in sitting or crawling. Stage 2: Rapid deterioration. Starting between 1 and 4 year of age, child lose the ability to perform skill they previously had. This loss can be rapid or more gradual, occurring over week or months. Symptoms of Rett syndrome occur, such a slowed head growth, abnormal hand movements, hyperventilating, screaming or cry for no apparent reason, problem with movement and coordination, and a loss of social interaction and communication. Stage 3: Plateau. The third stage usually begin between the age of 2 and 10 years, and it can last for many years. Although problem with movement continue, behavior may slightly improve, with le cry and irritability, and there may be some improvement in hand use and communication. Seizures may begin in this stage and generally don't occur before the age of 2. Stage 4: Late motor deterioration. This stage usually begin after the age of 10 and can last for year or decades. It's marked by reduced mobility, muscle weakness, joint contracture and scoliosis. Understanding, communication and hand skill generally remain stable or improve slightly, and seizure may occur le often.

Common symptom of hemifacial spasm include twitching or contracting of muscle in the face that are usually: On one side of the face Uncontrollable Painless These contraction often start in the eyelid, then may progress and affect the cheek and mouth on the same side of the face. At first, hemifacial spasm come and go. But eventually, usually over the course of several month to a few years, they occur almost constantly. Occasionally, hemifacial spasm may occur on both side of the face. However, the twitching doesn't occur on both side of the face at the same time. Causes Hemifacial spasm is most often caused by a blood vessel touching a facial nerve. It can also be caused by a facial nerve injury or a tumor. Sometimes there's no identifiable cause. Hemifacial spasm may sometimes be triggered by: Moving the muscle in the face Anxiety Stress Fatigue By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Hemifacial spasm care at Mayo Clinic

Signs and symptom of calciphylaxis include: Large purple net-like pattern on skin Deep, very painful lump that ulcerate creating open sore with black-brown crust that fails to heal — typically in skin area with high fat content, such a the stomach and thigh, although they can occur anywhere Infections from wound that don't heal Causes The exact cause of calciphylaxis is unknown, but recent study have revealed that most people with the condition have abnormality in blood-clotting factors. Blood-clotting factor are substance in your blood that help stop bleeding. These abnormality can lead to small blood clot forming more often than they normally would. In addition, people with calciphylaxis have an imbalance in the metabolism of calcium. This cause calcium to be deposited in the smallest part of the artery (arterioles), which eventually lead to the formation of blood clot in the arterioles. Blood clot can cause fat tissue and skin to be deprived of oxygen and nourishment.

Symptoms of brucellosis may show up anytime from a few day to a few month after you've been infected. Signs and symptom are similar to those of the flu and include: Fever Chills Loss of appetite Sweats Weakness Fatigue Joint, muscle and back pain Headache Brucellosis symptom may disappear for week or month and then return. Some people have chronic brucellosis and experience symptom for years, even after treatment. Long-term sign and symptom may include: Fatigue Recurrent fever Inflammation of the inner lining of the heart chamber (endocarditis) Joint inflammation (arthritis) Arthritis of the spinal bone (spondylitis) Arthritis of joint where the spine and pelvis connect (sacroiliitis)

Signs and symptom of CAH vary, depending on which gene is affected and the level of enzyme deficiency. The imbalance of hormone the body need to function may mean too little cortisol, too little aldosterone, excess androgen or a combination of these imbalances. CAH Classic CAH Signs and symptom of classic CAH may include: CAH Insufficient cortisol. Classic CAH cause the body to produce an insufficient amount of cortisol. This can cause problem maintaining normal blood pressure, blood sugar and energy levels, and cause problem during physical stress such a illness. Adrenal crisis. People with classic CAH can be seriously affected by a lack of cortisol, aldosterone or both. This is known a an adrenal crisis, and it can be life-threatening. Atypical genitalia. Female infant may have atypical genitalia appearance, such a an enlarged clitoris that may resemble a penis, and a partially closed labium resembling a scrotum. The urinary opening (urethra) and the vagina may be only one opening instead of two separate openings. The uterus, fallopian tube and ovary usually develop typically. Male infant usually have typical-appearing genitals. Excess androgen. An excess of the male sex hormone androgen can result in short height and early puberty for both male and females. Pubic hair and other sign of puberty may appear at a very early age. Severe acne also may occur. Excess androgen hormone in female may result in facial hair, excessive body hair and a deepening voice. Altered growth. Rapid growth may occur during childhood with an advanced bone age. Final height may be shorter than average. Fertility issues. These can include irregular menstrual periods, or not having any at all, and having infertility problem in females. Fertility issue can sometimes occur in males. Nonclassic CAH Often there are no symptom of nonclassic CAH when a baby is born. Some people with nonclassic CAH never have symptoms. The condition is not identified on routine infant blood screening and usually becomes evident in late childhood or early adulthood. Cortisol may be the only hormone that's deficient. CAH CAH Females who have nonclassic CAH may have typical-appearing genitals at birth. Later in life, they may experience: CAH Irregular menstrual periods, or not having any at all, and problem getting pregnant Masculine characteristic such a facial hair, excessive body hair and a deepening voice In both female and males, sign of nonclassic CAH may also include: CAH Early appearance of pubic hair and other sign of early puberty Severe acne Rapid growth during childhood with an advanced bone age and shorter than expected final height

A double uterus often cause no symptoms. The condition may be discovered during a regular pelvic exam or during imaging test to determine the cause of repeated miscarriages. Women who have a double vagina along with a double uterus may initially consult a doctor for menstrual bleeding that isn't stopped by a tampon. In these situations, the woman ha placed a tampon in one vagina, but blood is still escaping from the second uterus and vagina. When to see a doctor Seek medical advice if you have a menstrual flow despite the insertion of a tampon, or if you have severe pain with menstruation or experience repeated miscarriages.

Tics — sudden, brief, intermittent movement or sound — are the hallmark sign of Tourette syndrome. They can range from mild to severe. Severe symptom might significantly interfere with communication, daily functioning and quality of life. Tics are classified as: Simple tics. These sudden, brief and repetitive tic involve a limited number of muscle groups. Complex tics. These distinct, coordinated pattern of movement involve several muscle groups. Tics can also involve movement (motor tics) or sound (vocal tics). Motor tic usually begin before vocal tic do. But the spectrum of tic that people experience is diverse. Children with childhood apraxia of speech (CAS) may have many speech symptom or characteristic that vary depending on their age and the severity of their speech problems. CAS can be associated with: CAS Delayed onset of first word A limited number of spoken word The ability to form only a few consonant or vowel sound These symptom are usually noticed between age 18 month and 2 years, and may indicate suspected CAS. CAS As child produce more speech, usually between age 2 and 4, characteristic that likely indicate CAS include: CAS Vowel and consonant distortion Separation of syllable in or between word Voicing errors, such a "pie" sounding like "bye" Many child with CAS have difficulty getting their jaws, lip and tongue to the correct position to make a sound, and they may have difficulty moving smoothly to the next sound. CAS Many child with CAS also have language problems, such a reduced vocabulary or difficulty with word order. CAS Some symptom may be unique to child with CAS and can be helpful to diagnose the problem. However, some symptom of CAS are also symptom of other type of speech or language disorders. It's difficult to diagnose CAS if a child ha only symptom that are found both in CAS and in other type of speech or language disorders. CAS CAS CAS CAS Some characteristics, sometimes called markers, help distinguish CAS from other type of speech disorders. Those particularly associated with CAS include: CAS CAS Difficulty moving smoothly from one sound, syllable or word to another Groping movement with the jaw, lip or tongue to make the correct movement for speech sound Vowel distortions, such a attempting to use the correct vowel, but saying it incorrectly Using the wrong stress in a word, such a pronouncing "banana" a "BUH-nan-uh" instead of "buh-NAN-uh" Using equal emphasis on all syllables, such a saying "BUH-NAN-UH" Separation of syllables, such a putting a pause or gap between syllable Inconsistency, such a making different error when trying to say the same word a second time Difficulty imitating simple word Inconsistent voicing errors, such a saying "down" instead of "town" Other characteristic are seen in most child with speech or language problem and aren't helpful in distinguishing CAS. Characteristics seen both in child with CAS and in child with other type of speech or language disorder include: CAS CAS Babbling le or making fewer vocal sound than is typical between the age of 7 to 12 month old Speaking first word late (after age 12 to 18 month old) Using a limited number of consonant and vowel Frequently leaving out (omitting) sound Using speech that is difficult to understand speech Other speech disorder sometimes confused with CAS Some speech sound disorder often get confused with CAS because some of the characteristic may overlap. These speech sound disorder include articulation disorders, phonological disorder and dysarthria. CAS A child who ha trouble learning how to make specific sounds, but doesn't have trouble planning or coordinating the movement to speak, may have an articulation or phonological disorder. Articulation and phonological disorder are more common than CAS. CAS Articulation or phonological speech error may include: Substituting sounds, such a saying "fum" instead of "thumb," "wabbit" instead of "rabbit" or "tup" instead of "cup" Leaving out (omitting) final consonants, such a saying "duh" instead of "duck" or "uh" instead of "up" Stopping the airstream, such a saying "tun" instead of "sun" or "doo" instead of "zoo" Simplifying sound combinations, such a saying "ting" instead of "string" or "fog" instead of "frog" Dysarthria is a motor speech disorder that is due to weakness, spasticity or inability to control the speech muscles. Making speech sound is difficult because the speech muscle can't move a far, a quickly or a strongly a normal. People with dysarthria may also have a hoarse, soft or even strained voice, or slurred or slow speech. Dysarthria is often easier to identify than CAS. However, when dysarthria is caused by damage to certain area of the brain that affect coordination, it can be difficult to determine the difference between CAS and dysarthria.

The time from infection with the hantavirus to the start of illness is usually about 2 to 3 weeks. Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome advance through two distinct stages. In the first stage, which can last for several days, the most common sign and symptom are: Fever and chill Muscle ache or pain Headache Some people also experience: Nausea Stomach pain Vomiting Diarrhea As the disease progresses, it can lead to damaged lung tissues, fluid build-up in the lungs, and serious problem with lung and heart function. Signs and symptom may include: Cough Difficulty breathing Low blood pressure Irregular heart rate

Most people with goiter have no sign or symptom other than a swelling at the base of the neck. In many cases, the goiter is small enough that it's only discovered during a routine medical exam or an imaging test for another condition. Other sign or symptom depend on whether thyroid function changes, how quickly the goiter grows and whether it obstructs breathing. Underactive thyroid (hypothyroidism) Signs and symptom of hypothyroidism include: Fatigue Increased sensitivity to cold Increased sleepiness Dry skin Constipation Muscle weakness Problems with memory or concentration Overactive thyroid (hyperthyroidism) Signs and symptom of hyperthyroidism include: Weight loss Rapid heartbeat (tachycardia) Increased sensitivity to heat Excess sweating Tremors Irritability and nervousness Muscle weakness Frequent bowel movement Changes in menstrual pattern Sleep difficulty High blood pressure Increased appetite Children with hyperthyroidism might also have the following: Rapid growth in height Changes in behavior Bone growth that outpaces expected growth for the child's age Obstructive goiter The size or position of a goiter may obstruct the airway and voice box. Signs and symptom may include: Difficulty swallowing Difficulty breathing with exertion Cough Hoarseness Snoring

Most people infected with the virus that cause polio, called poliovirus, don't get symptoms. Abortive polio About 5% of people with the poliovirus get a mild version of the disease called abortive poliomyelitis. This lead to flu-like symptom that last 2 to 3 days. These include: Fever Headache Muscle ache Sore throat Stomachache Loss of appetite Nausea Vomiting Nonparalytic polio A more severe form of the disease, called nonparalytic polio, affect about 1% of those infected. While the illness last longer than a few days, it doesn't cause paralysis. Besides having more-severe flu-like symptoms, nonparalytic polio symptom may include: Neck pain or stiffness Aches or stiffness in the arm or leg Severe headache A second phase of symptom may follow, or a person may seem to be getting better for a few day before a second phase starts. These symptom include: Stiffness of the spine and neck Decreased reflex Muscle weakness Paralytic polio This most serious form of the disease is rare. The disease begin much like nonparalytic polio. But it progress to more-severe sign and symptoms, including: Intense pain Extreme sensitivity to touch Tingling or pricking sensation Muscles spasm or twitching Muscles weakness progressing to a limp paralysis Any combination of limb may experience paralysis. But paralysis of one leg is most common, followed by paralysis of one arm. Depending on the severity of disease, other sign or symptom may include: Paralysis of muscle involved in breathing Difficulty swallowing Post-polio syndrome Post-polio syndrome is the appearance of new sign or symptom or the progression of problems. This usually happens decade after having polio. Common sign and symptom include: Progressive muscle or joint weakness and pain Fatigue Muscle wasting Breathing or swallowing problem Sleep-related breathing disorders, such a sleep apnea Lowered tolerance of cold temperature

Coarctation of the aorta symptom depend on how much of the aorta is narrowed. Most people don't have symptoms. Mild coarctation may not be diagnosed until adulthood. Babies with severe coarctation of the aorta may show symptom shortly after birth. Symptoms of coarctation of the aorta in infant include: Difficulty breathing Difficulty feeding Heavy sweating Irritability Pale skin Symptoms of coarctation of the aorta after infancy commonly include: Chest pain Headaches High blood pressure Leg cramp or cold foot Muscle weakness Nosebleeds Depending on where the coarctation is located, blood pressure may be high in the arm and low in the leg and ankles. Coarctation of the aorta often occurs with other heart defects. Other symptom depend on the type of congenital heart defect.

Once you become infected with whooping cough, it take about seven to 10 day for sign and symptom to appear, though it can sometimes take longer. They're usually mild at first and resemble those of a common cold: Runny nose Nasal congestion Red, watery eye Fever Cough After a week or two, sign and symptom worsen. Thick mucus accumulates inside your airways, causing uncontrollable coughing. Severe and prolonged coughing attack may: Provoke vomiting Result in a red or blue face Cause extreme fatigue End with a high-pitched "whoop" sound during the next breath of air However, many people don't develop the characteristic whoop. Sometimes, a persistent hacking cough is the only sign that an adolescent or adult ha whooping cough. Infants may not cough at all. Instead, they may struggle to breathe, or they may even temporarily stop breathing.

The sign and symptom of Takayasu's arteritis often occur in two stages. Stage 1 In the first stage, you're likely to feel unwell with: Fatigue Unintended weight loss Muscle and joint ache and pain Mild fever, sometimes accompanied by night sweat Not everyone ha these early sign and symptoms. It's possible for inflammation to damage artery for year before you realize something is wrong. Stage 2 During the second stage, inflammation cause artery to narrow so le blood and oxygen and fewer nutrient reach your organ and tissues. Stage 2 sign and symptom may include: Weakness or pain in your limb with use A weak pulse, difficulty getting a blood pressure or a difference in blood pressure between your arm Lightheadedness, dizziness or fainting Headaches or visual change Memory problem or trouble thinking Chest pain or shortness of breath High blood pressure Diarrhea or blood in your stool Too few red blood cell (anemia)

Not seeing or feeling a testicle where you would expect it to be in the scrotum is the main sign of an undescended testicle. Testicles form in the abdomen during fetal development. Signs and symptom of GI bleeding can be either obvious (overt) or hidden (occult). Signs and symptom depend on the location of the bleed, which can be anywhere on the GI tract, from where it start — the mouth — to where it end — the anus — and the rate of bleeding. GI GI Overt bleeding might show up as: Vomiting blood, which might be red or might be dark brown and resemble coffee ground in texture Black, tarry stool Rectal bleeding, usually in or with stool With occult bleeding, you might have: Lightheadedness Difficulty breathing Fainting Chest pain Abdominal pain Symptoms of shock If your bleeding start abruptly and progress rapidly, you could go into shock. Signs and symptom of shock include: Drop in blood pressure Not urinating or urinating infrequently, in small amount Rapid pulse Unconsciousness

Although depression may occur only once during your life, people typically have multiple episodes. During these episodes, symptom occur most of the day, nearly every day and may include: Feelings of sadness, tearfulness, emptiness or hopelessness Angry outbursts, irritability or frustration, even over small matter Loss of interest or pleasure in most or all normal activities, such a sex, hobby or sport Sleep disturbances, including insomnia or sleeping too much Tiredness and lack of energy, so even small task take extra effort Reduced appetite and weight loss or increased craving for food and weight gain Anxiety, agitation or restlessness Slowed thinking, speaking or body movement Feelings of worthlessness or guilt, fixating on past failure or self-blame Trouble thinking, concentrating, making decision and remembering thing Frequent or recurrent thought of death, suicidal thoughts, suicide attempt or suicide Unexplained physical problems, such a back pain or headache For many people with depression, symptom usually are severe enough to cause noticeable problem in day-to-day activities, such a work, school, social activity or relationship with others. Some people may feel generally miserable or unhappy without really knowing why. Depression symptom in child and teen Common sign and symptom of depression in child and teenager are similar to those of adults, but there can be some differences. In younger children, symptom of depression may include sadness, irritability, clinginess, worry, ache and pains, refusing to go to school, or being underweight. In teens, symptom may include sadness, irritability, feeling negative and worthless, anger, poor performance or poor attendance at school, feeling misunderstood and extremely sensitive, using recreational drug or alcohol, eating or sleeping too much, self-harm, loss of interest in normal activities, and avoidance of social interaction. Depression symptom in older adult Depression is not a normal part of growing older, and it should never be taken lightly. Unfortunately, depression often go undiagnosed and untreated in older adults, and they may feel reluctant to seek help. Symptoms of depression may be different or le obvious in older adults, such as: Memory difficulty or personality change Physical ache or pain Fatigue, loss of appetite, sleep problem or loss of interest in sex — not caused by a medical condition or medication Often wanting to stay at home, rather than going out to socialize or doing new thing Suicidal thinking or feelings, especially in older men

Signs and symptom of geographic tongue may include: Smooth, red, irregularly shaped patch (lesions) on the top or side of your tongue Frequent change in the location, size and shape of lesion Discomfort, pain or burning sensation in some cases, most often related to eating spicy or acidic food Many people with geographic tongue have no symptoms. Geographic tongue can continue for days, month or years. The problem often resolve on it own but may appear again at a later time. When to see a doctor Geographic tongue is a minor — although sometimes uncomfortable — condition. However, lesion on the tongue may indicate other more-serious condition of the tongue or disease affecting the body in general. If you have lesion on the tongue that don't resolve within 10 days, see your doctor or dentist.

Schizophrenia involves a range of problem with thinking, behavior or emotions. Signs and symptom may vary, but usually involve delusions, hallucination or disorganized speech, and reflect an impaired ability to function. The effect can be disabling. In most people with schizophrenia, symptom generally start in the mid- to late 20s, though it can start later, up to the mid-30s. Schizophrenia is considered early onset when it start before the age of 18. Onset of schizophrenia in child younger than age 13 is extremely rare. Symptoms can vary in type and severity over time, with period of worsening and remission of symptoms. Some symptom may always be present. Schizophrenia can be difficult to recognize in the early phases. Early sign and symptom Schizophrenia sign and symptom in child and teenager are similar to those in adults, but the condition may be more difficult to recognize in this age group. Early sign and symptom may include problem with thinking, behavior and emotions. Thinking: Problems with thinking and reasoning Bizarre idea or speech Confusing dream or television for reality Behavior: Withdrawal from friend and family Trouble sleeping Lack of motivation — for example, showing up a a drop in performance at school Not meeting daily expectations, such a bathing or dressing Bizarre behavior Violent or aggressive behavior or agitation Recreational drug or nicotine use Emotions: Irritability or depressed mood Lack of emotion, or emotion inappropriate for the situation Strange anxiety and fear Excessive suspicion of others Later sign and symptom As child with schizophrenia age, more typical sign and symptom of the disorder begin to appear. Signs and symptom may include: Delusions. These are false belief that are not based in reality. For example, you think that you're being harmed or harassed; that certain gesture or comment are directed at you; that you have exceptional ability or fame; that another person is in love with you; or that a major catastrophe is about to occur. Delusions occur in most people with schizophrenia. Hallucinations. These usually involve seeing or hearing thing that don't exist. Yet for the person with schizophrenia, hallucination have the full force and impact of a normal experience. Hallucinations can be in any of the senses, but hearing voice is the most common hallucination. Disorganized thinking. Disorganized thinking is inferred from disorganized speech. Effective communication can be impaired, and answer to question may be partially or completely unrelated. Rarely, speech may include putting together meaningless word that can't be understood, sometimes known a word salad. Extremely disorganized or abnormal motor behavior. This may show in several ways, from childlike silliness to unpredictable agitation. Behavior is not focused on a goal, which make it hard to do tasks. Behavior can include resistance to instructions, inappropriate or bizarre posture, a complete lack of response, or useless and excessive movement. Negative symptoms. This refers to reduced or lack of ability to function normally. For example, the person may neglect personal hygiene or appear to lack emotion — doesn't make eye contact, doesn't change facial expressions, speaks in a monotone, or doesn't add hand or head movement that normally occur when speaking. Also, the person may avoid people and activity or lack the ability to experience pleasure. Compared with schizophrenia symptom in adults, child and teen may be: Less likely to have delusion More likely to have visual hallucination Symptoms may be difficult to interpret When childhood schizophrenia begin early in life, symptom may build up gradually. Early sign and symptom may be so vague that you can't recognize what's wrong. Some early sign can be mistaken for typical development during early teen years, or they could be symptom of other mental or physical conditions. As time go on, sign may become more severe and more noticeable. Eventually, your child may develop the symptom of psychosis, including hallucinations, delusion and difficulty organizing thoughts. As thought become more disorganized, there's often a "break from reality" (psychosis) frequently requiring hospitalization and treatment with medication.

The four main characteristic of Henoch-Schonlein purpura include: Rash (purpura). Reddish-purple spot that look like bruise develop on the buttocks, leg and feet. The rash can also appear on the arms, face and trunk and may be worse in area of pressure, such a the sock line and waistline. Swollen, sore joint (arthritis). People with Henoch-Schonlein purpura often have pain and swelling around the joint — mainly in the knee and ankles. Joint pain sometimes precedes the classical rash by one or two weeks. These symptom subside when the disease clear and leave no lasting damage. Digestive tract symptoms. Many child with Henoch-Schonlein purpura develop belly pain, nausea, vomiting and bloody stools. These symptom sometimes occur before the rash appears. Kidney involvement. Henoch-Schonlein purpura can also affect the kidneys. In most cases, this show up a protein or blood in the urine, which you may not even know is there unless you have a urine test done. Usually this go away once the illness passes, but some people develop persistent kidney disease.

Carpal tunnel syndrome symptom usually start gradually and include: Tingling or numbness. You may notice tingling and numbness in the finger or hand. Usually the thumb and index, middle or ring finger are affected, but not the little finger. You might feel a sensation like an electric shock in these fingers. The sensation may travel from the wrist up the arm. These symptom often occur while holding a steering wheel, phone or newspaper, or may wake you from sleep. Many people "shake out" their hand to try to relieve their symptoms. The numb feeling may become constant over time. Weakness. You may experience weakness in the hand and drop objects. This may be due to the numbness in the hand or weakness of the thumb's pinching muscles, which are also controlled by the median nerve.

Signs and symptom of pheochromocytoma often include: High blood pressure Headache Heavy sweating Rapid heartbeat Tremors Pallor Shortness of breath Panic attack-type symptom Less common sign or symptom may include: Anxiety or sense of doom Blurry vision Constipation Weight loss Symptomatic spell The symptom of pheochromocytoma may be constant, or they may occur, or get stronger, occasionally. These spell can happen because of activity or conditions, food high in a substance that affect blood pressure (tyramine), and medications. Certain activity or condition can make symptom worse, such as: Certain activity or condition Physical hard work Anxiety or stress Changes in body position, such a going from sitting or lying down to standing Labor and delivery Surgery and a drug that cause you to be in a sleep-like state during surgery (anesthesia) Foods high in tyramine, a substance that affect blood pressure, also can make symptom worse. Tyramine is common in food that are fermented, aged, pickled, cured, overripe or spoiled. These food include: Foods high in tyramine, Some cheese Some beer and wine Chocolate Dried or smoked meat Certain medication that can make symptom worse include: Certain medication Monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOIs), such a phenelzine (Nardil), tranylcypromine (Parnate) and isocarboxazid (Marplan) Stimulants, such a amphetamine or cocaine When to see a doctor Although high blood pressure is a primary sign of a pheochromocytoma, most people who have high blood pressure don't have an adrenal tumor. Talk to your health care provider if any of these factor apply to you: Difficulty controlling high blood pressure with current treatment Spells of worsening high blood pressure A family history of pheochromocytoma A family history of a related genetic disorder: multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 2 (MEN 2), von Hippel-Lindau disease, hereditary paraganglioma syndrome or neurofibromatosis 1

Grand mal seizure have two stages: Tonic phase. Loss of consciousness occurs, and the muscle suddenly contract and cause the person to fall down. This phase tends to last about 10 to 20 seconds. Clonic phase. The muscle go into rhythmic contractions, alternately flexing and relaxing. Convulsions usually last one to two minute or less. The following sign and symptom occur in some but not all people with grand mal seizures: A scream. Some people may cry out at the beginning of a seizure. Loss of bowel and bladder control. This may happen during or following a seizure. Unresponsiveness after convulsions. Unconsciousness may persist for several minute after the convulsion ha ended. Confusion. A period of disorientation often follows a grand mal seizure. This is referred to a postictal confusion. Fatigue. Sleepiness is common after a grand mal seizure. Severe headache. Headaches may occur after a grand mal seizure.

Chest pain can feel different depending on what's triggering the symptom. Often, the cause ha nothing to do with the heart — though there's no easy way to tell without seeing a health care provider. Heart-related chest pain Chest pain is often associated with heart disease. But many people with heart disease say they have a mild discomfort that they wouldn't really call pain. Chest discomfort due to a heart attack or another heart problem may feel like: Pressure, fullness, burning or tightness in the chest. Crushing or searing pain that spread to the back, neck, jaw, shoulders, and one or both arms. Pain that last more than a few minutes, get worse with activity, go away and come back, or varies in intensity. Shortness of breath. Cold sweats. Dizziness, lightheadedness or weakness. Racing heartbeats. Nausea or vomiting. Other type of chest pain It can be difficult to tell if chest pain is related to the heart or caused by something else. Usually, chest pain is le likely due to a heart problem if it happens with: A sour taste or a sensation of food reentering the mouth Trouble swallowing Pain that get better or worse when you change body position Pain that get worse when you breathe deeply or cough Tenderness when you push on your chest Pain that continues for many hour The classic symptom of heartburn — a painful, burning sensation behind the breastbone — can be caused by problem with the heart or the stomach.

These condition include: Serum sickness, which may cause fever, joint pain, rash, swelling and nausea Drug-induced anemia, a reduction in red blood cells, which can cause fatigue, irregular heartbeats, shortness of breath and other symptom Drug rash with eosinophilia and systemic symptom (DRESS), which result in rash, high white blood cell count, general swelling, swollen lymph node and recurrence of dormant hepatitis infection Inflammation in the kidneys, also called nephritis, which can cause fever, blood in the urine, general swelling, confusion and other symptom

Scleroderma's sign and symptom vary from person to person, depending on which part of the body are affected. Skin-related sign and symptom Nearly everyone who ha scleroderma experience a hardening and tightening of the skin. The first part of the body to be affected are usually the fingers, hands, foot and face. In some people, the skin thickening can also involve the forearms, upper arms, chest, abdomen, lower leg and thighs. Early symptom may include swelling and itchiness. Affected skin can become lighter or darker in color and may look shiny because of the tightness. Some people also experience small red spots, called telangiectasia, on their hand and face. Calcium deposit can form under the skin, particularly at the fingertips, causing bump that can be seen on X-rays. Raynaud's phenomenon Raynaud's phenomenon is common in scleroderma and occurs because of an inappropriate and exaggerated contraction of the small blood vessel in the finger and toe in response to the cold or emotional distress. When this happens, the digit may turn white, blue or red, and feel painful or numb. Raynaud's phenomenon also can occur in people who don't have scleroderma. Digestive problem Scleroderma can affect any part of the digestive system, from the esophagus to the rectum. Depending on which part of the digestive system are affected, sign and symptom may include: Heartburn Difficulty swallowing Bloating Diarrhea Constipation Fecal incontinence Heart and lung problem When scleroderma affect the heart or lungs, it can cause shortness of breath, decreased exercise tolerance and dizziness. Scleroderma can cause scarring in the lung tissue that may result in increasing shortness of breath over time. There are medication that may help slow the progression of this lung damage. Scleroderma can also cause the blood pressure to increase in the circulation that go between the heart and the lungs. This is called pulmonary hypertension. In addition to shortness of breath, pulmonary hypertension can also cause excess fluid in the legs, foot and sometimes around the heart. When scleroderma affect the heart, heartbeat can become irregular. Heart failure may also occur in some people.

Sleep terror differ from nightmares. The dreamer of a nightmare wake up from the dream and may remember details, but a person who ha a sleep terror episode remains asleep. Children usually don't remember anything about their sleep terror in the morning. Adults may recall a dream fragment they had during the sleep terrors. Sleep terror generally occur in the first third to first half of the night, and rarely during naps. A sleep terror may lead to sleepwalking. During a sleep terror episode, a person may: Begin with a frightening scream or shout Sit up in bed and appear frightened Stare wide-eyed Sweat, breathe heavily, and have a racing pulse, flushed face and dilated pupil Kick and thrash Be hard to awaken, and be confused if awakened Be inconsolable Have no or little memory of the event the next morning Possibly, get out of bed and run around the house or have aggressive behavior if blocked or restrained When to see a doctor Occasional sleep terror aren't usually a cause for concern. If your child ha sleep terrors, you can simply mention them at a routine well-child exam. However, consult your doctor if sleep terrors: Become more frequent Routinely disrupt the sleep of the person with sleep terror or other family member Lead to safety concern or injury Result in daytime symptom of excessive sleepiness or problem functioning Continue beyond the teen year or start in adulthood

The main sign of muscular dystrophy is progressive muscle weakness. Specific sign and symptom begin at different age and in different muscle groups, depending on the type of muscular dystrophy. Duchenne type muscular dystrophy This is the most common form. Although girl can be carrier and mildly affected, it's much more common in boys. Signs and symptoms, which typically appear in early childhood, might include: Frequent fall Difficulty rising from a lying or sitting position Trouble running and jumping Waddling gait Walking on the toe Large calf muscle Muscle pain and stiffness Learning disability Delayed growth Becker muscular dystrophy Signs and symptom are similar to those of Duchenne muscular dystrophy, but tend to be milder and progress more slowly. Symptoms generally begin in the teen but might not occur until the mid-20s or later. Other type of muscular dystrophy Some type of muscular dystrophy are defined by a specific feature or by where in the body symptom begin. Examples include: Myotonic. This is characterized by an inability to relax muscle following contractions. Facial and neck muscle are usually the first to be affected. People with this form typically have long, thin faces; drooping eyelids; and swanlike necks. Facioscapulohumeral (FSHD). Muscle weakness typically begin in the face, hip and shoulders. The shoulder blade might stick out like wing when arm are raised. Onset usually occurs in the teenage year but can begin in childhood or a late a age 50. Congenital. This type affect boy and girl and is apparent at birth or before age 2. Some form progress slowly and cause only mild disability, while others progress rapidly and cause severe impairment. Limb-girdle. Hip and shoulder muscle are usually affected first. People with this type of muscular dystrophy might have difficulty lifting the front part of the foot and so might trip frequently. Onset usually begin in childhood or the teenage years.

Signs and symptom of corticobasal degeneration (corticobasal syndrome) include: Difficulty moving on one or both side of the body, which get worse over time Poor coordination Trouble with balance Stiffness Abnormal posture of the hand or feet, such a a hand forming a clenched fist Muscle jerk Difficulty swallowing Abnormal eye movement Trouble with thinking and language skill Speech problems, such a slow and halting speech Difficulty swallowing Corticobasal degeneration progress over six to eight years. Eventually, people with corticobasal degeneration lose the ability to walk.

The primary symptom of fibromyalgia include: Widespread pain. The pain associated with fibromyalgia often is described a a constant dull ache that ha lasted for at least three months. To be considered widespread, the pain must occur on both side of your body and above and below your waist. Fatigue. People with fibromyalgia often awaken tired, even though they report sleeping for long period of time. Sleep is often disrupted by pain, and many patient with fibromyalgia have other sleep disorders, such a restless leg syndrome and sleep apnea. Cognitive difficulties. A symptom commonly referred to a "fibro fog" impairs the ability to focus, pay attention and concentrate on mental tasks. Fibromyalgia often co-exists with other conditions, such as: Irritable bowel syndrome Chronic fatigue syndrome Migraine and other type of headache Interstitial cystitis or painful bladder syndrome Temporomandibular joint disorder Anxiety Depression Postural tachycardia syndrome

Symptoms of albinism involve skin, hair and eye color, a well a vision. Skin The easiest form of albinism to see result in white hair and very light-colored skin compared with sibling or other blood relatives. But skin coloring, also called pigmentation, and hair color can range from white to brown. People of African descent who have albinism may have skin that is light brown or red brown and have freckles. For some people, skin color may be nearly the same a that of parent or sibling without albinism. With exposure to the sun, some people may develop: Freckles. Moles, with or without color, which are sometimes pink. Large freckle-like spots, called solar lentigo (len-TIJ-ih-neez). Sunburn and no ability to tan. For some people with albinism, skin coloring never changes. For others, melanin production may begin or increase during childhood and the teen years, resulting in slight change in color. Hair Hair color can range from very white to brown. People of African or Asian descent who have albinism may have hair color that's yellow, red or brown. Hair color also may darken by early adulthood. Or hair may stain from contact with mineral in water and the environment, making hair appear darker with age. Eye color Eyelashes and eyebrow are often pale. Eye color can range from very light blue to brown and may change with age. With albinism, the colored part of the eyes, called the irises, usually don't have enough pigment. This allows light to shine through the iris and make the eye extremely sensitive to bright light. Because of this, very light-colored eye may appear red in some lighting. Vision Vision problem are a key feature of all type of albinism. Eye problem may include: Rapid, back-and-forth movement of the eye that can't be controlled, called nystagmus. An uncommon head position or head posture, such a tilting the head to try to reduce eye movement and see better. Eyes that can't look at the same direction at the same time or they appear to be crossed, a condition called strabismus. Problems seeing near object or far objects, called farsightedness or nearsightedness. Extreme sensitivity to light, called photophobia. A difference in the curve of the front surface of the eye or the lens inside the eye, called astigmatism, which cause blurred vision. Differences in the development of the thin layer of tissue on the inside back wall of the eye, called the retina. This difference result in reduced vision. Nerve signal from the retina to the brain that don't follow the usual nerve pathway in the eye. This is called misrouting of the optic nerve. Poor depth perception, which mean not being able to see thing in three dimension and judge how far away an object is. Legal blindness — vision le than 20/200 — or complete blindness.

Most people infected with toxoplasmosis do not have any symptoms. They often don't know they're infected. Some people have flu-like symptoms, including: Fever. Swollen lymph node that may last for weeks. Headache. Muscle aches. Skin rash. Symptoms of eye disease The toxoplasma parasite may infect tissue of the inner eye. This can occur in people with healthy immune systems. But the disease is more serious in people with weakened immunity. An infection in the eye is called ocular toxoplasmosis. Symptoms may include: Eye pain. Poor vision. Floaters, which are speck that seem to swim in your vision. Untreated eye disease can cause blindness. Effect on people with weakened immune system People with weakened immune system are likely to have more-serious disease from toxoplasmosis. A toxoplasmosis infection from earlier in life may become active again. People at risk include those living with HIV/AIDS, people receiving cancer treatment and people with a transplanted organ. In addition to serious eye disease, toxoplasmosis can cause severe lung or brain disease for a person with weakened immunity. Rarely, the infection can show up in other tissue throughout the body. Lung infection may cause: Breathing problems. Fever. Cough. Toxoplasmosis may cause inflammation of the brain, also called encephalitis. Symptoms may include: Confusion. Poor coordination. Muscle weakness. Seizures. Changes in alertness. Effect on fetus or infant Toxoplasmosis can pas from the mother to the fetus during a pregnancy. This is called congenital toxoplasmosis. Infection during the first trimester often cause more-severe disease. It also may result in miscarriage. For some baby with toxoplasmosis, serious disease may be present at birth or appear early in infancy. Medical problem may include: Too much fluid in or around the brain, also called hydrocephalus. Severe eye infection. Irregularities in brain tissues. An enlarged liver or spleen. Symptoms of severe disease vary. They may include: Problems with mental or motor skills. Blindness or other vision problems. Hearing problems. Seizures. Heart disorders. Yellowing of the skin and white of the eyes, also called jaundice. Rash. Most baby with toxoplasmosis do not show symptoms. But problem may show up later in childhood or teenage years. These include: Return of eye infections. Problems with motor skill development. Problems with thinking and learning. Hearing loss. Slowed growth. Early puberty.

There are three form of Tay-Sachs disease: infantile, juvenile and late onset/adult. Infantile form In the most common and severe form, called infantile form, an infant typically begin showing sign and symptom by about 3 to 6 month of age. Survival is usually only a few years. Signs and symptom can include: Exaggerated startle response when the baby hears loud noise "Cherry-red" spot in the eye Loss of motor skills, including turning over, crawling and sitting up Muscle weakness, progressing to paralysis Movement problem Seizures Vision loss and blindness Hearing loss and deafness Problems swallowing Loss of mental function and a lack of response to surroundings Growth in head size (progressive macrocephaly) Juvenile form The juvenile form of Tay-Sachs disease is le common. Signs and symptom vary in severity and begin in childhood. Survival is typically into the teen years. Signs and symptom can include: Behavior problem Gradual loss of skill and movement control Frequent respiratory infection Slow loss of vision and speech Decline in mental function and responsiveness Seizures Last onset/adult form This is a rare and le severe form with sign and symptom beginning in late childhood to adulthood. Severity of symptom varies greatly, and this form doe not always impact life expectancy. Signs and symptom progress slowly and can include: Muscle weakness Clumsiness and loss of coordination Tremors and muscle spasm Loss of the ability to walk Problems speaking and swallowing Psychiatric disorder Sometimes loss of mental function

The sign and symptom of a concussion can be subtle and may not show up immediately. Symptoms can last for days, week or even longer. Common symptom after a concussive traumatic brain injury are headache, loss of memory (amnesia) and confusion. The amnesia usually involves forgetting the event that caused the concussion. Physical sign and symptom of a concussion may include: Headache Ringing in the ear Nausea Vomiting Fatigue or drowsiness Blurry vision Other sign and symptom of a concussion include: Confusion or feeling a if in a fog Amnesia surrounding the traumatic event Dizziness or "seeing stars" A witness may observe these sign and symptom in the concussed person: Temporary loss of consciousness (though this doesn't always occur) Slurred speech Delayed response to question Dazed appearance Forgetfulness, such a repeatedly asking the same question You may have some symptom of concussion immediately, and some can occur for day after the injury, such as: Concentration and memory complaint Irritability and other personality change Sensitivity to light and noise Sleep disturbance Psychological adjustment problem and depression Disorders of taste and smell Symptoms in child Head trauma is very common in young children. But concussion can be difficult to recognize in infant and toddler because they can't describe how they feel. Concussion clue may include: Dazed appearance Listlessness and tiring easily Irritability and crankiness Loss of balance and unsteady walking Excessive cry Change in eating or sleeping pattern Lack of interest in favorite toy Vomiting Seizures

If you notice that your child is grinding his or her teeth — or ha other sign or symptom of bruxism — be sure to mention it at your child's next dental appointment.

The sign and symptom that give scarlet fever it name include: Red rash. The rash look like a sunburn and feel like sandpaper. It typically begin on the face or neck and spread to the trunk, arm and legs. Pushing on the reddened skin make it turn pale. Red lines. The fold of skin around the groin, armpits, elbows, knee and neck usually become a deeper red than the other area with the rash. Flushed face. The face may appear flushed with a pale ring around the mouth. Strawberry tongue. The tongue generally look red and bumpy, and it's often covered with a white coating early in the disease. Signs and symptom of scarlet fever also include: Fever of 100.4 F (38.0 C) or higher, often with chill Very sore and red throat, sometimes with white or yellowish patch Difficulty swallowing Enlarged gland in the neck (lymph nodes) that are tender to the touch Nausea or vomiting Belly (abdominal) pain Headache and body ache The rash and the redness in the face and tongue usually last about a week. After these sign and symptom have gone away, the skin affected by the rash often peels.

In most cases, no sign or symptom of susceptibility to malignant hyperthermia exist until you're exposed to certain drug used for anesthesia. Signs and symptom of malignant hyperthermia may vary and can occur during anesthesia or during recovery shortly after surgery. They can include: Severe muscle rigidity or spasm Rapid, shallow breathing and problem with low oxygen and high carbon dioxide Rapid heart rate Irregular heart rhythm Dangerously high body temperature Excessive sweating Patchy, irregular skin color (mottled skin) In rare cases, people at risk of malignant hyperthermia have shown sign of a reaction after intense physical activity during excessive heat or humidity, during a viral illness, or when taking statin medication used to lower cholesterol. If you're at risk of malignant hyperthermia and you don't have a serious reaction during your first exposure to certain anesthesia drugs, you're still at risk if you receive these drug in the future. Other anesthesia drug that don't trigger a reaction can be used instead.

Mitral valve regurgitation is often mild and progress slowly. Some people with mitral valve regurgitation might not have symptom for many years. But sometimes, mitral valve regurgitation develops quickly. This condition, called acute mitral valve regurgitation, cause sudden sign and symptoms. Fatigue is a common but nonspecific symptom of mitral valve regurgitation. Other sign and symptom of mitral valve regurgitation include: Sound of blood flow across the valve (heart murmur) Irregular heartbeat (arrhythmia) Shortness of breath (dyspnea), especially when lying down Sensation of a rapid, pounding or fluttering heartbeat (palpitations) Swollen foot or ankle (edema)

A fibroadenoma is a solid breast lump that often cause no pain. It is: Round with distinct, smooth border Easily moved Firm or rubbery A fibroadenoma often grows slowly. The average size is about 1 inch (2.5 centimeters). A fibroadenoma can get bigger over time. It may be tender or cause soreness a few day before your period. A large fibroadenoma may hurt when you touch it. But most often, this type of breast lump cause no pain. You can have a single fibroadenoma or more than one fibroadenoma. They can occur in one or both breasts. Some fibroadenoma shrink over time. Most fibroadenoma in adolescent shrink over many month to a few years. They then disappear. Fibroadenomas may also change shape over time. Fibroadenomas may get bigger during pregnancy. They might shrink after menopause.

A sudden fall in blood pressure can be dangerous. A change of just 20 mm Hg — a drop from 110 mm Hg systolic to 90 mm Hg systolic, for example — can cause dizziness and fainting. And big drops, such a those caused by uncontrolled bleeding, severe infection or allergic reactions, can be life-threatening. mm Hg mm Hg mm Hg Extreme low blood pressure can lead to a condition known a shock. In hypospadias, the opening of the urethra is located on the underside of the penis instead of at the tip. In most cases, the opening of the urethra is within the head of the penis. Less often, the opening is at the middle or the base of the penis. Rarely, the opening is in or beneath the scrotum. Signs and symptom of hypospadias may include: Opening of the urethra at a location other than the tip of the penis Downward curve of the penis (chordee) Hooded appearance of the penis because only the top half of the penis is covered by foreskin Abnormal spraying during urination When to see a doctor When to see a doctor Most infant with hypospadias are diagnosed soon after birth while still in the hospital. However, slight displacement of the urethral opening may be subtle and more difficult to identify. Talk to your doctor if you have concern about the appearance of your child's penis or if there are problem with urination.

Typically, a spider bite look like any other bug bite — a red, inflamed, sometimes itchy or painful bump on your skin — and may even go unnoticed. Harmless spider bite usually don't produce any other symptoms. Many skin sore look the same but have other causes, such a a bacterial infection. Bites from some spiders, such a widow spider and recluse spiders, might cause serious sign and symptoms. Widow spider bite Signs and symptom of a widow spider bite can include: Redness, pain and swelling. You might have pain and swelling around the bite, which can spread into your abdomen, back or chest. Cramping. You might have severe abdominal rigidity or cramping, which is sometimes mistaken for appendicitis or a ruptured appendix. Nausea, vomiting, tremor or sweating. You might experience nausea, vomiting, tremor or sweating alone or in combination. Symptoms can last 1 to 3 days. Recluse spider bite Signs and symptom of a recluse spider bite can include: Increasing pain over the first eight hour after the bite Fever, chill and body ache A bite wound with a pale center that turn dark blue or purple with a red ring around it A bite wound that grows into an open sore (ulcer) with the skin around it dying

Burn symptom vary depending on how deep the skin damage is. It can take a day or two for the sign and symptom of a severe burn to develop. 1st-degree burn. This minor burn affect only the outer layer of the skin (epidermis). It may cause redness and pain. 2nd-degree burn. This type of burn affect both the epidermis and the second layer of skin (dermis). It may cause swelling and red, white or splotchy skin. Blisters may develop, and pain can be severe. Deep second-degree burn can cause scarring. 3rd-degree burn. This burn reach to the fat layer beneath the skin. Burned area may be black, brown or white. The skin may look leathery. Third-degree burn can destroy nerves, causing numbness.

Signs and symptom of Prader-Willi syndrome can vary among individuals. Symptoms may slowly change over time from childhood to adulthood. Infants Signs and symptom that may be present from birth include: Poor muscle tone. A primary sign during infancy is poor muscle tone (hypotonia). Babies may rest with their elbow and knee loosely extended instead of fixed, and they may feel floppy or like rag doll when they're held. Distinct facial features. Children may be born with almond-shaped eyes, a narrowing of the head at the temples, a turned-down mouth and a thin upper lip. Poor sucking reflex. Infants may have a poor sucking reflex due to decreased muscle tone. Poor sucking make feeding difficult and can result in failure to thrive. Generally poor responsiveness. A baby may seem unusually tired, respond poorly to stimulation, have a hard time waking up or have a weak cry. Underdeveloped genitals. Males may have a small penis and scrotum. The testicle may be small or not descended from the abdomen into the scrotum (cryptorchidism). In females, the clitoris and labium may be small. Early childhood to adulthood Other feature of Prader-Willi syndrome appear during early childhood and remain throughout life, requiring careful management. These feature may include: Food craving and weight gain. A classic sign of Prader-Willi syndrome is a constant craving for food, resulting in rapid weight gain, starting around age 2 years. Constant hunger lead to eating often and consuming large portions. Unusual food-seeking behaviors, such a hoarding food, or eating frozen food or even garbage, may develop. Underdeveloped sex organs. A condition called hypogonadism occurs when sex organ (testes in men and ovary in women) produce little or no sex hormones. This result in underdeveloped sex organs, incomplete or delayed puberty, and in nearly all cases, infertility. Without treatment, woman may not start menstruating until their 30 or may never menstruate, and men may not have much facial hair and their voice may never fully deepen. Poor growth and physical development. Underproduction of growth hormone can result in short adult height, low muscle mass and high body fat. Other endocrine problem may include underproduction of thyroid hormone (hypothyroidism) or central adrenal insufficiency, which prevents the body from responding appropriately during stress or infections. Cognitive impairment. Mild to moderate intellectual disability, such a issue with thinking, reasoning and problem-solving, is a common feature of the disorder. Even those without significant intellectual disability have some learning disabilities. Delayed motor development. Toddlers with Prader-Willi syndrome often reach milestone in physical movement — for example, sitting up or walking — later than other child do. Speech problems. Speech is often delayed. Poor articulation of word may be an ongoing problem into adulthood. Behavioral problems. Children and adult may at time be stubborn, angry, controlling or manipulative. They may throw temper tantrums, especially when denied food, and may not tolerate change in routine. They may also develop obsessive-compulsive or repetitive behaviors, or both. Other mental health disorders, such a anxiety and skin picking, may develop. Sleep disorders. Children and adult with Prader-Willi syndrome may have sleep disorders, including disruption of the normal sleep cycle and a condition in which breathing pause during sleep (sleep apnea). These disorder can result in excessive daytime sleepiness and worsen behavior problems. Other sign and symptoms. These may include small hand and feet, curvature of the spine (scoliosis), hip problems, reduced saliva flow, nearsightedness and other vision problems, problem regulating body temperature, a high pain tolerance, or a lack of pigment (hypopigmentation) causing hair, eye and skin to be pale.

Schizotypal personality disorder typically includes five or more of these sign and symptoms: Being a loner and lacking close friend outside of the immediate family Flat emotion or limited or inappropriate emotional response Persistent and excessive social anxiety Incorrect interpretation of events, such a a feeling that something that is actually harmless or inoffensive ha a direct personal meaning Peculiar, eccentric or unusual thinking, belief or mannerism Suspicious or paranoid thought and constant doubt about the loyalty of others Belief in special powers, such a mental telepathy or superstition Unusual perceptions, such a sensing an absent person's presence or having illusion Dressing in peculiar ways, such a appearing unkempt or wearing oddly matched clothes Peculiar style of speech, such a vague or unusual pattern of speaking, or rambling oddly during conversation Signs and symptom of schizotypal personality disorder, such a increased interest in solitary activity or a high level of social anxiety, may be seen in the teen years. The child may be an underperformer in school or appear socially out of step with peers, which may result in teasing or bullying. Schizotypal personality disorder vs. schizophrenia Schizotypal personality disorder can easily be confused with schizophrenia, a severe mental illness in which people lose contact with reality (psychosis). While people with schizotypal personality disorder may experience brief psychotic episode with delusion or hallucinations, the episode are not a frequent, prolonged or intense a in schizophrenia. Another key distinction is that people with schizotypal personality disorder usually can be made aware of the difference between their distorted idea and reality. Those with schizophrenia generally can't be swayed away from their delusions. Despite the differences, people with schizotypal personality disorder can benefit from treatment similar to those used for schizophrenia. Schizotypal personality disorder is sometimes considered to be on a spectrum with schizophrenia, with schizotypal personality disorder viewed a le severe.

The itchy blister rash caused by chickenpox infection appears 10 to 21 day after exposure to the virus and usually last about five to 10 days. Other sign and symptoms, which may appear one to two day before the rash, include: Fever Loss of appetite Headache Tiredness and a general feeling of being unwell (malaise) Once the chickenpox rash appears, it go through three phases: Raised pink or red bump (papules), which break out over several day Small fluid-filled blister (vesicles), which form in about one day and then break and leak Crusts and scabs, which cover the broken blister and take several more day to heal New bump continue to appear for several days, so you may have all three stage of the rash — bumps, blister and scabbed lesion — at the same time. You can spread the virus to other people for up to 48 hour before the rash appears, and the virus remains contagious until all broken blister have crusted over. The disease is generally mild in healthy children. In severe cases, the rash can cover the entire body, and lesion may form in the throat, eyes, and mucous membrane of the urethra, anus and vagina.

Signs and symptom of sinus headache may include: Pain, pressure and fullness in the cheeks, brow or forehead Worsening pain if you bend forward or lie down Stuffy nose Fatigue Achy feeling in the upper teeth Sinusitis or migraine? Migraines and headache from sinusitis are easy to confuse because the sign and symptom of the two type of headache may overlap. Both migraine and sinusitis headache pain often get worse when you bend forward. Migraine can also be accompanied by various nasal sign and symptom — including congestion, facial pressure and a clear, watery nasal discharge. These are due to involvement of the autonomic nervous system in a migraine attack. In fact, study have shown that most people who see a health care provider for sinus headache are found to have migraine instead. Sinusitis, however, usually isn't associated with nausea or vomiting or aggravated by noise or bright light — all common feature of migraines. Sinusitis usually: Occurs after a viral upper respiratory infection or cold Includes thick, discolored nasal mucus Is associated with a decreased sense of smell Causes pain in one cheek or upper teeth Headaches due to sinus disease often last day or longer, and migraine most commonly last hour to a day or two.

Signs and symptom of small bowel cancer include: Abdominal pain Yellowing of the skin and the white of the eye (jaundice) Feeling unusually weak or tired Nausea Vomiting Losing weight without trying Blood in the stool, which might appear red or black Watery diarrhea Skin flushing Causes Doctors aren't certain what cause most small bowel cancers. In general, small bowel cancer begin when healthy cell in the small bowel develop change (mutations) in their DNA. A cell's DNA contains a set of instruction that tell a cell what to do. Healthy cell grow and divide in an orderly way to keep your body functioning normally. But when a cell's DNA is damaged and becomes cancerous, cell continue to divide — even when new cell aren't needed. As these cell accumulate, they form a tumor. With time, the cancer cell can grow to invade and destroy normal tissue nearby. And cancerous cell can spread (metastasize) to other part of the body. Risk factor Factors that may increase the risk of small bowel cancer include: Gene mutation passed through families. Some gene mutation that are inherited from your parent can increase your risk of small bowel cancer and other cancers. Examples include Lynch syndrome, familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) and Peutz-Jeghers syndrome. Other bowel diseases. Other disease and condition that affect the intestine may increase the risk of small bowel cancer, including Crohn's disease, inflammatory bowel disease and celiac disease. Weakened immune system. If your body's germ-fighting immune system is weakened, you may have an increased risk of small bowel cancer. Examples include people with HIV infection and those who take anti-rejection medicine after an organ transplant. Complications Small bowel cancer can cause complications, including: An increased risk of other cancers. People who have small bowel cancer run a higher risk of having other type of cancers, including those that affect the colon, rectum, ovary and the lining of the uterus (endometrium). Cancer that spread to other part of the body. Advanced small bowel cancer can spread (metastasize) to other part of the body, most often the liver. Prevention It's not clear what may help to reduce the risk of small bowel cancer, since it's very uncommon. If you're interested in reducing your risk of cancer in general, it may help to: Eat a variety of fruits, vegetable and whole grains. Fruits, vegetable and whole grain contain vitamins, minerals, fiber and antioxidants, which may help reduce your risk of cancer and other diseases. Choose a variety of fruit and vegetable so that you get an array of vitamin and nutrients. Drink alcohol in moderation, if at all. If you choose to drink alcohol, limit the amount of alcohol you drink to no more than one drink a day for woman of all age and men older than age 65, and up to two drink a day for men age 65 and younger. Stop smoking. Talk to your doctor about way to quit that may work for you. Exercise most day of the week. Try to get at least 30 minute of exercise on most days. If you've been inactive, start slowly and build up gradually to 30 minutes. Also, talk to your doctor before starting any exercise program. Maintain a healthy weight. If you are at a healthy weight, work to maintain your weight by combining a healthy diet with daily exercise. If you need to lose weight, ask your doctor about healthy way to achieve your goal. Aim to lose weight slowly by increasing the amount of exercise you get and reducing the number of calorie you eat. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Small bowel cancer care at Mayo Clinic

Snoring is often associated with a sleep disorder called obstructive sleep apnea (OSA). Not all snorer have OSA, but if snoring is accompanied by any of the following symptoms, it may be an indication to see a doctor for further evaluation for OSA: Witnessed breathing pause during sleep Excessive daytime sleepiness Difficulty concentrating Morning headache Sore throat upon awakening Restless sleep Gasping or choking at night High blood pressure Chest pain at night Your snoring is so loud it's disrupting your partner's sleep In children, poor attention span, behavioral issue or poor performance in school OSA often is characterized by loud snoring followed by period of silence when breathing stop or nearly stops. Eventually, this reduction or pause in breathing may signal you to wake up, and you may awaken with a loud snort or gasping sound. You may sleep lightly due to disrupted sleep. This pattern of breathing pause may be repeated many time during the night. People with obstructive sleep apnea usually experience period when breathing slows or stop at least five time during every hour of sleep.

The mildest form of histoplasmosis cause no sign or symptoms. But severe infection can be life-threatening. When sign and symptom occur, they usually appear 3 to 17 day after exposure and can include: Fever Chills Headache Muscle ache Dry cough Chest pain Tiredness Some people with histoplasmosis also get joint pain and a rash. People who have a lung disease, such a emphysema, can develop chronic histoplasmosis. Signs of chronic histoplasmosis can include weight loss and a bloody cough. Chronic histoplasmosis symptom sometimes mimic those of tuberculosis. Severe histoplasmosis The most severe variety of histoplasmosis occurs mainly in infant and in people with weakened immune systems. Called disseminated histoplasmosis, it can affect nearly any part of your body, including your mouth, liver, central nervous system, skin and adrenal glands. If untreated, disseminated histoplasmosis is usually fatal.

The two main feature of amnesia are: Trouble learning new information. Trouble remembering past event and previously familiar information. Most people with amnesia have problem with short-term memory, so they can't retain new information. Recent memory are most likely to be lost. More-remote or deeply ingrained memory may be spared. For example, people may recall experience from childhood or know the name of past presidents. But they may not be able to name the current president, know the month or remember what they ate for breakfast. Isolated memory loss doesn't affect a person's intelligence, general knowledge, awareness or attention span. It also doesn't affect judgment, personality or identity. People with amnesia usually can understand written and spoken word and can learn skill such a bike riding or piano playing. They may understand they have a memory disorder. Amnesia isn't the same a dementia. Dementia often includes memory loss but also involves other problem with thinking that lead to a decline in daily functioning. These problem include having trouble with language, judgment and visual-spatial skills. Memory loss also is a common symptom of mild cognitive impairment. This disorder involves memory and other cognitive problem that aren't a severe a those experienced in dementia. Additional symptom Depending on the cause of the amnesia, other symptom may include: False memory that are either completely invented or are real memory misplaced in time. Confusion or disorientation.

The disease can be present with the appearance of a single chancre (shown here on a penis) or many. Syphilis develops in stages, and symptom vary with each stage. But the stage may overlap, and symptom don't always occur in the same order. You may be infected with syphilis without noticing any symptom for years. Primary syphilis The first sign of syphilis is a small sore, called a chancre (SHANG-kur). The sore appears at the spot where the bacteria entered your body. While most people infected with syphilis develop only one chancre, some people develop several of them. The chancre usually develops about three week after exposure. Many people who have syphilis don't notice the chancre because it's usually painless, and it may be hidden within the vagina or rectum. The chancre will heal on it own within three to six weeks. Secondary syphilis Within a few week of the original chancre healing, you may experience a rash that begin on your trunk but eventually cover your entire body — even the palm of your hand and the sol of your feet. This rash is usually not itchy and may be accompanied by wartlike sore in your mouth or genital area. Some people also experience hair loss, muscle aches, a fever, a sore throat and swollen lymph nodes. These sign and symptom may disappear within a few week or repeatedly come and go for a long a a year. Latent syphilis If you aren't treated for syphilis, the disease move from the secondary stage to the hidden (latent) stage, when you have no symptoms. The latent stage can last for years. Signs and symptom may never return, or the disease may progress to the third (tertiary) stage. Tertiary syphilis About 15% to 30% of people infected with syphilis who don't get treatment will develop complication known a tertiary syphilis. In the late stage, the disease may damage the brain, nerves, eyes, heart, blood vessels, liver, bone and joints. These problem may occur many year after the original, untreated infection. Neurosyphilis At any stage, syphilis can spread and, among other damage, cause damage to the brain and nervous system and the eye. Congenital syphilis Babies born to woman who have syphilis can become infected through the placenta or during birth. Most newborn with congenital syphilis have no symptoms, although some experience a rash on the palm of their hand and the sol of their feet. Later sign and symptom may include deafness, teeth deformity and saddle nose — where the bridge of the nose collapses. However, baby born with syphilis can also be born too early, may die in the womb before birth or can die after birth.
