Signs and symptom can vary greatly among girl and woman with triple X syndrome. Many experience no noticeable effect or have only mild symptoms. Being taller than average height is the most typical physical feature. Most female with triple X syndrome experience normal sexual development and have the ability to become pregnant. Some girl and woman with triple X syndrome have intelligence in the normal range, but possibly slightly lower when compared with siblings. Others may have intellectual disability and sometimes may have behavioral problems. Occasionally, significant symptom may occur, which vary among individuals. These sign and symptom may show up as: Delayed development of speech and language skills, a well a motor skills, such a sitting up and walking Learning disabilities, such a difficulty with reading, understanding or math Behavioral problems, such a attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or symptom of autism spectrum disorder Psychological problems, such a anxiety and depression Problems with fine and gross motor skills, memory, judgment and information processing Sometimes female with triple X syndrome have these sign and symptoms: Vertical fold of skin that cover the inner corner of the eye (epicanthal folds) Widely spaced eye Curved pinky finger Flat foot Breastbone with an inward bowed shape Weak muscle tone (hypotonia) Seizures Problems with the kidney Ovaries that don't work properly at a young age (premature ovarian failure)

Paget's disease of the breast affect your nipple and usually the skin (areola) surrounding it. It's easy to mistake the sign and symptom of Paget's disease of the breast for skin irritation (dermatitis) or another noncancerous (benign) skin condition. Possible sign and symptom of Paget's disease of the breast include: Flaky or scaly skin on your nipple Crusty, oozing or hardened skin resembling eczema on the nipple, areola or both Itching Redness A tingling or burning sensation Straw-colored or bloody nipple discharge A flattened or turned-in (inverted) nipple A lump in the breast Thickening skin on the breast Signs and symptom usually occur in one breast only. The disease typically start in the nipple and may spread to the areola and other area of the breast. The skin change may come and go early on or respond to topical treatment, making it appear a if your skin is healing. On average, sign and symptom occur for several month before a diagnosis is made.

Huntington's disease usually cause movement, cognitive and psychiatric disorder with a wide spectrum of sign and symptoms. Which symptom appear first varies greatly from person to person. Some symptom appear more dominant or have a greater effect on functional ability, but that can change throughout the course of the disease. Movement disorder The movement disorder associated with Huntington's disease can include both involuntary movement problem and impairment in voluntary movements, such as: Involuntary jerking or writhing movement (chorea) Muscle problems, such a rigidity or muscle contracture (dystonia) Slow or unusual eye movement Impaired gait, posture and balance Difficulty with speech or swallowing Impairments in voluntary movement — rather than involuntary movement — may have a greater impact on a person's ability to work, perform daily activities, communicate and remain independent. Cognitive disorder Cognitive impairment often associated with Huntington's disease include: Difficulty organizing, prioritizing or focusing on task Lack of flexibility or the tendency to get stuck on a thought, behavior or action (perseveration) Lack of impulse control that can result in outbursts, acting without thinking and sexual promiscuity Lack of awareness of one's own behavior and ability Slowness in processing thought or ''finding'' word Difficulty in learning new information Psychiatric disorder The most common psychiatric disorder associated with Huntington's disease is depression. This isn't simply a reaction to receiving a diagnosis of Huntington's disease. Instead, depression appears to occur because of injury to the brain and subsequent change in brain function. Signs and symptom may include: Feelings of irritability, sadness or apathy Social withdrawal Insomnia Fatigue and loss of energy Frequent thought of death, dying or suicide Other common psychiatric disorder include: Obsessive-compulsive disorder, a condition marked by recurrent, intrusive thought and repetitive behavior Mania, which can cause elevated mood, overactivity, impulsive behavior and inflated self-esteem Bipolar disorder, a condition with alternating episode of depression and mania In addition to the above disorders, weight loss is common in people with Huntington's disease, especially a the disease progresses. Symptoms of juvenile Huntington's disease The start and progression of Huntington's disease in younger people may be slightly different from that in adults. Problems that often present early in the course of the disease include: Behavioral change Difficulty paying attention Rapid, significant drop in overall school performance Behavioral problem Physical change Contracted and rigid muscle that affect gait (especially in young children) Tremors or slight involuntary movement Frequent fall or clumsiness Seizures

Spinal stenosis often cause no symptoms. When symptom do occur, they start slowly and get worse over time. Symptoms depend on which part of the spine is affected. In the lower back Spinal stenosis in the lower back can cause pain or cramping in one or both legs. This happens when you stand for a long time or when you walk. Symptoms get better when you bend forward or sit. Some people also have back pain. In the neck Spinal stenosis in the neck can cause: Numbness Tingling or weakness in a hand, leg, foot or arm Problems with walking and balance Neck pain Problems with the bowel or bladder

Signs and symptom of pulmonary fibrosis may include: Shortness of breath (dyspnea) A dry cough Fatigue Unexplained weight loss Aching muscle and joint Widening and rounding of the tip of the finger or toe (clubbing) The course of pulmonary fibrosis — and the severity of symptom — can vary considerably from person to person. Some people become ill very quickly with severe disease. Others have moderate symptom that worsen more slowly, over month or years. Some people may experience a rapid worsening of their symptom (acute exacerbation), such a severe shortness of breath, that may last for several day to weeks. People who have acute exacerbation may be placed on a mechanical ventilator. Doctors may also prescribe antibiotics, corticosteroid medication or other medication to treat an acute exacerbation.

Most people with colon polyp do not have any symptoms. You might not know you have a polyp until your health care provider find it during an exam of your colon. However, some people with colon polyp may have: Change in bowel habits. Constipation or diarrhea that last longer than a week may mean the presence of a larger colon polyp or cancer. However, several other condition also can cause change in bowel habits. Change in stool color. Blood can show up a red streak in your stool or make stool appear black. A change in color also may be caused by certain foods, medicine or dietary supplements. Iron deficiency anemia. Bleeding from polyp can happen slowly over time, without visible blood in your stool. Chronic bleeding may lead to iron deficiency anemia, which can make you feel tired and short of breath. Pain. A large colon polyp can block part of your bowel, leading to crampy abdominal pain. Rectal bleeding. This can be a sign of colon polyp or cancer or other conditions, such a hemorrhoid or minor tear of the anus.

Early warning sign and symptom Initial sign and symptom of diabetic hypoglycemia include: Looking pale (pallor) Shakiness Dizziness or lightheadedness Sweating Hunger or nausea An irregular or fast heartbeat Difficulty concentrating Feeling weak and having no energy (fatigue) Irritability or anxiety Headache Tingling or numbness of the lips, tongue or cheek Nighttime sign and symptom If diabetic hypoglycemia occurs when you're sleeping, sign and symptom that may disturb your sleep include: Damp sheet or nightclothes due to perspiration Nightmares Tiredness, irritability or confusion upon waking Severe sign and symptom If diabetic hypoglycemia isn't treated, sign and symptom of hypoglycemia worsen and can include: Confusion, unusual behavior or both, such a the inability to complete routine task Loss of coordination Difficulty speaking or slurred speech Blurry or tunnel vision Inability to eat or drink Muscle weakness Drowsiness Severe hypoglycemia may cause: Convulsions or seizure Unconsciousness Death, rarely Symptoms can differ from person to person or from episode to episode. Some people don't have any noticeable symptoms. It's also possible you won't have any symptom of hypoglycemia. It's important to monitor your blood sugar level regularly and keep track of how you're feeling when your blood sugar is low.

During the first few month after a loss, many sign and symptom of normal grief are the same a those of complicated grief. However, while normal grief symptom gradually start to fade over time, those of complicated grief linger or get worse. Complicated grief is like being in an ongoing, heightened state of mourning that keep you from healing. Signs and symptom of complicated grief may include: Intense sorrow, pain and rumination over the loss of your loved one Focus on little else but your loved one's death Extreme focus on reminder of the loved one or excessive avoidance of reminder Intense and persistent longing or pining for the deceased Problems accepting the death Numbness or detachment Bitterness about your loss Feeling that life hold no meaning or purpose Lack of trust in others Inability to enjoy life or think back on positive experience with your loved one Complicated grief also may be indicated if you continue to: Have trouble carrying out normal routine Isolate from others and withdraw from social activity Experience depression, deep sadness, guilt or self-blame Believe that you did something wrong or could have prevented the death Feel life isn't worth living without your loved one Wish you had died along with your loved one

The most common symptom associated with the yip is an involuntary muscle jerk, although some people experience tremors, twitches, spasm or freezing. Causes In some people, the yip are a type of focal dystonia, a condition that cause involuntary muscle contraction during a specific task. It's most likely related to overuse of a certain set of muscles, similar to writer's cramp. Anxiety worsens the effect. Some athlete become so anxious and self-focused — overthinking to the point of distraction — that their ability to execute a skill, such a putting, is impaired. "Choking" is an extreme form of performance anxiety that may compromise a golfer's or any athlete's game. Because epilepsy is caused by abnormal activity in the brain, seizure can affect any process your brain coordinates. Seizure sign and symptom may include: Temporary confusion A staring spell Stiff muscle Uncontrollable jerking movement of the arm and leg Loss of consciousness or awareness Psychological symptom such a fear, anxiety or deja vu Symptoms vary depending on the type of seizure. In most cases, a person with epilepsy will tend to have the same type of seizure each time, so the symptom will be similar from episode to episode. Doctors generally classify seizure a either focal or generalized, based on how and where the abnormal brain activity begins. Focal seizure When seizure appear to result from abnormal activity in just one area of your brain, they're called focal seizures. These seizure fall into two categories: Focal seizure without loss of consciousness. Once called simple partial seizures, these seizure don't cause a loss of consciousness. They may alter emotion or change the way thing look, smell, feel, taste or sound. Some people experience deja vu. This type of seizure may also result in involuntary jerking of one body part, such a an arm or leg, and spontaneous sensory symptom such a tingling, dizziness and flashing lights. Focal seizure with impaired awareness. Once called complex partial seizures, these seizure involve a change or loss of consciousness or awareness. This type of seizure may seem like being in a dream. During a focal seizure with impaired awareness, you may stare into space and not respond normally to your environment or perform repetitive movements, such a hand rubbing, chewing, swallowing or walking in circles. Symptoms of focal seizure may be confused with other neurological disorders, such a migraine, narcolepsy or mental illness. A thorough examination and testing are needed to distinguish epilepsy from other disorders. Generalized seizure Seizures that appear to involve all area of the brain are called generalized seizures. Six type of generalized seizure exist. Absence seizures. Absence seizures, previously known a petit mal seizures, typically occur in children. They're characterized by staring into space with or without subtle body movement such a eye blinking or lip smacking and only last between 5-10 seconds. These seizure may occur in clusters, happening a often a 100 time per day, and cause a brief loss of awareness. Tonic seizures. Tonic seizure cause stiff muscle and may affect consciousness. These seizure usually affect muscle in your back, arm and leg and may cause you to fall to the ground. Atonic seizures. Atonic seizures, also known a drop seizures, cause a loss of muscle control. Since this most often affect the legs, it often cause you to suddenly collapse or fall down. Clonic seizures. Clonic seizure are associated with repeated or rhythmic, jerking muscle movements. These seizure usually affect the neck, face and arms. Myoclonic seizures. Myoclonic seizure usually appear a sudden brief jerk or twitch and usually affect the upper body, arm and legs. Tonic-clonic seizures. Tonic-clonic seizures, previously known a grand mal seizures, are the most dramatic type of epileptic seizure. They can cause an abrupt loss of consciousness and body stiffening, twitching and shaking. They sometimes cause loss of bladder control or biting your tongue.

Signs and symptom — other than short stature — vary considerably across the spectrum of disorders. Disproportionate dwarfism Most people with dwarfism have disorder that cause disproportionately short stature. Usually, this mean that a person ha an average-size trunk and very short limbs, but some people may have a very short trunk and shortened (but disproportionately large) limbs. In these disorders, the head is disproportionately large compared with the body. Almost all people with disproportionate dwarfism have normal intellectual capacities. Rare exception are usually the result of a secondary factor, such a excess fluid around the brain (hydrocephalus). The most common cause of dwarfism is a disorder called achondroplasia, which cause disproportionately short stature. This disorder usually result in the following: An average-size trunk Short arm and legs, with particularly short upper arm and upper leg Short fingers, often with a wide separation between the middle and ring finger Limited mobility at the elbow A disproportionately large head, with a prominent forehead and a flattened bridge of the nose Progressive development of bowed leg Progressive development of swayed lower back An adult height around 4 foot (122 cm) Another cause of disproportionate dwarfism is a rare disorder called spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia congenita (SEDC). Signs may include: A very short trunk A short neck Shortened arm and leg Average-size hand and foot Broad, rounded chest Slightly flattened cheekbone Opening in the roof of the mouth (cleft palate) Hip deformity that result in thighbone turning inward A foot that's twisted or out of shape Instability of the neck bone Progressive hunching curvature of the upper spine Progressive development of swayed lower back Vision and hearing problem Arthritis and problem with joint movement Adult height ranging from 3 foot (91 cm) to just over 4 foot (122 cm) Proportionate dwarfism Proportionate dwarfism result from medical condition present at birth or appearing in early childhood that limit overall growth and development. So the head, trunk and limb are all small, but they're proportionate to each other. Because these disorder affect overall growth, many of them result in poor development of one or more body systems. Growth hormone deficiency is a relatively common cause of proportionate dwarfism. It occurs when the pituitary gland fails to produce an adequate supply of growth hormone, which is essential for normal childhood growth. Signs include: Height below the third percentile on standard pediatric growth chart Growth rate slower than expected for age Delayed or no sexual development during the teen year

The average time from infection to appearance of sign and symptom (incubation period) is 10 days. The incubation period can range from 3 to 21 days. The most common type of tetanus is called generalized tetanus. Signs and symptom begin gradually and then progressively worsen over two weeks. They usually start at the jaw and progress downward on the body. Signs and symptom of generalized tetanus include: Painful muscle spasm and stiff, immovable muscle (muscle rigidity) in your jaw Tension of muscle around your lips, sometimes producing a persistent grin Painful spasm and rigidity in your neck muscle Difficulty swallowing Rigid abdominal muscle Progression of tetanus result in repeated painful, seizure-like spasm that last for several minute (generalized spasms). Usually, the neck and back arch, the leg become rigid, the arm are drawn up to the body, and the fist are clenched. Muscle rigidity in the neck and abdomen may cause breathing difficulties. These severe spasm may be triggered by minor event that stimulate the sens — a loud sound, a physical touch, a draft or light. As the disease progresses, other sign and symptom may include: High blood pressure Low blood pressure Rapid heart rate Fever Extreme sweating Localized tetanus This uncommon form of tetanus result in muscle spasm near the site of a wound. While it's usually a le severe form of disease, it can progress to generalized tetanus. Cephalic tetanus This rare form of tetanus result from a head wound. It result in weakened muscle in the face and spasm of the jaw muscles. It also can progress to generalized tetanus.

Most people with hepatopulmonary syndrome have no symptoms. The sign and symptom of pneumonia vary from mild to severe, depending on factor such a the type of germ causing the infection, and your age and overall health. Mild sign and symptom often are similar to those of a cold or flu, but they last longer. Signs and symptom of pneumonia may include: Chest pain when you breathe or cough Confusion or change in mental awareness (in adult age 65 and older) Cough, which may produce phlegm Fatigue Fever, sweating and shaking chill Lower than normal body temperature (in adult older than age 65 and people with weak immune systems) Nausea, vomiting or diarrhea Shortness of breath Newborns and infant may not show any sign of the infection. Or they may vomit, have a fever and cough, appear restless or tired and without energy, or have difficulty breathing and eating. When to see a doctor See your doctor if you have difficulty breathing, chest pain, persistent fever of 102 F (39 C) or higher, or persistent cough, especially if you're coughing up pus. It's especially important that people in these high-risk group see a doctor: Adults older than age 65 Children younger than age 2 with sign and symptom People with an underlying health condition or weakened immune system People receiving chemotherapy or taking medication that suppresses the immune system For some older adult and people with heart failure or chronic lung problems, pneumonia can quickly become a life-threatening condition.

Symptoms vary, depending on the type of eating disorder. Anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa and binge-eating disorder are the most common eating disorders. Other eating disorder include rumination disorder and avoidant/restrictive food intake disorder. Anorexia nervosa Anorexia (an-o-REK-see-uh) nervosa — often simply called anorexia — is a potentially life-threatening eating disorder characterized by an abnormally low body weight, intense fear of gaining weight, and a distorted perception of weight or shape. People with anorexia use extreme effort to control their weight and shape, which often significantly interferes with their health and life activities. When you have anorexia, you excessively limit calorie or use other method to lose weight, such a excessive exercise, using laxative or diet aids, or vomiting after eating. Efforts to reduce your weight, even when underweight, can cause severe health problems, sometimes to the point of deadly self-starvation. Bulimia nervosa Bulimia (boo-LEE-me-uh) nervosa — commonly called bulimia — is a serious, potentially life-threatening eating disorder. When you have bulimia, you have episode of bingeing and purging that involve feeling a lack of control over your eating. Many people with bulimia also restrict their eating during the day, which often lead to more binge eating and purging. During these episodes, you typically eat a large amount of food in a short time, and then try to rid yourself of the extra calorie in an unhealthy way. Because of guilt, shame and an intense fear of weight gain from overeating, you may force vomiting or you may exercise too much or use other methods, such a laxatives, to get rid of the calories. If you have bulimia, you're probably preoccupied with your weight and body shape, and may judge yourself severely and harshly for your self-perceived flaws. You may be at a normal weight or even a bit overweight. Binge-eating disorder When you have binge-eating disorder, you regularly eat too much food (binge) and feel a lack of control over your eating. You may eat quickly or eat more food than intended, even when you're not hungry, and you may continue eating even long after you're uncomfortably full. After a binge, you may feel guilty, disgusted or ashamed by your behavior and the amount of food eaten. But you don't try to compensate for this behavior with excessive exercise or purging, a someone with bulimia or anorexia might. Embarrassment can lead to eating alone to hide your bingeing. A new round of bingeing usually occurs at least once a week. You may be normal weight, overweight or obese. Rumination disorder Rumination disorder is repeatedly and persistently regurgitating food after eating, but it's not due to a medical condition or another eating disorder such a anorexia, bulimia or binge-eating disorder. Food is brought back up into the mouth without nausea or gagging, and regurgitation may not be intentional. Sometimes regurgitated food is rechewed and reswallowed or spit out. The disorder may result in malnutrition if the food is spit out or if the person eats significantly le to prevent the behavior. The occurrence of rumination disorder may be more common in infancy or in people who have an intellectual disability. Avoidant/restrictive food intake disorder This disorder is characterized by failing to meet your minimum daily nutrition requirement because you don't have an interest in eating; you avoid food with certain sensory characteristics, such a color, texture, smell or taste; or you're concerned about the consequence of eating, such a fear of choking. Food is not avoided because of fear of gaining weight. The disorder can result in significant weight loss or failure to gain weight in childhood, a well a nutritional deficiency that can cause health problems.

Panic attack typically begin suddenly, without warning. They can strike at any time — when you're driving a car, at the mall, sound asleep or in the middle of a business meeting. You may have occasional panic attacks, or they may occur frequently. Panic attack have many variations, but symptom usually peak within minutes. You may feel fatigued and worn out after a panic attack subsides. Panic attack typically include some of these sign or symptoms: Sense of impending doom or danger Fear of loss of control or death Rapid, pounding heart rate Sweating Trembling or shaking Shortness of breath or tightness in your throat Chills Hot flash Nausea Abdominal cramping Chest pain Headache Dizziness, lightheadedness or faintness Numbness or tingling sensation Feeling of unreality or detachment One of the worst thing about panic attack is the intense fear that you'll have another one. You may fear having panic attack so much that you avoid certain situation where they may occur.

The chief symptom is an urge to move the legs. Common accompanying characteristic of RLS include: RLS Sensations that begin while resting. The sensation typically begin after you've been lying down or sitting for an extended time, such a in a car, airplane or movie theater. Relief with movement. The sensation of RLS lessens with movement, such a stretching, jiggling the legs, pacing or walking. Worsening of symptom in the evening. Symptoms occur mainly at night. Nighttime leg twitching. RLS may be associated with another, more common condition called periodic limb movement of sleep, which cause the leg to twitch and kick, possibly throughout the night, while you sleep. People typically describe RLS symptom a compelling, unpleasant sensation in the leg or feet. They usually happen on both side of the body. Less commonly, the sensation affect the arms. RLS The sensations, which generally occur within the limb rather than on the skin, are described as: Crawling Creeping Pulling Throbbing Aching Itching Electric Sometimes the sensation are difficult to explain. People with RLS usually don't describe the condition a a muscle cramp or numbness. They do, however, consistently describe the desire to move the legs. RLS It's common for symptom to fluctuate in severity. Sometimes, symptom disappear for period of time, then come back.

When gangrene affect the skin, sign and symptom may include: Changes in skin color — ranging from pale gray to blue, purple, black, bronze or red Swelling Blisters Sudden, severe pain followed by a feeling of numbness A foul-smelling discharge leaking from a sore Thin, shiny skin, or skin without hair Skin that feel cool or cold to the touch If gangrene affect tissue beneath the surface of your skin, such a gas gangrene or internal gangrene, you may also have a low-grade fever and generally feel unwell. If the germ that caused the gangrene spread through the body, a condition called septic shock can occur. Signs and symptom of septic shock include: Low blood pressure Fever, although some people may have a body temperature lower than 98.6 F (37 C) Rapid heart rate Lightheadedness Shortness of breath Confusion

Guillain-Barre syndrome often begin with tingling and weakness starting in your foot and leg and spreading to your upper body and arms. Some people notice the first symptom in the arm or face. As Guillain-Barre syndrome progresses, muscle weakness can turn into paralysis. Signs and symptom of Guillain-Barre syndrome may include: A pin and needle sensation in your fingers, toes, ankle or wrist Weakness in your leg that spread to your upper body Unsteady walking or inability to walk or climb stair Difficulty with facial movements, including speaking, chewing or swallowing Double vision or inability to move the eye Severe pain that may feel achy, shooting or cramplike and may be worse at night Difficulty with bladder control or bowel function Rapid heart rate Low or high blood pressure Difficulty breathing People with Guillain-Barre syndrome usually experience their most significant weakness within two week after symptom begin. Types Guillain-Barre syndrome ha several forms. The main type are: Acute inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy (AIDP), the most common form in North America and Europe. The most common sign of AIDP is muscle weakness that start in the lower part of your body and spread upward. Miller Fisher syndrome (MFS), in which paralysis start in the eyes. MFS is also associated with unsteady gait. MFS is le common in the U.S. but more common in Asia. Acute motor axonal neuropathy (AMAN) and acute motor-sensory axonal neuropathy (AMSAN) are le common in the U.S. But AMAN and AMSAN are more frequent in China, Japan and Mexico.

Chagas disease can cause a sudden, brief illness (acute), or it may be a long-lasting (chronic) condition. Symptoms range from mild to severe, although many people don't experience symptom until the chronic stage. Acute phase The acute phase of Chagas disease, which last for week or months, is often symptom-free. When sign and symptom do occur, they are usually mild and may include: Swelling at the infection site Fever Fatigue Rash Body ache Eyelid swelling Headache Loss of appetite Nausea, diarrhea or vomiting Swollen gland Enlargement of your liver or spleen Signs and symptom that develop during the acute phase usually go away on their own. In some cases, if the infection isn't treated, Chagas disease will advance to the chronic phase. Chronic phase Signs and symptom of the chronic phase of Chagas disease may occur 10 to 20 year after initial infection, or they may never occur. In severe cases, Chagas disease sign and symptom may include: Irregular heartbeat Heart failure Sudden cardiac arrest Difficulty swallowing due to enlarged esophagus Stomach pain or constipation due to enlarged colon

General sign and symptom of most type of vasculitis include: Fever Headache Fatigue Weight loss General ache and pain Other sign and symptom are related to the part of the body affected, including: Digestive system. If your stomach or intestine are affected, you may experience pain after eating. Ulcers and perforation are possible and may result in blood in the stool. Ears. Dizziness, ringing in the ear and abrupt hearing loss may occur. Eyes. Vasculitis can make your eye look red and itch or burn. Giant cell arteritis can cause double vision and temporary or permanent blindness in one or both eyes. This is sometimes the first sign of the disease. Hands or feet. Some type of vasculitis can cause numbness or weakness in a hand or foot. The palm of the hand and sol of the foot might swell or harden. Lungs. You may develop shortness of breath or even cough up blood if vasculitis affect your lungs. Skin. Bleeding under the skin can show up a red spots. Vasculitis can also cause lump or open sore on your skin.

The adult then produce larva that move through the bloodstream to muscle tissues, shown here. Signs and symptom of trichinosis infection and how severe the infection is can vary. This depends on the number of larva eaten in the infected meat. Possibly no sign or symptom Mild case of trichinosis — those with only a small number of parasite in your body — may cause no sign or symptoms. Symptoms can develop with moderate or heavy infestation ⸺ a large number of parasite in your body. These symptom sometimes get worse a the roundworm (trichinella) larva travel through your body. Initial sign and symptom You swallow roundworm (trichinella) larva in tiny sack (cysts) containing the parasite. Your digestive juice dissolve the cysts, releasing the larva into your body. The larva then enter the wall of your small intestine, where they grow into adult worm and mate. Digestive symptom can begin 1 to 2 day after infection. At this stage, you may experience: Diarrhea Stomach (abdominal) pain Severe tiredness and weakness (fatigue) Nausea and vomiting Later sign and symptom About a week after infection, the adult female worm produce larvae. The larva go through the wall of your intestine and enter your bloodstream, They travel around the body and bury themselves in muscle tissue. Here, each larva coil up and form a cyst around itself. The larva can live for month to year inside the muscle tissue. Symptoms caused by muscle tissue invasion usually start 2 to 8 week after infection and include: High fever and chill Muscle pain and tenderness Aching joint Swelling of the eyelid or face Weakness Headache Sensitivity to light Pink eye (conjunctivitis) Itchy, irritated skin With a large number of parasites, muscle pain and weakness can be severe. This can limit moving, breathing and speaking. Symptoms last for several months. But symptom generally lessen when the larva form cysts. Even after the infection is gone, fatigue, mild pain, weakness and diarrhea may last for month or years.

Signs and symptom of norovirus infection may start suddenly and include: Nausea Vomiting Stomach pain or cramp Watery or loose diarrhea Feeling ill Low-grade fever Muscle pain Signs and symptom usually begin 12 to 48 hour after your first exposure to a norovirus and last 1 to 3 days. Signs and symptom of recurrent breast cancer vary depending on where the cancer come back. Local recurrence In a local recurrence, cancer reappears in the same area a your original cancer. If you've undergone a lumpectomy, the cancer could recur in the remaining breast tissue. If you've undergone a mastectomy, the cancer could recur in the tissue that line the chest wall or in the skin. Signs and symptom of local recurrence within the same breast may include: A new lump in your breast or irregular area of firmness Changes to the skin of your breast Skin inflammation or area of redness Nipple discharge Signs and symptom of local recurrence on the chest wall after a mastectomy may include: One or more painless nodule on or under the skin of your chest wall A new area of thickening along or near the mastectomy scar Regional recurrence A regional breast cancer recurrence mean the cancer ha come back in the nearby lymph nodes. Signs and symptom of regional recurrence may include a lump or swelling in the lymph node located: Under your arm Near your collarbone In the groove above your collarbone In your neck Distant recurrence A distant (metastatic) recurrence mean the cancer ha traveled to distant part of the body, most commonly the bones, liver and lungs. Signs and symptom include: Persistent and worsening pain, such a chest, back or hip pain Persistent cough Difficulty breathing Loss of appetite Weight loss without trying Severe headache Seizures

Common anxiety sign and symptom include: Feeling nervous, restless or tense Having a sense of impending danger, panic or doom Having an increased heart rate Breathing rapidly (hyperventilation) Sweating Trembling Feeling weak or tired Trouble concentrating or thinking about anything other than the present worry Having trouble sleeping Experiencing gastrointestinal (GI) problem Having difficulty controlling worry Having the urge to avoid thing that trigger anxiety Several type of anxiety disorder exist: Agoraphobia (ag-uh-ruh-FOE-be-uh) is a type of anxiety disorder in which you fear and often avoid place or situation that might cause you to panic and make you feel trapped, helpless or embarrassed. Anxiety disorder due to a medical condition includes symptom of intense anxiety or panic that are directly caused by a physical health problem. Generalized anxiety disorder includes persistent and excessive anxiety and worry about activity or event — even ordinary, routine issues. The worry is out of proportion to the actual circumstance, is difficult to control and affect how you feel physically. It often occurs along with other anxiety disorder or depression. Panic disorder involves repeated episode of sudden feeling of intense anxiety and fear or terror that reach a peak within minute (panic attacks). You may have feeling of impending doom, shortness of breath, chest pain, or a rapid, fluttering or pounding heart (heart palpitations). These panic attack may lead to worrying about them happening again or avoiding situation in which they've occurred. Selective mutism is a consistent failure of child to speak in certain situations, such a school, even when they can speak in other situations, such a at home with close family members. This can interfere with school, work and social functioning. Separation anxiety disorder is a childhood disorder characterized by anxiety that's excessive for the child's developmental level and related to separation from parent or others who have parental roles. Social anxiety disorder (social phobia) involves high level of anxiety, fear and avoidance of social situation due to feeling of embarrassment, self-consciousness and concern about being judged or viewed negatively by others. Specific phobia are characterized by major anxiety when you're exposed to a specific object or situation and a desire to avoid it. Phobias provoke panic attack in some people. Substance-induced anxiety disorder is characterized by symptom of intense anxiety or panic that are a direct result of misusing drugs, taking medications, being exposed to a toxic substance or withdrawal from drugs. Other specified anxiety disorder and unspecified anxiety disorder are term for anxiety or phobia that don't meet the exact criterion for any other anxiety disorder but are significant enough to be distressing and disruptive.

As the disease progresses, symptom often spread to the wrists, knees, ankles, elbows, hip and shoulders. In most cases, symptom occur in the same joint on both side of your body. About 40% of people who have rheumatoid arthritis also experience sign and symptom that don't involve the joints. Areas that may be affected include: Skin Eyes Lungs Heart Kidneys Salivary gland Nerve tissue Bone marrow Blood vessel Rheumatoid arthritis sign and symptom may vary in severity and may even come and go. Periods of increased disease activity, called flares, alternate with period of relative remission — when the swelling and pain fade or disappear. Over time, rheumatoid arthritis can cause joint to deform and shift out of place.

Plague is divided into three main type — bubonic, septicemic and pneumonic — depending on which part of your body is involved. Signs and symptom vary depending on the type of plague. Bubonic plague Bubonic plague is the most common variety of the disease. It's named after the swollen lymph node (buboes) that typically develop in the first week after you become infected. Buboes may be: Situated in the groin, armpit or neck About the size of a chicken egg Tender and firm to the touch Other bubonic plague sign and symptom may include: Sudden onset of fever and chill Headache Fatigue or malaise Muscle ache Septicemic plague Septicemic plague occurs when plague bacteria multiply in your bloodstream. Signs and symptom include: Fever and chill Extreme weakness Abdominal pain, diarrhea and vomiting Bleeding from your mouth, nose or rectum, or under your skin Shock Blackening and death of tissue (gangrene) in your extremities, most commonly your fingers, toe and nose Pneumonic plague Pneumonic plague affect the lungs. It's the least common variety of plague but the most dangerous, because it can be spread from person to person via cough droplets. Signs and symptom can begin within a few hour after infection, and may include: Cough, with bloody mucus (sputum) Difficulty breathing Nausea and vomiting High fever Headache Weakness Chest pain Pneumonic plague progress rapidly and may cause respiratory failure and shock within two day of infection. Pneumonic plague need to be treated with antibiotic within a day after sign and symptom first appear, or the infection is likely to be fatal.

Signs and symptom of hemophilia vary, depending on your level of clotting factors. If your clotting-factor level is mildly reduced, you might bleed only after surgery or trauma. If your deficiency is severe, you can bleed easily for seemingly no reason. Signs and symptom of spontaneous bleeding include: Unexplained and excessive bleeding from cut or injuries, or after surgery or dental work Many large or deep bruise Unusual bleeding after vaccination Pain, swelling or tightness in your joint Blood in your urine or stool Nosebleeds without a known cause In infants, unexplained irritability Bleeding into the brain A simple bump on the head can cause bleeding into the brain for some people who have severe hemophilia. This rarely happens, but it's one of the most serious complication that can occur. Signs and symptom include: Painful, prolonged headache Repeated vomiting Sleepiness or lethargy Double vision Sudden weakness or clumsiness Convulsions or seizure

Priapism symptom vary depending on the type of priapism. The two main type of priapism are ischemic priapism and nonischemic priapism. Ischemic priapism Ischemic priapism, also called low-flow priapism, is the result of blood not being able to leave the penis. Blood is trapped in the penis because it cannot flow out of the vein of the penis or there is a problem with the contraction of smooth muscle within the erectile tissue of the penis. Ischemic priapism is the more common type of priapism and requires immediate medical care to prevent complication caused by not getting enough oxygen to the penile tissue. Signs and symptom include: Erection lasting more than four hour or unrelated to sexual interest or stimulation Rigid penile shaft, but the tip of penis (glans) is soft Progressively worsening penile pain Stuttering priapism — also called recurrent or intermittent priapism — is a form of ischemic priapism. An uncommon condition, stuttering priapism describes repetitive episode of prolonged erection and often includes episode of ischemic priapism. It occurs more often in male who have an inherited disorder characterized by abnormally shaped red blood cell (sickle cell disease). Sickle cell can block the blood vessel in the penis. In some cases, the condition start off with unwanted and painful erection of short duration and might progress over time to more-frequent and more-prolonged erections. Stuttering priapism may begin in childhood. Nonischemic priapism Nonischemic priapism, also known a high-flow priapism, occurs when blood flow through the artery of the penis isn't working properly. However, the penile tissue continue to receive some blood flow and oxygen. Nonischemic priapism often occurs due to trauma. Signs and symptom include: Erection lasting more than four hour or unrelated to sexual interest or stimulation Erect but not fully rigid penile shaft Usually not painful

In most cases, seasonal affective disorder symptom appear during late fall or early winter and go away during the sunnier day of spring and summer. Less commonly, people with the opposite pattern have symptom that begin in spring or summer. In either case, symptom may start out mild and become more severe a the season progresses. Signs and symptom of SAD may include: SAD Feeling listless, sad or down most of the day, nearly every day Losing interest in activity you once enjoyed Having low energy and feeling sluggish Having problem with sleeping too much Experiencing carbohydrate cravings, overeating and weight gain Having difficulty concentrating Feeling hopeless, worthless or guilty Having thought of not wanting to live Fall and winter SAD Symptoms specific to winter-onset SAD, sometimes called winter depression, may include: SAD Oversleeping Appetite changes, especially a craving for food high in carbohydrate Weight gain Tiredness or low energy Spring and summer SAD Symptoms specific to summer-onset seasonal affective disorder, sometimes called summer depression, may include: Trouble sleeping (insomnia) Poor appetite Weight loss Agitation or anxiety Increased irritability Seasonal change and bipolar disorder People who have bipolar disorder are at increased risk of seasonal affective disorder. In some people with bipolar disorder, episode of mania may be linked to a specific season. For example, spring and summer can bring on symptom of mania or a le intense form of mania (hypomania), anxiety, agitation and irritability. They may also experience depression during the fall and winter months.

The sign and symptom of dermatomyositis can appear suddenly or develop gradually over time. The most common sign and symptom include: Skin changes. A violet-colored or dusky red rash develops, most commonly on your face and eyelid and on your knuckles, elbows, knees, chest and back. The rash, which can be itchy and painful, is often the first sign of dermatomyositis. Muscle weakness. Progressive muscle weakness involves the muscle closest to the trunk, such a those in your hips, thighs, shoulders, upper arm and neck. The weakness affect both the left and right side of your body, and tends to gradually worsen.

Signs of dyslexia can be difficult to recognize before your child enters school, but some early clue may indicate a problem. Some common dyslexia symptom in teen and adult include: Difficulty reading, including reading aloud Slow and labor-intensive reading and writing Problems spelling Avoiding activity that involve reading Mispronouncing name or words, or problem retrieving word Spending an unusually long time completing task that involve reading or writing Difficulty summarizing a story Trouble learning a foreign language Difficulty doing math word problem

Signs and symptom of penicillin allergy often occur within an hour after taking the drug. Less commonly, reaction can occur hours, day or week later. Penicillin allergy sign and symptom may include: Skin rash Hives Itching Fever Swelling Shortness of breath Wheezing Runny nose Itchy, watery eye Anaphylaxis Anaphylaxis Anaphylaxis is a rare, life-threatening allergic reaction that cause the widespread dysfunction of body systems. Signs and symptom of anaphylaxis include: Tightening of the airway and throat, causing trouble breathing Nausea or abdominal cramp Vomiting or diarrhea Dizziness or lightheadedness Weak, rapid pulse Drop in blood pressure Seizures Loss of consciousness Delayed reaction resulting from penicillin allergy Less-common penicillin allergy reaction occur day or week after exposure to the drug and may persist for some time after you stop taking it. These condition include: Serum sickness, which may cause fever, joint pain, rash, swelling and nausea Drug-induced anemia, a reduction in red blood cells, which can cause fatigue, irregular heartbeats, shortness of breath, and other sign and symptom Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptom (DRESS), which result in rash, high white blood cell counts, general swelling, swollen lymph node and recurrence of dormant hepatitis infection Stevens-Johnson syndrome or toxic epidermal necrolysis, which involves severe blistering and peeling of the skin Inflammation in the kidney (nephritis), which can cause fever, blood in the urine, general swelling, confusion, and other sign and symptom Adverse event that are not allergic reaction You may experience side effect of penicillin — a happens with other medication — that are not an allergic reaction to the drug. Depending on the type of penicillin, common side effect may include mild nausea or diarrhea, headache, or vaginal itching. Signs or symptom of an infection for which you are being treated — or unrelated symptom — also may be mistaken a an allergic drug reaction.

Yellowing of the skin and the white of the eye — the main sign of infant jaundice — usually appears between the second and fourth day after birth. To check for infant jaundice, press gently on your baby's forehead or nose. If the skin look yellow where you pressed, it's likely your baby ha mild jaundice. If your baby doesn't have jaundice, the skin color should simply look slightly lighter than it normal color for a moment. Examine your baby in good lighting conditions, preferably in natural daylight.

The sign and symptom of HUS may vary, depending on the cause. Most case of HUS are caused by infection with certain strain of E. coli bacteria, which first affect the digestive tract. The initial sign and symptom of this form of HUS may include: HUS HUS HUS Diarrhea, which is often bloody Abdominal pain, cramping or bloating Vomiting Fever All form of HUS — no matter the cause — damage the blood vessels. This damage cause red blood cell to break down (anemia), blood clot to form in the blood vessel and kidney damage. Signs and symptom of these change include: HUS Pale coloring, including loss of pink color in cheek and inside the lower eyelid Extreme fatigue Shortness of breath Easy bruising or unexplained bruise Unusual bleeding, such a bleeding from the nose and mouth Decreased urination or blood in the urine Swelling (edema) of the legs, foot or ankles, and le often in the face, hands, foot or entire body Confusion, seizure or stroke High blood pressure When to see a doctor See your doctor immediately if you or your child experience bloody diarrhea or several day of diarrhea followed by: Decreased urine output Swelling Unexplained bruise Unusual bleeding Extreme fatigue Seek emergency care if you or your child doesn't urinate for 12 hour or more.

Milk allergy symptoms, which differ from person to person, occur a few minute to a few hour after you or your child drink milk or eats milk products. Immediate sign and symptom of milk allergy might include: Hives Wheezing Itching or tingling feeling around the lip or mouth Swelling of the lips, tongue or throat Coughing or shortness of breath Vomiting Signs and symptom that may take more time to develop include: Loose stool or diarrhea, which may contain blood Abdominal cramp Runny nose Watery eye Colic, in baby Milk allergy or milk intolerance? A true milk allergy differs from milk protein intolerance and lactose intolerance. Unlike milk allergy, intolerance doesn't involve the immune system. Milk intolerance requires different treatment from true milk allergy. Common sign and symptom of milk protein intolerance or lactose intolerance include digestive problems, such a bloating, gas or diarrhea, after consuming milk or product containing milk. Anaphylaxis Milk allergy can cause anaphylaxis, a life-threatening reaction that narrow the airway and can block breathing. Milk is the third most common food — after peanut and tree nut — to cause anaphylaxis. If you or your child ha a reaction to milk, tell your health care provider, no matter how mild the reaction. Tests can help confirm milk allergy, so you can avoid future and potentially worse reactions. Anaphylaxis is a medical emergency and requires treatment with an epinephrine (adrenaline) shot (EpiPen, Adrenaclick, others) and a trip to the emergency room. Signs and symptom start soon after milk consumption and can include: Constriction of airways, including a swollen throat that make it difficult to breathe Facial flushing Itching Shock, with a marked drop in blood pressure

Primary progressive aphasia symptom vary, depending on which portion of the brain's language area are involved. The condition ha three types, which cause different symptoms. Semantic variant primary progressive aphasia Signs and symptom include: Difficulty comprehending spoken or written language, particularly single word Trouble comprehending word meaning Struggling to name object Logopenic variant primary progressive aphasia Signs and symptom include: Difficulty retrieving word and word substitution Frequently pausing in speech while searching for word Difficulty repeating phrase or sentence Nonfluent-agrammatic variant primary progressive aphasia Signs and symptom include: Poor grammar in written and spoken form Trouble understanding complex sentence Using grammar incorrectly May be accompanied by speaking problem such a error in speech sound (known a apraxia of speech) Causes Primary progressive aphasia is caused by a shrinking (atrophy) of certain section (lobes) of the brain responsible for speech and language. In this case, the frontal, temporal or parietal lobes, primarily on the left side of the brain, are affected. Atrophy is associated with the presence of abnormal proteins, and brain activity or function in affected area might be reduced. Risk factor Risk factor for primary progressive aphasia include: Learning disabilities. If you had a childhood learning disability, particularly developmental dyslexia, you might be at somewhat higher risk of primary progressive aphasia. Certain gene mutations. Rare gene mutation have been linked to the disorder. If other member of your family have had primary progressive aphasia, you might be more likely to develop it. Complications People with primary progressive aphasia eventually lose the ability to speak and write, and to understand written and spoken language. Some people develop substantial difficulty forming sound to speak (a problem called apraxia of speech), even when their ability to write and comprehend are not significantly impaired. As the disease progresses, other mental skills, such a memory, can become impaired. Some people develop other neurological symptom such a problem with movement. With these complications, the affected person eventually will need help with day-to-day care. People with primary progressive aphasia can also develop depression or behavioral or social problem a the disease progresses. Other problem might include blunted emotion such a unconcern, poor judgment or inappropriate social behavior. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Primary progressive aphasia care at Mayo Clinic

Most sacral dimple are small and shallow. A sacral dimple is an indentation or pit in the skin on the lower back. It's usually located just above the crease between the buttocks. Causes There are no known cause for a sacral dimple. It is a congenital condition, meaning it's present at birth. Complications Rarely, sacral dimple are associated with a serious underlying abnormality of the spine or spinal cord. Examples include: Spina bifida. A very mild form of this condition, called spina bifida occulta, occurs when the spine doesn't close properly around the spinal cord, but the cord remains within the spinal canal. In most cases, spina bifida occulta cause no symptom and doesn't need treatment. Tethered cord syndrome. The spinal cord normally hang freely within the spinal canal. Tethered cord syndrome is a disorder that occurs when tissue attached to the spinal cord limit it movements. Signs and symptom may include weakness or numbness in the leg and bladder or bowel incontinence. A common sign of acromegaly is enlarged hand and feet. For example, you may notice that you aren't able to put on ring that used to fit, and that your shoe size ha progressively increased. Acromegaly may also cause gradual change in your face's shape, such a a protruding lower jaw and brow bone, an enlarged nose, thickened lips, and wider spacing between your teeth. Because acromegaly tends to progress slowly, early sign may not be obvious for years. Sometimes, people notice the physical change only by comparing old photo with newer ones. Overall, acromegaly sign and symptom tend to vary from one person to another, and may include any of the following: Enlarged hand and foot Enlarged facial features, including the facial bones, lips, nose and tongue Coarse, oily, thickened skin Excessive sweating and body odor Small outgrowth of skin tissue (skin tags) Fatigue and joint or muscle weakness Pain and limited joint mobility A deepened, husky voice due to enlarged vocal cord and sinus Severe snoring due to obstruction of the upper airway Vision problem Headaches, which may be persistent or severe Menstrual cycle irregularity in woman Erectile dysfunction in men Loss of interest in sex

Kleptomania symptom may include: Inability to resist powerful urge to steal item that you don't need Feeling increased tension, anxiety or arousal leading up to the theft Feeling pleasure, relief or satisfaction while stealing Feeling terrible guilt, remorse, self-loathing, shame or fear of arrest after the theft Return of the urge and a repetition of the kleptomania cycle Features People with kleptomania usually have these feature or characteristics: Unlike most shoplifters, people with kleptomania don't compulsively steal for personal gain, on a dare, for revenge or out of rebellion. They steal simply because the urge is so powerful that they can't resist it. Episodes of kleptomania generally happen suddenly, without planning and without help from another person. Most people with kleptomania steal from public places, such a stores. Some may steal from friend or acquaintances, such a at a party. Often, the stolen item have no value to the person with kleptomania, and the person can afford to buy them. The stolen item are usually stashed away, never to be used. Items also may be donated, given away to family or friends, or even secretly returned to the place from which they were stolen. Urges to steal may come and go or may occur with greater or lesser intensity over the course of time.

Signs and symptom of adrenal cancer include: Weight gain Muscle weakness Pink or purple stretch mark on the skin Hormone change in woman that might cause excess facial hair, hair loss on the head and irregular period Hormone change in men that might cause enlarged breast tissue and shrinking testicle Nausea Vomiting Abdominal bloating Back pain Fever Loss of appetite Loss of weight without trying Causes It's not clear what cause adrenal cancer. Adrenal cancer form when something creates change (mutations) in the DNA of an adrenal gland cell. A cell's DNA contains the instruction that tell a cell what to do. The mutation can tell the cell to multiply uncontrollably and to continue living when healthy cell would die. When this happens, the abnormal cell accumulate and form a tumor. The tumor cell can break away and spread (metastasize) to other part of the body. Risk factor Adrenal cancer happens more often in people with inherited syndrome that increase the risk of certain cancers. These inherited syndrome include: Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome Carney complex Li-Fraumeni syndrome Lynch syndrome Multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 1 (MEN 1) By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Adrenal cancer care at Mayo Clinic

Symptoms of PCOS often start around the time of the first menstrual period. Sometimes symptom develop later after you have had period for a while. PCOS The symptom of PCOS vary. A diagnosis of PCOS is made when you have at least two of these: PCOS PCOS Irregular periods. Having few menstrual period or having period that aren't regular are common sign of PCOS. The blister associated with dyshidrosis occur most commonly on the side of the finger and the palms. Sometimes the sol of the foot also can be affected. The blister are usually small — about the width of a standard pencil lead — and grouped in clusters, with an appearance similar to tapioca. Most people exposed to the cholera bacterium (Vibrio cholerae) don't become ill and don't know they've been infected. But because they shed cholera bacteria in their stool for seven to 14 days, they can still infect others through contaminated water. Most case of cholera that cause symptom cause mild or moderate diarrhea that's often hard to tell apart from diarrhea caused by other problems. Others develop more-serious sign and symptom of cholera, usually within a few day of infection. Symptoms of cholera infection can include: Diarrhea. Cholera-related diarrhea come on suddenly and can quickly cause dangerous fluid loss — a much a a quart (about 1 liter) an hour. Diarrhea due to cholera often ha a pale, milky appearance that resembles water in which rice ha been rinsed. Nausea and vomiting. Vomiting occurs especially in the early stage of cholera and can last for hours. Dehydration. Dehydration can develop within hour after cholera symptom start and range from mild to severe. A loss of 10% or more of body weight indicates severe dehydration. Signs and symptom of cholera dehydration include irritability, fatigue, sunken eyes, a dry mouth, extreme thirst, dry and shriveled skin that's slow to bounce back when pinched into a fold, little or no urinating, low blood pressure, and an irregular heartbeat. Dehydration can lead to a rapid loss of mineral in your blood that maintain the balance of fluid in your body. This is called an electrolyte imbalance. Electrolyte imbalance An electrolyte imbalance can lead to serious sign and symptom such as: Muscle cramps. These result from the rapid loss of salt such a sodium, chloride and potassium. Shock. This is one of the most serious complication of dehydration. It occurs when low blood volume cause a drop in blood pressure and a drop in the amount of oxygen in your body. If untreated, severe hypovolemic shock can cause death in minutes.

This melanoma show color variation and an irregular border, both of which are melanoma warning signs. Melanomas can develop anywhere on your body. They most often develop in area that have had exposure to the sun, such a your back, legs, arm and face. Melanomas can also occur in area that don't receive much sun exposure, such a the sol of your feet, palm of your hand and fingernail beds. These hidden melanoma are more common in people with darker skin. The first melanoma sign and symptom often are: A change in an existing mole The development of a new pigmented or unusual-looking growth on your skin Melanoma doesn't always begin a a mole. It can also occur on otherwise normal-appearing skin. Normal mole Normal mole are generally a uniform color — such a tan, brown or black — with a distinct border separating the mole from your surrounding skin. They're oval or round and usually smaller than 1/4 inch (about 6 millimeters) in diameter — the size of a pencil eraser. Most mole begin appearing in childhood and new mole may form until about age 40. By the time they are adults, most people have between 10 and 40 moles. Moles may change in appearance over time and some may even disappear with age. Unusual mole that may indicate melanoma To help you identify characteristic of unusual mole that may indicate melanoma or other skin cancers, think of the letter ABCDE: A is for asymmetrical shape. Look for mole with irregular shapes, such a two very different-looking halves. B is for irregular border. Look for mole with irregular, notched or scalloped border — characteristic of melanomas. C is for change in color. Look for growth that have many color or an uneven distribution of color. D is for diameter. Look for new growth in a mole larger than 1/4 inch (about 6 millimeters). E is for evolving. Look for change over time, such a a mole that grows in size or that change color or shape. Moles may also evolve to develop new sign and symptoms, such a new itchiness or bleeding. Cancerous (malignant) mole vary greatly in appearance. Some may show all of the change listed above, while others may have only one or two unusual characteristics. Hidden melanoma Melanomas can also develop in area of your body that have little or no exposure to the sun, such a the space between your toe and on your palms, soles, scalp or genitals. These are sometimes referred to a hidden melanoma because they occur in place most people wouldn't think to check. When melanoma occurs in people with darker skin, it's more likely to occur in a hidden area. Hidden melanoma include: Melanoma under a nail. Acral-lentiginous melanoma is a rare form of melanoma that can occur under a fingernail or toenail. It can also be found on the palm of the hand or the sol of the feet. It's more common in people of Asian descent, black people and in others with dark skin pigment. Melanoma in the mouth, digestive tract, urinary tract or vagina. Mucosal melanoma develops in the mucous membrane that line the nose, mouth, esophagus, anus, urinary tract and vagina. Mucosal melanoma are especially difficult to detect because they can easily be mistaken for other far more common conditions. Melanoma in the eye. Eye melanoma, also called ocular melanoma, most often occurs in the uvea — the layer beneath the white of the eye (sclera). An eye melanoma may cause vision change and may be diagnosed during an eye exam.

During prenatal visits, your health care provider might measure your fundal height — the distance from the top of your uterus to your pubic bone. A larger than expected fundal height could be a sign of fetal macrosomia. Excessive amniotic fluid (polyhydramnios). Having too much amniotic fluid — the fluid that surround and protects a baby during pregnancy — might be a sign that your baby is larger than average. The amount of amniotic fluid reflects your baby's urine output, and a larger baby produce more urine. Some condition that cause a baby to be larger might also increase his or her urine output.

They can appear on the genitals, in the pubic area or in the anal canal. In most cases, your body's immune system defeat an HPV infection before it creates warts. When wart do appear, they vary in appearance depending on which kind of HPV is involved: HPV HPV Genital warts. These appear a flat lesions, small cauliflower-like bump or tiny stemlike protrusions. In women, genital wart appear mostly on the vulva but can also occur near the anus, on the cervix or in the vagina. In men, genital wart appear on the penis and scrotum or around the anus. Genital wart rarely cause discomfort or pain, though they may itch or feel tender. Common warts. Common wart appear a rough, raised bump and usually occur on the hand and fingers. In most cases, common wart are simply unsightly, but they can also be painful or susceptible to injury or bleeding. Plantar warts. Plantar wart are hard, grainy growth that usually appear on the heel or ball of your feet. These wart might cause discomfort. Flat warts. Flat wart are flat-topped, slightly raised lesions. They can appear anywhere, but child usually get them on the face and men tend to get them in the beard area. Women tend to get them on the legs. Cervical cancer Nearly all cervical cancer are caused by HPV infections, but cervical cancer may take 20 year or longer to develop after an HPV infection. The HPV infection and early cervical cancer typically don't cause noticeable symptoms. Getting vaccinated against HPV infection is your best protection from cervical cancer. HPV HPV HPV HPV Because early cervical cancer doesn't cause symptoms, it's vital that woman have regular screening test to detect any precancerous change in the cervix that might lead to cancer. Current guideline recommend that woman age 21 to 29 have a Pap test every three years. Women age 30 to 65 are advised to continue having a Pap test every three years, or every five year if they also get the HPV DNA test at the same time. Women over 65 can stop testing if they've had three normal Pap test in a row, or two HPV DNA and Pap test with no abnormal results.

The most common sign of Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome is a heart rate greater than 100 beat a minute. Episodes of a fast heart rate (tachycardia) can begin suddenly and may last a few second or several hours. Episodes can occur during exercise or while at rest. Other sign and symptom of WPW syndrome are related to the fast heart rate and underlying heart rhythm problem (arrhythmia). The most common arrhythmia seen with WPW syndrome is supraventricular tachycardia. Supraventricular tachycardia cause episode of a fast, pounding heartbeat that begin and end abruptly. Some people with WPW syndrome also have a fast and chaotic heart rhythm problem called atrial fibrillation. WPW WPW WPW In general, sign and symptom that may occur in people with WPW syndrome include: WPW A rapid, fluttering or pounding heartbeat (palpitations) Chest pain Difficulty breathing Dizziness or lightheadedness Fainting Fatigue Shortness of breath Anxiety Symptoms in infant Signs and symptom of WPW syndrome in infant can include: WPW Pale or faded skin color (pallor) Blue or gray coloring to the skin, lip and nail (cyanosis) Restlessness or irritability Rapid breathing Poor eating Some people with an extra electrical pathway don't have sign or symptom of a fast heartbeat. This condition is called Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) pattern. It's often discovered by chance during a heart test.

Symptoms of endocarditis can vary from person to person. Endocarditis may develop slowly or suddenly. It depends on the type of germ causing the infection and whether there are other heart problems. Common symptom of endocarditis include: Aching joint and muscle Chest pain when you breathe Fatigue Flu-like symptoms, such a fever and chill Night sweat Shortness of breath Swelling in the feet, leg or belly A new or changed whooshing sound in the heart (murmur) Less common endocarditis symptom can include: Unexplained weight loss Blood in the urine Tenderness under the left rib cage (spleen) Painless red, purple or brown flat spot on the sol bottom of the foot or the palm of the hand (Janeway lesions) Painful red or purple bump or patch of darkened skin (hyperpigmented) on the tip of the finger or toe (Osler nodes) Tiny purple, red or brown round spot on the skin (petechiae), in the white of the eye or inside the mouth

Signs and symptom of acoustic neuroma are often easy to miss and may take many year to develop. They usually happen because of the tumor's effect on the hearing and balance nerves. Pressure from the tumor on nearby nerve controlling facial muscle and sensation (facial and trigeminal nerves), nearby blood vessels, or brain structure may also cause problems. As the tumor grows, it may cause more noticeable or severe sign and symptoms. Common sign and symptom of acoustic neuroma include: Hearing loss, usually gradually worsening over month to year — although in rare case sudden — and occurring on only one side or more severe on one side Ringing (tinnitus) in the affected ear Unsteadiness or loss of balance Dizziness (vertigo) Facial numbness and weakness or loss of muscle movement In rare cases, an acoustic neuroma may grow large enough to compress the brainstem and become life-threatening. When to see your doctor See your doctor if you notice hearing loss in one ear, ringing in your ear or trouble with your balance. Early diagnosis of an acoustic neuroma may help keep the tumor from growing large enough to cause serious consequences, such a total hearing loss.

Signs and symptom of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease may include: Weakness in your legs, ankle and foot Loss of muscle bulk in your leg and foot High foot arch Curled toe (hammertoes) Decreased ability to run Difficulty lifting your foot at the ankle (footdrop) Awkward or higher than normal step (gait) Frequent tripping or falling Decreased sensation or a loss of feeling in your leg and foot As Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease progresses, symptom may spread from the foot and leg to the hand and arms. The severity of symptom can vary greatly from person to person, even among family members. Causes Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is an inherited, genetic condition. It occurs when there are mutation in the gene that affect the nerve in your feet, legs, hand and arms. Sometimes, these mutation damage the nerves. Other mutation damage the protective coating that surround the nerve (myelin sheath). Both cause weaker message to travel between your limb and brain. Risk factor Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is hereditary, so you're at higher risk of developing the disorder if anyone in your immediate family ha the disease. Other cause of neuropathies, such a diabetes, may cause symptom similar to Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease. These other condition can also cause the symptom of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease to become worse. Medications such a the chemotherapy drug vincristine (Marqibo), paclitaxel (Abraxane) and others can make symptom worse. Be sure to let your doctor know about all of the medication you're taking. Complications Complications of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease vary in severity from person to person. Foot abnormality and difficulty walking are usually the most serious problems. Muscles may get weaker, and you may injure area of the body that experience decreased sensation. Sometimes the muscle in your foot may not receive your brain's signal to contract, so you're more likely to trip and fall. And your brain may not receive pain message from your feet, so if you've rubbed a blister on your toe, for example, it may get infected without your realizing it. You may also experience difficulty breathing, swallowing or speaking if the muscle that control these function are affected by Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease. Persistent depressive disorder symptom usually come and go over a period of years. The intensity of symptom can change over time. But symptom usually don't disappear for more than two month at a time. Also, major depression episode may occur before or during persistent depressive disorder. Symptoms of persistent depressive disorder can cause major problem in your life and may include: Sadness, emptiness or feeling down. Loss of interest in daily activities. Tiredness and lack of energy. Low self-esteem, self-criticism or feeling you're not capable. Trouble focusing clearly and trouble making decisions. Problems getting thing done well and on time. Quickly becoming annoyed, impatient or angry. Avoidance of social activities. Feelings of guilt and worry over the past. Poor appetite or overeating. Sleep problems. Hopelessness. In children, symptom of persistent depressive disorder may include depressed mood and being irritable, which mean easily becoming annoyed, impatient or angry.

Most septal displacement result in no symptoms, and you may not even know you have a deviated septum. Some septal deformities, however, may cause the following sign and symptoms: Obstruction of one or both nostrils. This blockage can make it difficult to breathe through the nostril or nostrils. You may notice this more when you have a cold or allergy that can cause your nasal passage to swell and narrow. Nosebleeds. The surface of your nasal septum may become dry, increasing your risk of nosebleeds. Facial pain. There is some debate about the possible nasal cause of facial pain. A possible cause of one-sided facial pain could be a severe deviated septum in which surface within the nose touch and cause pressure. Noisy breathing during sleep. A deviated septum or swelling of the tissue in your nose can be one of the many reason for noisy breathing during sleep. Awareness of the nasal cycle. The nose alternate between being obstructed on one side and then change to being obstructed on the other. This is called the nasal cycle. Being aware of the nasal cycle isn't typical and can indicate nasal obstruction. Preference for sleeping on a particular side. Some people may prefer to sleep on a particular side to optimize breathing through the nose at night if one nasal passage is narrowed.

A mold allergy cause the same sign and symptom that occur in other type of upper respiratory allergies. Signs and symptom of allergic rhinitis caused by a mold allergy can include: Sneezing Runny or stuffy nose Cough and postnasal drip Itchy eyes, nose and throat Watery eye Dry, scaly skin Mold allergy symptom vary from person to person and range from mild to severe. You might have year-round symptom or symptom that flare up only during certain time of the year. You might notice symptom when the weather is damp or when you're in indoor or outdoor space that have high concentration of mold. Mold allergy and asthma If you have a mold allergy and asthma, your asthma symptom can be triggered by exposure to mold spores. In some people, exposure to certain mold can cause a severe asthma attack. Signs and symptom of asthma include: Coughing Wheezing Shortness of breath Chest tightness

There are many different type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, but the most common sign and symptom include: Overly flexible joints. Because the connective tissue that hold joint together is looser, your joint can move far past the normal range of motion. Joint pain and dislocation are common. Stretchy skin. Weakened connective tissue allows your skin to stretch much more than usual. You may be able to pull a pinch of skin up away from your flesh, but it will snap right back into place when you let go. Your skin might also feel exceptionally soft and velvety. Fragile skin. Damaged skin often doesn't heal well. For example, the stitch used to close a wound often will tear out and leave a gaping scar. These scar may look thin and crinkly. Symptom severity can vary from person to person and depends on the specific type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that you have. The most common type is called hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. Vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome People who have vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome often share distinctive facial feature of a thin nose, thin upper lip, small earlobe and prominent eyes. They also have thin, translucent skin that bruise very easily. In fair-skinned people, the underlying blood vessel are very visible through the skin. Vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome can weaken your heart's largest artery (aorta), a well a the artery to other region of your body. A rupture of any of these larger blood vessel can be fatal. The vascular type can also weaken the wall of the uterus or large intestine — which also may rupture. Causes Different type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome are associated with a variety of genetic causes, some of which are inherited and passed on from parent to child. If you have the most common form, hypermobile Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, there's a 50% chance that you'll pas on the gene to each of your children. Complications Complications depend on the type of sign and symptom you have. For example, overly flexible joint can result in joint dislocation and early-onset arthritis. Fragile skin may develop prominent scarring. People who have vascular Ehlers-Danlos syndrome are at risk of often fatal rupture of major blood vessels. Some organs, such a the uterus and intestines, also may rupture. Pregnancy can increase the risk of a rupture in the uterus. Prevention If you have a personal or family history of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and you're thinking about starting a family, you may benefit from talking to a genetic counselor — a health care professional trained to ass the risk of inherited disorders. Genetic counseling can help you understand the inheritance pattern of the type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that affect you and the risk it pose for your children. In infants, the rash is mainly found on the neck, shoulder and chest. It can also show up in the armpits, elbow crease and groin. Types of heat rash The type of heat rash are classified according to how deep the sweat is trapped in the skin. Signs and symptom for each type vary. The mildest form of heat rash is called miliaria crystallina. It occurs when the opening of the sweat duct on the surface of the skin (sweat pore) is blocked. This form is marked by tiny, clear, fluid-filled bump that break easily. A type that occurs deeper in the skin is called miliaria rubra. It is sometimes called prickly heat. Signs and symptom include small, inflamed blister-like bump and itching or prickling in the affected area. Occasionally, the inflamed bump of miliaria rubra fill with pus. This form is called miliaria pustulosa. A le common form of heat rash is called miliaria profunda. It affect the deepest layer of the skin (dermis). It cause firm, painful or itchy inflamed bump that look like goose bump and may break open.
