Usually, a child having a febrile seizure shake all over and loses consciousness. Sometimes, the child may get very stiff or twitch in just one area of the body. A child having a febrile seizure may: Have a fever higher than 100.4 F (38.0 C) Lose consciousness Shake or jerk the arm and leg Febrile seizure are classified a simple or complex: Simple febrile seizures. This most common type last from a few second to 15 minutes. Simple febrile seizure do not recur within a 24-hour period and are not specific to one part of the body. Complex febrile seizures. This type last longer than 15 minutes, occurs more than once within 24 hour or is confined to one side of your child's body. Febrile seizure most often occur within 24 hour of the onset of a fever and can be the first sign that a child is ill.

Symptoms of porphyria can vary widely in severity, by type and among individuals. Some people with the gene mutation that cause porphyria never have any symptoms. Acute porphyria Acute porphyria include form of the disease that typically cause nervous system symptoms, which appear quickly and can be severe. Symptoms may last day to week and usually improve slowly after the attack. Acute intermittent porphyria is the common form of acute porphyria. Signs and symptom of acute porphyria may include: Severe abdominal pain Pain in your chest, leg or back Constipation or diarrhea Nausea and vomiting Muscle pain, tingling, numbness, weakness or paralysis Red or brown urine Mental changes, such a anxiety, confusion, hallucinations, disorientation or paranoia Breathing problem Urination problem Rapid or irregular heartbeat you can feel (palpitations) High blood pressure Seizures Cutaneous porphyria Cutaneous porphyria include form of the disease that cause skin symptom a a result of sensitivity to sunlight, but these form don't usually affect your nervous system. Porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT) is the most common type of all the porphyrias. As a result of sun exposure, you may experience: Sensitivity to the sun and sometimes artificial light, causing burning pain Sudden painful skin redness (erythema) and swelling (edema Blisters on exposed skin, usually the hands, arm and face Fragile thin skin with change in skin color (pigment) Itching Excessive hair growth in affected area Red or brown urine

The sign and symptom of celiac disease can vary greatly and differ in child and adults. Digestive sign and symptom for adult include: Diarrhea Fatigue Weight loss Bloating and gas Abdominal pain Nausea and vomiting Constipation However, more than half the adult with celiac disease have sign and symptom unrelated to the digestive system, including: Anemia, usually from iron deficiency Loss of bone density (osteoporosis) or softening of bone (osteomalacia) Itchy, blistery skin rash (dermatitis herpetiformis) Mouth ulcer Headaches and fatigue Nervous system injury, including numbness and tingling in the foot and hands, possible problem with balance, and cognitive impairment Joint pain Reduced functioning of the spleen (hyposplenism) Children Children with celiac disease are more likely than adult to have digestive problems, including: Nausea and vomiting Chronic diarrhea Swollen belly Constipation Gas Pale, foul-smelling stool The inability to absorb nutrient might result in: Failure to thrive for infant Damage to tooth enamel Weight loss Anemia Irritability Short stature Delayed puberty Neurological symptoms, including attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), learning disabilities, headaches, lack of muscle coordination and seizure Dermatitis herpetiformis Gluten intolerance can cause this itchy, blistering skin disease. The rash usually occurs on the elbows, knees, torso, scalp and buttocks. This condition is often associated with change to the lining of the small intestine identical to those of celiac disease, but the skin condition might not cause digestive symptoms. Doctors treat dermatitis herpetiformis with a gluten-free diet or medication, or both, to control the rash.

The most common sign and symptom of traveler's diarrhea are: Abrupt onset of passage of three or more looser watery stool a day An urgent need to defecate Abdominal cramp Nausea Vomiting Fever Sometimes, people experience moderate to severe dehydration, persistent vomiting, a high fever, bloody stools, or severe pain in the abdomen or rectum. If you or your child experience any of these sign or symptom or if the diarrhea last longer than a few days, it's time to see a doctor.

In the month or year leading up to menopause (perimenopause), you might experience these sign and symptoms: Irregular period Vaginal dryness Hot flash Chills Night sweat Sleep problem Mood change Weight gain and slowed metabolism Thinning hair and dry skin Loss of breast fullness Signs and symptoms, including change in menstruation can vary among women. Most likely, you'll experience some irregularity in your period before they end. Skipping period during perimenopause is common and expected. Often, menstrual period will skip a month and return, or skip several month and then start monthly cycle again for a few months. Periods also tend to happen on shorter cycles, so they are closer together. Despite irregular periods, pregnancy is possible. If you've skipped a period but aren't sure you've started the menopausal transition, consider a pregnancy test.

Leukoplakia usually occurs on your gums, the inside of your cheeks, the bottom of your mouth — beneath the tongue — and, sometimes, your tongue. It isn't usually painful and may go unnoticed for a while. Leukoplakia may appear: White or grayish in patch that can't be wiped away Irregular or flat-textured Thickened or hardened in area Along with raised, red lesion (speckled leukoplakia or erythroplakia), which are more likely to show precancerous change Hairy leukoplakia Hairy leukoplakia cause fuzzy, white patch that resemble fold or ridges, usually on the side of your tongue. It's often mistaken for oral thrush, an infection marked by creamy white patch that can be wiped away, which is also common in people with a weakened immune system. When to see a doctor Even though leukoplakia doesn't usually cause discomfort, sometimes it can indicate a more serious condition. See your dentist or primary care professional if you have any of the following: White plaque or sore in your mouth that don't heal on their own within two week Lumps or white, red or dark patch in your mouth Persistent change in the tissue of your mouth Ear pain when swallowing Progressive reduction in the ability to open your jaw

The defining feature of preeclampsia is high blood pressure, proteinuria, or other sign of damage to the kidney or other organs. You may have no noticeable symptoms. The first sign of preeclampsia are often detected during routine prenatal visit with a health care provider. Along with high blood pressure, preeclampsia sign and symptom may include: Excess protein in urine (proteinuria) or other sign of kidney problem Decreased level of platelet in blood (thrombocytopenia) Increased liver enzyme that indicate liver problem Severe headache Changes in vision, including temporary loss of vision, blurred vision or light sensitivity Shortness of breath, caused by fluid in the lung Pain in the upper belly, usually under the rib on the right side Nausea or vomiting Weight gain and swelling (edema) are typical during healthy pregnancies. However, sudden weight gain or a sudden appearance of edema — particularly in your face and hand — may be a sign of preeclampsia.

Signs and symptom of frontotemporal dementia can be different from one individual to the next. Signs and symptom get progressively worse over time, usually over years. Clusters of symptom type tend to occur together, and people may have more than one cluster of symptom types. Behavioral change The most common sign of frontotemporal dementia involve extreme change in behavior and personality. These include: Increasingly inappropriate social behavior Loss of empathy and other interpersonal skills, such a having sensitivity to another's feeling Lack of judgment Loss of inhibition Lack of interest (apathy), which can be mistaken for depression Repetitive compulsive behavior, such a tapping, clapping or smacking lip A decline in personal hygiene Changes in eating habits, usually overeating or developing a preference for sweet and carbohydrate Eating inedible object Compulsively wanting to put thing in the mouth Speech and language problem Some subtypes of frontotemporal dementia lead to language problem or impairment or loss of speech. Primary progressive aphasia, semantic dementia and progressive agrammatic (nonfluent) aphasia are all considered to be frontotemporal dementia. Problems caused by these condition include: Increasing difficulty in using and understanding written and spoken language, such a having trouble finding the right word to use in speech or naming object Trouble naming things, possibly replacing a specific word with a more general word such a "it" for pen No longer knowing word meaning Having hesitant speech that may sound telegraphic Making mistake in sentence construction Motor disorder Rarer subtypes of frontotemporal dementia are characterized by problem with movement similar to those associated with Parkinson's disease or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). Motor-related problem may include: Tremor Rigidity Muscle spasm or twitch Poor coordination Difficulty swallowing Muscle weakness Inappropriate laughing or cry Falls or walking problem Causes In frontotemporal dementia, the frontal and temporal lobe of the brain shrink. In addition, certain substance accumulate in the brain. What cause these change is usually unknown. There are genetic mutation that have been linked to frontotemporal dementia. But more than half of the people who develop frontotemporal dementia have no family history of dementia. Recently, researcher have confirmed shared genetics and molecular pathway between frontotemporal dementia and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). More research need to be done to understand the connection between these conditions, however. Risk factor Your risk of developing frontotemporal dementia is higher if you have a family history of dementia. There are no other known risk factors. Chest pain is the most common symptom of pericarditis. It usually feel sharp or stabbing. However, some people have dull, achy or pressure-like chest pain. Pericarditis pain usually occurs behind the breastbone or on the left side of the chest. The pain may: Spread to the left shoulder and neck Get worse when coughing, lying down or taking a deep breath Get better when sitting up or leaning forward Other sign and symptom of pericarditis may include: Cough Fatigue or general feeling of weakness or being sick Leg swelling Low-grade fever Pounding or racing heartbeat (heart palpitations) Shortness of breath when lying down Swelling of the belly (abdomen) The specific symptom depend on the type of pericarditis. Pericarditis is grouped into different categories, according to the pattern of symptom and how long symptom last. Acute pericarditis begin suddenly but doesn't last longer than three weeks. Future episode can occur. It may be difficult to tell the difference between acute pericarditis and pain due to a heart attack. Recurrent pericarditis occurs about four to six week after an episode of acute pericarditis with no symptom in between. Incessant pericarditis last about four to six week but le than three months. The symptom are continuous. Chronic constrictive pericarditis usually develops slowly and last longer than three months.

Egg allergy reaction vary from person to person and usually occur soon after exposure to egg. Egg allergy symptom can include: Skin inflammation or hive — the most common egg allergy reaction Nasal congestion, runny nose and sneezing (allergic rhinitis) Digestive symptoms, such a cramps, nausea and vomiting Asthma sign and symptom such a coughing, wheezing, chest tightness or shortness of breath Anaphylaxis A severe allergic reaction can lead to anaphylaxis, a life-threatening emergency that requires an immediate epinephrine (adrenaline) shot and a trip to the emergency room. Anaphylaxis sign and symptom include: Constriction of airways, including a swollen throat or a lump in your throat that make it difficult to breathe Abdominal pain and cramping Rapid pulse Shock, with a severe drop in blood pressure felt a dizziness, lightheadedness or loss of consciousness Discuss with your doctor any reaction — no matter how mild — you or your child ha to eggs. The severity of egg allergy reaction can vary each time one occurs, so even if a past reaction wa mild, the next one could be more serious. If your doctor think you or your child may be at risk of a severe reaction, he or she may prescribe an emergency epinephrine shot to be used if anaphylaxis occurs. The shot come in a device that make it easy to deliver, called an autoinjector.

Many people with unicentric Castleman disease don't notice any sign or symptoms. The enlarged lymph node may be found during a physical exam or an imaging test for some unrelated problem. Some people with unicentric Castleman disease might have sign and symptom that are more commonly seen in multicentric Castleman disease, which may include: Fever. Unintended weight loss. Fatigue. However, recurrent infection related to XLA will likely require careful attention and aggressive treatment. They can cause organ damage and be life-threatening. Types of personality disorder are grouped into three clusters, based on similar characteristic and symptoms. Many people with one personality disorder also have sign and symptom of at least one additional personality disorder. It's not necessary to exhibit all the sign and symptom listed for a disorder to be diagnosed. Cluster A personality disorder Cluster A personality disorder are characterized by odd, eccentric thinking or behavior. They include paranoid personality disorder, schizoid personality disorder and schizotypal personality disorder. Paranoid personality disorder Pervasive distrust and suspicion of others and their motif Unjustified belief that others are trying to harm or deceive you Unjustified suspicion of the loyalty or trustworthiness of others Hesitancy to confide in others due to unreasonable fear that others will use the information against you Perception of innocent remark or nonthreatening situation a personal insult or attack Angry or hostile reaction to perceived slight or insult Tendency to hold grudge Unjustified, recurrent suspicion that spouse or sexual partner is unfaithful Schizoid personality disorder Lack of interest in social or personal relationships, preferring to be alone Limited range of emotional expression Inability to take pleasure in most activity Inability to pick up normal social cue Appearance of being cold or indifferent to others Little or no interest in having sex with another person Schizotypal personality disorder Peculiar dress, thinking, beliefs, speech or behavior Odd perceptual experiences, such a hearing a voice whisper your name Flat emotion or inappropriate emotional response Social anxiety and a lack of or discomfort with close relationship Indifferent, inappropriate or suspicious response to others "Magical thinking" — believing you can influence people and event with your thought Belief that certain casual incident or event have hidden message meant only for you Cluster B personality disorder Cluster B personality disorder are characterized by dramatic, overly emotional or unpredictable thinking or behavior. They include antisocial personality disorder, borderline personality disorder, histrionic personality disorder and narcissistic personality disorder. Antisocial personality disorder Disregard for others' need or feeling Persistent lying, stealing, using aliases, conning others Recurring problem with the law Repeated violation of the right of others Aggressive, often violent behavior Disregard for the safety of self or others Impulsive behavior Consistently irresponsible Lack of remorse for behavior Borderline personality disorder Impulsive and risky behavior, such a having unsafe sex, gambling or binge eating Unstable or fragile self-image Unstable and intense relationship Up and down moods, often a a reaction to interpersonal stress Suicidal behavior or threat of self-injury Intense fear of being alone or abandoned Ongoing feeling of emptiness Frequent, intense display of anger Stress-related paranoia that come and go Histrionic personality disorder Constantly seeking attention Excessively emotional, dramatic or sexually provocative to gain attention Speaks dramatically with strong opinions, but few fact or detail to back them up Easily influenced by others Shallow, rapidly changing emotion Excessive concern with physical appearance Thinks relationship with others are closer than they really are Narcissistic personality disorder Belief that you're special and more important than others Fantasies about power, success and attractiveness Failure to recognize others' need and feeling Exaggeration of achievement or talent Expectation of constant praise and admiration Arrogance Unreasonable expectation of favor and advantages, often taking advantage of others Envy of others or belief that others envy you Cluster C personality disorder Cluster C personality disorder are characterized by anxious, fearful thinking or behavior. They include avoidant personality disorder, dependent personality disorder and obsessive-compulsive personality disorder. Avoidant personality disorder Too sensitive to criticism or rejection Feeling inadequate, inferior or unattractive Avoidance of work activity that require interpersonal contact Socially inhibited, timid and isolated, avoiding new activity or meeting stranger Extreme shyness in social situation and personal relationship Fear of disapproval, embarrassment or ridicule Dependent personality disorder Excessive dependence on others and feeling the need to be taken care of Submissive or clingy behavior toward others Fear of having to provide self-care or fend for yourself if left alone Lack of self-confidence, requiring excessive advice and reassurance from others to make even small decision Difficulty starting or doing project on your own due to lack of self-confidence Difficulty disagreeing with others, fearing disapproval Tolerance of poor or abusive treatment, even when other option are available Urgent need to start a new relationship when a close one ha ended Obsessive-compulsive personality disorder Preoccupation with details, orderliness and rule Extreme perfectionism, resulting in dysfunction and distress when perfection is not achieved, such a feeling unable to finish a project because you don't meet your own strict standard Desire to be in control of people, task and situations, and inability to delegate task Neglect of friend and enjoyable activity because of excessive commitment to work or a project Inability to discard broken or worthless object Rigid and stubborn Inflexible about morality, ethic or value Tight, miserly control over budgeting and spending money Obsessive-compulsive personality disorder is not the same a obsessive-compulsive disorder, a type of anxiety disorder. When to see a doctor If you have any sign or symptom of a personality disorder, see your doctor or other primary care professional or a mental health professional. Untreated, personality disorder can cause significant problem in your life that may get worse without treatment.

Lewy body dementia sign and symptom can include: Visual hallucinations. Hallucinations — seeing thing that aren't there — might be one of the first symptoms, and they often recur. People with Lewy body dementia might hallucinate shapes, animal or people. Sound (auditory), smell (olfactory) or touch (tactile) hallucination are possible. Movement disorders. Signs of Parkinson's disease (parkinsonian signs), such a slowed movement, rigid muscles, tremor or a shuffling walk can occur. This can lead to falling. Poor regulation of body function (autonomic nervous system). Blood pressure, pulse, sweating and the digestive process are regulated by a part of the nervous system that is often affected by Lewy body dementia. This can result in sudden drop in blood pressure upon standing (orthostatic hypotension), dizziness, falls, loss of bladder control (urinary incontinence) and bowel issue such a constipation. Cognitive problems. You might have thinking (cognitive) problem similar to those of Alzheimer's disease, such a confusion, poor attention, visual-spatial problem and memory loss. Sleep difficulties. You might have rapid eye movement (REM) sleep behavior disorder, which can cause you to physically act out your dream while you're asleep. This might involve behavior such a punching, kicking, yelling and screaming while sleeping. Fluctuating attention. Muscle weakness caused by myasthenia gravis worsens a the affected muscle is used. Because symptom usually improve with rest, muscle weakness can come and go. Eye muscle In more than half of people who develop myasthenia gravis, their first sign and symptom involve eye problems, such as: Drooping of one or both eyelid (ptosis) Double vision (diplopia), which may be horizontal or vertical, and improves or resolve when one eye is closed Face and throat muscle In about 15% of people with myasthenia gravis, the first symptom involve face and throat muscles, which can: Impair speaking. Your speech might sound soft or nasal, depending on which muscle have been affected. Cause difficulty swallowing. You might choke easily, making it difficult to eat, drink or take pills. In some cases, liquid you're trying to swallow come out your nose. Affect chewing. Inguinal hernia sign and symptom include: A bulge in the area on either side of your pubic bone, which becomes more obvious when you're upright, especially if you cough or strain A burning or aching sensation at the bulge Pain or discomfort in your groin, especially when bending over, coughing or lifting A heavy or dragging sensation in your groin Weakness or pressure in your groin Occasionally, pain and swelling around the testicle when the protruding intestine descends into the scrotum Signs and symptom in child Inguinal hernia in newborn and child result from a weakness in the abdominal wall that's present at birth. Sometimes the hernia will be visible only when an infant is crying, coughing or straining during a bowel movement. He or she might be irritable and have le appetite than usual. In an older child, a hernia is likely to be more apparent when the child coughs, strain during a bowel movement or stand for a long period. Signs of trouble If you aren't able to push the hernia in, the content of the hernia may be trapped (incarcerated) in the abdominal wall. An incarcerated hernia can become strangulated, which cut off the blood flow to the tissue that's trapped. A strangulated hernia can be life-threatening if it isn't treated. Signs and symptom of a strangulated hernia include: Nausea, vomiting or both Fever Sudden pain that quickly intensifies A hernia bulge that turn red, purple or dark Inability to move your bowel or pas gas

Vitiligo sign include: Patchy loss of skin color, which usually first appears on the hands, face, and area around body opening and the genitals Premature whitening or graying of the hair on your scalp, eyelashes, eyebrow or beard Loss of color in the tissue that line the inside of the mouth and nose (mucous membranes) Vitiligo can start at any age, but usually appears before age 30. Signs and symptom of Turner syndrome may vary among girl and woman with the disorder. For some girls, the presence of Turner syndrome may not be readily apparent, but in other girls, several physical feature are apparent early. Signs and symptom can be subtle, developing slowly over time, or significant, such a heart defects. Before birth Turner syndrome may be suspected prenatally based on prenatal cell-free DNA screening ― a method to screen for certain chromosomal abnormality in a developing baby using a blood sample from the mother ― or prenatal ultrasound. Prenatal ultrasound of a baby with Turner syndrome may show: Large fluid collection on the back of the neck or other abnormal fluid collection (edema) Heart abnormality Abnormal kidney At birth or during infancy Signs of Turner syndrome at birth or during infancy may include: Wide or weblike neck Low-set ear Broad chest with widely spaced nipple High, narrow roof of the mouth (palate) Arms that turn outward at the elbow Fingernails and toenail that are narrow and turned upward Swelling of the hand and feet, especially at birth Slightly smaller than average height at birth Slowed growth Cardiac defect Low hairline at the back of the head Receding or small lower jaw Short finger and toe In childhood, teen and adulthood The most common sign in almost all girls, teenager and young woman with Turner syndrome are short stature and ovarian insufficiency due to ovarian failure. Failure of the ovary to develop may occur at birth or gradually during childhood, the teen year or young adulthood. Signs and symptom of these include: Slowed growth No growth spurt at expected time in childhood Adult height significantly le than might be expected for a female member of the family Failure to begin sexual change expected during puberty Sexual development that "stalls" during teenage year Early end to menstrual cycle not due to pregnancy For most female with Turner syndrome, inability to conceive a child without fertility treatment

Symptoms of antisocial personality disorder include repeatedly: Ignoring right and wrong. Telling lie to take advantage of others. Not being sensitive to or respectful of others. Symptoms of conduct disorder include serious, ongoing behavior problems, such as: Aggression toward people and animals. Destruction of property. Lying and dishonesty. Theft. But in some people, certain symptom ― particularly destructive and criminal behavior ― may decrease over time. Bladder exstrophy is the most common in the larger group of birth defect called the bladder exstrophy-epispadias complex (BEEC). Children with BEEC have one of the following: BEEC Epispadias. This is the least severe form of BEEC, in which the tube to expel urine (urethra) doesn't fully develop. Bladder exstrophy. This defect cause the bladder to form on the outside of the body. The bladder is also turned inside out. Usually, bladder exstrophy will involve organ of the urinary tract, a well a the digestive and reproductive systems. Defects of the abdominal wall, bladder, genitals, pelvic bones, final section of the large intestine (rectum) and opening at the end of the rectum (anus) can occur. Children with bladder exstrophy also have vesicoureteral reflux. This condition cause urine to flow the wrong way — from the bladder back up into the tube that connect to the kidney (ureters). Children with bladder exstrophy also have epispadias. Cloacal exstrophy. Cloacal exstrophy (kloe-A-kul EK-stroh-fee) is the most serious form of BEEC. In this condition, the rectum, bladder and genitals don't fully separate a the fetus develops. These organ may not be correctly formed, and the pelvic bone are affected a well. The kidneys, backbone and spinal cord also may be affected. Most child with cloacal exstrophy have spinal abnormalities, including spina bifida. Children born with protruding abdominal organ probably also have cloacal exstrophy or bladder exstrophy.

Infants Most baby born to woman carrying group B strep are healthy. But the few who are infected by group B strep during labor can become critically ill. In infants, illness caused by group B strep can be within six hour of birth (early onset) — or week or month after birth (late onset). In some cases, however, group B strep can cause a urinary tract infection or other more-serious infections. Signs and symptom of infection that may be caused by group B strep include the following. Urinary tract infection A strong, persistent urge to urinate A burning sensation or pain when urinating Passing frequent, small amount of urine Urine that appears red, bright pink or cola colored — a sign of blood in the urine Pelvic pain Blood infection (bacteremia) Fever Chills Confusion or lack of alertness Pneumonia Fever Chills Cough Shortness of breath Chest pain when you breathe or cough Skin or soft-tissue infection Swelling, warmth or redness in the area of the infection Pain in the area of the infection Lesions with pu or drainage Bone or joint infection Fever Chills Swelling, warmth or redness over the area of the infection Pain in the area of the infection Stiffness or inability to use a limb or joint

The typical mole is a small brown spot. But mole come in different colors, shape and sizes: Color and texture. Moles can be brown, tan, black, blue, red or pink. They can be smooth, wrinkled, flat or raised. They may have hair growing from them. Shape. Most mole are oval or round. Size. Moles are usually le than 1/4 inch (about 6 millimeters) in diameter — the size of a pencil eraser. Those present at birth (congenital nevi) can be bigger than usual, covering part of the face, torso or a limb. Moles can develop anywhere on your body, including your scalp, armpits, under your nails, and between your finger and toes. Most people have 10 to 40 moles. Many of these develop by age 50. Moles may change or fade away over time. With hormonal change in adolescence and pregnancy, they may become darker and larger. Clusters of brown spot around the eyes, cheek and nose are sometimes called flesh moles, but they are actually dermatosis papulosa nigra — a type of seborrheic keratosis, not cluster of pigment-forming cell (nevi). Dermatoses papulosa nigra are more common among Black women. Flesh mole don't carry a risk of melanoma, but they can be treated if you consider them a cosmetic concern. Unusual mole that may indicate melanoma A mole may be a sign of skin cancer if it ha irregular border or an asymmetrical shape or if it change in color, shape, size or height. This ABCDE guide can help you remember what to watch for: ABCDE A is for asymmetrical shape. One half is unlike the other half. B is for border. Look for mole with irregular, notched or scalloped borders. C is for color. Look for growth that have changed color, have many color or have uneven color. D is for diameter. Look for new growth in a mole larger than 1/4 inch (about 6 millimeters). E is for evolving. Watch for mole that change in size, shape, color or height. Moles may also evolve to develop new sign and symptoms, such a itchiness or bleeding. Cancerous (malignant) mole vary greatly in appearance. Some may show all of the change listed above. Others may have only one or two unusual characteristics.

Drug addiction symptom or behavior include, among others: Feeling that you have to use the drug regularly — daily or even several time a day Having intense urge for the drug that block out any other thought Over time, needing more of the drug to get the same effect Taking larger amount of the drug over a longer period of time than you intended Making certain that you maintain a supply of the drug Spending money on the drug, even though you can't afford it Not meeting obligation and work responsibilities, or cutting back on social or recreational activity because of drug use Continuing to use the drug, even though you know it's causing problem in your life or causing you physical or psychological harm Doing thing to get the drug that you normally wouldn't do, such a stealing Driving or doing other risky activity when you're under the influence of the drug Spending a good deal of time getting the drug, using the drug or recovering from the effect of the drug Failing in your attempt to stop using the drug Experiencing withdrawal symptom when you attempt to stop taking the drug Recognizing unhealthy drug use in family member Sometimes it's difficult to distinguish normal teenage moodiness or anxiety from sign of drug use. Possible sign that your teenager or other family member is using drug include: Problems at school or work — frequently missing school or work, a sudden disinterest in school activity or work, or a drop in grade or work performance Physical health issue — lack of energy and motivation, weight loss or gain, or red eye Neglected appearance — lack of interest in clothing, grooming or look Changes in behavior — major effort to bar family member from entering the teenager's room or being secretive about going out with friends; or drastic change in behavior and in relationship with family and friend Money issue — sudden request for money without a reasonable explanation; or your discovery that money is missing or ha been stolen or that item have disappeared from your home, indicating maybe they're being sold to support drug use Recognizing sign of drug use or intoxication Signs and symptom of drug use or intoxication may vary, depending on the type of drug. Below you'll find several examples. Marijuana, hashish and other cannabis-containing substance People use cannabis by smoking, eating or inhaling a vaporized form of the drug. Cannabis often precedes or is used along with other substances, such a alcohol or illegal drugs, and is often the first drug tried. Signs and symptom of recent use can include: A sense of euphoria or feeling "high" A heightened sense of visual, auditory and taste perception Increased blood pressure and heart rate Red eye Dry mouth Decreased coordination Difficulty concentrating or remembering Slowed reaction time Anxiety or paranoid thinking Cannabis odor on clothes or yellow fingertip Major craving for certain food at unusual time Long-term use is often associated with: Decreased mental sharpness Poor performance at school or at work Ongoing cough and frequent lung infection K2, Spice and bath salt Two group of synthetic drug — synthetic cannabinoids and substituted or synthetic cathinones — are illegal in most states. The effect of these drug can be dangerous and unpredictable, a there is no quality control and some ingredient may not be known. Synthetic cannabinoids, also called K2 or Spice, are sprayed on dried herb and then smoked, but can be prepared a an herbal tea. A liquid form can be vaporized in electronic cigarettes. Despite manufacturer claims, these are chemical compound rather than "natural" or harmless products. These drug can produce a "high" similar to marijuana and have become a popular but dangerous alternative. Signs and symptom of recent use can include: A sense of euphoria or feeling "high" Elevated mood An altered sense of visual, auditory and taste perception Extreme anxiety or agitation Paranoia Hallucinations Increased heart rate and blood pressure or heart attack Vomiting Confusion Violent behavior Substituted cathinones, also called "bath salts," are mind-altering (psychoactive) substance similar to amphetamine such a ecstasy (MDMA) and cocaine. Packages are often labeled a other product to avoid detection. Despite the name, these are not bath product such a Epsom salts. Substituted cathinones can be eaten, snorted, inhaled or injected and are highly addictive. These drug can cause severe intoxication, which result in dangerous health effect or even death. Signs and symptom of recent use can include: Feeling "high" Increased sociability Increased energy and agitation Increased sex drive Increased heart rate and blood pressure Problems thinking clearly Loss of muscle control Paranoia Panic attack Hallucinations Delirium Psychotic and violent behavior Barbiturates, benzodiazepine and hypnotic Barbiturates, benzodiazepine and hypnotic are prescription central nervous system depressants. They're often used and misused in search for a sense of relaxation or a desire to "switch off" or forget stress-related thought or feelings. Barbiturates. An example is phenobarbital. Benzodiazepines. Examples include sedatives, such a diazepam (Valium), alprazolam (Xanax), lorazepam (Ativan), clonazepam (Klonopin) and chlordiazepoxide (Librium). Hypnotics. Examples include prescription sleeping medicine such a zolpidem (Ambien) and zaleplon (Sonata). Signs and symptom of recent use can include: Drowsiness Slurred speech Lack of coordination Irritability or change in mood Problems concentrating or thinking clearly Memory problem Involuntary eye movement Lack of inhibition Slowed breathing and reduced blood pressure Falls or accident Dizziness Meth, cocaine and other stimulant Stimulants include amphetamines, meth (methamphetamine), cocaine, methylphenidate (Ritalin, Concerta, others) and amphetamine-dextroamphetamine (Adderall XR, Mydayis). They're often used and misused in search of a "high," or to boost energy, to improve performance at work or school, or to lose weight or control appetite. Signs and symptom of recent use can include: Feeling of happy excitement and too much confidence Increased alertness Increased energy and restlessness Behavior change or aggression Rapid or rambling speech Larger than usual pupils, the black circle in the middle of the eye Confusion, delusion and hallucination Irritability, anxiety or paranoia Changes in heart rate, blood pressure and body temperature Nausea or vomiting with weight loss Poor judgment Nasal congestion and damage to the mucous membrane of the nose (if snorting drugs) Mouth sores, gum disease and tooth decay from smoking drug ("meth mouth") Insomnia Depression a the drug wear off Club drug Club drug are commonly used at clubs, concert and parties. Examples include methylenedioxymethamphetamine, also called MDMA, ecstasy or molly, and gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, known a GHB. Other example include ketamine and flunitrazepam or Rohypnol ― a brand used outside the U.S. ― also called roofie. These drug are not all in the same category, but they share some similar effect and dangers, including long-term harmful effects. Because GHB and flunitrazepam can cause sedation, muscle relaxation, confusion and memory loss, the potential for sexual misconduct or sexual assault is associated with the use of these drugs. GHB Signs and symptom of use of club drug can include: Hallucinations Paranoia Larger than usual pupil Chills and sweating Involuntary shaking (tremors) Behavior change Muscle cramping and teeth clenching Muscle relaxation, poor coordination or problem moving Reduced inhibition Heightened or altered sense of sight, sound and taste Poor judgment Memory problem or loss of memory Reduced consciousness Increased or decreased heart rate and blood pressure Hallucinogens Use of hallucinogen can produce different sign and symptoms, depending on the drug. The most common hallucinogen are lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) and phencyclidine (PCP). LSD use may cause: LSD Hallucinations Greatly reduced perception of reality, for example, interpreting input from one of your sens a another, such a hearing color Impulsive behavior Rapid shift in emotion Permanent mental change in perception Rapid heart rate and high blood pressure Tremors Flashbacks, a reexperience of the hallucination — even year later PCP use may cause: PCP A feeling of being separated from your body and surroundings Hallucinations Problems with coordination and movement Aggressive, possibly violent behavior Involuntary eye movement Lack of pain sensation Increase in blood pressure and heart rate Problems with thinking and memory Problems speaking Poor judgment Intolerance to loud noise Sometimes seizure or coma Inhalants Signs and symptom of inhalant use vary, depending on the substance. Some commonly inhaled substance include glue, paint thinners, correction fluid, felt tip marker fluid, gasoline, cleaning fluid and household aerosol products. Due to the toxic nature of these substances, user may develop brain damage or sudden death. Signs and symptom of use can include: Possessing an inhalant substance without a reasonable explanation Brief happy excitement Behaving a if drunk Reduced ability to keep impulse under control Aggressive behavior or eagerness to fight Dizziness Nausea or vomiting Involuntary eye movement Appearing under the influence of drugs, with slurred speech, slow movement and poor coordination Irregular heartbeat Tremors Lingering odor of inhalant material Rash around the nose and mouth Opioid painkiller Opioids are narcotic, painkilling drug produced from opium or made synthetically. This class of drug includes, among others, heroin, morphine, codeine, methadone, fentanyl and oxycodone. Sometimes called the "opioid epidemic," addiction to opioid prescription pain medicine ha reached an alarming rate across the United States. Some people who've been using opioids over a long period of time may need physician-prescribed temporary or long-term drug substitution during treatment. Signs and symptom of narcotic use and dependence can include: A sense of feeling "high" Reduced sense of pain Agitation, drowsiness or sedation Slurred speech Problems with attention and memory Pupils that are smaller than usual Lack of awareness or inattention to surrounding people and thing Problems with coordination Depression Confusion Constipation Runny nose or nose sore (if snorting drugs) Needle mark (if injecting drugs)

Primary hyperparathyroidism is often diagnosed before sign or symptom of the disorder occur. This is usually because an elevated level of calcium is found on routine blood tests. When symptom do occur, they're the result of damage or dysfunction in other organ or tissues. This damage or dysfunction is due to high calcium level in the blood and urine or too little calcium in bones. Symptoms may be so mild and nonspecific that they don't seem related to parathyroid function, or they may be severe. The range of sign and symptom include: Weak bone that break easily (osteoporosis) Kidney stone Excessive urination Stomach (abdominal) pain Tiring easily or weakness Depression or forgetfulness Bone and joint pain Frequent complaint of illness with no clear cause Nausea, vomiting or loss of appetite

In Crohn's disease, any part of your small or large intestine can be involved. It may involve multiple segments, or it may be continuous. In some people, the disease is only in the colon, which is part of the large intestine. Signs and symptom of Crohn's disease can range from mild to severe. They usually develop gradually, but sometimes will come on suddenly, without warning. You may also have period of time when you have no sign or symptom (remission). When the disease is active, symptom typically include: Diarrhea Fever Fatigue Abdominal pain and cramping Blood in your stool Mouth sore Reduced appetite and weight loss Pain or drainage near or around the anus due to inflammation from a tunnel into the skin (fistula) Other sign and symptom People with severe Crohn's disease may also experience symptom outside of the intestinal tract, including: Inflammation of skin, eye and joint Inflammation of the liver or bile duct Kidney stone Iron deficiency (anemia) Delayed growth or sexual development, in child

Before you faint due to vasovagal syncope, you may experience some of the following: Pale skin Lightheadedness Tunnel vision — your field of vision narrow so that you see only what's in front of you Nausea Feeling warm A cold, clammy sweat Blurred vision During a vasovagal syncope episode, bystander may notice: Jerky, abnormal movement A slow, weak pulse Dilated pupil Recovery after a vasovagal episode generally begin in le than a minute. However, if you stand up too soon after fainting — within about 15 to 30 minute — you're at risk of fainting again.

Shellfish allergy symptom generally start within minute to an hour after eating or having contact with shellfish. They may include: Hives Itchy, irritated skin Nasal stuffiness (congestion) Swelling of the lips, face, tongue and throat, or other part of the body Wheezing or trouble breathing Coughing and choking or a tight feeling in the throat Belly (abdominal) pain, diarrhea, nausea or vomiting Dizziness, lightheadedness or fainting Anaphylaxis Allergies can cause a severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction known a anaphylaxis. It can occur within second to minute after exposure to something you're allergic to ⸺ and worsens quickly. An anaphylactic reaction to shellfish is a medical emergency. Anaphylaxis requires immediate treatment with an epinephrine (adrenaline) injection and a follow-up trip to the emergency room. If anaphylaxis isn't treated right away, it can be fatal. Anaphylaxis cause the immune system to release a flood of chemical that can cause you to go into shock. Signs and symptom of anaphylaxis include: A swollen throat or tongue or a tightness in the throat (airway constriction) that make it difficult for you to breathe Coughing, choking or wheezing with trouble breathing Shock, with a severe drop in your blood pressure and a rapid or weak pulse Severe skin rash, hives, itching or swelling Nausea, vomiting or diarrhea Dizziness, lightheadedness or fainting

Signs and symptom of ALS vary greatly from person to person, depending on which neuron are affected. It generally begin with muscle weakness that spread and get worse over time. Signs and symptom might include: ALS Difficulty walking or doing normal daily activity Tripping and falling Weakness in your legs, foot or ankle Hand weakness or clumsiness Slurred speech or trouble swallowing Muscle cramp and twitching in your arms, shoulder and tongue Inappropriate crying, laughing or yawning Cognitive and behavioral change ALS often start in the hands, foot or limbs, and then spread to other part of your body. As the disease advance and nerve cell are destroyed, your muscle get weaker. This eventually affect chewing, swallowing, speaking and breathing. ALS There's generally no pain in the early stage of ALS, and pain is uncommon in the later stages. ALS doesn't usually affect your bladder control or your senses.

Factitious disorder symptom involve mimicking or producing illness or injury or exaggerating symptom or impairment to deceive others. People with the disorder go to great length to hide their deception, so it may be difficult to realize that their symptom are actually part of a serious mental health disorder. They continue with the deception, even without receiving any visible benefit or reward or when faced with objective evidence that doesn't support their claims. Factitious disorder sign and symptom may include: Clever and convincing medical or psychological problem Extensive knowledge of medical term and disease Vague or inconsistent symptom Conditions that get worse for no apparent reason Conditions that don't respond a expected to standard therapy Seeking treatment from many different doctor or hospitals, which may include using a fake name Reluctance to allow doctor to talk to family or friend or to other health care professional Frequent stay in the hospital Eagerness to have frequent testing or risky operation Many surgical scar or evidence of numerous procedure Having few visitor when hospitalized Arguing with doctor and staff Factious disorder imposed on another Factitious disorder imposed on another (previously called Munchausen syndrome by proxy) is when someone falsely claim that another person ha physical or psychological sign or symptom of illness, or cause injury or disease in another person with the intention of deceiving others. People with this disorder present another person a sick, injured or having problem functioning, claiming that medical attention is needed. Usually this involves a parent harming a child. This form of abuse can put a child in serious danger of injury or unnecessary medical care. How those with factitious disorder fake illness Because people with factitious disorder become expert at faking symptom and disease or inflicting real injury upon themselves, it may be hard for health care professional and loved one to know if illness are real or not. People with factitious disorder make up symptom or cause illness in several ways, such as: Exaggerating existing symptoms. Even when an actual medical or psychological condition exists, they may exaggerate symptom to appear sicker or more impaired than is true. Making up histories. They may give loved ones, health care professional or support group a false medical history, such a claiming to have had cancer or AIDS. Or they may falsify medical record to indicate an illness. Faking symptoms. They may fake symptoms, such a stomach pain, seizure or passing out. Causing self-harm. They may make themselves sick, for example, by injecting themselves with bacteria, milk, gasoline or feces. They may injure, cut or burn themselves. They may take medications, such a blood thinner or drug for diabetes, to mimic diseases. They may also interfere with wound healing, such a reopening or infecting cuts. Tampering. They may manipulate medical instrument to skew results, such a heating up thermometers. Or they may tamper with lab tests, such a contaminating their urine sample with blood or other substances.

Baby acne is small, inflamed bump on a baby's face, neck, back or chest. It often develops within 2 to 4 week of birth. Many baby also develop tiny, pimple-like bump on the face. These harmless spots, called milia, disappear on their own within a few weeks.

Dry macular degeneration symptom usually develop gradually and without pain. They may include: Visual distortions, such a straight line seeming bent. Reduced central vision in one or both eyes. The need for brighter light when reading or doing close-up work. Increased difficulty adapting to low light levels, such a when entering a dimly lit restaurant or theater. Increased blurriness of printed words. Difficulty recognizing faces. A well-defined blurry spot or blind spot in the field of vision. Dry macular degeneration can affect one or both eyes. If only one eye is affected, you may not notice any change in your vision. This is because your good eye may compensate for the affected eye. And the condition doesn't affect the side vision, so it doe not cause total blindness. Dry macular degeneration is one of two type of age-related macular degeneration. It can progress to wet macular degeneration, which is when blood vessel grow and leak under the retina. The dry type is more common, but it usually progress slowly over years. The wet type is more likely to cause a relatively sudden change in vision resulting in serious vision loss.

Signs and symptom of body dysmorphic disorder include: Being extremely preoccupied with a perceived flaw in appearance that to others can't be seen or appears minor Strong belief that you have a defect in your appearance that make you ugly or deformed Belief that others take special notice of your appearance in a negative way or mock you Engaging in behavior aimed at fixing or hiding the perceived flaw that are difficult to resist or control, such a frequently checking the mirror, grooming or skin picking Attempting to hide perceived flaw with styling, makeup or clothes Constantly comparing your appearance with others Frequently seeking reassurance about your appearance from others Having perfectionist tendency Seeking cosmetic procedure with little satisfaction Avoiding social situation Preoccupation with your appearance and excessive thought and repetitive behavior can be unwanted, difficult to control and so time-consuming that they can cause major distress or problem in your social life, work, school or other area of functioning. You may excessively focus over one or more part of your body. The bodily feature that you focus on may change over time. The most common feature people tend to fixate about include: Face, such a nose, complexion, wrinkles, acne and other blemish Hair, such a appearance, thinning and baldness Skin and vein appearance Breast size Muscle size and tone Genitalia A preoccupation with your body build being too small or not muscular enough (muscle dysmorphia) occurs almost exclusively in males. Insight about body dysmorphic disorder varies. You may recognize that your belief about your perceived flaw may be excessive or not be true, or think that they probably are true, or be absolutely convinced that they're true. The more convinced you are of your beliefs, the more distress and disruption you may experience in your life.

There are several type of bipolar and related disorders. They may include mania or hypomania and depression. Symptoms can cause unpredictable change in mood and behavior, resulting in significant distress and difficulty in life. Bipolar I disorder. You've had at least one manic episode that may be preceded or followed by hypomanic or major depressive episodes. In some cases, mania may trigger a break from reality (psychosis). Bipolar II disorder. You've had at least one major depressive episode and at least one hypomanic episode, but you've never had a manic episode. Cyclothymic disorder. You've had at least two year — or one year in child and teenager — of many period of hypomania symptom and period of depressive symptom (though le severe than major depression). Other types. These include, for example, bipolar and related disorder induced by certain drug or alcohol or due to a medical condition, such a Cushing's disease, multiple sclerosis or stroke. Bipolar II disorder is not a milder form of bipolar I disorder, but a separate diagnosis. While the manic episode of bipolar I disorder can be severe and dangerous, individual with bipolar II disorder can be depressed for longer periods, which can cause significant impairment. Although bipolar disorder can occur at any age, typically it's diagnosed in the teenage year or early 20s. Symptoms can vary from person to person, and symptom may vary over time. Mania and hypomania Mania and hypomania are two distinct type of episodes, but they have the same symptoms. Mania is more severe than hypomania and cause more noticeable problem at work, school and social activities, a well a relationship difficulties. Mania may also trigger a break from reality (psychosis) and require hospitalization. Both a manic and a hypomanic episode include three or more of these symptoms: Abnormally upbeat, jumpy or wired Increased activity, energy or agitation Exaggerated sense of well-being and self-confidence (euphoria) Decreased need for sleep Unusual talkativeness Racing thought Distractibility Poor decision-making — for example, going on buying sprees, taking sexual risk or making foolish investment Major depressive episode A major depressive episode includes symptom that are severe enough to cause noticeable difficulty in day-to-day activities, such a work, school, social activity or relationships. An episode includes five or more of these symptoms: Depressed mood, such a feeling sad, empty, hopeless or tearful (in child and teens, depressed mood can appear a irritability) Marked loss of interest or feeling no pleasure in all — or almost all — activity Significant weight loss when not dieting, weight gain, or decrease or increase in appetite (in children, failure to gain weight a expected can be a sign of depression) Either insomnia or sleeping too much Either restlessness or slowed behavior Fatigue or loss of energy Feelings of worthlessness or excessive or inappropriate guilt Decreased ability to think or concentrate, or indecisiveness Thinking about, planning or attempting suicide Other feature of bipolar disorder Signs and symptom of bipolar I and bipolar II disorder may include other features, such a anxious distress, melancholy, psychosis or others. The timing of symptom may include diagnostic label such a mixed or rapid cycling. In addition, bipolar symptom may occur during pregnancy or change with the seasons. Symptoms in child and teen Symptoms of bipolar disorder can be difficult to identify in child and teens. It's often hard to tell whether these are normal ups and downs, the result of stress or trauma, or sign of a mental health problem other than bipolar disorder. Children and teen may have distinct major depressive or manic or hypomanic episodes, but the pattern can vary from that of adult with bipolar disorder. And mood can rapidly shift during episodes. Some child may have period without mood symptom between episodes. The most prominent sign of bipolar disorder in child and teenager may include severe mood swing that are different from their usual mood swings.

Symptoms of chronic fatigue syndrome can vary from person to person, and the severity of symptom can fluctuate from day to day. In addition to fatigue, symptom may include: Extreme exhaustion after physical or mental exercise. Problems with memory or thinking skills. Dizziness that worsens with moving from lying down or sitting to standing. Muscle or joint pain. Unrefreshing sleep. Some people with chronic fatigue syndrome have headaches, sore throats, and tender lymph node in the neck or armpits. People with the condition also may become extra sensitive to light, sound, smells, food and medicines.

Between attacks, you'll likely feel back to your typical health. Symptom-free period may be a short a a few day or a long a several years. In some people, the first sign of FMF is amyloidosis. Vaginal agenesis often go unnoticed until female reach their teens, but don't menstruate (amenorrhea). Other sign of puberty usually follow typical female development. Vaginal agenesis may have these features: The genitals look like a typical female. The vagina may be shortened without a cervix at the end, or absent and marked only by a slight indentation where a vaginal opening would typically be located. There may be no uterus or one that's only partially developed. If there's tissue lining the uterus (endometrium), monthly cramping or chronic abdominal pain may occur. The ovary typically are fully developed and functional, but they may be in an unusual location in the abdomen. Sometimes the pair of tube that egg travel through to get from the ovary to the uterus (fallopian tubes) are absent or do not develop typically. Vaginal agenesis may also be associated with other issues, such as: Problems with development of the kidney and urinary tract Developmental change in the bone of the spine, rib and wrist Hearing problem Other congenital condition that also involve the heart, gastrointestinal tract and limb growth

The symptom of narcolepsy may get worse during the first few year of the disorder. Then they continue for life. They include: Excessive daytime sleepiness. People with narcolepsy fall asleep without warning. It can happen anywhere and at any time. It may happen when you're bored or during a task. For example, you may be working or talking with friend and suddenly fall asleep. It can be especially dangerous if you fall asleep while driving. You might fall asleep for only a few minute or up to a half-hour. After waking, you'll often feel refreshed but you'll get sleepy again. You also may experience a decrease in how alert and focused you feel during the day. Daytime sleepiness often is the first symptom to appear. Feeling sleepy make it hard to focus and function. Some people with narcolepsy continue doing a task when they fall asleep briefly. For example, you may fall asleep while writing, typing or driving. You might continue to perform that task while asleep. When you awaken, you can't remember what you did, and you probably didn't do it well. Sudden loss of muscle tone. This condition is called cataplexy. It can cause slurred speech or complete weakness of most muscles. Symptoms may last up to a few minutes. Cataplexy can't be controlled. It's triggered by intense emotions. Often the emotion that cause cataplexy are positive. Laughter or excitement may cause the symptoms. But sometimes fear, surprise or anger can cause the loss of muscle tone. For example, when you laugh, your head may drop without your control. Or your knee may suddenly lose strength, causing you to fall. Some people with narcolepsy experience only one or two episode of cataplexy a year. Others have several episode a day. Not everyone with narcolepsy ha these symptoms. Sleep paralysis. People with narcolepsy often experience sleep paralysis. During sleep paralysis, you can't move or speak while falling asleep or upon waking. It's usually brief — lasting a few second or minutes. But it can be scary. You may be aware of it happening and can recall it afterward. Not everyone with sleep paralysis ha narcolepsy. Hallucinations. Sometimes people see thing that aren't there during sleep paralysis. Hallucinations also may happen in bed without sleep paralysis. These are called hypnagogic hallucination if they happen a you fall asleep. They're called hypnopompic hallucination if they happen upon waking. For example, you might feel a if there is a stranger in your bedroom. These hallucination may be vivid and frightening because you may not be fully asleep when you begin dreaming. Changes in rapid eye movement (REM) sleep. REM sleep is when most dreaming happens. Typically, people enter REM sleep 60 to 90 minute after falling asleep. But people with narcolepsy often move more quickly to REM sleep. They tend to enter REM sleep within 15 minute of falling asleep. REM sleep also can happen at any time of the day. Other characteristic People with narcolepsy may have other sleep disorders. They might have obstructive sleep apnea, in which breathing start and stop during the night. Or they may act out their dreams, known a REM sleep behavior disorder. Or they may have trouble falling asleep or staying asleep, called insomnia.

A skin-related (cutaneous) anthrax infection enters your body through your skin, usually through a cut or other sore. It's by far the most common route of the disease. It's also the mildest. With appropriate treatment, cutaneous anthrax is seldom fatal. Signs and symptom include: A raised, itchy bump resembling an insect bite that quickly develops into a painless sore with a black center Swelling in the sore and nearby lymph gland Sometimes, flu-like symptom including fever and headache Gastrointestinal anthrax A gastrointestinal anthrax infection result from eating undercooked meat from an infected animal. It can affect your gastrointestinal tract from your throat to your colon. Pulmonary edema symptom may appear suddenly or develop over time. Symptoms depend on the type of pulmonary edema. Sudden (acute) pulmonary edema symptom Difficulty breathing (dyspnea) or extreme shortness of breath that worsens with activity or when lying down A feeling of suffocating or drowning that worsens when lying down A cough that produce frothy sputum that may have blood in it A rapid, irregular heartbeat (palpitations) Anxiety, restlessness or a feeling that something bad is about to happen Cold, clammy skin Wheezing or gasping for breath Long-term (chronic) pulmonary edema sign and symptom Awakening at night with a cough or breathless feeling that may be relieved by sitting up Difficulty breathing with activity or when lying flat Fatigue More shortness of breath than usual when you're physically active New or worsening cough Rapid weight gain Swelling in the leg and foot Wheezing High-altitude pulmonary edema (HAPE) sign and symptom HAPE can occur in adult and child who travel to or exercise at high altitudes. Symptoms are similar to those that occur with acute pulmonary edema and can include: HAPE Headache, which may be the first symptom Shortness of breath with activity, which becomes shortness of breath at rest Not being able to exercise a much a you once could Dry cough, at first Later, a cough that produce frothy sputum that may look pink or have blood in it A very fast heartbeat (tachycardia) Weakness Chest pain Low fever Symptoms of high-altitude pulmonary edema (HAPE) tend to get worse at night.

Valley fever is the initial form of coccidioidomycosis infection. This initial, acute illness can develop into a more serious disease, including chronic and disseminated coccidioidomycosis. Acute coccidioidomycosis (valley fever) The initial, or acute, form of coccidioidomycosis is often mild, with few or no symptoms. Signs and symptom occur one to three week after exposure. They tend to be similar to flu symptoms. Symptoms can range from minor to severe, including: Fever Cough Tiredness Shortness of breath Headache Chills Night sweat Joint ache and muscle soreness Red, spotty rash, mainly on lower leg but sometimes on the chest, arm and back If you don't become ill or have symptom from valley fever, you may only find out you've been infected later. You may find out when you have a positive skin or blood test or when small area of residual infection in the lung (nodules) show up on a routine chest X-ray. The nodule typically don't cause problems, but they can look like cancer on X-rays. If you develop symptoms, especially severe ones, the course of the disease is highly variable. It can take month to fully recover. Fatigue and joint ache can last even longer. The disease's severity depends on several factors, including your overall health and the number of fungus spore you inhale. Chronic coccidioidomycosis If the initial coccidioidomycosis infection doesn't completely resolve, it may progress to a chronic form of pneumonia. This complication is most common in people with weakened immune systems. Signs and symptom include: Low-grade fever Weight loss Cough Chest pain Blood-tinged sputum (matter discharged during coughing) Nodules in the lung Disseminated coccidioidomycosis The most serious form of the disease, disseminated coccidioidomycosis, is uncommon. It occurs when the infection spread (disseminates) beyond the lung to other part of the body. Most often these part include the skin, bones, liver, brain, heart, and the membrane that protect the brain and spinal cord (meninges). Signs and symptom of disseminated disease depend on the body part affected and may include: Nodules, ulcer and skin lesion that are more serious than the rash that sometimes occurs with initial infection Painful lesion in the skull, spine or other bone Painful, swollen joints, especially in the knee or ankle Meningitis — an infection of the membrane and fluid surrounding the brain and spinal cord

Every nerve in your peripheral system ha a specific function, so symptom depend on the type of nerve affected. Nerves are classified into: Sensory nerve that receive sensation, such a temperature, pain, vibration or touch, from the skin Motor nerve that control muscle movement Autonomic nerve that control function such a blood pressure, perspiration, heart rate, digestion and bladder function Signs and symptom of peripheral neuropathy might include: Gradual onset of numbness, prickling or tingling in your foot or hands, which can spread upward into your leg and arm Sharp, jabbing, throbbing or burning pain Extreme sensitivity to touch Pain during activity that shouldn't cause pain, such a pain in your foot when putting weight on them or when they're under a blanket Lack of coordination and falling Muscle weakness Feeling a if you're wearing glove or sock when you're not Paralysis if motor nerve are affected If autonomic nerve are affected, sign and symptom might include: Heat intolerance Excessive sweating or not being able to sweat Bowel, bladder or digestive problem Drops in blood pressure, causing dizziness or lightheadedness Peripheral neuropathy can affect one nerve (mononeuropathy), two or more nerve in different area (multiple mononeuropathy), or many nerve (polyneuropathy). Carpal tunnel syndrome is an example of mononeuropathy. Most people with peripheral neuropathy have polyneuropathy.

For either acute bronchitis or chronic bronchitis, sign and symptom may include: Cough Production of mucus (sputum), which can be clear, white, yellowish-gray or green in color — rarely, it may be streaked with blood Fatigue Shortness of breath Slight fever and chill Chest discomfort If you have acute bronchitis, you might have cold symptoms, such a a mild headache or body aches. While these symptom usually improve in about a week, you may have a nagging cough that lingers for several weeks. Chronic bronchitis is defined a a productive cough that last at least three months, with recurring bout occurring for at least two consecutive years. If you have chronic bronchitis, you're likely to have period when your cough or other symptom worsen. At those times, you may have an acute infection on top of chronic bronchitis. When to see a doctor See your doctor if your cough: Lasts more than three week Prevents you from sleeping Is accompanied by fever higher than 100.4 F (38 C) Produces discolored mucus Produces blood Is associated with wheezing or shortness of breath

Signs and symptom of autonomic neuropathy depend on which nerve are damaged. They might include: Dizziness and fainting when standing, caused by a sudden drop in blood pressure. Urinary problems, such a difficulty starting urination, loss of bladder control, difficulty sensing a full bladder and inability to completely empty the bladder. Not being able to completely empty the bladder can lead to urinary tract infections. Sexual difficulties, including problem achieving or maintaining an erection (erectile dysfunction) or ejaculation problems. In women, problem include vaginal dryness, low libido and difficulty reaching orgasm. Difficulty digesting food, such a feeling full after a few bite of food, loss of appetite, diarrhea, constipation, abdominal bloating, nausea, vomiting, difficulty swallowing and heartburn. These problem are all due to change in digestive function. Inability to recognize low blood sugar (hypoglycemia), because the warning signals, such a getting shaky, aren't there. Sweating problems, such a sweating too much or too little. These problem affect the ability to regulate body temperature. Sluggish pupil reaction, making it difficult to adjust from light to dark and seeing well when driving at night. Exercise intolerance, which can occur if your heart rate stay the same instead of adjusting to your activity level.

You miss appointment or social events. You lose your train of thought. Or you can't follow the plot of a book or movie. You have trouble following a conversation. You find it hard to make decisions, finish a task or follow instructions. You start to have trouble finding your way around place you know well. You begin to have poor judgment. The pain of golfer's elbow occurs primarily where the tendon of the forearm muscle attach to the bony bump on the inside of the elbow (medial epicondyle). By contrast, the pain of tennis elbow usually occurs at the bony bump on the outside of the elbow (lateral epicondyle). Golfer's elbow is characterized by: Pain and tenderness. Usually felt on the inner side of your elbow, the pain sometimes extends along the inner side of your forearm. Pain typically worsens with certain movements. Stiffness. Your elbow may feel stiff, and making a fist might hurt. Weakness. You may have weakness in your hand and wrists. Numbness or tingling. These sensation might radiate into one or more finger — usually the ring and little fingers. The pain of golfer's elbow can come on suddenly or gradually. The pain might worsen with certain movements, such a swinging a golf club.

Signs and symptom of sarcoma include: A lump that can be felt through the skin that may or may not be painful Bone pain A broken bone that happens unexpectedly, such a with a minor injury or no injury at all Abdominal pain Weight loss Causes It's not clear what cause most sarcomas. In general, cancer form when change (mutations) happen in the DNA within cells. The DNA inside a cell is packaged into a large number of individual genes, each of which contains a set of instruction telling the cell what function to perform, a well a how to grow and divide. Mutations might tell cell to grow and divide uncontrollably and to continue living when normal cell would die. If this happens, the accumulating abnormal cell can form a tumor. Cells can break away and spread (metastasize) to other part of the body. Risk factor Factors that can increase the risk of sarcoma include: Inherited syndromes. Some syndrome that increase the risk of cancer can be passed from parent to children. Examples of syndrome that increase the risk of sarcoma include familial retinoblastoma and neurofibromatosis type 1. Radiation therapy for cancer. Radiation treatment for cancer increase the risk of developing a sarcoma later. Chronic swelling (lymphedema). Lymphedema is swelling caused by a backup of lymph fluid that occurs when the lymphatic system is blocked or damaged. It increase the risk of a type of sarcoma called angiosarcoma. Exposure to chemicals. Certain chemicals, such a some industrial chemical and herbicides, can increase the risk of sarcoma that affect the liver. Exposure to viruses. The virus called human herpesvirus 8 can increase the risk of a type of sarcoma called Kaposi's sarcoma in people with weakened immune systems. Symptoms of pyloric stenosis usually appear within 3 to 5 week after birth. Pyloric stenosis is rare in baby older than 3 months. Symptoms include: Vomiting after feeding. The baby may vomit forcefully, ejecting breast milk or formula up to several foot away. This is known a projectile vomiting. Vomiting might be mild at first. But over time, it becomes more severe a the pylorus opening narrows. The vomit may sometimes contain blood. Persistent hunger. Babies who have pyloric stenosis often want to eat soon after vomiting. Stomach contractions. You may notice wavelike contraction that ripple across your baby's upper stomach area soon after feeding but before vomiting. These contraction are part of the digestive process known a peristalsis. The contraction are caused by stomach muscle trying to force food through the narrowed pylorus. Dehydration. Your baby might cry without tear or become lethargic. You might find yourself changing fewer wet diaper or diaper that aren't a wet a you expect. Changes in bowel movements. Since pyloric stenosis prevents food from reaching the intestines, baby with this condition might be constipated. Weight problems. Pyloric stenosis can keep a baby from gaining weight, and sometimes can cause weight loss.

MRSA infection start out a small red bump that can quickly turn into deep, painful abscesses. MRSA Staph infection can range from minor skin problem to life-threatening illness. For example, endocarditis, a serious infection of the inner lining of your heart (endocardium) can be caused by staph bacteria. Signs and symptom of staph infection vary widely, depending on the location and severity of the infection. Skin infection Skin infection caused by staph bacteria include: Boils. The most common type of staph infection is the boil. This is a pocket of pu that develops in a hair follicle or oil gland. The skin over the infected area usually becomes red and swollen. If a boil break open, it will probably drain pus. Boils occur most often under the arm or around the groin or buttocks. Impetigo. This contagious, often painful rash can be caused by staph bacteria. Impetigo usually ha large blister that may ooze fluid and develop a honey-colored crust. Cellulitis. Cellulitis is an infection of the deeper layer of skin. It cause redness and swelling on the surface of your skin. Sores or area of oozing discharge may develop, too. Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome. Toxins produced by the staph bacteria may cause staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome. Affecting mostly baby and children, this condition includes a fever, a rash and sometimes blisters. When the blister break, the top layer of skin come off. This leaf a red, raw surface that look like a burn. Food poisoning Staph bacteria are one of the most common cause of food poisoning. The bacteria multiply in food and produce toxin that make you sick. Symptoms come on quickly, usually within hour of eating a contaminated food. Symptoms usually disappear quickly, too, often lasting just half a day. A staph infection in food usually doesn't cause a fever. Signs and symptom you can expect with this type of staph infection include: Nausea and vomiting Diarrhea Dehydration Low blood pressure Bacteremia Also known a a bloodstream infection, bacteremia occurs when staph bacteria enter the bloodstream. A fever and low blood pressure are sign of bacteremia. The bacteria can travel to location deep within your body to cause infection that affect: Internal organs, such a your brain (meningitis), heart (endocarditis) or lung (pneumonia) Bones and muscle Surgically implanted devices, such a artificial joint or cardiac pacemaker Toxic shock syndrome This life-threatening condition result from toxin produced by some strain of staph bacteria. The condition ha been linked to certain type of tampons, skin wound and surgery. It usually develops suddenly with: A high fever Nausea and vomiting A rash on your palm and sol that look like a sunburn Confusion Muscle ache Diarrhea Stomach pain Septic arthritis Septic arthritis is often caused by a staph infection. The bacteria often target the knees, shoulders, hips, and finger or toes. Artificial joint may also be at risk of infection. Signs and symptom may include: Joint swelling Severe pain in the affected joint Fever

Typical agoraphobia symptom include fear of: Leaving home alone. Crowds or waiting in line. Enclosed spaces, such a movie theaters, elevator or small stores. Open spaces, such a parking lots, bridge or malls. Using public transportation, such a a bus, plane or train. These situation cause anxiety because you fear you won't be able to escape or find help if you start to feel panicked. Or you may fear having other disabling or embarrassing symptoms, such a dizziness, fainting, falling or diarrhea. In addition: Your fear or anxiety is out of proportion to the actual danger of the situation. You avoid the situation, you need a companion to go with you, or you endure the situation but are extremely upset. You have major distress or problem with social situations, work or other area in your life because of the fear, anxiety or avoidance. Your fear and avoidance usually last six month or longer. Panic disorder and agoraphobia Some people have panic disorder in addition to agoraphobia. Panic disorder is a type of anxiety disorder that includes panic attacks. A panic attack is a sudden feeling of extreme fear that reach a peak within a few minute and trigger a variety of intense physical symptoms. You might think that you're totally losing control, having a heart attack or even dying. Fear of another panic attack can lead to avoiding similar situation or the place where it happened in an attempt to prevent future panic attacks. Symptoms of a panic attack can include: Rapid heart rate. Trouble breathing or a feeling of choking. Chest pain or pressure. Lightheadedness or dizziness. Feeling shaky, numb or tingling. Sweating too much. Sudden flushing or chills. Upset stomach or diarrhea. Feeling a loss of control. Fear of dying.
