Encephalitis may cause many different symptom including confusion, personality changes, seizure or problem with movement. Encephalitis also may cause change in sight or hearing. Most people with infectious encephalitis have flu-like symptoms, such as: Headache. Fever. Aches in muscle or joints. Fatigue or weakness. Typically, these are followed by more-severe symptom over a period of hour to days, such as: Stiff neck. Confusion, agitation or hallucinations. Seizures. Loss of sensation or being unable to move certain area of the face or body. Irregular movements. Muscle weakness. Problems with speech or hearing. Loss of consciousness, including coma. In infant and young children, sign and symptom also might include: Bulging in the soft spot of an infant's skull, known a fontanels. Nausea and vomiting. Stiffness affecting the whole body. Poor feeding or not waking for a feeding. Irritability. In case of autoimmune encephalitis, symptom may develop more slowly over several weeks. Flu-like symptom are le common, but can sometimes happen week before more-severe symptom start. Symptoms are different for everyone, but it's common for people to have a combination of symptom including: Changes in personality. Memory loss. Problems understanding what is real and what is not, known a psychosis. Seeing or hearing thing that aren't there. These are called hallucinations. Seizures. Changes in vision. Sleep problems. Muscle weakness. Loss of sensation. Problems walking. Abnormal movements. Bladder and bowel problems.

The uvea consists of structure of the eye beneath the white of the eye (sclera). It ha three parts: (1) the iris, which is the colored part of the eye; (2) the ciliary body, which is the structure in the eye that secretes the transparent liquid within the front of the eye; and (3) the choroid, which is the layer of blood vessel between the sclera and the retina. The signs, symptom and characteristic of uveitis may include: Eye redness. Eye pain. Light sensitivity. Blurred vision. Dark, floating spot in your field of vision (floaters). Decreased vision. Symptoms may occur suddenly and get worse quickly, though in some cases, they develop gradually. They may affect one or both eyes. Occasionally, there are no symptoms, and sign of uveitis are observed on a routine eye exam. The uvea is the middle layer of tissue in the wall of the eye. It consists of the iris, the ciliary body and the choroid. When you look at your eye in the mirror, you will see the white part of the eye (sclera) and the colored part of the eye (iris). The iris is located inside the front of the eye. The ciliary body is a structure behind the iris. The choroid is a layer of blood vessel between the retina and the sclera. The retina line the inside of the back of the eye, like wallpaper. The inside of the back of the eye is filled with a gel-like liquid called vitreous. The type of uveitis you have depends on which part or part of the eye are inflamed: Anterior uveitis affect the inside of the front of your eye (between the cornea and the iris) and the ciliary body. It is also called iritis and is the most common type of uveitis. Intermediate uveitis affect the retina and blood vessel just behind the lens (pars plana) a well a the gel in the center of the eye (vitreous). Posterior uveitis affect a layer on the inside of the back of your eye, either the retina or the choroid. Panuveitis occurs when all layer of the uvea are inflamed, from the front to the back of your eye. When to seek medical advice Contact your doctor if you think you have the warning sign of uveitis. He or she may refer you to an eye specialist (ophthalmologist). If you're having significant eye pain and unexpected vision problems, seek immediate medical attention.

An allergic reaction (contact dermatitis) usually begin within hour to day after exposure to nickel. The reaction may last a long a 2 to 4 weeks. The reaction tends to occur only where your skin came into contact with nickel, but sometimes may appear in other place on your body. Nickel allergy sign and symptom include: Rash or bump on the skin Itching, which may be severe Redness or change in skin color Dry patch of skin that may resemble a burn Blisters and draining fluid in severe case

Scabies symptom include: Itching, often severe and usually worse at night Thin, wavy tunnel made up of tiny blister or bump on the skin Scabies is often found in the skin folds. But scabies can appear on many part of the body. In adult and older children, scabies is most often found: Between the finger and toe In the armpit Around the waist Along the inside of the wrist On the inner elbow On the sol of the foot On the chest Around the nipple Around the belly button Around the genitals In the groin area On the buttock In infant and young children, common site of scabies usually include the: Fingers Face, scalp and neck Palms of the hand Soles of the foot If you've had scabies before, symptom may start within a few day of exposure. If you've never had scabies, it can take a long a six week for symptom to start. You can still spread scabies even if you don't have any symptom yet.

Often, compression of the celiac artery doesn't cause any symptoms. However, those with median arcuate ligament syndrome (MALS) can have long-term (chronic) stomach pain. The symptom may be due to a lack of blood flow through the celiac artery or compression on nerve in the area. Symptoms of MALS include: MALS Pain in the upper middle stomach area, which may go away when leaning forward Stomach pain after eating, exercising or changing body position Bloating Diarrhea Fear of eating food due to pain, leading to significant weight loss — usually greater than 20 pound (9.1 kilograms) Nausea and vomiting

Bee sting can produce different reactions, ranging from temporary pain and discomfort to a severe allergic reaction. Having one type of reaction doesn't mean you'll always have the same reaction every time you're stung or that the next reaction will necessarily be more severe. Mild reaction Most of the time, bee sting symptom are minor and include: Instant, sharp burning pain at the sting site A red welt at the sting area Slight swelling around the sting area In most people, the swelling and pain go away within a few hours. Moderate reaction Some people who get stung by a bee or other insect have a bit stronger reaction, with sign and symptom such as: Extreme redness Swelling at the site of the sting that gradually enlarges over the next day or two Moderate reaction tend to resolve over five to 10 days. Having a moderate reaction doesn't mean you'll have a severe allergic reaction the next time you're stung. But some people develop similar moderate reaction each time they're stung. If this happens to you, talk to your doctor about treatment and prevention, especially if the reaction becomes more severe each time. Severe allergic reaction A severe allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) to bee sting is potentially life-threatening and requires emergency treatment. A small percentage of people who are stung by a bee or other insect quickly develop anaphylaxis. Signs and symptom of anaphylaxis include: Skin reactions, including hive and itching and flushed or pale skin Difficulty breathing Swelling of the throat and tongue A weak, rapid pulse Nausea, vomiting or diarrhea Dizziness or fainting Loss of consciousness People who have a severe allergic reaction to a bee sting have a 25% to 65% chance of anaphylaxis the next time they're stung. Talk to your doctor or an allergy specialist about prevention measure such a immunotherapy ("allergy shots") to avoid a similar reaction in case you get stung again. Multiple bee sting Generally, insect such a bee and wasp aren't aggressive and only sting in self-defense. In most cases, this result in one or perhaps a few stings. In some case a person will disrupt a hive or swarm of bee and get multiple stings. Some type of bee — such a Africanized honeybee — are more likely than are other bee to swarm, stinging in a group. If you get stung more than a dozen times, the accumulation of venom may induce a toxic reaction and make you feel quite sick. Signs and symptom include: Nausea, vomiting or diarrhea Headache A feeling of spinning (vertigo) Convulsions Fever Dizziness or fainting Multiple sting can be a medical emergency in children, older adults, and people who have heart or breathing problems.

The main vulvodynia symptom is pain in your genital area, which can be characterized as: Burning Soreness Stinging Rawness Painful intercourse (dyspareunia) Throbbing Itching Your pain might be constant or occasional. It might occur only when the sensitive area is touched (provoked). You might feel the pain in your entire vulvar area (generalized), or the pain might be localized to a certain area, such a the opening of your vagina (vestibule). Vulvar tissue might look slightly inflamed or swollen. More often, your vulva appears normal. A similar condition, vestibulodynia, cause pain only when pressure is applied to the area surrounding the entrance to your vagina.

Symptoms specific to the type of infection, such a painful urination from a urinary tract infection or worsening cough from pneumonia. Symptoms of sepsis are not specific. They can vary from person to person, and sepsis may appear differently in child than in adults. Symptoms of septic shock Sepsis may progress to septic shock. Septic shock is a severe drop in blood pressure. Progression to septic shock raise the risk of death. Symptoms of septic shock include: Not being able to stand up. Strong sleepiness or hard time staying awake. Major change in mental status, such a extreme confusion.

Signs and symptom of trichotillomania often include: Repeatedly pulling your hair out, typically from your scalp, eyebrow or eyelashes, but sometimes from other body areas, and site may vary over time An increasing sense of tension before pulling, or when you try to resist pulling A sense of pleasure or relief after the hair is pulled Noticeable hair loss, such a shortened hair or thinned or bald area on the scalp or other area of your body, including sparse or missing eyelash or eyebrow Preference for specific type of hair, ritual that accompany hair pulling or pattern of hair pulling Biting, chewing or eating pulled-out hair Playing with pulled-out hair or rubbing it across your lip or face Repeatedly trying to stop pulling out your hair or trying to do it le often without success Significant distress or problem at work, school or in social situation related to pulling out your hair Many people who have trichotillomania also pick their skin, bite their nail or chew their lips. Sometimes pulling hair from pet or doll or from materials, such a clothes or blankets, may be a sign. Most people with trichotillomania pull hair in private and generally try to hide the disorder from others. For people with trichotillomania, hair pulling can be: Focused. Some people pull their hair intentionally to relieve tension or distress — for example, pulling hair out to get relief from the overwhelming urge to pull hair. Some people may develop elaborate ritual for pulling hair, such a finding just the right hair or biting pulled hairs. Automatic. Some people pull their hair without even realizing they're doing it, such a when they're bored, reading or watching TV. The same person may do both focused and automatic hair pulling, depending on the situation and mood. Certain position or ritual may trigger hair pulling, such a resting your head on your hand or brushing your hair. Trichotillomania can be related to emotions: Negative emotions. For many people with trichotillomania, hair pulling is a way of dealing with negative or uncomfortable feelings, such a stress, anxiety, tension, boredom, loneliness, fatigue or frustration. Positive feelings. People with trichotillomania often find that pulling out hair feel satisfying and provides a measure of relief. As a result, they continue to pull their hair to maintain these positive feelings. Trichotillomania is a long-term (chronic) disorder. Without treatment, symptom can vary in severity over time. For example, the hormonal change of menstruation can worsen symptom in women. For some people, if not treated, symptom can come and go for weeks, month or year at a time. Rarely, hair pulling end within a few year of starting. When to see a doctor If you can't stop pulling out your hair or you feel embarrassed or ashamed by your appearance a a result of your hair pulling, talk to your doctor. Trichotillomania is not just a bad habit, it's a mental health disorder, and it's unlikely to get better without treatment.

Signs and symptom of Klinefelter syndrome vary widely among male with the disorder. Many boy with Klinefelter syndrome show few or only mild signs. Signs and symptom of Klinefelter syndrome also vary by age. Babies Signs and symptom may include: Weak muscle Slow motor development — taking longer than average to sit up, crawl and walk Delay in speaking Problems at birth, such a testicle that haven't descended into the scrotum Boys and teenager Signs and symptom may include: Taller than average stature Longer legs, shorter torso and broader hip compared with other boy Absent, delayed or incomplete puberty After puberty, le muscle and le facial and body hair compared with other teen Small, firm testicle Small penis Enlarged breast tissue (gynecomastia) Weak bone Low energy level Tendency to be shy and sensitive Difficulty expressing thought and feeling or socializing Problems with reading, writing, spelling or math Men Signs and symptom may include: Low sperm count or no sperm Small testicle and penis Low sex drive Taller than average height Weak bone Decreased facial and body hair Less muscular compared with other men Enlarged breast tissue Increased belly fat

The primary sign of pseudobulbar affect (PBA) is frequent, involuntary and uncontrollable outburst of cry or laughing that are exaggerated or not connected to your emotional state. Laughter often turn to tears. Your mood will appear normal between episodes, which can occur at any time. Crying appears to be a more common sign of PBA than laughing. The degree of the emotional response caused by PBA is often striking, with cry or laughing lasting up to several minutes. For example, you might laugh uncontrollably in response to a mildly amusing comment. Or you might laugh or cry in situation that others don't see a funny or sad. These emotional response typically represent a change from how you would have previously responded. Because pseudobulbar affect often involves crying, the condition is frequently mistaken for depression. However, PBA episode tend to be short in duration, while depression cause a persistent feeling of sadness. Also, people with PBA often lack certain feature of depression, such a sleep disturbance or a loss of appetite. But depression is common among those who have pseudobulbar affect. When to see a doctor If you think you have PBA, talk to your doctor. If you have a neurological condition, you might already be treated by a doctor who can diagnose PBA. Helpful specialist include neuropsychologists, neurologist and psychiatrists. It's suspected that many case of pseudobulbar affect go unreported and undiagnosed due to a lack of awareness about the condition.

A specific phobia involves an intense, persistent fear of a specific object or situation that's out of proportion to the actual risk. There are many type of phobias, and it's not unusual to experience a specific phobia about more than one object or situation. Specific phobia can also occur along with other type of anxiety disorders. Common category of specific phobia are a fear of: Situations, such a airplanes, enclosed space or going to school Nature, such a thunderstorm or height Animals or insects, such a dog or spider Blood, injection or injury, such a needles, accident or medical procedure Others, such a choking, vomiting, loud noise or clown Each specific phobia is referred to by it own term. Examples of more common term include acrophobia for the fear of height and claustrophobia for the fear of confined spaces. No matter what specific phobia you have, it's likely to produce these type of reactions: An immediate feeling of intense fear, anxiety and panic when exposed to or even thinking about the source of your fear Awareness that your fear are unreasonable or exaggerated but feeling powerless to control them Worsening anxiety a the situation or object get closer to you in time or physical proximity Doing everything possible to avoid the object or situation or enduring it with intense anxiety or fear Difficulty functioning normally because of your fear Physical reaction and sensations, including sweating, rapid heartbeat, tight chest or difficulty breathing Feeling nauseated, dizzy or fainting around blood or injury In children, possibly tantrums, clinging, crying, or refusing to leave a parent's side or approach their fear When to see a doctor When to see a doctor An unreasonable fear can be an annoyance — having to take the stair instead of an elevator or driving the long way to work instead of taking the freeway, for instance — but it isn't considered a specific phobia unless it seriously disrupts your life. If anxiety negatively affect functioning in work, school or social situations, talk with your doctor or a mental health professional. Childhood fears, such a fear of the dark, of monster or of being left alone, are common, and most child outgrow them. But if your child ha a persistent, excessive fear that interferes with daily functioning at home or school, talk to your child's doctor. Most people can be helped with the right therapy. And therapy tends to be easier when the phobia is addressed right away rather than waiting.

The muscle contraction involved in cervical dystonia can cause your head to twist in a variety of directions, including: Chin toward shoulder Ear toward shoulder Chin straight up Chin straight down The most common type of twisting associated with cervical dystonia is when your chin is pulled toward your shoulder. Some people experience a combination of abnormal head postures. A jerking motion of the head also may occur. Many people who have cervical dystonia also experience neck pain that can radiate into the shoulders. The disorder can also cause headaches. In some people, the pain from cervical dystonia can be exhausting and disabling. Causes In most people with cervical dystonia, the cause is unknown. Some people who have cervical dystonia have a family history of the disorder. Researchers have found gene mutation associated with cervical dystonia. Cervical dystonia is also sometimes linked to head, neck or shoulder injuries. Risk factor Risk factor for cervical dystonia include: Age. While the disorder can occur in people of any age, it most commonly begin after age 30. Your sex. Women are more likely to develop cervical dystonia than are men. Family history. If a close family member ha cervical dystonia or some other type of dystonia, you are at higher risk of developing the disorder. Complications In some cases, the involuntary muscle contraction associated with cervical dystonia can spread to nearby area of your body. The most common location include the face, jaw, arm and trunk. People who have cervical dystonia may also develop bone spur that may reduce the amount of space in the spinal canal. This can cause tingling, numbness and weakness in the arms, hands, leg or feet. Alcohol use disorder can be mild, moderate or severe, based on the number of symptom you experience. Signs and symptom may include: Being unable to limit the amount of alcohol you drink Wanting to cut down on how much you drink or making unsuccessful attempt to do so Spending a lot of time drinking, getting alcohol or recovering from alcohol use Feeling a strong craving or urge to drink alcohol Failing to fulfill major obligation at work, school or home due to repeated alcohol use Continuing to drink alcohol even though you know it's causing physical, social, work or relationship problem Giving up or reducing social and work activity and hobby to use alcohol Using alcohol in situation where it's not safe, such a when driving or swimming Developing a tolerance to alcohol so you need more to feel it effect or you have a reduced effect from the same amount Experiencing withdrawal symptom — such a nausea, sweating and shaking — when you don't drink, or drinking to avoid these symptom Alcohol use disorder can include period of being drunk (alcohol intoxication) and symptom of withdrawal. Alcohol intoxication result a the amount of alcohol in your bloodstream increases. The higher the blood alcohol concentration is, the more likely you are to have bad effects. Alcohol intoxication cause behavior problem and mental changes. These may include inappropriate behavior, unstable moods, poor judgment, slurred speech, problem with attention or memory, and poor coordination. You can also have period called "blackouts," where you don't remember events. Very high blood alcohol level can lead to coma, permanent brain damage or even death. Alcohol withdrawal can occur when alcohol use ha been heavy and prolonged and is then stopped or greatly reduced. It can occur within several hour to 4 to 5 day later. Signs and symptom include sweating, rapid heartbeat, hand tremors, problem sleeping, nausea and vomiting, hallucinations, restlessness and agitation, anxiety, and occasionally seizures. Symptoms can be severe enough to impair your ability to function at work or in social situations. What is considered 1 drink? The National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism defines one standard drink a any one of these: 12 ounce (355 milliliters) of regular beer (about 5% alcohol) 8 to 9 ounce (237 to 266 milliliters) of malt liquor (about 7% alcohol) 5 ounce (148 milliliters) of wine (about 12% alcohol) 1.5 ounce (44 milliliters) of hard liquor or distilled spirit (about 40% alcohol)

Asthma symptom vary from person to person. You may have infrequent asthma attacks, have symptom only at certain time — such a when exercising — or have symptom all the time. Asthma sign and symptom include: Shortness of breath Chest tightness or pain Wheezing when exhaling, which is a common sign of asthma in child Trouble sleeping caused by shortness of breath, coughing or wheezing Coughing or wheezing attack that are worsened by a respiratory virus, such a a cold or the flu Signs that your asthma is probably worsening include: Asthma sign and symptom that are more frequent and bothersome Increasing difficulty breathing, a measured with a device used to check how well your lung are working (peak flow meter) The need to use a quick-relief inhaler more often For some people, asthma sign and symptom flare up in certain situations: Exercise-induced asthma, which may be worse when the air is cold and dry Occupational asthma, triggered by workplace irritant such a chemical fumes, gas or dust Allergy-induced asthma, triggered by airborne substances, such a pollen, mold spores, cockroach waste, or particle of skin and dried saliva shed by pet (pet dander)

Parkinson's disease sign and symptom can be different for everyone. Early sign may be mild and go unnoticed. Symptoms often begin on one side of the body and usually remain worse on that side, even after symptom begin to affect the limb on both sides. Parkinson's sign and symptom may include: Tremor. A tremor, or rhythmic shaking, usually begin in a limb, often your hand or fingers. You may rub your thumb and forefinger back and forth. This is known a a pill-rolling tremor. Your hand may tremble when it's at rest. The shaking may decrease when you are performing tasks. Slowed movement (bradykinesia). Over time, Parkinson's disease may slow your movement, making simple task difficult and time-consuming. Your step may become shorter when you walk. It may be difficult to get out of a chair. You may drag or shuffle your foot a you try to walk. Rigid muscles. Muscle stiffness may occur in any part of your body. The stiff muscle can be painful and limit your range of motion. Impaired posture and balance. Your posture may become stooped. Or you may fall or have balance problem a a result of Parkinson's disease. Loss of automatic movements. You may have a decreased ability to perform unconscious movements, including blinking, smiling or swinging your arm when you walk. Speech changes. You may speak softly, quickly, slur or hesitate before talking. Your speech may be more of a monotone rather than have the usual speech patterns. Writing changes. It may become hard to write, and your writing may appear small.

Legionnaires' disease usually develops two to 10 day after exposure to legionella bacteria. It frequently begin with the following sign and symptoms: Headache Muscle ache Fever that may be 104 F (40 C) or higher By the second or third day, you'll develop other sign and symptom that can include: Cough, which might bring up mucus and sometimes blood Shortness of breath Chest pain Gastrointestinal symptoms, such a nausea, vomiting and diarrhea Confusion or other mental change Although Legionnaires' disease primarily affect the lungs, it occasionally can cause infection in wound and in other part of the body, including the heart. A mild form of Legionnaires' disease — known a Pontiac fever — can produce fever, chills, headache and muscle aches. Pontiac fever doesn't infect your lungs, and symptom usually clear within two to five days.

The primary symptom of endometriosis is pelvic pain, often associated with menstrual periods. Although many experience cramping during their menstrual periods, those with endometriosis typically describe menstrual pain that's far worse than usual. Pain also may increase over time. Common sign and symptom of endometriosis include: Painful period (dysmenorrhea). Pelvic pain and cramping may begin before and extend several day into a menstrual period. You may also have lower back and abdominal pain. Pain with intercourse. Pain during or after sex is common with endometriosis. Pain with bowel movement or urination. You're most likely to experience these symptom during a menstrual period. Excessive bleeding. You may experience occasional heavy menstrual period or bleeding between period (intermenstrual bleeding). Infertility. Sometimes, endometriosis is first diagnosed in those seeking treatment for infertility. Other sign and symptoms. You may experience fatigue, diarrhea, constipation, bloating or nausea, especially during menstrual periods. The severity of your pain may not be a reliable indicator of the extent of your condition. You could have mild endometriosis with severe pain, or you could have advanced endometriosis with little or no pain. Endometriosis is sometimes mistaken for other condition that can cause pelvic pain, such a pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) or ovarian cysts. It may be confused with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS), a condition that cause bout of diarrhea, constipation and abdominal cramping. IBS can accompany endometriosis, which can complicate the diagnosis.

Body temperature vary slightly from person to person and at different time of day. The average temperature ha traditionally been defined a 98.6 F (37 C). A temperature taken using a mouth thermometer (oral temperature) that's 100 F (37.8 C) or higher is generally considered to be a fever. Depending on what's causing a fever, other fever sign and symptom may include: Sweating Chills and shivering Headache Muscle ache Loss of appetite Irritability Dehydration General weakness Taking a temperature To take a temperature, you can choose from several type of thermometers, including oral, rectal, ear (tympanic) and forehead (temporal artery) thermometers. Oral and rectal thermometer generally provide the most accurate measurement of core body temperature. Ear or forehead thermometers, although convenient, provide le accurate temperature measurements. In infants, a rectal temperature, if doable, is somewhat more accurate. When reporting a temperature to your health care provider, give both the reading and the type of thermometer used.

Foodborne botulism Symptoms of foodborne botulism typically begin 12 to 36 hour after the toxin get into your body. But depending on how much toxin you consumed, the start of symptom may range from a few hour to a few days. Symptoms of foodborne botulism include: Trouble swallowing or speaking Dry mouth Facial weakness on both side of the face Blurred or double vision Drooping eyelid Trouble breathing Nausea, vomiting and stomach cramp Paralysis Wound botulism Symptoms of wound botulism appear about 10 day after the toxin enters your body. Wound botulism symptom include: Trouble swallowing or speaking Facial weakness on both side of the face Blurred or double vision Drooping eyelid Trouble breathing Paralysis The area around the wound may not always appear swollen and show a change of color. Infant botulism Problems generally begin 18 to 36 hour after the toxin enters the baby's body. Symptoms include: Constipation, which is often the first symptom Floppy movement due to muscle weakness and trouble controlling the head Weak cry Irritability Drooling Drooping eyelid Tiredness Trouble sucking or feeding Paralysis Certain symptom don't typically occur with botulism. For example, botulism doesn't usually raise blood pressure or heart rate or cause fever or confusion. Sometimes, though, wound botulism may cause fever. Iatrogenic botulism In iatrogenic botulism — when the toxin is injected for cosmetic or medical reason — there have been rare occurrence of serious side effects. These may include headache, facial paralysis, and muscle weakness.

The primary feature of ADHD include inattention and hyperactive-impulsive behavior. ADHD symptom start before age 12, and in some children, they're noticeable a early a 3 year of age. ADHD symptom can be mild, moderate or severe, and they may continue into adulthood. ADHD ADHD ADHD ADHD occurs more often in male than in females, and behavior can be different in boy and girls. For example, boy may be more hyperactive and girl may tend to be quietly inattentive. ADHD There are three subtypes of ADHD: ADHD Predominantly inattentive. The majority of symptom fall under inattention. Predominantly hyperactive/impulsive. The majority of symptom are hyperactive and impulsive. Combined. This is a mix of inattentive symptom and hyperactive/impulsive symptoms. Inattention A child who show a pattern of inattention may often: Fail to pay close attention to detail or make careless mistake in schoolwork Have trouble staying focused in task or play Appear not to listen, even when spoken to directly Have difficulty following through on instruction and fail to finish schoolwork or chore Have trouble organizing task and activity Avoid or dislike task that require focused mental effort, such a homework Lose item needed for task or activities, for example, toys, school assignments, pencil Be easily distracted Forget to do some daily activities, such a forgetting to do chore Hyperactivity and impulsivity A child who show a pattern of hyperactive and impulsive symptom may often: Fidget with or tap his or her hand or feet, or squirm in the seat Have difficulty staying seated in the classroom or in other situation Be on the go, in constant motion Run around or climb in situation when it's not appropriate Have trouble playing or doing an activity quietly Talk too much Blurt out answers, interrupting the questioner Have difficulty waiting for his or her turn Interrupt or intrude on others' conversations, game or activity Typical developmental behavior vs. ADHD Most healthy child are inattentive, hyperactive or impulsive at one time or another. It's typical for preschooler to have short attention span and be unable to stick with one activity for long. Even in older child and teenagers, attention span often depends on the level of interest. The same is true of hyperactivity. Young child are naturally energetic — they often are still full of energy long after they've worn their parent out. In addition, some child just naturally have a higher activity level than others do. Children should never be classified a having ADHD just because they're different from their friend or siblings. ADHD Children who have problem in school but get along well at home or with friend are likely struggling with something other than ADHD. The same is true of child who are hyperactive or inattentive at home, but whose schoolwork and friendship remain unaffected.

People who have KTS may have the following features, which can range from mild to more extensive: KTS Port-wine stain. This pink to reddish-purple birthmark is caused by extra tiny blood vessel (capillaries) in the top layer of skin. The birthmark often cover part of one leg but can involve any portion of the skin. It may get darker or lighter with age. Vein malformations. These include swollen, twisted vein (varicose veins), usually on the surface of the legs. Deeper malformed vein in the arms, legs, abdomen and pelvis also can occur. There may be spongy tissue filled with small vein in or under the skin. Malformed vein may become more prominent with age. Overgrowth of bone and soft tissue. This begin in infancy and may be limited to one leg, but it can occur in an arm or, rarely, in the trunk or face. This overgrowth of bone and tissue creates a larger and longer extremity. Rarely, there may be fusion of finger or toe or extra finger or toes. Lymphatic system malformations. The lymphatic system — part of the immune system that protects against infection and disease and transport lymphatic fluid — can be malformed. Extra lymphatic vessel can be present that don't work properly and can lead to fluid leakage into the tissue and swelling. Other conditions. KTS can also include cataracts, glaucoma, hip dislocation at birth, purple-red skin coloring when cold and blood-clotting problems.

The sign and symptom of a brain tumor depend on the brain tumor's size and location. Symptoms also might depend on how fast the brain tumor is growing, which is also called the tumor grade. General sign and symptom caused by brain tumor may include: Headache or pressure in the head that is worse in the morning. Headaches that happen more often and seem more severe. Headaches that are sometimes described a tension headache or migraines. Nausea or vomiting. Eye problems, such a blurry vision, seeing double or losing sight on the side of your vision. Losing feeling or movement in an arm or a leg. Trouble with balance. Speech problems. Feeling very tired. Confusion in everyday matters. Memory problems. Having trouble following simple commands. Personality or behavior changes. Seizures, especially if there is no history of seizures. Hearing problems. Dizziness or a sense that the world is spinning, also called vertigo. Feeling very hungry and gaining weight. Brain tumor that aren't cancerous tend to cause symptom that develop slowly. Noncancerous brain tumor also are called benign brain tumors. They might cause subtle symptom that you don't notice at first. The symptom might get worse over month or years. Cancerous brain tumor cause symptom that get worse quickly. Cancerous brain tumor also are called brain cancer or malignant brain tumors. They cause symptom that come on suddenly. They get worse in a matter of day or weeks. Brain tumor headache Headaches are the most common symptom of brain tumors. Headaches happen in about half of people with brain tumors. Headaches can happen if a growing brain tumor press on healthy cell around it. Or a brain tumor can cause swelling in the brain that increase pressure in the head and lead to a headache. Headache pain caused by brain tumor is often worse when you wake up in the morning. But it can happen at any time. Some people have headache that wake them from sleep. Brain tumor headache tend to cause pain that's worse when coughing or straining. People with brain tumor most often report that the headache feel like a tension headache. Some people say the headache feel like a migraine. Brain tumor in the back of the head might cause a headache with neck pain. If the brain tumor happens in the front of the head, the headache might feel like eye pain or sinus pain. The frontal lobe is important for cognitive function and control of voluntary movement or activity. The parietal lobe process information about temperature, taste, touch and movement, while the occipital lobe is primarily responsible for vision. The temporal lobe process memories, integrating them with sensation of taste, sound, sight and touch. They might cause someone to see, taste or smell something that isn't there. Sometimes the taste or smell is unpleasant or unusual.

Signs and symptom of respiratory syncytial virus infection most commonly appear about four to six day after exposure to the virus. In adult and older children, RSV usually cause mild cold-like sign and symptoms. These may include: RSV Congested or runny nose Dry cough Low-grade fever Sore throat Sneezing Headache In severe case RSV infection can spread to the lower respiratory tract, causing pneumonia or bronchiolitis — inflammation of the small airway passage entering the lungs. Signs and symptom may include: RSV Fever Severe cough Wheezing — a high-pitched noise that's usually heard on breathing out (exhaling) Rapid breathing or difficulty breathing — the person may prefer to sit up rather than lie down Bluish color of the skin due to lack of oxygen (cyanosis) Infants are most severely affected by RSV. Signs and symptom of severe RSV infection in infant include: RSV RSV Short, shallow and rapid breathing Struggling to breathe — chest muscle and skin pull inward with each breath Cough Poor feeding Unusual tiredness (lethargy) Irritability Most child and adult recover in one to two weeks, although some might have repeated wheezing. Severe or life-threatening infection requiring a hospital stay may occur in premature infant or in anyone who ha chronic heart or lung problems. RSV and COVID-19 Because RSV and coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) are both type of respiratory viruses, some symptom of RSV and COVID-19 can be similar. In children, COVID-19 often result in mild symptom such a fever, runny nose and cough. For adult with COVID-19, symptom may be more severe and may include trouble breathing. RSV RSV COVID-19 COVID-19 COVID-19 Having RSV may lower immunity and increase the risk of getting COVID-19 — for kid and adults. And these infection may occur together, which can worsen the severity of COVID-19 illness. RSV COVID-19 COVID-19 If you have symptom of a respiratory illness, your doctor may recommend testing for COVID-19.

A benign peripheral nerve tumor can cause symptom if it press on the nerve in which it is growing or on nearby nerves, blood vessel or tissues. As the tumor grows, it may be more likely to cause symptoms, but even small tumor can sometimes cause symptoms. Symptoms depend on the location of the tumor and which tissue it affects. Symptoms may include: Swelling or a lump under your skin Pain, tingling or numbness Weakness or loss of function in the affected area Dizziness or loss of balance Causes The cause of benign peripheral nerve tumor usually isn't known. Some are passed down in families. The most common type of benign peripheral nerve tumor is a schwannoma. A schwannoma typically start in a single bundle inside the main nerve, shifting the rest of the nerve. Another common type is a neurofibroma. A neurofibroma also often form inside the nerve. Sometimes it grows from several nerve bundles. Perineuriomas are rare and can grow from inside or outside the nerve. Tumors outside a nerve can cause problem when they press on the nerve. Other benign tumor that form outside nerve are soft lump of slow-growing fat cell called lipoma and ganglion cysts. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Benign peripheral nerve tumor care at Mayo Clinic

Nearsightedness sign or symptom may include: Blurry vision when looking at distant object The need to squint or partially close the eyelid to see clearly Headaches Eyestrain Children may have difficulty seeing thing on white board or screen projection in the classroom. Younger child might not express difficulty seeing, but they may have the following behavior that suggest difficulty seeing: Persistently squint Seem unaware of distant object Blink excessively Rub their eye frequently Sit close to the television Adults with myopia may notice difficulty reading street sign or sign in a store. Some people may experience blurry vision in dim light, a with nighttime driving, even if they see clearly in daylight. This condition is called night myopia.

There are no specific symptom that have been clearly linked to CTE. Some of the possible sign and symptom of CTE can occur in many other conditions. In the few people with proved CTE, sign and symptom have included cognitive, behavioral, mood and motor changes. CTE CTE CTE Cognitive impairment Difficulty thinking (cognitive impairment) Memory loss Problems with planning, organization and carrying out task (executive function) Behavioral change Impulsive behavior Aggression Mood disorder Depression or apathy Emotional instability Substance misuse Suicidal thought or behavior Motor symptom Parkinsonism Motor neuron disease CTE symptom don't develop right after a head injury, but expert believe that they might develop over year or decade after repeated head trauma. Experts currently believe that CTE symptom appear in two forms. In early life between the late 20 and early 30s, the first form of CTE may cause mental health and behavioral issue including depression, anxiety, impulsivity and aggression. The second form of CTE is thought to cause symptom later in life, around age 60. These sign and symptom include memory and thinking problem that are likely to progress to dementia. CTE CTE CTE CTE The full list of sign to look for in people with CTE at autopsy is still unknown. It is unclear what kind of symptoms, if any, CTE may cause during life. Little is known right now about how CTE progresses.

Signs and symptom of antiphospholipid syndrome can include: Blood clot in leg (DVT). Signs of a DVT include pain, swelling and redness. These clot can travel to the lung (pulmonary embolism). Repeated miscarriage or stillbirths. Other complication of pregnancy include dangerously high blood pressure (preeclampsia) and premature delivery. Stroke. A stroke can occur in a young person who ha antiphospholipid syndrome but no known risk factor for cardiovascular diseases. Transient ischemic attack (TIA). Similar to a stroke, a TIA usually last only a few minute and cause no permanent damage. Rash. Some people develop a red rash with a lacy, net-like pattern. Less common sign and symptom include: Neurological symptoms. Chronic headaches, including migraines; dementia and seizure are possible when a blood clot block blood flow to part of the brain. Cardiovascular disease. Antiphospholipid syndrome can damage heart valves. Low blood platelet count (thrombocytopenia). This decrease in blood cell needed for clotting can cause episode of bleeding, particularly from the nose and gums. Bleeding into the skin will appear a patch of small red spots.

There might be no sign or symptom in the early stage of cardiomyopathy. But a the condition advances, sign and symptom usually appear, including: Breathlessness with activity or even at rest Swelling of the legs, ankle and foot Bloating of the abdomen due to fluid buildup Cough while lying down Difficulty lying flat to sleep Fatigue Heartbeats that feel rapid, pounding or fluttering Chest discomfort or pressure Dizziness, lightheadedness and fainting Signs and symptom tend to get worse unless treated. In some people, the condition worsens quickly; in others, it might not worsen for a long time.

Ulcerative colitis symptom can vary, depending on the severity of inflammation and where it occurs. Signs and symptom may include: Diarrhea, often with blood or pu Rectal bleeding — passing small amount of blood with stool Abdominal pain and cramping Rectal pain Urgency to defecate Inability to defecate despite urgency Weight loss Fatigue Fever In children, failure to grow Most people with ulcerative colitis have mild to moderate symptoms. The course of ulcerative colitis may vary, with some people having long period when it go away. This is called remission. Types Health care provider often classify ulcerative colitis according to it location. Symptoms of each type often overlap. Types of ulcerative colitis include: Ulcerative proctitis. Inflammation is confined to the area closest to the anus, also called the rectum. Rectal bleeding may be the only sign of the disease. Proctosigmoiditis. Inflammation involves the rectum and sigmoid colon — the lower end of the colon. Symptoms include bloody diarrhea, abdominal cramp and pain, and an inability to move the bowel despite the urge to do so. This is called tenesmus. Left-sided colitis. Inflammation extends from the rectum up through the sigmoid and descending portion of the colon. Symptoms include bloody diarrhea, abdominal cramping and pain on the left side, and urgency to defecate. Pancolitis. This type often affect the entire colon and cause bout of bloody diarrhea that may be severe, abdominal cramp and pain, fatigue, and significant weight loss.

With REM sleep behavior disorder, instead of experiencing the normal temporary paralysis of your arm and leg (atonia) during REM sleep, you physically act out your dreams. The onset can be gradual or sudden, and episode may occur occasionally or several time a night. The disorder often worsens with time. Symptoms of REM sleep behavior disorder may include: Movement, such a kicking, punching, arm flailing or jumping from bed, in response to action-filled or violent dreams, such a being chased or defending yourself from an attack Noises, such a talking, laughing, shouting, emotional outcry or even cursing Being able to recall the dream if you awaken during the episode

The primary symptom of microcephaly is having a head size that is much smaller than that of other child of the same age and sex. Head size is a measure of the distance around the top of the child's head (circumference). Using standardized growth charts, health care provider compare the measurement with other children's measurement in percentiles. Some child just have small heads, with a measurement that fall below an established value for child of the same age and sex. In child with microcephaly, head size measure much smaller than average for the child's age and sex. A child with more-severe microcephaly may also have a sloping forehead.

Feelings of shyness or discomfort in certain situation aren't necessarily sign of social anxiety disorder, particularly in children. Comfort level in social situation vary, depending on personality trait and life experiences. Some people are naturally reserved and others are more outgoing. In contrast to everyday nervousness, social anxiety disorder includes fear, anxiety and avoidance that interfere with relationships, daily routines, work, school or other activities. Social anxiety disorder typically begin in the early to mid-teens, though it can sometimes start in younger child or in adults. Emotional and behavioral symptom Signs and symptom of social anxiety disorder can include constant: Fear of situation in which you may be judged negatively Worry about embarrassing or humiliating yourself Intense fear of interacting or talking with stranger Fear that others will notice that you look anxious Fear of physical symptom that may cause you embarrassment, such a blushing, sweating, trembling or having a shaky voice Avoidance of doing thing or speaking to people out of fear of embarrassment Avoidance of situation where you might be the center of attention Anxiety in anticipation of a feared activity or event Intense fear or anxiety during social situation Analysis of your performance and identification of flaw in your interaction after a social situation Expectation of the worst possible consequence from a negative experience during a social situation For children, anxiety about interacting with adult or peer may be shown by crying, having temper tantrums, clinging to parent or refusing to speak in social situations. Performance type of social anxiety disorder is when you experience intense fear and anxiety during speaking or performing in public but not in other type of more general social situations. Physical symptom Physical sign and symptom can sometimes accompany social anxiety disorder and may include: Blushing Fast heartbeat Trembling Sweating Upset stomach or nausea Trouble catching your breath Dizziness or lightheadedness Feeling that your mind ha gone blank Muscle tension Avoiding common social situation Common, everyday experience may be hard to endure when you have social anxiety disorder, including: Interacting with unfamiliar people or stranger Attending party or social gathering Going to work or school Starting conversation Making eye contact Dating Entering a room in which people are already seated Returning item to a store Eating in front of others Using a public restroom Social anxiety disorder symptom can change over time. They may flare up if you're facing a lot of changes, stress or demand in your life. Although avoiding situation that produce anxiety may make you feel better in the short term, your anxiety is likely to continue over the long term if you don't get treatment. When to see a doctor See your doctor or a mental health professional if you fear and avoid normal social situation because they cause embarrassment, worry or panic.

Most people who have Paget's disease of bone have no symptoms. When symptom occur, the most common complaint is bone pain. Because this disease cause your body to generate new bone faster than normal, the rapid remodeling produce bone that's le organized and weaker than normal bone, which can lead to bone pain, deformity and fractures. The disease might affect only one or two area of your body or might be widespread. Your sign and symptoms, if any, will depend on the affected part of your body. Pelvis. Paget's disease of bone in the pelvis can cause hip pain. Skull. An overgrowth of bone in the skull can cause hearing loss or headaches. Spine. If your spine is affected, nerve root can become compressed. This can cause pain, tingling and numbness in an arm or leg. Leg. As the bone weaken, they may bend — causing you to become bowlegged. Enlarged and misshapen bone in your leg can put extra stress on nearby joints, which may cause osteoarthritis in your knee or hip.

Pulmonary embolism symptom can vary greatly, depending on how much of your lung is involved, the size of the clots, and whether you have underlying lung or heart disease. Common symptom include: Shortness of breath. This symptom usually appears suddenly. Trouble catching your breath happens even when resting and get worse with physical activity. Chest pain. You may feel like you're having a heart attack. The pain is often sharp and felt when you breathe in deeply. The pain can stop you from being able to take a deep breath. You also may feel it when you cough, bend or lean over. Fainting. You may pas out if your heart rate or blood pressure drop suddenly. This is called syncope. Other symptom that can occur with pulmonary embolism include: A cough that may include bloody or blood-streaked mucus Rapid or irregular heartbeat Lightheadedness or dizziness Excessive sweating Fever Leg pain or swelling, or both, usually in the back of the lower leg Clammy or discolored skin, called cyanosis

When the heart beat too fast, it may not pump enough blood to the rest of the body. So the organ and tissue may not get enough oxygen. Signs and symptom that occur during an episode of ventricular tachycardia are due to a lack of oxygen and may include: Chest pain (angina) Dizziness Pounding heartbeat (palpitations) Lightheadedness Shortness of breath Ventricular tachycardia may go away on it own within 30 second (nonsustained V-tach) or last more than 30 second (sustained V-tach or VT). Brief episode may not cause any symptoms. But sustained VT can cause serious problems, including: V-tach V-tach VT VT Fainting Loss of consciousness Cardiac arrest (sudden death)

Foot drop make it difficult to lift the front part of the foot, so it might drag on the floor when you walk. To help the foot clear the floor, a person with foot drop may raise the thigh more than usual when walking, a though climbing stairs. This unusual kind of walking, called steppage gait, might cause the foot to slap down onto the floor with each step. In some cases, the skin on the top of the foot and toe feel numb. Depending on the cause, foot drop can affect one or both feet.

Some people with hemochromatosis never have symptoms. Early symptom often overlap with those of other common conditions. Symptoms may include: Joint pain. Abdominal pain. Fatigue. Weakness. Diabetes. Loss of sex drive. Impotence. Heart failure. Liver failure. Bronze or gray skin color. Memory fog. When symptom typically appear The most common type of hemochromatosis is present at birth. But most people don't experience symptom until later in life — usually after age 40 in men and after age 60 in women. Women are more likely to develop symptom after menopause, when they no longer lose iron with menstruation and pregnancy.

Signs and symptom of oral lichen planus affect the mucous membrane of the mouth. Appearance The lesion may appear as: Lacy, white, raised patch of tissue Red, swollen, tender patch of tissue Open sore Location These lesion may appear on the: Inside of the cheeks, the most common location Gums Tongue Inner tissue of the lip Palate Pain or discomfort The white, lacy patch may not cause discomfort when they appear on the inside of the cheeks. However, symptom accompanying red, swollen patch and open sore may include: Burning sensation or pain Sensitivity to hot, acidic or spicy food Bleeding and irritation with tooth brushing Inflammation of the gum (gingivitis) Painful, thickened patch on the tongue Discomfort when speaking, chewing or swallowing Other type of lichen planus If you have oral lichen planus, you may have lichen planus lesion affecting other part of your body. Skin. Lesions usually appear a purplish, flat-topped bump that are often itchy. Genitals. Lesions on the female genitalia often cause pain or burning and discomfort with intercourse. The lesion are usually red and eroded and occasionally appear a white areas. Lesions can also occur on male genitalia. Ears. Lichen planus of the ear can lead to hearing loss. Scalp. When skin lesion appear on the scalp, they may cause temporary or permanent hair loss. Nails. Though rare, lichen planus of the toenail or fingernail may result in ridge on the nails, thinning or splitting of nails, and temporary or permanent nail loss. Eyes. Rarely, lichen planus may involve the mucous membrane surface of the eyes, and can cause scarring and blindness. Esophagus. Lichen planus of the esophagus is rare, but when it occurs, it may result in a narrowing of the esophagus or the formation of tightened, ringlike band in the esophagus that can make swallowing difficult.

Stomach acid make the pain worse, a doe having an empty stomach. The pain can often be relieved by eating certain food that buffer stomach acid or by taking an acid-reducing medication, but then it may come back. The pain may be worse between meal and at night. Many people with peptic ulcer don't even have symptoms. Less often, ulcer may cause severe sign or symptom such as: Vomiting or vomiting blood — which may appear red or black Dark blood in stools, or stool that are black or tarry Trouble breathing Feeling faint Nausea or vomiting Unexplained weight loss Appetite change

COPD Signs and symptom of COPD may include: COPD Shortness of breath, especially during physical activity Wheezing Chest tightness A chronic cough that may produce mucus (sputum) that may be clear, white, yellow or greenish Frequent respiratory infection Lack of energy Unintended weight loss (in later stages) Swelling in ankles, foot or leg People with COPD are also likely to experience episode called exacerbations, during which their symptom become worse than the usual day-to-day variation and persist for at least several days.

Signs and symptom of sickle cell anemia usually appear around 6 month of age. They vary from person to person and may change over time. Signs and symptom can include: Anemia. Sickle cell break apart easily and die. Red blood cell usually live for about 120 day before they need to be replaced. But sickle cell typically die in 10 to 20 days, leaving a shortage of red blood cell (anemia). Without enough red blood cells, the body can't get enough oxygen and this cause fatigue. Episodes of pain. Periodic episode of extreme pain, called pain crises, are a major symptom of sickle cell anemia. Pain develops when sickle-shaped red blood cell block blood flow through tiny blood vessel to your chest, abdomen and joints. The pain varies in intensity and can last for a few hour to a few days. Some people have only a few pain crisis a year. Others have a dozen or more a year. A severe pain crisis requires a hospital stay. Some adolescent and adult with sickle cell anemia also have chronic pain, which can result from bone and joint damage, ulcers, and other causes. Swelling of hand and feet. The swelling is caused by sickle-shaped red blood cell blocking blood circulation in the hand and feet. Frequent infections. Sickle cell can damage the spleen, increasing vulnerability to infections. Infants and child with sickle cell anemia commonly receive vaccination and antibiotic to prevent potentially life-threatening infections, such a pneumonia. Delayed growth or puberty. Red blood cell provide the body with the oxygen and nutrient needed for growth. A shortage of healthy red blood cell can slow growth in infant and child and delay puberty in teenagers. Vision problems. Tiny blood vessel that supply the eye can become plugged with sickle cells. This can damage the retina — the portion of the eye that process visual image — and lead to vision problems.

Some people with a dAVF may not have any symptoms. However, noticeable symptom can be characterized either a aggressive or benign. dAVF Aggressive dAVF symptom can result either from bleeding in the brain (intracerebral hemorrhage) or from neurological effect of nonhemorrhaging neurological deficit (NHNDs). Aggressive dAVF symptom dAVF Bleeding in the brain often cause a sudden headache with varying degree of neurological disability related to the location and size of the hemorrhage. By contrast, an NHND usually develops more gradually, over day to weeks, and typically produce symptom related to it location. NHND These aggressive symptom can include: Difficulty walking, fall Seizures Speech or language issue Facial pain Dementia Parkinsonism Coordination issue Burning or prickling sensation Weakness Apathy Failure to thrive Symptoms related to increased pressure such a headaches, nausea and vomiting. Other dAVF symptom can include hearing issues, such a a bruit behind the ear, also known a pulsatile tinnitus. Other symptom include vision problem such as: Other dAVF symptom dAVF Visual deterioration Eye bulge Swelling in the eye lining Eye-related palsy Cavernous sinus syndrome. In rare cases, progressive dementia may occur due to venous hypertension.

The characteristic sign and symptom of progressive supranuclear palsy include: A loss of balance while walking. A tendency to fall backward can occur very early in the disease. An inability to aim your eye properly. You may not be able to look downward, or experience blurring and double vision. This difficulty with focusing the eye can make some people spill food or appear disinterested in conversation because of poor eye contact. Additional sign and symptom of progressive supranuclear palsy vary and may mimic those of Parkinson's disease and dementia. They generally get worse over time and may include: Stiffness (especially of the neck) and awkward movement Falling, especially falling backward Slow or slurred speech Problems with swallowing, which may cause gagging or choking Sensitivity to bright light Sleep disturbance Loss of interest in pleasurable activity Impulsive behavior, or laughing or cry for no reason Difficulties with reasoning, problem-solving and decision-making Depression and anxiety A surprised or frightened facial expression, resulting from rigid facial muscle Dizziness

Urinary tract infection commonly occur in people with vesicoureteral reflux. A urinary tract infection (UTI) doesn't always cause noticeable sign and symptoms, though most people have some. These sign and symptom can include: A strong, persistent urge to urinate A burning sensation when urinating The need to pas small amount of urine frequently Cloudy urine Fever Pain in your side (flank) or abdomen A UTI may be difficult to diagnose in children, who may have only nonspecific sign and symptoms. Signs and symptom in infant with a UTI may also include: UTI UTI An unexplained fever Lack of appetite Irritability As your child get older, untreated vesicoureteral reflux can lead to: Bed-wetting Constipation or loss of control over bowel movement High blood pressure Protein in urine Another indication of vesicoureteral reflux, which may be detected before birth by sonogram, is swelling of the kidney or the urine-collecting structure of one or both kidney (hydronephrosis) in the fetus, caused by the backup of urine into the kidneys.

An orgasm is a peak feeling of intense pleasure in response to stimulating sexual activity. Vaginal penetration during sex indirectly stimulates the clitoris. But this may not be enough stimulation for orgasm. Many woman may also need direct manual or oral stimulation of the clitoris to reach orgasm. Anorgasmia, or female orgasmic disorder, is defined a experiencing any of these in a significant way: Delayed orgasm Absence of orgasm Fewer orgasm Less-intense orgasm Anorgasmia can also be: Lifelong, if you've never had an orgasm Acquired, if you have new problem with having orgasm Situational, if you have problem with orgasm only in certain situations, with certain kind of stimulation or with certain partner Generalized, if you have problem with orgasm in any situation Women who don't always reach orgasm during sexual encounter may not find it distressing. In that case, the lack of an orgasm is not considered a disorder.

Migraine aura symptom include temporary visual or other disturbance that usually strike before other migraine symptom — such a intense head pain, nausea, and sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine aura usually occurs within an hour before head pain begin and generally last le than 60 minutes. Sometimes migraine aura occurs without headache, especially in people age 50 and older. Visual sign and symptom Most people who have migraine with aura develop temporary visual sign and symptoms, which tend to start in the center of the field of vision and spread outward. These might include: Blind spot (scotomas), which are sometimes outlined by simple geometric design Zigzag line that gradually float across your field of vision Shimmering spot or star Changes in vision or vision loss Flashes of light Other disturbance Other temporary disturbance sometimes associated with migraine aura include: Numbness, typically felt a tingling in one hand or on one side of your face that may spread slowly along a limb Speech or language difficulty Muscle weakness

Salmonella infection is usually caused by eating raw or undercooked meat, poultry, and egg or egg product or by drinking unpasteurized milk. The incubation period — the time between exposure and illness — can be 6 hour to 6 days. Often, people who have salmonella infection think they have the stomach flu. Possible sign and symptom of salmonella infection include: Diarrhea Stomach (abdominal) cramp Fever Nausea Vomiting Chills Headache Blood in the stool Signs and symptom of salmonella infection generally last a few day to a week. Diarrhea may last up to 10 days, but it may take several month before bowel return to usual stool habits. A few variety of salmonella bacteria result in typhoid fever, a sometimes deadly disease that is more common in developing countries.

Sometimes it's difficult to recognize the difference between a strong-willed or emotional child and one with oppositional defiant disorder. It's common for child to show oppositional behavior at certain stage of development. Symptoms of ODD generally begin during preschool years. Sometimes ODD may develop later, but almost always before the early teen years. Oppositional and defiant behavior are frequent and ongoing. They cause severe problem with relationships, social activities, school and work, for both the child and the family. ODD ODD Emotional and behavioral symptom of ODD generally last at least six months. They include angry and irritable mood, argumentative and defiant behavior, and hurtful and revengeful behavior. ODD Angry and irritable mood Angry and irritable mood Often and easily loses temper. Is frequently touchy and easily annoyed by others. Is often angry and resentful. Argumentative and defiant behavior Argumentative and defiant behavior Often argues with adult or people in authority. Often actively defies or refuse to follow adults' request or rules. Often annoys or upset people on purpose. Often blame others for their own mistake or misbehavior. Hurtful and revengeful behavior Hurtful and revengeful behavior Says mean and hateful thing when upset. Tries to hurt the feeling of others and seek revenge, also called being vindictive. Has shown vindictive behavior at least twice in the past six months. Severity Severity ODD can be mild, moderate or severe: ODD Mild. Symptoms occur only in one setting, such a only at home, school, work or with peers. Moderate. Some symptom occur in at least two settings. Severe. Some symptom occur in three or more settings. For some children, symptom may first be seen only at home. But with time, problem behavior also may happen in other settings, such a school, social activity and with friends.

Vocal cord open when you breathe and then close to produce sound when vibrating together. Your vocal cord are two flexible band of muscle tissue that sit at the entrance to the windpipe (trachea). When you speak, the band come together and vibrate to make sound. The rest of the time, the vocal cord are relaxed in an open position so that you can breathe. In most case of vocal cord paralysis, only one vocal cord is paralyzed. Paralysis of both of your vocal cord is a rare but serious condition. This can cause difficulty with speech and significant problem with breathing and swallowing. Signs and symptom of vocal cord paralysis may include: A breathy quality to the voice Hoarseness Noisy breathing Shortness of breath Loss of vocal pitch Choking or coughing while swallowing food, drink or saliva The need to take frequent breath while speaking Inability to speak loudly Loss of your gag reflex Ineffective coughing Frequent throat clearing

Most canker sore are round or oval with a white or yellow center and a red border. They form inside your mouth — on or under your tongue, inside your cheek or lips, at the base of your gums, or on your soft palate. You might notice a tingling or burning sensation a day or two before the sore actually appear. There are several type of canker sores, including minor, major and herpetiform sores. Minor canker sore Minor canker sore are the most common and: Are usually small Are oval shaped with a red edge Heal without scarring in one to two week Major canker sore Major canker sore are le common and: Are larger and deeper than minor canker sore Are usually round with defined borders, but may have irregular edge when very large Can be extremely painful May take up to six week to heal and can leave extensive scarring Herpetiform canker sore Herpetiform canker sore are uncommon and usually develop later in life, but they're not caused by herpes virus infection. These canker sores: Are pinpoint size Often occur in cluster of 10 to 100 sores, but may merge into one large ulcer Have irregular edge Heal without scarring in one to two week

Dystonia affect different people in different ways. Muscle spasm might: Begin in a single area, such a your leg, neck or arm. Focal dystonia that begin after age 21 usually start in the neck, arm or face. It tends to remain focal or become segmental. Occur during a specific action, such a writing by hand. Worsen with stress, fatigue or anxiety. Become more noticeable over time. Areas of the body that can be affected include: Neck (cervical dystonia). Contractions cause your head to twist and turn to one side, or pull forward or backward, sometimes causing pain. Eyelids. Rapid blinking or spasm cause your eye to close (blepharospasms) and make it difficult for you to see. Spasms usually aren't painful but might increase when you're in bright light, reading, watching TV, under stress or interacting with people. Your eye might feel dry, gritty or sensitive to light. Jaw or tongue (oromandibular dystonia). You might experience slurred speech, drooling, and difficulty chewing or swallowing. Oromandibular dystonia can be painful and often occurs in combination with cervical dystonia or blepharospasm. Voice box and vocal cord (laryngeal dystonia). You might have a tight or whispering voice. Hand and forearm. Some type of dystonia occur only while you do a repetitive activity, such a writing (writer's dystonia) or playing a specific musical instrument (musician's dystonia). Symptoms usually don't happen when your arm is at rest.

Babies born with hypoplastic left heart syndrome usually are seriously ill soon after birth. Symptoms include: Grayish-blue color of the lip and gum (cyanosis) Rapid, difficult breathing Poor feeding Cold hand and foot Weak pulse Being unusually drowsy or inactive If the natural connection between the heart's left and right side (foramen ovale and ductus arteriosus) are allowed to close in the first few day of life in baby with hypoplastic left heart syndrome, they can go into shock and possibly die. Signs of shock include: Cool, clammy skin that can be pale or lip that can be bluish-gray A weak and rapid pulse Breathing that may be slow and shallow or very rapid Dull eye that seem to stare A baby in shock might be conscious or unconscious.

The factor V Leiden mutation doe not itself cause any symptoms. Since factor V Leiden is a risk for developing blood clot in the leg or lungs, the first indication that you have the disorder may be the development of an abnormal blood clot. Some clot do no damage and disappear on their own. Others can be life-threatening. Symptoms of a blood clot depend on what part of your body is affected. A clot in a deep vein This is known a deep vein thrombosis (DVT), which most commonly occurs in the legs. A DVT may not cause any symptoms. If sign and symptom do occur, they can include: Pain Swelling Redness Warmth A clot that travel to your lung Known a a pulmonary embolism, this occurs when a portion of a DVT break free and travel through the right side of your heart to your lung, where it block blood flow. This can be a life-threatening situation. Signs and symptom may include: Sudden shortness of breath Chest pain when breathing in A cough that produce bloody or blood-streaked sputum Rapid heartbeat

The first symptom of smallpox usually appear 12 to 14 day after you're exposed to the smallpox virus. However, the virus can be in your body from 7 to 19 day before you look or feel sick. This time is called the incubation period. After the incubation period, sudden flu-like symptom occur. These include: Fever Muscle ache Headache Severe fatigue Severe back pain Vomiting, sometimes A few day later, flat, red spot appear on the body. They may start in the mouth and on the tongue and then spread to the skin. The face, arm and leg are often affected first, followed by the torso, hand and feet. Within a day or two, many of the spot turn into small blister filled with clear fluid. Later, the blister fill with pus. These sore are called pustules. Scabs form 8 to 9 day later and eventually fall off, leaving deep, pitted scars. Smallpox can be spread from person to person when the rash appears and until the scab fall off.

Signs and symptom of systemic mastocytosis depend on the part of the body affected by excessive mast cells. Too many mast cell can build up in the skin, liver, spleen, bone marrow or intestines. Less commonly, other organ such a the brain, heart or lung also may be affected. Signs and symptom of systemic mastocytosis may include: Flushing, itching or hive Abdominal pain, diarrhea, nausea or vomiting Anemia or bleeding disorder Bone and muscle pain Enlarged liver, spleen or lymph node Depression, mood change or problem concentrating The mast cell are triggered to produce substance that cause inflammation and symptoms. People have different triggers, but the most common one include: Alcohol Skin irritation Spicy food Exercise Insect sting Certain medication When to see a doctor When to see a doctor Talk to your doctor if you have problem with flushing or hives, or if you have concern about the sign or symptom listed above. Causes Most case of systemic mastocytosis are caused by a random change (mutation) in the KIT gene. Typically this flaw in the KIT gene is not inherited. Too many mast cell are produced and build up in tissue and body organs, releasing substance such a histamine, leukotrienes and cytokine that cause inflammation and symptoms. Complications Complications of systemic mastocytosis can include: Anaphylactic reaction. This severe allergic reaction includes sign and symptom such a rapid heartbeat, fainting, loss of consciousness and shock. If you have a severe allergic reaction, you may need an injection of epinephrine. Blood disorders. These can include anemia and poor blood clotting. Peptic ulcer disease. Chronic stomach irritation can lead to ulcer and bleeding in your digestive tract. Reduced bone density. Because systemic mastocytosis can affect your bone and bone marrow, you may be at risk of bone problems, such a osteoporosis. Organ failure. A buildup of mast cell in body organ can cause inflammation and damage to the organ. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Systemic mastocytosis care at Mayo Clinic

Signs and symptom of malaria may include: Fever Chills General feeling of discomfort Headache Nausea and vomiting Diarrhea Abdominal pain Muscle or joint pain Fatigue Rapid breathing Rapid heart rate Cough Some people who have malaria experience cycle of malaria "attacks." An attack usually start with shivering and chills, followed by a high fever, followed by sweating and a return to normal temperature. Malaria sign and symptom typically begin within a few week after being bitten by an infected mosquito. However, some type of malaria parasite can lie dormant in your body for up to a year.

Signs and symptom of hemorrhoid usually depend on the type of hemorrhoid. External hemorrhoid These are under the skin around your anus. Signs and symptom might include: Itching or irritation in your anal region Pain or discomfort Swelling around your anus Bleeding Internal hemorrhoid Internal hemorrhoid lie inside the rectum. Heart disease symptom depend on the type of heart disease. Symptoms of heart disease in the blood vessel Coronary artery disease is a common heart condition that affect the major blood vessel that supply the heart muscle. Cholesterol deposit (plaques) in the heart artery are usually the cause of coronary artery disease. The buildup of these plaque is called atherosclerosis (ath-ur-o-skluh-ROE-sis). Atherosclerosis reduces blood flow to the heart and other part of the body. It can lead to a heart attack, chest pain (angina) or stroke. Coronary artery disease symptom may be different for men and women. For instance, men are more likely to have chest pain. Women are more likely to have other symptom along with chest discomfort, such a shortness of breath, nausea and extreme fatigue. Symptoms of coronary artery disease can include: Chest pain, chest tightness, chest pressure and chest discomfort (angina) Shortness of breath Pain in the neck, jaw, throat, upper belly area or back Pain, numbness, weakness or coldness in the leg or arm if the blood vessel in those body area are narrowed You might not be diagnosed with coronary artery disease until you have a heart attack, angina, stroke or heart failure. It's important to watch for heart symptom and discus concern with your health care provider. Heart (cardiovascular) disease can sometimes be found early with regular health checkups.
