A Mayo Clinic cardiologist explains. {Music playing} Stephen Kopecky, M.D., Cardiovascular Disease, Mayo Clinic: I'm Dr. Stephen Kopecky, a cardiologist at Mayo Clinic. In this video, we'll cover the basic of coronary artery disease. What is it? Who get it? The symptoms, diagnosis and treatment. Whether you're looking for answer for yourself or someone you love, we're here to give you the best information available. Coronary artery disease, also called CAD, is a condition that affect your heart. It is the most common heart disease in the United States. CAD happens when coronary artery struggle to supply the heart with enough blood, oxygen and nutrients. Cholesterol deposits, or plaques, are almost always to blame. These buildup narrow your arteries, decreasing blood flow to your heart. This can cause chest pain, shortness of breath or even a heart attack. CAD typically take a long time to develop. So often, patient don't know that they have it until there's a problem. But there are way to prevent coronary artery disease, and way to know if you're at risk and way to treat it. Who get it? Anyone can develop CAD. It begin when fats, cholesterol and other substance gather along the wall of your arteries. This process is called atherosclerosis. It's typically no cause for concern. However, too much buildup can lead to a blockage, obstructing blood flow. There are a number of risk factors, common red flags, that can contribute to this and ultimately lead to coronary artery disease. First, getting older can mean more damaged and narrowed arteries. Second, men are generally at a greater risk. But the risk for woman increase after menopause. Existing health condition matter, too. High blood pressure can thicken your arteries, narrowing your blood flow. High cholesterol level can increase the rate of plaque buildup. Diabetes is also associated with higher risk, a is being overweight. Your lifestyle play a large role a well. Physical inactivity, long period of unrelieved stress in your life, an unhealthy diet and smoking can all increase your risk. And finally, family history. If a close relative wa diagnosed at an early age with heart disease, you're at a greater risk. All these factor together can paint a picture of your risk for developing CAD. What are the symptoms? When coronary artery become narrow, the heart doesn't get enough oxygen-rich blood. Remember, unlike most pumps, the heart ha to pump it own energy supply. It's working harder with less. And you may begin to notice these sign and symptom of pressure or tightness in your chest. This pain is called angina. It may feel like somebody is standing on your chest. When your heart can't pump enough blood to meet your body's needs, you might develop shortness of breath or extreme fatigue during activities. And if an artery becomes totally blocked, it lead to a heart attack. Classic sign and symptom of a heart attack include crushing, substernal chest pain, pain in your shoulder or arms, shortness of breath, and sweating. However, many heart attack have minimal or no symptom and are found later during routine testing. How is it diagnosed? Diagnosing CAD start by talking to your doctor. They'll be able to look at your medical history, do a physical exam and order routine blood work. Depending on that, they may suggest one or more of the following tests: an electrocardiogram or ECG, an echocardiogram or soundwave test of the heart, stress test, cardiac catheterization and angiogram, or a cardiac CT scan. How is it treated? Treating coronary artery disease usually mean making change to your lifestyle. This might be eating healthier foods, exercising regularly, losing excess weight, reducing stress or quitting smoking. The good news is these change can do a lot to improve your outlook. Living a healthier life translates to having healthier arteries. When necessary, treatment could involve drug like aspirin, cholesterol-modifying medications, beta-blockers, or certain medical procedure like angioplasty or coronary artery bypass surgery. What now? Discovering you have coronary artery disease can be overwhelming. But be encouraged. There are thing you can do to manage and live with this condition. Reducing cholesterol, lowering blood pressure, quitting tobacco, eating healthier, exercising and managing your stress can make a world of difference. Better heart health start by educating yourself. So don't be afraid to seek out information and ask your doctor about coronary artery disease. If you'd like to learn even more about this condition, watch our other related video or visit Mayoclinic.org. We wish you well. Show transcript for video What is coronary artery disease? Heart disease symptom caused by irregular heartbeat (heart arrhythmias) The heart may beat too quickly, too slowly or irregularly. Heart arrhythmia symptom can include: Chest pain or discomfort Dizziness Fainting (syncope) or near fainting Fluttering in the chest Lightheadedness Racing heartbeat (tachycardia) Shortness of breath Slow heartbeat (bradycardia) Heart disease symptom caused by congenital heart defect Serious congenital heart defect usually are noticed soon after birth. Congenital heart defect symptom in child could include: Pale gray or blue skin or lip (cyanosis) Swelling in the legs, belly area or area around the eye In an infant, shortness of breath during feedings, leading to poor weight gain Less-serious congenital heart defect are often not diagnosed until later in childhood or during adulthood. Symptoms of congenital heart defect that usually aren't immediately life-threatening include: Easily getting short of breath during exercise or activity Easily tiring during exercise or activity Swelling of the hands, ankle or foot Heart disease symptom caused by diseased heart muscle (cardiomyopathy) Early stage of cardiomyopathy may not cause noticeable symptoms. As the condition worsens, symptom may include: Dizziness, lightheadedness and fainting Fatigue Feeling short of breath during activity or at rest Feeling short of breath at night when trying to sleep or waking up short of breath Irregular heartbeat that feel rapid, pounding or fluttering Swollen legs, ankle or foot Heart disease symptom caused by heart valve problem (valvular heart disease) The heart ha four valve — the aortic, mitral, pulmonary and tricuspid valves. They open and close to move blood through the heart. Many thing can damage the heart valves. A heart valve may become narrowed (stenosis), leaky (regurgitation or insufficiency) or close improperly (prolapse). Valvular heart disease is also called heart valve disease. Depending on which valve isn't working properly, heart valve disease symptom generally include: Chest pain Fainting (syncope) Fatigue Irregular heartbeat Shortness of breath Swollen foot or ankle Endocarditis is an infection that affect the heart valve and inner lining of the heart chamber and heart valve (endocardium). Endocarditis symptom can include: Dry or persistent cough Fever Heartbeat change Shortness of breath Skin rash or unusual spot Swelling of the leg or belly area Weakness or fatigue

Atrioventricular canal defect can involve only the two upper chamber of the heart or all four chambers. In both types, extra blood flow into the lungs. Symptoms depend on whether the defect is partial or complete. Complete defect The condition affect all of the heart's chambers. Symptoms of a complete atrioventricular canal defect usually develop in the first week of life. Symptoms are generally similar to those of heart failure. They may include: Blue or gray skin color due to low oxygen level Difficulty breathing or rapid breathing Excessive sweating Fatigue Irregular or rapid heartbeat Lack of appetite Poor weight gain Swelling in the legs, ankle and foot Wheezing Partial defect The condition affect only the two upper heart chambers. Symptoms of a partial atrioventricular canal defect may not appear until early adulthood. The symptom may be due to complication such a heart valve problems, high blood pressure in the lung or heart failure. Symptoms may include: Fatigue and weakness Nausea and lack of appetite Persistent cough or wheezing Rapid or irregular heartbeat, also called an arrhythmia Reduced ability to exercise Shortness of breath Swelling in the legs, ankle and foot Chest pressure or pain

Alcohol poisoning sign and symptom include: Confusion Vomiting Seizures Slow breathing (less than eight breath a minute) Irregular breathing (a gap of more than 10 second between breaths) Blue-tinged skin or pale skin Low body temperature (hypothermia) Passing out (unconsciousness) and can't be awakened When to see a doctor It's not necessary to have all the above sign or symptom before you seek medical help. A person with alcohol poisoning who is unconscious or can't be awakened is at risk of dying. Alcohol poisoning is an emergency If you suspect that someone ha alcohol poisoning — even if you don't see the classic sign and symptom — seek immediate medical care. Here's what to do: Call 911 or your local emergency number immediately. Never assume the person will sleep off alcohol poisoning. Be prepared to provide information. If you know, be sure to tell hospital or emergency personnel the kind and amount of alcohol the person drank, and when. Don't leave an unconscious person alone. Because alcohol poisoning affect the way the gag reflex works, someone with alcohol poisoning may choke on his or her own vomit and not be able to breathe. While waiting for help, don't try to make the person vomit because he or she could choke. Help a person who is vomiting. Try to keep him or her sitting up. If the person must lie down, make sure to turn his or her head to the side — this help prevent choking. Try to keep the person awake to prevent loss of consciousness. Don't be afraid to get help It can be difficult to decide if you think someone is drunk enough to warrant medical intervention, but it's best to err on the side of caution. You may worry about the consequence for yourself or your friend or loved one, particularly if you're underage. But the consequence of not getting the right help in time can be far more serious.

Signs and symptom depend on the type of dissociative disorder you have, but may include: Memory loss (amnesia) of certain time periods, events, people and personal information A sense of being detached from yourself and your emotion A perception of the people and thing around you a distorted and unreal A blurred sense of identity Significant stress or problem in your relationships, work or other important area of your life Inability to cope well with emotional or professional stress Mental health problems, such a depression, anxiety, and suicidal thought and behavior There are three major dissociative disorder defined in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-5), published by the American Psychiatric Association: Dissociative amnesia. The main symptom is memory loss that's more severe than normal forgetfulness and that can't be explained by a medical condition. You can't recall information about yourself or event and people in your life, especially from a traumatic time. Dissociative amnesia can be specific to event in a certain time, such a intense combat, or more rarely, can involve complete loss of memory about yourself. It may sometimes involve travel or confused wandering away from your life (dissociative fugue). An episode of amnesia usually occurs suddenly and may last minutes, hours, or rarely, month or years. Dissociative identity disorder. Formerly known a multiple personality disorder, this disorder is characterized by "switching" to alternate identities. You may feel the presence of two or more people talking or living inside your head, and you may feel a though you're possessed by other identities. Each identity may have a unique name, personal history and characteristics, including obvious difference in voice, gender, mannerism and even such physical quality a the need for eyeglasses. There also are difference in how familiar each identity is with the others. People with dissociative identity disorder typically also have dissociative amnesia and often have dissociative fugue. Depersonalization-derealization disorder. This involves an ongoing or episodic sense of detachment or being outside yourself — observing your actions, feelings, thought and self from a distance a though watching a movie (depersonalization). Other people and thing around you may feel detached and foggy or dreamlike, time may be slowed down or sped up, and the world may seem unreal (derealization). You may experience depersonalization, derealization or both. Symptoms, which can be profoundly distressing, may last only a few moment or come and go over many years. When to see a doctor Some people with dissociative disorder present in a crisis with traumatic flashback that are overwhelming or associated with unsafe behavior. People with these symptom should be seen in an emergency room. If you or a loved one ha le urgent symptom that may indicate a dissociative disorder, call your doctor. Suicidal thought or behavior If you have thought of hurting yourself or someone else, call 911 or your local emergency number immediately, go to an emergency room, or confide in a trusted relative or friend. Or contact a suicide hotline. In the U.S., call or text 988 to reach the 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline, available 24 hour a day, seven day a week. Or use the Lifeline Chat. Services are free and confidential.

Most people with parvovirus infection have no sign or symptoms. When symptom do appear, they vary greatly depending on how old you are when you get the disease. Parvovirus symptom in child Early sign and symptom of parvovirus infection in child may include: Fever Upset stomach Headache Runny nose Distinctive facial rash Several day after the appearance of early symptoms, a distinctive bright red rash may appear on your child's face — usually on both cheeks. Eventually it may spread to the arms, trunk, thigh and buttocks, where the rash ha a pink, lacy, slightly raised appearance. The rash may be itchy, especially on the sol of the feet. Generally, the rash occurs near the end of the illness. It's possible to mistake the rash for other viral rash or a medicine-related rash. The rash may come and go for up to three weeks, becoming more visible when your child is exposed to extreme temperature or spends time in the sun. Parvovirus symptom in adult Adults don't usually develop the slapped-cheek rash. Instead, the most noticeable symptom of parvovirus infection in adult is joint soreness, lasting day to weeks. Joints most commonly affected are the hands, wrists, knee and ankles.

Testicles form in the abdomen during fetal development. During the final month of development, the testicle gradually descend into the scrotum. If this descent isn't completed at birth, the testicle usually descends within a few months. If your son ha a retractile testicle, the testicle originally descended a it should, but doesn't remain in place. Signs and symptom of a retractile testicle include: The testicle may be moved by hand from the groin into the scrotum and won't immediately retreat to the groin. The testicle might spontaneously appear in the scrotum and remain there for a time. The testicle might spontaneously disappear again for a time. Retractile testicle is different from undescended testicle (cryptorchidism). An undescended testicle is one that never entered the scrotum.

Signs and symptom of cerebral palsy can vary greatly from person to person. Cerebral palsy can affect the whole body, or it might be limited primarily to one or two limbs, or one side of the body. Generally, sign and symptom include problem with movement and coordination, speech and eating, development, and other problems. Movement and coordination Stiff muscle and exaggerated reflex (spasticity), the most common movement disorder Variations in muscle tone, such a being either too stiff or too floppy Stiff muscle with normal reflex (rigidity) Lack of balance and muscle coordination (ataxia) Tremors or jerky involuntary movement Slow, writhing movement Favoring one side of the body, such a only reaching with one hand or dragging a leg while crawling Difficulty walking, such a walking on toes, a crouched gait, a scissors-like gait with knee crossing, a wide gait or an asymmetrical gait Difficulty with fine motor skills, such a buttoning clothes or picking up utensil Speech and eating Delays in speech development Difficulty speaking Difficulty with sucking, chewing or eating Excessive drooling or problem with swallowing Development Delays in reaching motor skill milestones, such a sitting up or crawling Learning difficulty Intellectual disability Delayed growth, resulting in smaller size than would be expected Other problem Damage to the brain can contribute to other neurological problems, such as: Seizures (epilepsy) Difficulty hearing Problems with vision and abnormal eye movement Abnormal touch or pain sensation Bladder and bowel problems, including constipation and urinary incontinence Mental health conditions, such a emotional disorder and behavioral problem The brain disorder causing cerebral palsy doesn't change with time, so the symptom usually don't worsen with age. However, a the child get older, some symptom might become more or le apparent. And muscle shortening and muscle rigidity can worsen if not treated aggressively.

You're more likely to have a nightmare in the second half of your night. Nightmares may occur rarely or more frequently, even several time a night. Episodes are generally brief, but they cause you to awaken, and returning to sleep can be difficult. A nightmare may involve these features: Your dream seems vivid and real and is very upsetting, often becoming more disturbing a the dream unfolds. Your dream storyline is usually related to threat to safety or survival, but it can have other disturbing themes. Your dream awakens you. You feel scared, anxious, angry, sad or disgusted a a result of your dream. You feel sweaty or have a pounding heartbeat while in bed. You can think clearly upon awakening and can recall detail of your dream. Your dream cause distress that keep you from falling back to sleep easily. Nightmares are only considered a disorder if you experience: Frequent occurrence Major distress or impairment during the day, such a anxiety or persistent fear, or bedtime anxiety about having another nightmare Problems with concentration or memory, or you can't stop thinking about image from your dream Daytime sleepiness, fatigue or low energy Problems functioning at work or school or in social situation Behavior problem related to bedtime or fear of the dark Having a child with nightmare disorder can cause significant sleep disturbance and distress for parent or caregivers. When to see a doctor Occasional nightmare aren't usually a cause for concern. If your child ha nightmares, you can simply mention them at a routine well-child exam. However, consult your doctor if nightmares: Occur frequently and persist over time Routinely disrupt sleep Cause fear of going to sleep Cause daytime behavior problem or difficulty functioning

You may not notice any symptom at first. However, some woman who have an ectopic pregnancy have the usual early sign or symptom of pregnancy — a missed period, breast tenderness and nausea. If you take a pregnancy test, the result will be positive. Still, an ectopic pregnancy can't continue a normal. As the fertilized egg grows in the improper place, sign and symptom become more noticeable. Early warning of ectopic pregnancy Often, the first warning sign of an ectopic pregnancy are light vaginal bleeding and pelvic pain. If blood leak from the fallopian tube, you may feel shoulder pain or an urge to have a bowel movement. Your specific symptom depend on where the blood collect and which nerve are irritated. Emergency symptom If the fertilized egg continues to grow in the fallopian tube, it can cause the tube to rupture. Heavy bleeding inside the abdomen is likely. Symptoms of this life-threatening event include extreme lightheadedness, fainting and shock.

Shedding light on dangerous faint Click here for an infographic to learn more Shedding light on dangerous faint Click here for an infographic to learn more Some people with long QT syndrome (LQTS) do not have any noticeable symptoms. The condition may be discovered when an electrocardiogram (ECG) or genetic testing is done for other reasons. Fainting (syncope) is the most common symptom of long QT syndrome. A fainting spell from long QT syndrome can occur with little to no warning. Some people have fainting warning sign first, including: Blurred vision Lightheadedness Pounding heartbeat (palpitations) Weakness Fainting occurs when the heart temporarily beat in an unorganized way. You might faint when you're excited, angry or scared or during exercise. Things that startle you — for example, a telephone or an alarm clock — can cause you to lose consciousness. Long QT syndrome may also cause seizure in some people. Symptoms of long QT syndrome sometimes occur during sleep. Most people with symptom of LQTS have their first episode by age 40. When the condition is present at birth (congenital long QT syndrome), symptom may occur during the first week to month of life or later in childhood. LQTS Generally, after a long QT episode, the heart return to it typical rhythm. If the heart doesn't reset itself or if an external defibrillator isn't used in time to reset the heart rhythm, sudden death will occur.

Symptoms of somatic symptom disorder may be: Specific sensations, such a pain or shortness of breath, or more general symptoms, such a fatigue or weakness Unrelated to any medical cause that can be identified, or related to a medical condition such a cancer or heart disease, but more significant than what's usually expected A single symptom, multiple symptom or varying symptom Mild, moderate or severe Pain is the most common symptom, but whatever your symptoms, you have excessive thoughts, feeling or behavior related to those symptoms, which cause significant problems, make it difficult to function and sometimes can be disabling. These thoughts, feeling and behavior can include: Constant worry about potential illness Viewing normal physical sensation a a sign of severe physical illness Fearing that symptom are serious, even when there is no evidence Thinking that physical sensation are threatening or harmful Feeling that medical evaluation and treatment have not been adequate Fearing that physical activity may cause damage to your body Repeatedly checking your body for abnormality Frequent health care visit that don't relieve your concern or that make them worse Being unresponsive to medical treatment or unusually sensitive to medication side effect Having a more severe impairment than is usually expected from a medical condition For somatic symptom disorder, more important than the specific physical symptom you experience is the way you interpret and react to the symptom and how they impact your daily life.

Symptoms of depression after childbirth vary, and they can range from mild to severe. Baby blue symptom Symptoms of baby blue — which last only a few day to a week or two after your baby is born — may include: Mood swing Anxiety Sadness Irritability Feeling overwhelmed Crying Reduced concentration Appetite problem Trouble sleeping Postpartum depression symptom Postpartum depression may be mistaken for baby blue at first — but the symptom are more intense and last longer. These may eventually interfere with your ability to care for your baby and handle other daily tasks. Symptoms usually develop within the first few week after giving birth. But they may begin earlier — during pregnancy — or later — up to a year after birth. Postpartum depression symptom may include: Depressed mood or severe mood swing Crying too much Difficulty bonding with your baby Withdrawing from family and friend Loss of appetite or eating much more than usual Inability to sleep, called insomnia, or sleeping too much Overwhelming tiredness or loss of energy Less interest and pleasure in activity you used to enjoy Intense irritability and anger Fear that you're not a good mother Hopelessness Feelings of worthlessness, shame, guilt or inadequacy Reduced ability to think clearly, concentrate or make decision Restlessness Severe anxiety and panic attack Thoughts of harming yourself or your baby Recurring thought of death or suicide Untreated, postpartum depression may last for many month or longer. Postpartum psychosis With postpartum psychosis — a rare condition that usually develops within the first week after delivery — the symptom are severe. Symptoms may include: Feeling confused and lost Having obsessive thought about your baby Hallucinating and having delusion Having sleep problem Having too much energy and feeling upset Feeling paranoid Making attempt to harm yourself or your baby Postpartum psychosis may lead to life-threatening thought or behavior and requires immediate treatment. Postpartum depression in the other parent Studies show that new father can experience postpartum depression, too. They may feel sad, tired, overwhelmed, anxious, or have change in their usual eating and sleeping patterns. These are the same symptom that mother with postpartum depression experience. Fathers who are young, have a history of depression, experience relationship problem or are struggling financially are most at risk of postpartum depression. Postpartum depression in father — sometimes called paternal postpartum depression — can have the same negative effect on partner relationship and child development a postpartum depression in mother can. If you're a partner of a new mother and are having symptom of depression or anxiety during your partner's pregnancy or after your child's birth, talk to your health care provider. Similar treatment and support provided to mother with postpartum depression can help treat postpartum depression in the other parent.

Rashes appear differently depending on skin tone. Hand-foot-and-mouth disease may cause all of the following symptom or only some of them. They include: Fever. Sore throat. Feeling sick. Painful, blister-like lesion on the tongue, gum and inside of the cheeks. A rash on the palms, sol and sometimes the buttocks. The rash is not itchy, but sometimes it ha blisters. Depending on skin tone, the rash may appear red, white, gray, or only show a tiny bumps. Fussiness in infant and toddlers. Loss of appetite. The usual period from initial infection to the time symptom appear (incubation period) is 3 to 6 days. Children may get a fever and develop a sore throat. They sometimes lose their appetite and don't feel well. One or two day after the fever begins, painful sore may develop in the front of the mouth or throat. A rash on the hand and foot and sometimes on the buttock may also appear. Sores that develop in the back of the mouth and throat may suggest a related viral illness called herpangina. Other feature of herpangina include a sudden high fever and, in some instances, seizure. In rare cases, sore develop on the hands, foot or other part of the body.

Mild atherosclerosis usually doesn't have any symptoms. Atherosclerosis symptom usually don't happen until an artery is so narrowed or clogged that it can't supply enough blood to organ and tissues. Sometimes a blood clot completely block blood flow. The clot may break apart and can trigger a heart attack or stroke. Symptoms of moderate to severe atherosclerosis depend on which artery are affected. For example: If you have atherosclerosis in your heart arteries, you may have chest pain or pressure (angina). If you have atherosclerosis in the artery leading to your brain, you may have sudden numbness or weakness in your arm or legs, difficulty speaking or slurred speech, temporary loss of vision in one eye, or drooping muscle in your face. These signal a transient ischemic attack (TIA). Untreated, a TIA can lead to a stroke. If you have atherosclerosis in the artery in your arm and legs, you may have symptom of peripheral artery disease, such a leg pain when walking (claudication) or decreased blood pressure in an affected limb. If you have atherosclerosis in the artery leading to your kidneys, you may develop high blood pressure or kidney failure.

Throughout the menopausal transition, some subtle — and some not-so-subtle — change in your body may take place. You might experience: Irregular periods. As ovulation becomes more unpredictable, the length of time between period may be longer or shorter, your flow may be light to heavy, and you may skip some periods. If you have a persistent change of seven day or more in the length of your menstrual cycle, you may be in early perimenopause. If you have a space of 60 day or more between periods, you're likely in late perimenopause. Hot flash and sleep problems. Hot flash are common during perimenopause. The intensity, length and frequency vary. Sleep problem are often due to hot flash or night sweats, but sometimes sleep becomes unpredictable even without them. Mood changes. Mood swings, irritability or increased risk of depression may happen during perimenopause. The cause of these symptom may be sleep disruption associated with hot flashes. Mood change may also be caused by factor not related to the hormonal change of perimenopause. Vaginal and bladder problems. When estrogen level diminish, your vaginal tissue may lose lubrication and elasticity, making intercourse painful. Low estrogen may also leave you more vulnerable to urinary or vaginal infections. Loss of tissue tone may contribute to urinary incontinence. Decreasing fertility. As ovulation becomes irregular, your ability to conceive decreases. However, a long a you're having periods, pregnancy is still possible. If you wish to avoid pregnancy, use birth control until you've had no period for 12 months. Changes in sexual function. During perimenopause, sexual arousal and desire may change. But if you had satisfactory sexual intimacy before menopause, this will likely continue through perimenopause and beyond. Loss of bone. With declining estrogen levels, you start to lose bone more quickly than you replace it, increasing your risk of osteoporosis — a disease that cause fragile bones. Changing cholesterol levels. Declining estrogen level may lead to unfavorable change in your blood cholesterol levels, including an increase in low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol — the "bad" cholesterol — which contributes to an increased risk of heart disease. At the same time, high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol — the "good" cholesterol — decrease in many woman a they age, which also increase the risk of heart disease.

Symptoms of ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome often begin within a week after using injectable medication to stimulate ovulation, though sometimes it can take two week or longer for symptom to appear. Symptoms can range from mild to severe and may worsen or improve over time. Mild to moderate OHSS With mild to moderate ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, symptom can include: Mild to moderate abdominal pain Abdominal bloating or increased waist size Nausea Vomiting Diarrhea Tenderness in the area of your ovary Some woman who use injectable fertility drug get a mild form of OHSS. This usually go away after about a week. But, if pregnancy occurs, symptom of OHSS may worsen and last several day to weeks. OHSS OHSS Severe OHSS With severe ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, you might have: Rapid weight gain — more than 2.2 pound (1 kilogram) in 24 hour Severe abdominal pain Severe, persistent nausea and vomiting Blood clot Decreased urination Shortness of breath Tight or enlarged abdomen

You might not have symptom in the early stage of diabetic retinopathy. As the condition progresses, you might develop: Spots or dark string floating in your vision (floaters) Blurred vision Fluctuating vision Dark or empty area in your vision Vision loss When to see an eye doctor Careful management of your diabetes is the best way to prevent vision loss. If you have diabetes, see your eye doctor for a yearly eye exam with dilation — even if your vision seems fine. Developing diabetes when pregnant (gestational diabetes) or having diabetes before becoming pregnant can increase your risk of diabetic retinopathy. If you're pregnant, your eye doctor might recommend additional eye exam throughout your pregnancy. Contact your eye doctor right away if your vision change suddenly or becomes blurry, spotty or hazy. The symptom of HIV and AIDS vary, depending on the phase of infection. HIV AIDS Primary infection (Acute HIV) Some people infected by HIV develop a flu-like illness within 2 to 4 week after the virus enters the body. This illness, known a primary (acute) HIV infection, may last for a few weeks. HIV HIV Possible sign and symptom include: Fever Headache Muscle ache and joint pain Rash Sore throat and painful mouth sore Swollen lymph glands, mainly on the neck Diarrhea Weight loss Cough Night sweat These symptom can be so mild that you might not even notice them. However, the amount of virus in your bloodstream (viral load) is quite high at this time. As a result, the infection spread more easily during primary infection than during the next stage. Clinical latent infection (Chronic HIV) In this stage of infection, HIV is still present in the body and in white blood cells. However, many people may not have any symptom or infection during this time. HIV This stage can last for many year if you're receiving antiretroviral therapy (ART). Some people develop more severe disease much sooner. Symptomatic HIV infection As the virus continues to multiply and destroy your immune cell — the cell in your body that help fight off germ — you may develop mild infection or chronic sign and symptom such as: Fever Fatigue Swollen lymph node — often one of the first sign of HIV infection Diarrhea Weight loss Oral yeast infection (thrush) Shingles (herpes zoster) Pneumonia Progression to AIDS Access to better antiviral treatment ha dramatically decreased death from AIDS worldwide, even in resource-poor countries. Thanks to these life-saving treatments, most people with HIV in the U.S. today don't develop AIDS. Untreated, HIV typically turn into AIDS in about 8 to 10 years. AIDS HIV AIDS HIV AIDS When AIDS occurs, your immune system ha been severely damaged. You'll be more likely to develop disease that wouldn't usually cause illness in a person with a healthy immune system. These are called opportunistic infection or opportunistic cancers. AIDS The sign and symptom of some of these infection may include: Sweats Chills Recurring fever Chronic diarrhea Swollen lymph gland Persistent white spot or unusual lesion on your tongue or in your mouth Persistent, unexplained fatigue Weakness Weight loss Skin rash or bump

Common sign and symptom of psoriasis include: A patchy rash that varies widely in how it look from person to person, ranging from spot of dandruff-like scaling to major eruption over much of the body Rashes that vary in color, tending to be shade of purple with gray scale on brown or Black skin and pink or red with silver scale on white skin Small scaling spot (commonly seen in children) Dry, cracked skin that may bleed Itching, burning or soreness Cyclic rash that flare for a few week or month and then subside There are several type of psoriasis, each of which varies in it sign and symptoms: Plaque psoriasis. The most common type of psoriasis, plaque psoriasis cause dry, itchy, raised skin patch (plaques) covered with scales. There may be few or many. They usually appear on the elbows, knees, lower back and scalp. The patch vary in color, depending on skin color. The affected skin might heal with temporary change in color (post inflammatory hyperpigmentation), particularly on brown or Black skin. Nail psoriasis. Psoriasis can affect fingernail and toenails, causing pitting, abnormal nail growth and discoloration. Psoriatic nail might loosen and separate from the nail bed (onycholysis). Severe disease may cause the nail to crumble. Guttate psoriasis. Guttate psoriasis primarily affect young adult and children. It's usually triggered by a bacterial infection such a strep throat. It's marked by small, drop-shaped, scaling spot on the trunk, arm or legs. Inverse psoriasis. Inverse psoriasis mainly affect the skin fold of the groin, buttock and breasts. It cause smooth patch of inflamed skin that worsen with friction and sweating. Fungal infection may trigger this type of psoriasis. Pustular psoriasis. Pustular psoriasis, a rare type, cause clearly defined pus-filled blisters. It can occur in widespread patch or on small area of the palm or soles. Erythrodermic psoriasis. The least common type of psoriasis, erythrodermic psoriasis can cover the entire body with a peeling rash that can itch or burn intensely. It can be short-lived (acute) or long-term (chronic).

You can have emphysema for many year without noticing any sign or symptoms. The main symptom of emphysema is shortness of breath, which usually begin gradually. You may start avoiding activity that cause you to be short of breath, so the symptom doesn't become a problem until it start interfering with daily tasks. Emphysema eventually cause shortness of breath even while you're at rest. When to see a doctor See your doctor if you've had unexplained shortness of breath for several months, especially if it's getting worse or it's interfering with your daily activities. Don't ignore it by telling yourself it's because you're aging or out of shape. Seek immediate medical attention if: You're so short of breath, you can't climb stair Your lip or fingernail turn blue or gray with exertion You're not mentally alert

Chondrosarcoma tends to grow slowly, so it might not cause sign and symptom at first. When they occur, sign and symptom of chondrosarcoma may include: Increasing pain A growing lump or area of swelling Weakness or bowel and bladder control problems, if the cancer press on the spinal cord Causes It's not clear what cause chondrosarcoma. Doctors know that cancer begin when a cell develops change (mutations) in it DNA. A cell's DNA contains the instruction that tell it what to do. The instruction tell the cell to multiply quickly and to continue living when healthy cell would die. The accumulating cell form a tumor that can grow to invade and destroy normal body tissue. In time, cell can break away and spread (metastasize) to other area of the body. Risk factor Factors that can increase the risk of chondrosarcoma include: Increasing age. Chondrosarcoma occurs most often in middle-aged and older adults, though it can occur at any age. Other bone diseases. Ollier's disease and Maffucci's syndrome are condition that cause noncancerous bone growth (enchondromas) in the body. These growth sometimes transform into chondrosarcoma. Scabs eventually form and the sore heal, but they tend to recur. Most people infected with HSV don't know they have it. They may have no symptom or have very mild symptoms. HSV Symptoms start about 2 to 12 day after exposure to the virus. They may include: Pain or itching around the genitals Small bump or blister around the genitals, anus or mouth Painful ulcer that form when blister rupture and ooze or bleed Scabs that form a the ulcer heal Painful urination Discharge from the urethra, the tube that release urine from the body Discharge from the vagina During the first outbreak, you may commonly have flu-like symptom such as: Fever Headache Body ache Swollen lymph node in the groin Differences in symptom location Sores appear where the infection enters the body. You can spread the infection by touching a sore and then rubbing or scratching another area of your body. That includes your finger or eyes. Sore can develop on or in the: Buttocks Thighs Rectum Anus Mouth Urethra Vulva Vagina Cervix Penis Scrotum Repeat outbreak After the first outbreak of genital herpes, symptom often appear again. These are called recurrent outbreak or recurrent episodes. How often recurrent outbreak happen varies widely. You'll usually have the most outbreak the first year after infection. They may appear le often over time. Your symptom during recurrent outbreak usually don't last a long and aren't a severe a the first. You may have warning sign a few hour or day before a new outbreak starts. These are called prodromal symptoms. They include: Genital pain Tingling or shooting pain in the legs, hip or buttock

Common sign and symptom of chronic sinusitis include: Nasal inflammation Thick, discolored discharge from the nose (runny nose) Drainage down the back of the throat (postnasal drainage) Blocked or stuffy (congested) nose causing difficulty breathing through your nose Pain, tenderness and swelling around your eyes, cheeks, nose or forehead Reduced sense of smell and taste Other sign and symptom can include: Ear pain Headache Aching in your upper jaw and teeth Cough or throat clearing Sore throat Bad breath Fatigue Chronic sinusitis and acute sinusitis have similar sign and symptoms. But acute sinusitis is a temporary infection of the sinus often associated with a cold. The sign and symptom of chronic sinusitis last at least 12 weeks, but you may have several episode of acute sinusitis before developing chronic sinusitis. Fever isn't a common sign of chronic sinusitis, but you might have one with acute sinusitis.

Measles sign and symptom appear around 10 to 14 day after exposure to the virus. Signs and symptom of measles typically include: Fever Dry cough Runny nose Sore throat Inflamed eye (conjunctivitis) Tiny white spot with bluish-white center on a red background found inside the mouth on the inner lining of the cheek — also called Koplik's spot A skin rash made up of large, flat blotch that often flow into one another The infection occurs in stage over 2 to 3 weeks. Infection and incubation. For the first 10 to 14 day after infection, the measles virus spread in the body. There are no sign or symptom of measles during this time. Nonspecific sign and symptoms. Measles typically begin with a mild to moderate fever, often with a persistent cough, a runny nose, inflamed eye (conjunctivitis) and a sore throat. This relatively mild illness may last 2 to 3 days. Acute illness and rash. The rash is made up of small red spots, some of which are slightly raised. Spots and bump in tight cluster give the skin a splotchy red appearance. The face break out first. Over the next few days, the rash spread down the arms, chest and back, then over the thighs, lower leg and feet. At the same time, the fever rise sharply, often a high a 104 to 105.8 F (40 to 41 C). Recovery. The measles rash may last about seven days. The rash gradually fade first from the face and last from the thigh and feet. As other symptom of the illness go away, the cough and darkening or peeling of the skin where the rash wa may stay for about 10 days. When can a person spread the measles virus? A person with measles can spread the virus to others for about eight days, starting four day before the rash appears and ending when the rash ha been present for four days.

Both psoriatic arthritis and psoriasis are chronic disease that worsen over time. However, you might have period when your symptom improve or go away temporarily. Psoriatic arthritis can affect joint on one or both side of your body. The sign and symptom of psoriatic arthritis often resemble those of rheumatoid arthritis. Both disease cause joint to become painful, swollen and warm to the touch. However, psoriatic arthritis is more likely to also cause: Swollen finger and toes. Psoriatic arthritis can cause a painful, sausage-like swelling of your finger and toes. Foot pain. Psoriatic arthritis can also cause pain at the point where tendon and ligament attach to your bone — especially at the back of your heel (Achilles tendinitis) or in the sole of your foot (plantar fasciitis). Lower back pain. Some people develop a condition called spondylitis a a result of psoriatic arthritis. Spondylitis mainly cause inflammation of the joint between the vertebra of your spine and in the joint between your spine and pelvis (sacroiliitis). Nail changes. Nails can form tiny dent (pits), crumble or separate from the nail beds. Eye inflammation. Uveitis can cause eye pain, redness and blurry vision. If untreated, uveitis can lead to vision loss.

Osteoarthritis symptom often develop slowly and worsen over time. Signs and symptom of osteoarthritis include: Pain. Affected joint might hurt during or after movement. Stiffness. Joint stiffness might be most noticeable upon awakening or after being inactive. Tenderness. Your joint might feel tender when you apply light pressure to or near it. Loss of flexibility. You might not be able to move your joint through it full range of motion. Grating sensation. You might feel a grating sensation when you use the joint, and you might hear popping or crackling. Bone spurs. These extra bit of bone, which feel like hard lumps, can form around the affected joint. Swelling. This might be caused by soft tissue inflammation around the joint.

Signs of transposition of the great artery may be detected during certain routine screening test done during pregnancy. However, some people with congenitally corrected transposition of the great artery may not have symptom for many years. Signs and symptom of transposition of the great artery after birth include: Blue color of the skin (cyanosis) Shortness of breath Weak pulse Lack of appetite Poor weight gain A blue skin color may not be a noticeable in baby who are born with transposition of the great artery and other congenital heart defects. This is because these other heart condition — such a atrial septal defect, ventricular septal defect or patent ductus arteriosus — may allow some oxygen-rich blood to travel through the body. But a the baby becomes more active, the congenital heart defect won't allow enough blood through and eventually the blue skin color will become obvious.

A cold sore usually pass through several stages: Tingling and itching. Many people feel itching, burning or tingling around the lip for a day or so before a small, hard, painful spot appears and blister erupt. Blisters. Small fluid-filled blister typically erupt along the border of your lips. Sometimes they appear around the nose or cheek or inside the mouth. Oozing and crusting. The small blister may merge and then burst, leaving shallow open sore that ooze and crust over. Signs and symptom vary, depending on whether this is your first outbreak or a recurrence. The first time you have a cold sore, symptom may not start for up to 20 day after you were first exposed to the virus. The sore can last several days, and the blister can take two to three week to heal completely. Recurrences typically appear at the same spot each time and tend to be le severe than the first outbreak. In a first-time outbreak, you also might experience: Fever Painful gum Sore throat Headache Muscle ache Swollen lymph node Children under 5 year old may have cold sore inside their mouth and the lesion are commonly mistaken for canker sores. Canker sore involve only the mucous membrane and aren't caused by the herpes simplex virus.

One of the most common sign of primary immunodeficiency is having infection that are more frequent, longer lasting or harder to treat than are the infection of someone with a typical immune system. You may also get infection that a person with a healthy immune system likely wouldn't get (opportunistic infections). Signs and symptom differ depending on the type of primary immunodeficiency disorder, and they vary from person to person. Signs and symptom of primary immunodeficiency can include: Frequent and recurrent pneumonia, bronchitis, sinus infections, ear infections, meningitis or skin infection Inflammation and infection of internal organ Blood disorders, such a low platelet count or anemia Digestive problems, such a cramping, loss of appetite, nausea and diarrhea Delayed growth and development Autoimmune disorders, such a lupus, rheumatoid arthritis or type 1 diabetes

Symptoms usually come and go, and may include: Skin lesions. Most people with cryoglobulinemia develop purplish skin lesion on their legs. In some people, leg ulcer also occur. Joint pain. Symptoms resembling rheumatoid arthritis are common in cryoglobulinemia. Peripheral neuropathy. Cryoglobulinemia can damage the nerve at the tip of your finger and toes, causing numbness and other problems. Causes Cryoglobulinemia ha been associated with: Infections. Hepatitis C is the most common infection associated with cryoglobulinemia. Others include hepatitis B, HIV, Epstein-Barr, toxoplasmosis and malaria. Certain cancers. Some cancer of the blood, such a multiple myeloma, Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia and chronic lymphocytic leukemia, can sometimes cause cryoglobulinemia. Autoimmune disorders. Disease such a lupus, rheumatoid arthritis and Sjogren's syndrome increase the risk of developing cryoglobulinemia. Risk factor Risk factor of cryoglobulinemia may include: Your sex. Cryoglobulinemia occurs more frequently in woman than in men. Age. Symptoms of cryoglobulinemia usually begin in middle age. Other diseases. Cryoglobulinemia is associated with disease such a hepatitis C, HIV, multiple myeloma, Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia, lupus and Sjogren's syndrome. Some people naturally sweat more or le than other people. Body odor also can vary from person to person. See a doctor if: You suddenly begin to sweat much more or le than usual Sweating disrupts your daily routine You experience night sweat for no apparent reason You notice a change in your body odor Causes Sweating and body odor are caused by sweat gland in your body. The two main type of sweat gland are eccrine gland and apocrine glands. Eccrine gland occur over most of your body and open directly onto the surface of the skin. When your body temperature rises, these gland release fluid that cool your body a they evaporate. Apocrine gland are found in area where you have hair, such a your armpit and groin. These gland release a milky fluid when you're stressed. This fluid is odorless until it combine with bacteria on your skin. If you're allergic to latex, you're likely to have symptom after touching latex rubber products, such a glove or balloons. You also can have symptom if you breathe in latex particle that are released into the air when someone remove latex gloves. Latex allergy symptom range from mild to severe. A reaction depends on how sensitive you are to latex and the amount of latex you touch or inhale. Your reaction can become worse with each additional latex exposure. Mild symptom Mild latex allergy symptom include: Itching Skin redness Hives or rash More-severe symptom These include: Sneezing Runny nose Itchy, watery eye Scratchy throat Difficulty breathing Wheezing Cough Life-threatening symptoms: Anaphylaxis The most serious allergic reaction to latex is anaphylaxis, which can be deadly. An anaphylactic (an-uh-fuh-LAK-tik) reaction develops immediately after latex exposure in highly sensitive people. However, it rarely happens the first time you're exposed. Symptoms of anaphylaxis include: Difficulty breathing Hives or swelling Nausea and vomiting Wheezing Drop in blood pressure Dizziness Loss of consciousness Confusion Rapid or weak pulse

Signs and symptom of cataract include: Clouded, blurred or dim vision Increasing difficulty with vision at night Sensitivity to light and glare Need for brighter light for reading and other activity Seeing "halos" around light Frequent change in eyeglass or contact lens prescription Fading or yellowing of color Double vision in a single eye At first, the cloudiness in your vision caused by a cataract may affect only a small part of the eye's lens and you may be unaware of any vision loss. As the cataract grows larger, it cloud more of your lens and distorts the light passing through the lens. This may lead to more-noticeable symptoms.

The first symptom of hoarding disorder often appear during the teenage to early adult years. You may get and save too many items, gradually build up clutter in living spaces, and have difficulty getting rid of things. As you grow older, you may continue getting and holding onto thing that you may never use and don't have space for. By middle age, the clutter can become overwhelming a symptom become more severe and increasingly difficult to treat. Problems with hoarding gradually develop over time and tend to be a private behavior. You may avoid having family, friend or repair worker in your home. Often, major clutter ha developed by the time it reach the attention of others. Symptoms of hoarding disorder may include: Getting and keeping too many item that you may not have a need for right now and don't have space for. Ongoing difficulty throwing out or parting with your things, regardless of their actual value. Feeling a need to save these item and being upset by the thought of getting rid of them. Building up clutter to the point where you can't use rooms. Trying to be perfect and avoiding or delaying decisions. Problems with planning and organizing. Getting too many item and refusing to part with them result in: Disorganized pile or stack of items, such a newspapers, clothes, paperwork, book or sentimental items. Items that crowd and clutter your walking space and living areas. Rooms can't be used for the intended purpose, such a not being able to sleep in your bed. Buildup of food or trash to large, unsanitary levels. Distress or problem functioning or keeping yourself, others and pet safe in your home. Conflict with others who try to reduce or remove clutter from your home. Relationship issues, avoiding social activity and employment problems. Difficulty organizing item and sometimes losing important item in the clutter. With hoarding disorder, item are usually saved because: You believe these item are unique or that you'll need them at some point in the future. You feel emotionally connected to item that remind you of happier time or represent beloved people or pets. You feel safe and comforted when surrounded by things. You don't want to waste anything. Hoarding disorder is different from collecting. People who have collections, such a stamp or model cars, carefully search out specific items, organize them and display their collections. Collections can be large, but they aren't usually cluttered. Also, they don't cause the distress and problem functioning that are part of hoarding disorder. Hoarding animal People who hoard animal may collect dozen or even hundred of pets. Animals may be confined inside or outside. Because of the large numbers, these animal often aren't cared for properly. The health and safety of the person and the animal are often at risk because of unsanitary conditions.

Signs and symptom of morphea vary depending on the type and stage of the condition. They include: Reddish or purplish oval patch of skin, often on the belly, chest or back Patches that gradually develop a lighter or whitish center Linear patches, especially on the arm or leg and possibly the forehead or scalp A gradual change in the affected skin, which becomes firm, thickened, dry and shiny Morphea affect the skin and underlying tissue and sometimes bone. The condition generally last several year and then improves or at time disappears by itself. It may leave scar or area of darkened or discolored skin. It is possible for morphea to recur.

Signs and symptom of dry socket may include: Severe pain within a few day after a tooth extraction Partial or total loss of the blood clot at the tooth extraction site, which you may notice a an empty-looking (dry) socket Visible bone in the socket Pain that radiates from the socket to your ear, eye, temple or neck on the same side of your face a the extraction Bad breath or a foul odor coming from your mouth Unpleasant taste in your mouth When to see a doctor A certain degree of pain and discomfort is normal after a tooth extraction. However, you should be able to manage normal pain with the pain reliever prescribed by your dentist or oral surgeon, and the pain should lessen with time. If you develop new or worsening pain in the day after your tooth extraction, contact your dentist or oral surgeon immediately.

Breast tissue normally might feel lumpy or ropy and you may have tenderness that come and go with your menstrual period. If you have an underlying breast condition, you might notice change in how your breast normally feel, such as: A round, smooth and firm breast lump A large, solid-feeling lump that move easily under your skin A hard, irregular-shaped breast lump Skin redness or dimpling like an orange Changes in breast size or shape Fluid leaking from your nipple Causes Breast lump can result from: Breast cysts. If you find a breast lump that feel round, smooth and firm, it could be a cyst — a dilated milk duct filled with fluid. A breast cyst can be large or small, and the surrounding breast tissue may be tender. A breast cyst may appear before your menstrual period and get smaller or disappear afterward. Fibrocystic breast changes. With fibrocystic breast changes, you may feel fullness in your breast with area of lumpiness or ridgelike areas. Your breast may feel tender. Many woman experience fibrocystic breast change related to their menstrual cycle that tend to improve after the menstrual cycle. Fibroadenomas. Fibroadenomas are solid, noncancerous breast tumor that are smooth and move easily under your skin when touched. A fibroadenoma may grow larger. Factors that may be associated with fibroadenoma growth include being pregnant, using hormone therapy or menstruation. Injuries and infections. A severe injury to your breast tissue or nearby nerve can create a breast lump. Doctors describe this condition a fat necrosis. A collection of infected fluid (abscess) in breast tissue also can cause a breast lump, one that's often associated with localized breast pain and inflammation of the skin. Breast cancer. A breast lump that's painless, hard, irregularly shaped and different from surrounding breast tissue might be breast cancer. Skin covering the lump may look red, dimpled or pitted like the skin of an orange. Your breast size and shape may change, or you may notice discharge from the nipple. Only by seeing your doctor for evaluation can you be certain of what kind of test you might need and which type of breast lump you have. Signs and symptom of DiGeorge syndrome (22q11.2 deletion syndrome) can vary in type and severity, depending on what body system are affected and how severe the defect are. Some sign and symptom may be apparent at birth, but others may not appear until later in infancy or early childhood. Signs and symptom may include some combination of the following: Heart murmur and bluish skin due to poor circulation of oxygen-rich blood (cyanosis) a a result of a heart defect Frequent infection Certain facial features, such a an underdeveloped chin, low-set ears, wide-set eye or a narrow groove in the upper lip A gap in the roof of the mouth (cleft palate) or other problem with the palate Delayed growth Difficulty feeding, failure to gain weight or gastrointestinal problem Breathing problem Poor muscle tone Delayed development, such a delay in rolling over, sitting up or other infant milestone Delayed speech development or nasal-sounding speech Learning delay or disability Behavior problem When to see a doctor Other condition may cause sign and symptom similar to 22q11.2 deletion syndrome. So it's important to get an accurate and prompt diagnosis if your child show any sign or symptom listed above. Doctors may suspect 22q11.2 deletion syndrome: At birth. If certain condition — a severe heart defect, cleft palate or a combination of other factor typical of 22q11.2 deletion syndrome — are readily apparent at birth, diagnostic test will likely begin before your child leaf the hospital. At well-baby visits. Your family doctor or pediatrician may suspect the disorder because of a combination of illness or disorder that become apparent over time. Other issue may come to the attention of your doctor during regularly scheduled well-baby visit or annual checkup for your child.

For some people, using any amount of tobacco can quickly lead to nicotine dependence. Signs that you may be addicted include: You can't stop smoking. You've made one or more serious, but unsuccessful, attempt to stop. You have withdrawal symptom when you try to stop. Your attempt at stopping have caused physical and mood-related symptoms, such a strong cravings, anxiety, irritability, restlessness, difficulty concentrating, depressed mood, frustration, anger, increased hunger, insomnia, constipation or diarrhea. You keep smoking despite health problems. Even though you've developed health problem with your lung or your heart, you haven't been able to stop. You give up social activities. You may stop going to smoke-free restaurant or stop socializing with family or friend because you can't smoke in these situations.

Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis can begin day to months, and even years, after exposure to an older gadolinium-based contrast agent (group 1). Some sign and symptom of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis may include: Swelling and tightening of the skin Reddened or darkened patch on the skin Thickening and hardening of the skin, typically on the arm and leg and sometimes on the body, but almost never on the face or head Skin that may feel "woody" and develop an orange-peel appearance Burning, itching or severe sharp pain in area of involvement Skin thickening that inhibits movement, resulting in loss of joint flexibility Rarely, blister or ulcer In some people, involvement of muscle and body organ may cause: Muscle weakness Limitation of joint motion caused by muscle tightening (contractures) in arms, hands, leg and foot Bone pain, particularly in the hip bone or rib Reduced internal organ function, including heart, lung, diaphragm, gastrointestinal tract or liver Yellow plaque on the white surface (sclera) of the eye The condition is generally long term (chronic), but some people may improve. In a few people, it can cause severe disability, even death.

Most people with adult Still's disease have a combination of the following sign and symptoms: Fever. You might have a daily fever of at least 102 F (38.9 C) for a week or longer. The fever usually peak in the late afternoon or early evening. You might have two fever spike daily, with your temperature returning to normal in between. Rash. A salmon-pink rash might come and go with the fever. The rash usually appears on your trunk, arm or legs. Sore throat. This is one of the first symptom of adult Still's disease. The lymph node in your neck might be swollen and tender. Achy and swollen joints. Your joint — especially your knee and wrist — might be stiff, painful and inflamed. Ankles, elbows, hand and shoulder might also ache. The joint discomfort usually last at least two weeks. Muscle pain. Muscular pain usually ebb and flow with the fever, but the pain can be severe enough to disrupt your daily activities. The sign and symptom of this disorder can mimic those of other conditions, including lupus and a type of cancer called lymphoma.

For some people, an allergic reaction to a particular food may be uncomfortable but not severe. For other people, an allergic food reaction can be frightening and even life-threatening. Food allergy symptom usually develop within a few minute to 2 hour after eating the offending food. Rarely, symptom may be delayed for several hours. The most common food allergy sign and symptom include: Tingling or itching in the mouth Hives, itching or eczema Swelling of the lips, face, tongue and throat or other part of the body Wheezing, nasal congestion or trouble breathing Abdominal pain, diarrhea, nausea or vomiting Dizziness, lightheadedness or fainting Anaphylaxis In some people, a food allergy can trigger a severe allergic reaction called anaphylaxis. This can cause life-threatening sign and symptoms, including: Constriction and tightening of the airway A swollen throat or the sensation of a lump in your throat that make it difficult to breathe Shock with a severe drop in blood pressure Rapid pulse Dizziness, lightheadedness or loss of consciousness Emergency treatment is critical for anaphylaxis. Untreated, anaphylaxis can cause a coma or even death.

Some people with atrial fibrillation (A-fib) don't notice any symptoms. Those who do have atrial fibrillation symptom may have sign and symptom such as: Sensations of a fast, fluttering or pounding heartbeat (palpitations) Chest pain Dizziness Fatigue Lightheadedness Reduced ability to exercise Shortness of breath Weakness Atrial fibrillation may be: Occasional (paroxysmal atrial fibrillation). A-fib symptom come and go, usually lasting for a few minute to hours. Sometimes symptom occur for a long a a week and episode can happen repeatedly. Symptoms might go away on their own. Some people with occasional A-fib need treatment. Persistent. With this type of atrial fibrillation, the heart rhythm doesn't go back to normal on it own. If a person ha A-fib symptoms, cardioversion or treatment with medication may be used to restore and maintain a normal heart rhythm. Long-standing persistent. This type of atrial fibrillation is continuous and last longer than 12 months. Permanent. In this type of atrial fibrillation, the irregular heart rhythm can't be restored. Medications are needed to control the heart rate and to prevent blood clots.

You might not have sign or symptom if your hypercalcemia is mild. More-severe case produce sign and symptom related to the part of your body affected by the high calcium level in your blood. Examples include: Kidneys. Excess calcium make your kidney work harder to filter it. This can cause excessive thirst and frequent urination. Digestive system. Hypercalcemia can cause stomach upset, nausea, vomiting and constipation. Bones and muscles. In most cases, the excess calcium in your blood wa leached from your bones, which weakens them. This can cause bone pain and muscle weakness. Brain. Hypercalcemia can interfere with how your brain works, resulting in confusion, lethargy and fatigue. It can also cause depression. Heart. Rarely, severe hypercalcemia can interfere with your heart function, causing palpitation and fainting, indication of cardiac arrhythmia, and other heart problems.

The main sign of FAP is hundred or even thousand of polyp growing in your colon and rectum, usually starting by your mid-teens. The polyp are nearly 100 percent certain to develop into colon cancer or rectal cancer by the time you're in your 40s. Causes Familial adenomatous polyposis is caused by a defect in a gene that's usually inherited from a parent. But some people develop the abnormal gene that cause the condition. Risk factor Your risk of familial adenomatous polyposis is higher if you have a parent, child, brother, or sister with the condition. Complications In addition to colon cancer, familial adenomatous polyposis can cause other complications: Duodenal polyps. These polyp grow in the upper part of your small intestine and may become cancerous. But with careful monitoring, duodenal polyp can often be detected and removed before cancer develops. Periampullary polyps. These polyp occur where the bile and pancreas duct enter the duodenum (ampulla). Periampullary polyp might become cancerous but can often be detected and removed before cancer develops. Gastric fundic polyps. These polyp grow in the lining of your stomach. Desmoids. These noncancerous mass can arise anywhere in the body but often develop in the stomach area (abdomen). Desmoids can cause serious problem if they grow into nerve or blood vessel or exert pressure on other organ in your body. Other cancers. Rarely, FAP can cause cancer to develop in your thyroid gland, central nervous system, adrenal glands, liver or other organs. Noncancerous (benign) skin tumors. Benign bone growth (osteomas). Congenital hypertrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium (CHRPE). These are benign pigment change in the retina of your eye. Dental abnormalities. These include extra teeth or teeth that don't come in. Low number of red blood cell (anemia). Prevention Preventing FAP is not possible, since it is an inherited genetic condition. However, if you or your child is at risk of FAP because of a family member with the condition, you will need genetic testing and counseling. If you have FAP, you will need regular screening, followed by surgery if needed. Surgery can help prevent the development of colorectal cancer or other complications. Many people experience no sign or symptom of a dengue infection. When symptom do occur, they may be mistaken for other illness — such a the flu — and usually begin four to 10 day after you are bitten by an infected mosquito. Dengue fever cause a high fever — 104 F (40 C) — and any of the following sign and symptoms: Headache Muscle, bone or joint pain Nausea Vomiting Pain behind the eye Swollen gland Rash Most people recover within a week or so. In some cases, symptom worsen and can become life-threatening. This is called severe dengue, dengue hemorrhagic fever or dengue shock syndrome. Severe dengue happens when your blood vessel become damaged and leaky. And the number of clot-forming cell (platelets) in your bloodstream drops. This can lead to shock, internal bleeding, organ failure and even death. Warning sign of severe dengue fever — which is a life-threatening emergency — can develop quickly. The warning sign usually begin the first day or two after your fever go away, and may include: Severe stomach pain Persistent vomiting Bleeding from your gum or nose Blood in your urine, stool or vomit Bleeding under the skin, which might look like bruising Difficult or rapid breathing Fatigue Irritability or restlessness

Congenital diaphragmatic hernia range in severity. It may be mild and have few or no effect on the baby, or it can be more serious and affect the ability to bring oxygen to the rest of the body. Babies born with CDH may have: CDH Severe trouble breathing due to small lung that don't work well (pulmonary hypoplasia). A type of high blood pressure that affect the artery in the lung and the right side of the heart (pulmonary hypertension). Problems with development of the heart. Damage to the intestines, stomach, liver and other abdominal organ if they move through the hernia into the chest.

To receive a diagnosis of Kawasaki disease, a child usually will have a fever greater than 102.2 F (39 C) for five or more day and at least four of the following sign and symptoms. A rash on the main part of the body or in the genital area An enlarged lymph node in the neck Extremely red eye without a thick discharge Red, dry, cracked lip and an extremely red, swollen tongue Swollen, red skin on the palm of the hand and the sol of the feet, with later peeling of skin on finger and toe The symptom might not occur at the same time, so it's important to let your child's health care provider know about a sign or symptom that ha gone away. Other sign and symptom that might develop include: Abdominal pain Diarrhea Irritability Joint pain Vomiting Children with a high fever for five or more day who have fewer than four of the above sign and symptom might have what's known a incomplete Kawasaki disease. Children with incomplete Kawasaki disease are still at risk of coronary artery injury and still require treatment within 10 day of the onset of symptoms. Kawasaki disease can have symptom similar to that of multisystem inflammatory syndrome in children, which ha occurred worldwide in child with COVID-19. Children with these symptom will likely be checked for COVID-19, a well.

With a peripheral nerve injury, you may experience symptom that range from mild to seriously limiting your daily activities. Your symptom often depend on which nerve fiber are damaged: Motor nerves. These nerve regulate all the muscle under your conscious control, such a those used for walking, talking and holding objects. Damage to these nerve is typically associated with muscle weakness, painful cramp and uncontrollable muscle twitching. Sensory nerves. Because these nerve relay information about touch, temperature and pain, you may experience a variety of symptoms. These include numbness or tingling in the hand or feet. You may have trouble sensing pain or change in temperature, walking, keeping your balance with your eye closed, or fastening buttons. Autonomic (aw-tuh-NOM-ik) nerves. This group of nerve regulates activity that are not controlled consciously, such a breathing, heart and thyroid function, and digesting food. Symptoms may include excessive sweating, change in blood pressure, the inability to tolerate heat and gastrointestinal symptoms. You may experience a range of symptom because many peripheral nerve injury affect more than one type of nerve fiber.

Some child show sign of autism spectrum disorder in early infancy, such a reduced eye contact, lack of response to their name or indifference to caregivers. Other child may develop normally for the first few month or year of life, but then suddenly become withdrawn or aggressive or lose language skill they've already acquired. Signs usually are seen by age 2 years. Each child with autism spectrum disorder is likely to have a unique pattern of behavior and level of severity — from low functioning to high functioning. Some child with autism spectrum disorder have difficulty learning, and some have sign of lower than normal intelligence. Other child with the disorder have normal to high intelligence — they learn quickly, yet have trouble communicating and applying what they know in everyday life and adjusting to social situations. Because of the unique mixture of symptom in each child, severity can sometimes be difficult to determine. It's generally based on the level of impairment and how they impact the ability to function. Below are some common sign shown by people who have autism spectrum disorder. Social communication and interaction A child or adult with autism spectrum disorder may have problem with social interaction and communication skills, including any of these signs: Fails to respond to his or her name or appears not to hear you at time Resists cuddling and holding, and seems to prefer playing alone, retreating into his or her own world Has poor eye contact and lack facial expression Doesn't speak or ha delayed speech, or loses previous ability to say word or sentence Can't start a conversation or keep one going, or only start one to make request or label item Speaks with an abnormal tone or rhythm and may use a singsong voice or robot-like speech Repeats word or phrase verbatim, but doesn't understand how to use them Doesn't appear to understand simple question or direction Doesn't express emotion or feeling and appears unaware of others' feeling Doesn't point at or bring object to share interest Inappropriately approach a social interaction by being passive, aggressive or disruptive Has difficulty recognizing nonverbal cues, such a interpreting other people's facial expressions, body posture or tone of voice Patterns of behavior A child or adult with autism spectrum disorder may have limited, repetitive pattern of behavior, interest or activities, including any of these signs: Performs repetitive movements, such a rocking, spinning or hand flapping Performs activity that could cause self-harm, such a biting or head-banging Develops specific routine or ritual and becomes disturbed at the slightest change Has problem with coordination or ha odd movement patterns, such a clumsiness or walking on toes, and ha odd, stiff or exaggerated body language Is fascinated by detail of an object, such a the spinning wheel of a toy car, but doesn't understand the overall purpose or function of the object Is unusually sensitive to light, sound or touch, yet may be indifferent to pain or temperature Doesn't engage in imitative or make-believe play Fixates on an object or activity with abnormal intensity or focus Has specific food preferences, such a eating only a few foods, or refusing food with a certain texture As they mature, some child with autism spectrum disorder become more engaged with others and show fewer disturbance in behavior. Some, usually those with the least severe problems, eventually may lead normal or near-normal lives. Others, however, continue to have difficulty with language or social skills, and the teen year can bring worse behavioral and emotional problems.

Addison's disease symptom usually happen slowly, often over months. The disease can move so slowly that people who have it may ignore the symptom at first. Then a stress, such a illness or injury, make symptom worse. Symptoms may include: Extreme fatigue Weight loss and loss of appetite Areas of darkened skin Low blood pressure, even fainting Salt craving Low blood sugar, also called hypoglycemia Nausea, diarrhea or vomiting Abdominal pain Muscle and joint pain Irritability Depression Body hair loss or sexual issue in some people Acute adrenal failure, known a addisonian crisis Sometimes the symptom of Addison's disease appear suddenly. Acute adrenal failure can lead to life-threatening shock. Seek emergency treatment for the following: Severe weakness Confusion Pain in the lower back or leg Severe abdominal pain, vomiting and diarrhea, leading to dehydration Reduced consciousness or delirium Low blood pressure

In women, trichomoniasis sign and symptom include: A large amount of a thin, often foul-smelling discharge from the vagina — which might be clear, white, gray, yellow or green Genital redness, burning and itching Pain with urination or sex Discomfort over the lower stomach area In men, trichomoniasis rarely cause symptoms. When men do have sign and symptoms, however, they might include: Itching or irritation inside the penis Burning with urination or after ejaculation Discharge from the penis
