Traumatic brain injury can have wide-ranging physical and psychological effects. Some sign or symptom may appear immediately after the traumatic event, while others may appear day or week later. Mild traumatic brain injury The sign and symptom of mild traumatic brain injury may include: Physical symptom Headache Nausea or vomiting Fatigue or drowsiness Problems with speech Dizziness or loss of balance Sensory symptom Sensory problems, such a blurred vision, ringing in the ears, a bad taste in the mouth or change in the ability to smell Sensitivity to light or sound Cognitive, behavioral or mental symptom Loss of consciousness for a few second to a few minute No loss of consciousness, but a state of being dazed, confused or disoriented Memory or concentration problem Mood change or mood swing Feeling depressed or anxious Difficulty sleeping Sleeping more than usual Moderate to severe traumatic brain injury Moderate to severe traumatic brain injury can include any of the sign and symptom of mild injury, a well a these symptom that may appear within the first hour to day after a head injury: Physical symptom Loss of consciousness from several minute to hour Persistent headache or headache that worsens Repeated vomiting or nausea Convulsions or seizure Dilation of one or both pupil of the eye Clear fluid draining from the nose or ear Inability to awaken from sleep Weakness or numbness in finger and toe Loss of coordination Cognitive or mental symptom Profound confusion Agitation, combativeness or other unusual behavior Slurred speech Coma and other disorder of consciousness Children's symptom Infants and young child with brain injury might not be able to communicate headaches, sensory problems, confusion and similar symptoms. In a child with traumatic brain injury, you may observe: Change in eating or nursing habit Unusual or easy irritability Persistent cry and inability to be consoled Change in ability to pay attention Change in sleep habit Seizures Sad or depressed mood Drowsiness Loss of interest in favorite toy or activity

The most common sign and symptom of juvenile idiopathic arthritis are: Pain. While your child might not complain of joint pain, you may notice that he or she limp — especially first thing in the morning or after a nap. Swelling. Joint swelling is common but is often first noticed in larger joint such a the knee. Stiffness. You might notice that your child appears clumsier than usual, particularly in the morning or after naps. Fever, swollen lymph node and rash. In some cases, high fever, swollen lymph node or a rash on the trunk may occur — which is usually worse in the evenings. Juvenile idiopathic arthritis can affect one joint or many. There are several different subtypes of juvenile idiopathic arthritis, but the main one are systemic, oligoarticular and polyarticular. Which type your child ha depends on symptoms, the number of joint affected, and if a fever and rash are prominent features. Like other form of arthritis, juvenile idiopathic arthritis is characterized by time when symptom flare up and time when symptom may be minimal.

Hidradenitis suppurativa can affect one or several area of the body. Signs and symptom of the condition include: Blackheads. Blackheads appear in small pitted area of skin, often appearing in pairs. Painful pea-sized lumps. The condition usually start with a single, painful lump under the skin that persists for week or months. More bump may form later, usually in area where you have more sweat and oil gland or where the skin rub together, such a the armpits, groin, buttock and breasts. Leaking bump or sores. Some bump or sore get bigger, break open and drain pu with an odor. Tunnels. Over time, tunnel might form under the skin, connecting the lumps. These wound heal very slowly, if at all, and drain blood and pus. Some people with this condition experience only mild symptoms. The course of the disease is highly variable. Excess weight and being a smoker are associated with worse symptoms, but even people who are thin and don't smoke can experience severe disease.

Signs and symptom depend on the type of adjustment disorder and can vary from person to person. You experience more stress than would normally be expected in response to a stressful event, and the stress cause significant problem in your life. Adjustment disorder affect how you feel and think about yourself and the world and may also affect your action or behavior. Some example include: Feeling sad, hopeless or not enjoying thing you used to enjoy Frequent cry Worrying or feeling anxious, nervous, jittery or stressed out Trouble sleeping Lack of appetite Difficulty concentrating Feeling overwhelmed Difficulty functioning in daily activity Withdrawing from social support Avoiding important thing such a going to work or paying bill Suicidal thought or behavior Symptoms of an adjustment disorder start within three month of a stressful event and last no longer than 6 month after the end of the stressful event. However, persistent or chronic adjustment disorder can continue for more than 6 months, especially if the stressor is ongoing, such a unemployment. When to see a doctor Usually stressor are temporary, and we learn to cope with them over time. Symptoms of adjustment disorder get better because the stress ha eased. But sometimes the stressful event remains a part of your life. Or a new stressful situation come up, and you face the same emotional struggle all over again. Talk to your doctor if you continue to struggle or if you're having trouble getting through each day. You can get treatment to help you cope better with stressful event and feel better about life again. If you have concern about your child's adjustment or behavior, talk with your child's pediatrician. Suicidal thought or behavior If you have thought of hurting yourself or someone else, call 911 or your local emergency number immediately, go to an emergency room, or confide in a trusted relative or friend. Or contact a suicide hotline. In the U.S., call or text 988 to reach the 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline, available 24 hour a day, seven day a week. Or use the Lifeline Chat. Services are free and confidential.

Generalized anxiety disorder symptom can vary. They may include: Persistent worrying or anxiety about a number of area that are out of proportion to the impact of the event Overthinking plan and solution to all possible worst-case outcome Perceiving situation and event a threatening, even when they aren't Difficulty handling uncertainty Indecisiveness and fear of making the wrong decision Inability to set aside or let go of a worry Inability to relax, feeling restless, and feeling keyed up or on edge Difficulty concentrating, or the feeling that your mind "goes blank" Physical sign and symptom may include: Fatigue Trouble sleeping Muscle tension or muscle ache Trembling, feeling twitchy Nervousness or being easily startled Sweating Nausea, diarrhea or irritable bowel syndrome Irritability There may be time when your worry don't completely consume you, but you still feel anxious even when there's no apparent reason. For example, you may feel intense worry about your safety or that of your loved ones, or you may have a general sense that something bad is about to happen. Your anxiety, worry or physical symptom cause you significant distress in social, work or other area of your life. Worries can shift from one concern to another and may change with time and age. Symptoms in child and teenager Children and teenager may have similar worry to adults, but also may have excessive worry about: Performance at school or sporting event Family members' safety Being on time (punctuality) Earthquakes, nuclear war or other catastrophic event A child or teen with excessive worry may: Feel overly anxious to fit in Be a perfectionist Redo task because they aren't perfect the first time Spend excessive time doing homework Lack confidence Strive for approval Require a lot of reassurance about performance Have frequent stomachache or other physical complaint Avoid going to school or avoid social situation When to see a doctor Some anxiety is normal, but see your doctor if: You feel like you're worrying too much, and it's interfering with your work, relationship or other part of your life You feel depressed or irritable, have trouble with drinking or drugs, or you have other mental health concern along with anxiety You have suicidal thought or behavior — seek emergency treatment immediately Your worry are unlikely to simply go away on their own, and they may actually get worse over time. Try to seek professional help before your anxiety becomes severe — it may be easier to treat early on.

Hay fever symptom can include: Runny nose and nasal stuffiness (congestion) Watery, itchy, red eye (allergic conjunctivitis) Sneezing Cough Itchy nose, roof of mouth or throat Mucus that run down the back of your throat (postnasal drip) Swollen, bruised-appearing skin under the eye (allergic shiners) Extreme tiredness (fatigue), often due to poor sleep Hay fever trigger Your hay fever sign and symptom may occur year-round or may start or worsen at a particular time of year (seasonal). Hay fever trigger include: Tree pollen, which is common in early spring Grass pollen, which is common in late spring and summer Ragweed pollen, which is common in fall Dust mite and cockroach droppings, which are present year-round Dander from pets, which can be bothersome year-round but might cause worse symptom in winter, when house are closed up Spores from indoor and outdoor fungi and molds, which can be both seasonal and year-round Hay fever or common cold? Symptoms can be similar, so it can be difficult to tell which one you have. The main symptom of transient global amnesia is being unable to create new memory and remember the recent past. Once that symptom is confirmed, ruling out other possible cause of amnesia is important. You must have these sign and symptom to be diagnosed with transient global amnesia: Sudden onset of confusion that includes memory loss, seen by a witness Being awake and alert and knowing who you are, despite memory loss Normal cognition, such a the ability to recognize and name familiar object and follow simple direction No sign of damage to a particular area of the brain, such a being unable to move an arm or leg, movement you can't control, or problem understanding word More symptom and history that may help diagnose transient global amnesia: Symptoms lasting no more than 24 hour and generally shorter Gradual return of memory No recent head injury No sign of seizure during the period of amnesia No history of active epilepsy Another common sign of transient global amnesia due to the inability to create new memory includes repetitive questioning, usually of the same question — for example, "What am I doing here?" or "How did we get here?"

Persistent and recurrent episode of depersonalization or derealization or both cause distress and problem functioning at work or school or in other important area of your life. During these episodes, you are aware that your sense of detachment is only a feeling and not reality. The experience and feeling of the disorder can be difficult to describe. Worry about "going crazy" can cause you to become preoccupied with checking that you exist and determining what's actually real. Symptoms usually begin in the mid- to late teen or early adulthood. Depersonalization-derealization disorder is rare in child and older adults. Depersonalization symptom Symptoms of depersonalization include: Feelings that you're an outside observer of your thoughts, feelings, your body or part of your body — for example, a if you were floating in air above yourself Feeling like a robot or that you're not in control of your speech or movement The sense that your body, leg or arm appear distorted, enlarged or shrunken, or that your head is wrapped in cotton Emotional or physical numbness of your sens or response to the world around you A sense that your memory lack emotion, and that they may or may not be your own memory Derealization symptom Symptoms of derealization include: Feelings of being alienated from or unfamiliar with your surroundings — for example, like you're living in a movie or a dream Feeling emotionally disconnected from people you care about, a if you were separated by a glass wall Surroundings that appear distorted, blurry, colorless, two-dimensional or artificial, or a heightened awareness and clarity of your surroundings Distortions in perception of time, such a recent event feeling like distant past Distortions of distance and the size and shape of object Episodes of depersonalization-derealization disorder may last hours, days, week or even month at a time. In some people, these episode turn into ongoing feeling of depersonalization or derealization that may periodically get better or worse.

Most people infected with ascariasis have no sign or symptoms. Moderate to heavy infestation cause various sign or symptoms, depending on which part of your body is affected. In the lung After you swallow the tiny (microscopic) ascariasis eggs, they hatch in the small intestine and the larva migrate through the bloodstream or lymphatic system into the lungs. At this stage, you may experience sign and symptom similar to asthma or pneumonia, including: Persistent cough Shortness of breath Wheezing After spending 10 to 14 day in the lungs, the larva travel to the throat, where you cough them up and then swallow them. In the intestine The larva mature into adult worm in the small intestine, and the adult worm typically live in the intestine until they die. In mild or moderate ascariasis, the intestinal infestation can cause: Vague abdominal pain Nausea and vomiting Diarrhea or bloody stool If you have a large number of worm in the intestine, you might have: Severe abdominal pain Fatigue Vomiting Weight loss or malnutrition A worm in your vomit or stool

By definition, chronic daily headache occur 15 day or more a month, for longer than three months. True (primary) chronic daily headache aren't caused by another condition. There are short-lasting and long-lasting chronic daily headaches. Long-lasting headache last more than four hours. They include: Chronic migraine Chronic tension-type headache New daily persistent headache Hemicrania continuum Chronic migraine This type typically occurs in people with a history of episodic migraines. Chronic migraine tend to: Affect one side or both side of your head Have a pulsating, throbbing sensation Cause moderate to severe pain And they cause at least one of the following: Nausea, vomiting or both Sensitivity to light and sound Chronic tension-type headache These headache tend to: Affect both side of your head Cause mild to moderate pain Cause pain that feel pressing or tightening, but not pulsating New daily persistent headache These headache come on suddenly, usually in people without a headache history. They become constant within three day of your first headache. They: Often affect both side of your head Cause pain that feel like pressing or tightening, but not pulsating Cause mild to moderate pain Might have feature of chronic migraine or chronic tension-type headache Hemicrania continuum These headaches: Affect only one side of your head Are daily and continuous with no pain-free period Cause moderate pain with spike of severe pain Respond to the prescription pain reliever indomethacin (Indocin) Can become severe with development of migraine-like symptom In addition, hemicrania continuum headache are associated with at least one of the following: Tearing or redness of the eye on the affected side Nasal congestion or runny nose Drooping eyelid or pupil narrowing Sensation of restlessness

Signs and symptom of CRPS include: CRPS Continuous burning or throbbing pain, usually in the arm, leg, hand or foot Sensitivity to touch or cold Swelling of the painful area Changes in skin temperature — alternating between sweaty and cold Changes in skin color, ranging from white and blotchy to red or blue Changes in skin texture, which may become tender, thin or shiny in the affected area Changes in hair and nail growth Joint stiffness, swelling and damage Muscle spasms, tremor and weakness (atrophy) Decreased ability to move the affected body part Symptoms may change over time and vary from person to person. Pain, swelling, redness, noticeable change in temperature and hypersensitivity (particularly to cold and touch) usually occur first. Over time, the affected limb can become cold and pale. It may undergo skin and nail change a well a muscle spasm and tightening. Once these change occur, the condition is often irreversible. CRPS occasionally may spread from it source to elsewhere in the body, such a the opposite limb. CRPS In some people, sign and symptom of CRPS go away on their own. In others, sign and symptom may persist for month to years. Treatment is likely to be most effective when started early in the course of the illness.

Lipomas can occur anywhere in the body. They are typically: Situated just under the skin. They commonly occur in the neck, shoulders, back, abdomen, arm and thighs. Soft and doughy to the touch. They also move easily with slight finger pressure. Generally small. Lipomas are typically le than 2 inch (5 centimeters) in diameter, but they can grow. Sometimes painful. Lipomas can be painful if they grow and press on nearby nerve or if they contain many blood vessels.

Most people with binge-eating disorder are overweight or obese, but you may be at a normal weight. Behavioral and emotional sign and symptom of binge-eating disorder include: Eating unusually large amount of food in a specific amount of time, such a over a two-hour period Feeling that your eating behavior is out of control Eating even when you're full or not hungry Eating rapidly during binge episode Eating until you're uncomfortably full Frequently eating alone or in secret Feeling depressed, disgusted, ashamed, guilty or upset about your eating Frequently dieting, possibly without weight loss Unlike a person with bulimia, after a binge, you don't regularly compensate for extra calorie eaten by vomiting, using laxative or exercising excessively. You may try to diet or eat normal meals. But restricting your diet may simply lead to more binge eating. The severity of binge-eating disorder is determined by how often episode of bingeing occur during a week.

Basal cell carcinoma usually develops on sun-exposed part of your body, especially your head and neck. Less often, basal cell carcinoma can develop on part of your body usually protected from the sun, such a the genitals. Basal cell carcinoma appears a a change in the skin, such a a growth or a sore that won't heal. These change in the skin (lesions) usually have one of the following characteristics: A shiny, skin-colored bump that's translucent, meaning you can see a bit through the surface. The bump can look pearly white or pink on white skin. On brown and Black skin, the bump often look brown or glossy black. Tiny blood vessel might be visible, though they may be difficult to see on brown and Black skin. The bump may bleed and scab over. A brown, black or blue lesion — or a lesion with dark spot — with a slightly raised, translucent border. A flat, scaly patch with a raised edge. Over time, these patch can grow quite large. A white, waxy, scar-like lesion without a clearly defined border.

Suicide warning sign or suicidal thought include: Talking about suicide — for example, making statement such a "I'm going to kill myself," "I wish I were dead" or "I wish I hadn't been born" Getting the mean to take your own life, such a buying a gun or stockpiling pill Withdrawing from social contact and wanting to be left alone Having mood swings, such a being emotionally high one day and deeply discouraged the next Being preoccupied with death, dying or violence Feeling trapped or hopeless about a situation Increasing use of alcohol or drug Changing normal routine, including eating or sleeping pattern Doing risky or self-destructive things, such a using drug or driving recklessly Giving away belonging or getting affair in order when there's no other logical explanation for doing this Saying goodbye to people a if they won't be seen again Developing personality change or being severely anxious or agitated, particularly when experiencing some of the warning sign listed above Warning sign aren't always obvious, and they may vary from person to person. Some people make their intention clear, while others keep suicidal thought and feeling secret.

Pericardial mesothelioma, which affect tissue that surround the heart, can cause sign and symptom such a breathing difficulty and chest pains. Mesothelioma of tunica vaginalis, which affect tissue surrounding the testicles, may be first detected a swelling or a mass on a testicle.

Children The first sign of intussusception in an otherwise healthy infant may be sudden, loud cry caused by belly pain. Infants who have belly pain may pull their knee to their chest when they cry. The pain of intussusception come and goes, usually every 15 to 20 minute at first. These painful episode last longer and happen more often a time passes. Other symptom of intussusception include: Stool mixed with blood and mucus — sometimes referred to a currant jelly stool because of it appearance. Vomiting. A lump in the belly. Weakness or lack of energy. Diarrhea. Not everyone ha all of the symptoms. Some infant have no obvious pain. Some child don't pas blood or have a lump in the belly. And some older child have pain but no other symptoms. Adults Intussusception is rare in adults. Also, because symptom of the disorder often overlap with the symptom of other disorders, it's more challenging to identify. The most common symptom is belly pain that come and goes. Nausea and vomiting also may occur. People sometimes have symptom for week before seeking medical attention.

Placental abruption is most likely to occur in the last trimester of pregnancy, especially in the last few week before birth. Signs and symptom of placental abruption include: Vaginal bleeding, although there might not be any Abdominal pain Back pain Uterine tenderness or rigidity Uterine contractions, often coming one right after another Abdominal pain and back pain often begin suddenly. The amount of vaginal bleeding can vary greatly, and doesn't necessarily indicate how much of the placenta ha separated from the uterus. It's possible for the blood to become trapped inside the uterus, so even with a severe placental abruption, there might be no visible bleeding. In some cases, placental abruption develops slowly (chronic abruption), which can cause light, intermittent vaginal bleeding. Your baby might not grow a quickly a expected, and you might have low amniotic fluid or other complications.

Post-traumatic stress disorder symptom may start within one month of a traumatic event, but sometimes symptom may not appear until year after the event. These symptom cause significant problem in social or work situation and in relationships. They can also interfere with your ability to go about your normal daily tasks. PTSD symptom are generally grouped into four types: intrusive memories, avoidance, negative change in thinking and mood, and change in physical and emotional reactions. Symptoms can vary over time or vary from person to person. Intrusive memory Intrusive memory Symptoms of intrusive memory may include: Recurrent, unwanted distressing memory of the traumatic event Reliving the traumatic event a if it were happening again (flashbacks) Upsetting dream or nightmare about the traumatic event Severe emotional distress or physical reaction to something that reminds you of the traumatic event Avoidance Avoidance Symptoms of avoidance may include: Trying to avoid thinking or talking about the traumatic event Avoiding places, activity or people that remind you of the traumatic event Negative change in thinking and mood Negative change in thinking and mood Symptoms of negative change in thinking and mood may include: Negative thought about yourself, other people or the world Hopelessness about the future Memory problems, including not remembering important aspect of the traumatic event Difficulty maintaining close relationship Feeling detached from family and friend Lack of interest in activity you once enjoyed Difficulty experiencing positive emotion Feeling emotionally numb Changes in physical and emotional reaction Changes in physical and emotional reaction Symptoms of change in physical and emotional reaction (also called arousal symptoms) may include: Being easily startled or frightened Always being on guard for danger Self-destructive behavior, such a drinking too much or driving too fast Trouble sleeping Trouble concentrating Irritability, angry outburst or aggressive behavior Overwhelming guilt or shame For child 6 year old and younger, sign and symptom may also include: Re-enacting the traumatic event or aspect of the traumatic event through play Frightening dream that may or may not include aspect of the traumatic event Intensity of symptom Intensity of symptom PTSD symptom can vary in intensity over time. You may have more PTSD symptom when you're stressed in general, or when you come across reminder of what you went through. For example, you may hear a car backfire and relive combat experiences. Or you may see a report on the news about a sexual assault and feel overcome by memory of your own assault. When to see a doctor When to see a doctor If you have disturbing thought and feeling about a traumatic event for more than a month, if they're severe, or if you feel you're having trouble getting your life back under control, talk to your doctor or a mental health professional. Getting treatment a soon a possible can help prevent PTSD symptom from getting worse. If you have suicidal thought If you have suicidal thought If you or someone you know ha suicidal thoughts, get help right away through one or more of these resources: Reach out to a close friend or loved one. Contact a minister, a spiritual leader or someone in your faith community. Contact a suicide hotline. In the U.S., call or text 988 to reach the 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline, available 24 hour a day, seven day a week. Or use the Lifeline Chat. Services are free and confidential. Make an appointment with your doctor or a mental health professional. When to get emergency help When to get emergency help If you think you may hurt yourself or attempt suicide, call 911 or your local emergency number immediately. If you know someone who's in danger of attempting suicide or ha made a suicide attempt, make sure someone stay with that person to keep him or her safe. Call 911 or your local emergency number immediately. Or, if you can do so safely, take the person to the nearest hospital emergency room.

Renal artery stenosis often doesn't cause any sign or symptom until it's advanced. The condition may be discovered incidentally during testing for something else. Your health care provider may also suspect a problem if you have: High blood pressure that begin suddenly or worsens without explanation High blood pressure that begin before age 30 or after age 50 As renal artery stenosis progresses, other sign and symptom may include: High blood pressure that's hard to control A whooshing sound a blood flow through a narrowed vessel (bruit), which your doctor hears through a stethoscope placed over your kidney Elevated protein level in the urine or other sign of a problem with kidney function Worsening kidney function during treatment for high blood pressure Fluid overload and swelling in your body's tissue Treatment-resistant heart failure When to seek medical advice Make an appointment with your doctor if you have any persistent sign or symptom that worry you.

Optic neuritis usually affect one eye. Symptoms might include: Pain. Most people who develop optic neuritis have eye pain that's worsened by eye movement. Sometimes the pain feel like a dull ache behind the eye. Vision loss in one eye. Most people have at least some temporary reduction in vision, but the extent of loss varies. Noticeable vision loss usually develops over hour or day and improves over several week to months. Vision loss is permanent in some people. Visual field loss. Side vision loss can occur in any pattern, such a central vision loss or peripheral vision loss. Loss of color vision. Optic neuritis often affect color perception. You might notice that color appear le vivid than normal. Flashing lights. Some people with optic neuritis report seeing flashing or flickering light with eye movements.

Signs and symptom of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma include: Round patch of skin that may be raised or scaly and might be itchy Patches of skin that appear lighter in color than surrounding skin Lumps that form on the skin and may break open Enlarged lymph node Hair loss Thickening of the skin on the palm of the hand and sol of the foot A rash-like skin redness over the entire body that is intensely itchy Causes The exact cause of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma isn't known. In general, cancer begin when cell develop change (mutations) in their DNA. A cell's DNA contains instruction that tell a cell what to do. The DNA mutation tell the cell to grow and multiply rapidly, creating many abnormal cells. In cutaneous T-cell lymphoma, the mutation cause too many abnormal T cell that attack the skin. T cell are part of your immune system, and they normally help your body fight germs. Doctors don't know why the cell attack the skin. Skin cancer develops primarily on area of sun-exposed skin, including the scalp, face, lips, ears, neck, chest, arm and hands, and on the leg in women. But it can also form on area that rarely see the light of day — your palms, beneath your fingernail or toenails, and your genital area. Skin cancer affect people of all skin tones, including those with darker complexions. When melanoma occurs in people with dark skin tones, it's more likely to occur in area not normally exposed to the sun, such a the palm of the hand and sol of the feet. Basal cell carcinoma sign and symptom Basal cell carcinoma usually occurs in sun-exposed area of your body, such a your neck or face. Basal cell carcinoma may appear as: A pearly or waxy bump A flat, flesh-colored or brown scar-like lesion A bleeding or scabbing sore that heals and return Squamous cell carcinoma sign and symptom Most often, squamous cell carcinoma occurs on sun-exposed area of your body, such a your face, ear and hands. People with darker skin are more likely to develop squamous cell carcinoma on area that aren't often exposed to the sun. Squamous cell carcinoma may appear as: A firm, red nodule A flat lesion with a scaly, crusted surface Melanoma sign and symptom Melanoma can develop anywhere on your body, in otherwise normal skin or in an existing mole that becomes cancerous. Melanoma most often appears on the face or the trunk of affected men. In women, this type of cancer most often develops on the lower legs. In both men and women, melanoma can occur on skin that hasn't been exposed to the sun. Melanoma can affect people of any skin tone. In people with darker skin tones, melanoma tends to occur on the palm or soles, or under the fingernail or toenails. Melanoma sign include: A large brownish spot with darker speckle A mole that change in color, size or feel or that bleeds A small lesion with an irregular border and portion that appear red, pink, white, blue or blue-black A painful lesion that itch or burn Dark lesion on your palms, soles, fingertip or toes, or on mucous membrane lining your mouth, nose, vagina or anus Signs and symptom of le common skin cancer Other, le common type of skin cancer include: Kaposi sarcoma. This rare form of skin cancer develops in the skin's blood vessel and cause red or purple patch on the skin or mucous membranes. Kaposi sarcoma mainly occurs in people with weakened immune systems, such a people with AIDS, and in people taking medication that suppress their natural immunity, such a people who've undergone organ transplants. Other people with an increased risk of Kaposi sarcoma include young men living in Africa or older men of Italian or Eastern European Jewish heritage. Merkel cell carcinoma. Merkel cell carcinoma cause firm, shiny nodule that occur on or just beneath the skin and in hair follicles. Merkel cell carcinoma is most often found on the head, neck and trunk. Sebaceous gland carcinoma. This uncommon and aggressive cancer originates in the oil gland in the skin. Sebaceous gland carcinoma — which usually appear a hard, painless nodule — can develop anywhere, but most occur on the eyelid, where they're frequently mistaken for other eyelid problems.

The sign and symptom of hypopituitarism usually develop gradually and get worse over time. They are sometimes subtle and may be overlooked for month or even years. But for some people, sign and symptom develop suddenly. Signs and symptom of hypopituitarism vary from person to person, depending on which pituitary hormone are affected and to what degree. In people who have more than one pituitary hormone deficiency, the second deficiency may increase or, in some cases, hide the symptom of the first deficiency. Growth hormone (GH) deficiency In children, GH deficiency may cause growth problem and short stature. Most adult who have GH deficiency don't have any symptoms, but for some adult it can cause: GH GH Fatigue Muscle weakness Changes in body fat composition Lack of ambition Social isolation Luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) deficiency Deficiency of these hormones, called gonadotropins, affect the reproductive system. In women, the deficiency decrease egg and estrogen production from the ovaries. In men, the deficiency decrease sperm and testosterone production from the testicles. Women and men may experience a lower sex drive, infertility or fatigue. In child and adolescents, delayed puberty is usually the only symptom. Women may also have symptom such as: Hot flash Irregular or no period Loss of pubic hair An inability to produce milk for breast-feeding Men may also have symptom such as: Erectile dysfunction Decreased facial or body hair Mood change Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) deficiency This hormone control the thyroid gland. A TSH deficiency lead to low level of thyroid hormone (hypothyroidism). This cause symptom such as: TSH Fatigue Weight gain Dry skin Constipation Sensitivity to cold or difficulty staying warm Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) deficiency This hormone help your adrenal gland work properly, and help your body react to stress. Symptoms of ACTH deficiency include: ACTH Severe fatigue Low blood pressure, which may lead to fainting Frequent and prolonged infection Nausea, vomiting or abdominal pain Confusion Anti-diuretic hormone (ADH) deficiency This hormone, which is also called vasopressin, help your body balance it fluid levels. An ADH deficiency can cause a disorder called diabetes insipidus, which can cause: ADH Excessive urination Extreme thirst Electrolyte imbalance Prolactin deficiency Prolactin is the hormone that tell the body when to start making breast milk. Low level of prolactin can cause woman to have problem making milk for breast-feeding.

Symptoms of delirium usually begin over a few hour or a few days. They typically occur with a medical problem. Symptoms often come and go during the day. There may be period of no symptoms. Symptoms tend to be worse at night when it's dark and thing look le familiar. They also tend to be worse in setting that aren't familiar, such a in a hospital. Primary symptom include the following. Reduced awareness of surroundings This may result in: Trouble focusing on a topic or changing topic Getting stuck on an idea rather than responding to question Being easily distracted Being withdrawn, with little or no activity or little response to surroundings Poor thinking skill This may appear as: Poor memory, such a forgetting recent event Not knowing where they are or who they are Trouble with speech or recalling word Rambling or nonsense speech Trouble understanding speech Trouble reading or writing Behavior and emotional change These may include: Anxiety, fear or distrust of others Depression A short temper or anger A sense of feeling elated Lack of interest and emotion Quick change in mood Personality change Seeing thing that others don't see Being restless, anxious or combative Calling out, moaning or making other sound Being quiet and withdrawn — especially in older adult Slowed movement or being sluggish Changes in sleep habit A switched night-day sleep-wake cycle Types of delirium Experts have identified three types: Hyperactive delirium. This may be the easiest type to recognize. People with this type may be restless and pace the room. They also may be anxious, have rapid mood swing or see thing that aren't there. People with this type often resist care. Hypoactive delirium. People with this type may be inactive or have reduced activity. They tend to be sluggish or drowsy. They might seem to be in a daze. They don't interact with family or others. Mixed delirium. Symptoms involve both type of delirium. The person may quickly switch back and forth from being restless and sluggish. Delirium and dementia Delirium and dementia may be hard to tell apart, and a person may have both. Someone with dementia ha a gradual decline of memory and other thinking skill due to damage or loss of brain cells. The most common cause of dementia is Alzheimer's disease, which come on slowly over month or years. Delirium often occurs in people with dementia. However, episode of delirium don't always mean a person ha dementia. Tests for dementia shouldn't be done during a delirium episode because the result could be misleading. Some difference between the symptom of delirium and dementia include: Onset. The onset of delirium occurs within a short time — within a day or two. Dementia usually begin with minor symptom that get worse over time. Attention. The ability to stay focused or maintain focus is impaired with delirium. A person in the early stage of dementia remains generally alert. Someone with dementia often isn't sluggish or agitated. Rapid change in symptoms. Delirium symptom can come and go several time during the day. While people with dementia have better and worse time of day, their memory and thinking skill typically stay at a constant level.

Your limb have specific area of muscle (compartments). Your lower leg, for example, ha four compartments. Chronic exertional compartment syndrome often occurs in the same compartment of an affected limb on both side of the body, usually the lower leg. Signs and symptom can include: Aching, burning or cramping pain in a compartment of the affected limb Tightness in the affected limb Numbness or tingling in the affected limb Weakness of the affected limb Foot drop, in severe cases, if leg are affected Occasionally, swelling or bulging a a result of a muscle hernia Pain caused by chronic exertional compartment syndrome typically follows this pattern: Begins consistently after a certain time, distance or intensity of exertion after you start exercising the affected limb Progressively worsens a you exercise Becomes le intense or stop completely within 15 minute of stopping the activity Over time, recovery time after exercise may increase Taking a complete break from exercise or performing only low-impact activity might relieve your symptoms, but relief is usually only temporary. Once you take up running again, for instance, those familiar symptom usually come back.

There are three general type of thoracic outlet syndrome: Neurogenic (neurologic) thoracic outlet syndrome. This most common type of thoracic outlet syndrome is characterized by compression of the brachial plexus. The brachial plexus is a network of nerve that come from your spinal cord and control muscle movement and sensation in your shoulder, arm and hand. Venous thoracic outlet syndrome. This type of thoracic outlet syndrome occurs when one or more of the vein under the collarbone (clavicle) are compressed, resulting in blood clots. Arterial thoracic outlet syndrome. This is the least common type of TOS. It occurs when one of the artery under the collarbone is compressed, resulting in bulging of the artery, also known a an aneurysm. It's possible to have a mix of the three different type of thoracic outlet syndrome, with multiple part of the thoracic outlet being compressed. Thoracic outlet syndrome symptom can vary depending on the type. When nerve are compressed, sign and symptom of neurogenic thoracic outlet syndrome include: Numbness or tingling in your arm or finger Pain or ache in your neck, shoulder, arm or hand Weakening grip Signs and symptom of venous thoracic outlet syndrome can include: Discoloration of your hand (bluish color) Arm pain and swelling Blood clot in vein in the upper area of your body Arm fatigue with activity Paleness or abnormal color in one or more finger or your hand Throbbing lump near your collarbone Signs and symptom of arterial thoracic outlet syndrome can include: Cold fingers, hand or arm Hand and arm pain Lack of color (pallor) or bluish discoloration (cyanosis) in one or more of your finger or your entire hand Weak or no pulse in the affected arm

Usually, a split (cleft) in the lip or palate is immediately identifiable at birth. Cleft lip and cleft palate may appear as: A split in the lip and roof of the mouth (palate) that affect one or both side of the face A split in the lip that appears a only a small notch in the lip or extends from the lip through the upper gum and palate into the bottom of the nose A split in the roof of the mouth that doesn't affect the appearance of the face Less commonly, a cleft occurs only in the muscle of the soft palate (submucous cleft palate), which are at the back of the mouth and covered by the mouth's lining. This type of cleft often go unnoticed at birth and may not be diagnosed until later when sign develop. Signs and symptom of submucous cleft palate may include: Difficulty with feeding Difficulty swallowing, with potential for liquid or food to come out the nose Nasal speaking voice Chronic ear infection

A tumor is an abnormal growth or mass of tissue. A cyst is a lesion that contains liquid or semisolid material. Examples of jaw tumor and cyst include: Ameloblastoma. This rare, usually noncancerous (benign) tumor begin in the cell that form the protective enamel lining on the teeth. It develops most often in the jaw near the molars. The most common type is aggressive, forming large tumor and growing into the jawbone. Although this tumor can recur after treatment, aggressive surgical treatment will typically reduce the chance of recurrence. Central giant cell granuloma. Central giant cell granuloma are benign lesion that grow from bone cells. They most often occur in the front portion of the lower jaw. One type of these tumor can grow rapidly, cause pain and destroy bone, and ha a tendency to recur after surgical treatment. The other type is le aggressive and may not have symptoms. Rarely, a tumor may shrink or resolve on it own, but typically these tumor require surgical treatment. Dentigerous cyst. This cyst originates from tissue that surround a tooth before it erupts into the mouth. This is the most common form of cyst that affect the jaws. Most often these cyst will occur around wisdom teeth that are not fully erupted, but they can also involve other teeth. Odontogenic keratocyst. This cyst is also referred to a a keratocystic odontogenic tumor because of it tumorlike tendency to recur after surgical treatment. Although this cyst is typically slow growing, it can still be destructive to the jaw and teeth if left untreated over a long period of time. Most often the cyst develops in the lower jaw near the third molars. These cyst may also be found in people with an inherited condition called nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome. Odontogenic myxoma. This is a rare, slow-growing, benign tumor that occurs most often in the lower jaw. The tumor can be large and aggressively invade the jaw and surrounding tissue and displace teeth. Odontogenic myxoma are known to recur after surgical treatment; however, the chance of tumor recurrence are typically lessened by more-aggressive form of surgical treatment. Odontoma. This benign tumor is the most common odontogenic tumor. Odontomas often have no symptoms, but they may interfere with tooth development or eruption. Odontomas are made up of dental tissue that grows around a tooth in the jaw. They can resemble an oddly shaped tooth or can be a small or large calcified tumor. These tumor may be part of some genetic syndromes. Other type of cyst and tumors. These include adenomatoid odontogenic tumor, calcifying epithelial odontogenic tumor, glandular odontogenic cyst, squamous odontogenic tumor, calcifying odontogenic cyst, cementoblastoma, aneurysmal bone cyst, ossifying fibroma, osteoblastoma. central odontogenic fibroma and others.

There are no specific symptom that indicate a conjoined twin pregnancy. As with other twin pregnancies, the uterus may grow faster than it doe with a single baby. And there may be more tiredness, nausea and vomiting early in the pregnancy. Conjoined twin can be diagnosed early in the pregnancy using an ultrasound. How twin are joined Conjoined twin are usually classified according to where they're joined. The twin sometimes share organ or other part of their bodies. Each pair of conjoined twin is unique. Conjoined twin may be joined at any of these sites: Chest. Thoracopagus (thor-uh-KOP-uh-gus) twin are joined face to face at the chest. They often have a shared heart and may also share one liver and upper intestine. This is one of the most common site of conjoined twins. Abdomen. Omphalopagus (om-fuh-LOP-uh-gus) twin are joined near the bellybutton. Many omphalopagus twin share the liver and some part of the upper digestive (gastrointestinal or GI) tract. Some twin share the lower part of the small intestine (ileum) and the longest part of the large intestine (colon). They generally do not share a heart. Base of spine. Pygopagus (pie-GOP-uh-gus) twin are commonly joined back to back at the base of the spine and the buttocks. Some pygopagus twin share the lower gastrointestinal (GI) tract. A few twin share the genital and urinary organs. Length of spine. Rachipagus (ray-KIP-uh-gus), also called rachiopagus (ray-kee-OP-uh-gus), twin are joined back to back along the length of the spine. This type is very rare. Pelvis. Ischiopagus (is-kee-OP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the pelvis, either face to face or end to end. Many ischiopagus twin share the lower GI tract, a well a the liver and genital and urinary tract organs. Each twin may have two leg or, le commonly, the twin share two or three legs. Trunk. Parapagus (pa-RAP-uh-gus) twin are joined side to side at the pelvis and part or all of the belly (abdomen) and chest, but with separate heads. The twin can have two, three or four arm and two or three legs. Head. Craniopagus (kray-nee-OP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the back, top or side of the head, but not the face. Craniopagus twin share a portion of the skull. But their brain are usually separate, though they may share some brain tissue. Head and chest. Cephalopagus (sef-uh-LOP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the head and upper body. The face are on opposite side of a single shared head, and they share a brain. These twin rarely survive. In rare cases, twin may be conjoined with one twin smaller and le fully formed than the other (asymmetric conjoined twins). In extremely rare cases, one twin may be found partially developed within the other twin (fetus in fetu).

Essential tremor sign and symptoms: Begin gradually, usually more prominently on one side of the body Worsen with movement Usually occur in the hand first, affecting one hand or both hand Can include a "yes-yes" or "no-no" motion of the head May be aggravated by emotional stress, fatigue, caffeine or temperature extreme Essential tremor vs. Parkinson's disease Many people associate tremor with Parkinson's disease, but the two condition differ in key ways: Timing of tremors. Essential tremor of the hand usually occurs when you use your hands. Tremors from Parkinson's disease are most prominent when your hand are at your side or resting in your lap. Associated conditions. Essential tremor doesn't cause other health problems, but Parkinson's disease is associated with stooped posture, slow movement and dragging the foot when walking. However, people with essential tremor sometimes develop other neurological sign and symptoms, such a an unsteady walk. Parts of the body affected. Essential tremor mainly involves your hands, head and voice. Parkinson's disease tremor usually start in your hands, and can affect your legs, chin and other part of your body.

Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor sometimes don't cause symptoms. When they do, sign and symptom can include: Stomach ulcer Heartburn Diabetes Weakness Fatigue Muscle cramp Indigestion Diarrhea Weight loss Skin rash Constipation Pain in your abdomen or back Yellowing of your skin or eye Low blood sugar Causes It's not clear what cause most pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor occur when hormone-producing cell in the pancreas (islet cells) develop change (mutations) in their DNA — the material that provides instruction for every chemical process in your body. DNA mutation cause change in these instructions. One result is that cell may begin to grow out of control and eventually form a tumor — a mass of cancerous cells. Sometimes the cancer cell break away and spread to other organs, such a the liver. Some inherited syndrome increase the risk of this type of cancer, including: Multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 1 (MEN 1) syndrome Von Hippel-Lindau disease Von Recklinghausen's disease (neurofibromatosis 1) Tuberous sclerosis Risk factor Factors that are associated with an increased risk of pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor include: Being male. Men are much more likely than woman to develop these tumors. A family history of pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. If a family member wa diagnosed with pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor, your risk is increased. You may have multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 1 (MEN 1) syndrome, which increase the risk of this type of tumor. Tetralogy of Fallot symptom vary, depending on the amount of blood flow that's blocked. Signs and symptom may include: A bluish coloration of the skin caused by low blood oxygen level (cyanosis) Shortness of breath and rapid breathing, especially during feeding or exercise Poor weight gain Tiring easily during play or exercise Irritability Prolonged cry Heart murmur Fainting An abnormal, rounded shape of the nail bed in the finger and toe (clubbing) Tet spell Sometimes, baby who have tetralogy of Fallot will suddenly develop deep blue skin, nail and lip after cry or feeding, or when agitated. These episode are called tet spells. Tet spell are caused by a rapid drop in the amount of oxygen in the blood. Tet spell are most common in young infants, around 2 to 4 month old. Toddlers or older child might instinctively squat when they're short of breath. Squatting increase blood flow to the lungs.

Children get the same type of headache adult do, but their symptom may be a little different. For example, migraine pain in adult often last at least four hour — but in children, the pain may not last a long. Differences in symptom may make it difficult to pinpoint headache type in a child, especially in a younger child who can't describe symptoms. In general, though, certain symptom tend to fall more frequently into certain categories. Migraine Migraines can cause: Pulsating or throbbing head pain Pain that worsens with activity Nausea Vomiting Abdominal pain Extreme sensitivity to light and sound Even infant can have migraines. A child who's too young to tell you what's wrong may cry or rock back and forth to indicate severe pain. Tension-type headache Tension-type headache can cause: A pressing tightness in the muscle of the head or neck Mild to moderate, nonpulsating pain on both side of the head Pain that's not worsened by physical activity Headache that's not accompanied by nausea or vomiting, a is often the case with migraine Younger child may withdraw from regular play and want to sleep more. Tension-type headache can last from 30 minute to several days. Cluster headache Cluster headache are uncommon in child under 10 year of age. They usually: Occur in group of five or more episodes, ranging from one headache every other day to eight a day Involve sharp, stabbing pain on one side of the head that last le than three hour Are accompanied by teariness, congestion, runny nose, or restlessness or agitation Chronic daily headache Doctors use the phrase "chronic daily headache" (CDH) for migraine and tension-type headache that occur more than 15 day a month. CDH may be caused by an infection, minor head injury or taking pain medication — even nonprescription pain medication — too often.

Signs and symptom of a tension-type headache include: Dull, aching head pain Sensation of tightness or pressure across the forehead or on the side and back of the head Tenderness in the scalp, neck and shoulder muscle Tension-type headache are divided into two main category — episodic and chronic. Episodic tension-type headache Episodic tension-type headache can last from 30 minute to a week. Frequent episodic tension-type headache occur le than 15 day a month for at least three months. Frequent episodic tension-type headache may become chronic. Chronic tension-type headache This type of tension-type headache last hour and may be continuous. If your headache occur 15 or more day a month for at least three months, they're considered chronic. Tension-type headache versus migraine Tension-type headache can be difficult to distinguish from migraines. Plus, if you have frequent episodic tension-type headaches, you can also have migraines. Unlike some form of migraine, tension-type headache usually aren't associated with visual disturbances, nausea or vomiting. Although physical activity typically aggravates migraine pain, it doesn't make tension-type headache pain worse. An increased sensitivity to either light or sound can occur with a tension-type headache, but this symptom isn't common.

If you have schizoid personality disorder, it's likely that you: Prefer being alone and choose to do activity alone Don't want or enjoy close relationship Feel little if any desire for sexual relationship Feel like you can't experience pleasure Have difficulty expressing emotion and reacting appropriately to situation May seem humorless, indifferent or emotionally cold to others May appear to lack motivation and goal Don't react to praise or critical remark from others Schizoid personality disorder usually begin by early adulthood, though some feature may be noticeable during childhood. These feature may cause you to have trouble functioning well in school, a job, socially or in other area of life. However, you may do reasonably well in your job if you mostly work alone. Schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia Although a different disorder, schizoid personality disorder can have some similar symptom to schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia, such a a severely limited ability to make social connection and a lack of emotional expression. People with these disorder may be viewed a odd or eccentric. Even though the name may sound similar, unlike schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia, people with schizoid personality disorder: Are in touch with reality, so they're unlikely to experience paranoia or hallucination Make sense when they speak (although the tone may not be lively), so they don't have conversational pattern that are strange and hard to follow When to see a doctor People with schizoid personality disorder usually only seek treatment for a related problem, such a depression. If someone close to you ha urged you to seek help for symptom common to schizoid personality disorder, make an appointment with a health care or mental health professional. If you suspect a loved one may have schizoid personality disorder, gently suggest that the person seek medical attention. It might help to offer to go along to the first appointment.

Symptoms of an AVM vary based on where it's found. Often the first symptom appear after bleeding occurs. Besides bleeding, symptom can include: AVM Progressive loss of neurological function Headaches Nausea and vomiting Seizures Loss of consciousness Other possible symptom include: Weak muscle Paralysis in one part of the body Loss of coordination that can cause problem with gait Problems performing task that require planning Weakness in the lower extremity Back pain Dizziness Vision problems, including losing part of the field of vision, loss of control of eye movement or swelling of part of the optic nerve Problems with speech or understanding language Unusual sensation including numbness, tingling or sudden pain Memory loss or dementia Hallucinations Confusion Children and teen might have trouble with learning or behavior. One type of AVM called a vein of Galen defect cause symptom that appear at or shortly after birth. A vein of Galen defect is situated deep inside the brain. Signs can include: AVM A buildup of fluid in the brain that cause enlargement of the head Swollen vein on the scalp Seizures Failure to thrive Congestive heart failure

Symptoms of jet lag can vary. You may experience only one symptom or you may have many. Jet lag symptom may include: Sleep problem such a not being able to fall asleep or waking up early. Daytime fatigue. Not being able to focus or function at your usual level. Stomach problem such a constipation or diarrhea. A general feeling of not being well. Mood changes. Symptoms are worse the farther you travel Jet lag symptom usually occur within a day or two after traveling across at least two time zones. Symptoms are likely to be worse or last longer the farther you travel. This is especially true if you fly east. It usually take about a day to recover for each time zone crossed.

When asked to locate your pain, you might sweep your hand over your entire pelvic area rather than point to a single spot. You might describe your chronic pelvic pain in one or more of the following ways: Severe and steady pain Pain that come and go (intermittent) Dull aching Sharp pain or cramping Pressure or heaviness deep within your pelvis In addition, you may experience: Pain during intercourse Pain while having a bowel movement or urinating Pain when you sit for long period of time Your discomfort may intensify after standing for long period and may be relieved when you lie down. The pain may be mild and annoying, or it may be so severe that you miss work, can't sleep and can't exercise. When to see a doctor With any chronic pain problem, it can be difficult to know when you should go to the doctor. In general, make an appointment with your doctor if your pelvic pain disrupts your daily life or if your symptom seem to be getting worse.

Signs and symptom of sarcoidosis vary depending on which organ are affected. Sarcoidosis sometimes develops gradually and produce symptom that last for years. Other times, symptom appear suddenly and then disappear just a quickly. Many people with sarcoidosis have no symptoms, so the disease may be discovered only when a chest X-ray is done for another reason. General symptom Sarcoidosis can begin with these sign and symptoms: Fatigue Swollen lymph node Weight loss Pain and swelling in joints, such a the ankle Lung symptom Sarcoidosis most often affect the lung and may cause lung problems, such as: Persistent dry cough Shortness of breath Wheezing Chest pain Skin symptom Sarcoidosis may cause skin problems, which may include: A rash of red or reddish-purple bumps, usually located on the shin or ankles, which may be warm and tender to the touch Disfiguring sore (lesions) on the nose, cheek and ear Areas of skin that are darker or lighter in color Growths under the skin (nodules), particularly around scar or tattoo Eye symptom Sarcoidosis can affect the eye without causing any symptoms, so it's important to have your eye checked regularly. When eye sign and symptom do occur, they may include: Blurred vision Eye pain Burning, itching or dry eye Severe redness Sensitivity to light Heart symptom Cardiac sarcoidosis: A heart under attack Click here for an infographic to learn more Cardiac sarcoidosis: A heart under attack Click here for an infographic to learn more Signs and symptom related to cardiac sarcoidosis may include: Chest pain Shortness of breath (dyspnea) Fainting (syncope) Fatigue Irregular heartbeat (arrhythmias) Rapid or fluttering heart beat (palpitations) Swelling caused by excess fluid (edema) Sarcoidosis can also affect calcium metabolism, the nervous system, the liver and spleen, muscles, bone and joints, the kidneys, lymph nodes, or any other organ.

Most thyroid nodule don't cause sign or symptoms. But occasionally some nodule become so large that they can: Be felt Be seen, often a a swelling at the base of your neck Press on your windpipe or esophagus, causing shortness of breath or difficulty swallowing In some cases, thyroid nodule produce additional thyroxine, a hormone secreted by your thyroid gland. The extra thyroxine can cause symptom of an overproduction of thyroid hormone (hyperthyroidism), such as: Unexplained weight loss Increased sweating Tremor Nervousness Rapid or irregular heartbeat Only a small number of thyroid nodule are cancerous. But determining which nodule are cancerous can't be done by evaluating your symptom alone. Most cancerous thyroid nodule are slow growing and may be small when your doctor discovers them. Aggressive thyroid cancer are rare with nodule that may be large, firm, fixed and rapid growing.

Possible symptom include severe pain in or around one eye or on one side of your head. There may be tearing, nasal stuffiness and a runny nostril on the affected side of the head. A cluster headache strike quickly, usually without warning, although you might first have migraine-like nausea and aura. Common sign and symptom during a headache include: Excruciating pain that is generally situated in, behind or around one eye, but may radiate to other area of your face, head and neck One-sided pain Restlessness Excessive tearing Redness of your eye on the affected side Stuffy or runny nose on the affected side Forehead or facial sweating on the affected side Pale skin (pallor) or flushing on your face Swelling around your eye on the affected side Drooping eyelid on the affected side People with cluster headache, unlike those with migraine, are likely to pace or sit and rock back and forth. Some migraine-like symptom — including sensitivity to light and sound — can occur with a cluster headache, though usually on one side. Cluster period characteristic A cluster period generally last for several week to months. The starting date and the duration of each cluster period might be consistent from period to period. For example, cluster period can occur seasonally, such a every spring or every fall. Most people have episodic cluster headaches. In episodic cluster headaches, the headache occur for one week to a year, followed by a pain-free remission period lasting 3 month or longer before another cluster headache develops. Chronic cluster period might continue for more than a year, or pain-free period might last le than one month. During a cluster period: Headaches usually occur every day, sometimes several time a day A single attack can last from 15 minute to three hour The attack often occur at the same time each day Most attack occur at night, usually 1 to 2 hour after you go to bed The pain usually end a suddenly a it began, with rapidly decreasing intensity. After attacks, most people are pain-free but exhausted.

The symptom of an alpha-gal allergic reaction usually take longer to start compared with those of other food allergies. Most reaction to common food allergen — peanut or shellfish, for example — happen within minute after you are exposed to them. In alpha-gal syndrome, reaction usually appear about 3 to 6 hour after you are exposed. Foods that can cause a reaction include: Red meat, such a beef, pork or lamb. Organ meats. Products made from mammals, such a gelatin or dairy products. Symptoms of alpha-gal syndrome may include: Hives, itching, or itchy, scaly skin. Swelling of the lips, face, tongue and throat, or other body parts. Wheezing or shortness of breath. Stomach pain, diarrhea, upset stomach or vomiting. The time delay between eating meat product and getting an allergic reaction may be one reason alpha-gal syndrome wa not understood at first. For example, a possible connection between a T-bone steak with dinner and hive at midnight is far from clear. Researchers think they know the reason for the delayed reaction. They say it's due to the alpha-gal molecule taking longer than other allergen to be digested and enter the system that move blood through the body.

Schizophrenia involves a range of problem with thinking (cognition), behavior and emotions. Signs and symptom may vary, but usually involve delusions, hallucination or disorganized speech, and reflect an impaired ability to function. Symptoms may include: Delusions. These are false belief that are not based in reality. For example, you think that you're being harmed or harassed; certain gesture or comment are directed at you; you have exceptional ability or fame; another person is in love with you; or a major catastrophe is about to occur. Delusions occur in most people with schizophrenia. Hallucinations. These usually involve seeing or hearing thing that don't exist. Yet for the person with schizophrenia, they have the full force and impact of a normal experience. Hallucinations can be in any of the senses, but hearing voice is the most common hallucination. Disorganized thinking (speech). Disorganized thinking is inferred from disorganized speech. Effective communication can be impaired, and answer to question may be partially or completely unrelated. Rarely, speech may include putting together meaningless word that can't be understood, sometimes known a word salad. Extremely disorganized or abnormal motor behavior. This may show in a number of ways, from childlike silliness to unpredictable agitation. Behavior isn't focused on a goal, so it's hard to do tasks. Behavior can include resistance to instructions, inappropriate or bizarre posture, a complete lack of response, or useless and excessive movement. Negative symptoms. This refers to reduced or lack of ability to function normally. For example, the person may neglect personal hygiene or appear to lack emotion (doesn't make eye contact, doesn't change facial expression or speaks in a monotone). Also, the person may lose interest in everyday activities, socially withdraw or lack the ability to experience pleasure. Symptoms can vary in type and severity over time, with period of worsening and remission of symptoms. Some symptom may always be present. In men, schizophrenia symptom typically start in the early to mid-20s. In women, symptom typically begin in the late 20s. It's uncommon for child to be diagnosed with schizophrenia and rare for those older than age 45. Symptoms in teenager Schizophrenia symptom in teenager are similar to those in adults, but the condition may be more difficult to recognize. This may be in part because some of the early symptom of schizophrenia in teenager are common for typical development during teen years, such as: Withdrawal from friend and family A drop in performance at school Trouble sleeping Irritability or depressed mood Lack of motivation Also, recreational substance use, such a marijuana, methamphetamine or LSD, can sometimes cause similar sign and symptoms. Compared with schizophrenia symptom in adults, teen may be: Less likely to have delusion More likely to have visual hallucination

Long-term infection with the hepatitis C virus is known a chronic hepatitis C. Chronic hepatitis C is usually a "silent" infection for many years, until the virus damage the liver enough to cause the sign and symptom of liver disease. Signs and symptom include: Bleeding easily Bruising easily Fatigue Poor appetite Yellow discoloration of the skin and eye (jaundice) Dark-colored urine Itchy skin Fluid buildup in your abdomen (ascites) Swelling in your leg Weight loss Confusion, drowsiness and slurred speech (hepatic encephalopathy) Spiderlike blood vessel on your skin (spider angiomas) Every chronic hepatitis C infection start with an acute phase. Acute hepatitis C usually go undiagnosed because it rarely cause symptoms. When sign and symptom are present, they may include jaundice, along with fatigue, nausea, fever and muscle aches. Acute symptom appear one to three month after exposure to the virus and last two week to three months. Acute hepatitis C infection doesn't always become chronic. Some people clear HCV from their body after the acute phase, an outcome known a spontaneous viral clearance. In study of people diagnosed with acute HCV, rate of spontaneous viral clearance have varied from 15% to 25%. Acute hepatitis C also responds well to antiviral therapy.

Normally when you blink, your eyelid distribute tear evenly across your eyes, keeping the surface of the eye lubricated. These tear drain into small opening on the inner part of your eyelid (puncta). If you have ectropion, your lower lid pull away from your eye and tear don't drain properly into the puncta. The resulting sign and symptom can include: Watery eye (excessive tearing). Without proper drainage, your tear may pool and constantly flow over your eyelids. Excessive dryness. Ectropion can cause your eye to feel dry, gritty and sandy. Irritation. Stagnant tear or dryness can irritate your eyes, causing a burning sensation and redness in your eyelid and the white of your eyes. Sensitivity to light. Stagnant tear or dry eye can irritate the surface of the cornea, making you sensitive to light.

Adults and child who have familial hypercholesterolemia have very high level of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol in their blood. LDL cholesterol is known a "bad" cholesterol because it can build up in the wall of the arteries, making them hard and narrow. LDL This excess cholesterol is sometimes deposited in certain portion of the skin, some tendon and around the iris of the eyes: Skin. The most common spot for cholesterol deposit to occur is on the hands, elbow and knees. They also can occur in the skin around the eyes. Tendons. Cholesterol deposit may thicken the Achilles tendon, along with some tendon in the hands. Eyes. High cholesterol level can cause corneal arcus, a white or gray ring around the iris of the eye. This happens most commonly in older people, but it can occur in younger people who have familial hypercholesterolemia. Causes Familial hypercholesterolemia is caused by a gene alteration that's passed down from one or both parents. People who have this condition are born with it. This change prevents the body from ridding itself of the type of cholesterol that can build up in the artery and cause heart disease. Risk factor The risk of familial hypercholesterolemia is higher if one or both of your parent have the gene alteration that cause it. Most people who have the condition receive one affected gene. But in rare cases, a child can get the affected gene from both parents. This can cause a more severe form of the condition. Familial hypercholesterolemia may be more common in certain populations, including: Ashkenazi Jews Some Lebanese group French Canadians Complications People who have familial hypercholesterolemia have a higher risk of heart disease and death at a younger age. Heart attack may occur before age 50 in men and age 60 in women. The rarer and more severe variety of the condition, if undiagnosed or untreated, can cause death before age 20. Cyclothymia symptom alternate between emotional high and lows. The high of cyclothymia include symptom of an elevated mood (hypomanic symptoms). The low consist of mild or moderate depressive symptoms. Cyclothymia symptom are similar to those of bipolar I or II disorder, but they're le severe. When you have cyclothymia, you can typically function in your daily life, though not always well. The unpredictable nature of your mood shift may significantly disrupt your life because you never know how you're going to feel. Hypomanic symptom Signs and symptom of the high of cyclothymia may include: An exaggerated feeling of happiness or well-being (euphoria) Extreme optimism Inflated self-esteem Talking more than usual Poor judgment that can result in risky behavior or unwise choice Racing thought Irritable or agitated behavior Excessive physical activity Increased drive to perform or achieve goal (sexual, work related or social) Decreased need for sleep Tendency to be easily distracted Inability to concentrate Depressive symptom Signs and symptom of the low of cyclothymia may include: Feeling sad, hopeless or empty Tearfulness Irritability, especially in child and teenager Loss of interest in activity once considered enjoyable Changes in weight Feelings of worthlessness or guilt Sleep problem Restlessness Fatigue or feeling slowed down Problems concentrating Thinking of death or suicide

Vascular dementia symptom vary, depending on the part of your brain where blood flow is impaired. Symptoms often overlap with those of other type of dementia, especially Alzheimer's disease dementia. But unlike Alzheimer's disease, the most significant symptom of vascular dementia tend to involve speed of thinking and problem-solving rather than memory loss. Vascular dementia sign and symptom include: Confusion Trouble paying attention and concentrating Reduced ability to organize thought or action Decline in ability to analyze a situation, develop an effective plan and communicate that plan to others Slowed thinking Difficulty with organization Difficulty deciding what to do next Problems with memory Restlessness and agitation Unsteady gait Sudden or frequent urge to urinate or inability to control passing urine Depression or apathy Vascular dementia symptom may be most clear-cut when they occur suddenly following a stroke. When change in your thinking and reasoning seem clearly linked to a stroke, this condition is sometimes called post-stroke dementia. Sometimes a characteristic pattern of vascular dementia symptom follows a series of stroke or ministrokes. Changes in your thought process occur in noticeable step downward from your previous level of function, unlike the gradual, steady decline that typically occurs in Alzheimer's disease dementia. But vascular dementia can also develop very gradually, just like Alzheimer's disease dementia. What's more, vascular disease and Alzheimer's disease often occur together. Studies show that many people with dementia and evidence of brain vascular disease also have Alzheimer's disease.

Transient ischemic attack usually last a few minutes. Most sign and symptom disappear within an hour, though rarely symptom may last up to 24 hours. The sign and symptom of a TIA resemble those found early in a stroke and may include sudden onset of: TIA Weakness, numbness or paralysis in the face, arm or leg, typically on one side of the body Slurred or garbled speech or difficulty understanding others Blindness in one or both eye or double vision Vertigo or loss of balance or coordination You may have more than one TIA, and the recurrent sign and symptom may be similar or different depending on which area of the brain is involved.

There are four main type of diabetic neuropathy. You can have one type or more than one type of neuropathy. Your symptom depend on the type you have and which nerve are affected. Usually, symptom develop gradually. You may not notice anything is wrong until considerable nerve damage ha occurred. Peripheral neuropathy This type of neuropathy may also be called distal symmetric peripheral neuropathy. It's the most common type of diabetic neuropathy. It affect the foot and leg first, followed by the hand and arms. Signs and symptom of peripheral neuropathy are often worse at night, and may include: Numbness or reduced ability to feel pain or temperature change Tingling or burning feeling Sharp pain or cramp Muscle weakness Extreme sensitivity to touch — for some people, even a bedsheet's weight can be painful Serious foot problems, such a ulcers, infections, and bone and joint damage Autonomic neuropathy The autonomic nervous system control blood pressure, heart rate, sweating, eyes, bladder, digestive system and sex organs. Diabetes can affect nerve in any of these areas, possibly causing sign and symptom including: A lack of awareness that blood sugar level are low (hypoglycemia unawareness) Drops in blood pressure when rising from sitting or lying down that may cause dizziness or fainting (orthostatic hypotension) Bladder or bowel problem Slow stomach emptying (gastroparesis), causing nausea, vomiting, sensation of fullness and loss of appetite Difficulty swallowing Changes in the way the eye adjust from light to dark or far to near Increased or decreased sweating Problems with sexual response, such a vaginal dryness in woman and erectile dysfunction in men Proximal neuropathy (diabetic polyradiculopathy) This type of neuropathy often affect nerve in the thighs, hips, buttock or legs. It can also affect the abdominal and chest area. Symptoms are usually on one side of the body, but may spread to the other side. Proximal neuropathy may include: Severe pain in the buttock, hip or thigh Weak and shrinking thigh muscle Difficulty rising from a sitting position Chest or abdominal wall pain Mononeuropathy (focal neuropathy) Mononeuropathy refers to damage to a single, specific nerve. The nerve may be in the face, torso, arm or leg. Mononeuropathy may lead to: Difficulty focusing or double vision Paralysis on one side of the face Numbness or tingling in the hand or finger Weakness in the hand that may result in dropping thing Pain in the shin or foot Weakness causing difficulty lifting the front part of the foot (foot drop) Pain in the front of the thigh
