The severity of sign and symptom of radiation sickness depends on how much radiation you've absorbed. How much you absorb depends on the strength of the radiated energy, the time of your exposures, and the distance between you and the source of radiation. Signs and symptom are also affected by the type of exposure — such a total or partial body. The severity of radiation sickness also depends on how sensitive the affected tissue is. For instance, the gastrointestinal system and bone marrow are highly sensitive to radiation. Initial sign and symptom The initial sign and symptom of treatable radiation sickness are usually nausea and vomiting. The amount of time between exposure and when these symptom develop is a clue to how much radiation a person ha absorbed. After the first round of sign and symptoms, a person with radiation sickness may have a brief period with no apparent illness, followed by the onset of new, more-serious symptoms. If you've had a mild exposure, it may take hour to week before any sign and symptom begin. But with severe exposure, sign and symptom can begin minute to day after exposure. Possible symptom include: Nausea and vomiting Diarrhea Headache Fever Dizziness and disorientation Weakness and fatigue Hair loss Bloody vomit and stool from internal bleeding Infections Low blood pressure

The sign and symptom of aspergillosis vary with the type of illness you develop: Allergic reaction Some people with asthma or cystic fibrosis have an allergic reaction to aspergillus mold. Signs and symptom of this condition, known a allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, include: Fever A cough that may bring up blood or plug of mucus Worsening asthma Aspergilloma Certain chronic lung (pulmonary) conditions, such a emphysema, tuberculosis or advanced sarcoidosis, can cause air space (cavities) to form in the lungs. When people with lung cavity are also infected with aspergillus, fungus fiber may find their way into the cavity and grow into tangled mass (fungus balls) known a aspergillomas. Aspergillomas may produce no symptom or cause only a mild cough at first. Over time and without treatment, however, aspergillomas can worsen the underlying chronic lung condition and possibly cause: A cough that often brings up blood (hemoptysis) Wheezing Shortness of breath Unintentional weight loss Fatigue Invasive aspergillosis This is the most severe form of aspergillosis. It occurs when the infection spread rapidly from the lung to the brain, heart, kidney or skin. Invasive aspergillosis occurs only in people whose immune system are weakened a a result of cancer chemotherapy, bone marrow transplantation or a disease of the immune system. Untreated, this form of aspergillosis may be fatal. Signs and symptom depend on which organ are affected, but in general, invasive aspergillosis can cause: Fever and chill A cough that brings up blood (hemoptysis) Shortness of breath Chest or joint pain Headaches or eye symptom Skin lesion Other type of aspergillosis Aspergillus can invade area of your body other than your lungs, such a your sinuses. In your sinuses, the fungus can cause a stuffy nose sometimes accompanied by drainage that may contain blood. Fever, facial pain and headache may also occur.

For most people, antibiotic-associated diarrhea cause mild sign and symptoms, such as: Loose stool More-frequent bowel movement Antibiotic-associated diarrhea is likely to begin about a week after you start taking an antibiotic. In addition to causing loose stool and more-frequent bowel movements, C. difficile infection can cause: Severe diarrhea and dehydration Lower abdominal pain and cramping Low-grade fever Nausea Loss of appetite When to see a doctor Call your doctor right away if you have serious sign and symptom of antibiotic-associated diarrhea. Symptoms may go unrecognized at first, or they may only occur when the heart is beating hard like during exercise. As the coronary artery continue to narrow, le and le blood get to the heart and symptom can become more severe or frequent. Coronary artery disease sign and symptom can include: Chest pain (angina). You may feel pressure or tightness in your chest. Some people say it feel like someone is standing on their chest. The chest pain usually occurs on the middle or left side of the chest. Activity or strong emotion can trigger angina. The pain usually go away within minute after the triggering event ends. In some people, especially women, the pain may be brief or sharp and felt in the neck, arm or back. Shortness of breath. You may feel like you can't catch your breath. Fatigue. If the heart can't pump enough blood to meet your body's needs, you may feel unusually tired. Heart attack. A completely blocked coronary artery will cause a heart attack. The classic sign and symptom of a heart attack include crushing chest pain or pressure, shoulder or arm pain, shortness of breath, and sweating. Women may have le typical symptoms, such a neck or jaw pain, nausea and fatigue. Some heart attack don't cause any noticeable sign or symptoms.

Most brain aneurysm that haven't ruptured don't cause symptoms. This is especially true if they're small. Brain aneurysm may be found during imaging test that are done for other conditions. However, a ruptured aneurysm is a very serious condition, typically causing a severe headache. And if an unruptured aneurysm press against brain tissue or nerves, it may cause pain and other symptoms. Ruptured aneurysm A sudden, severe headache is the key symptom of a ruptured aneurysm. This headache is often described by people a the worst headache they've ever experienced. In addition to a severe headache, symptom of a ruptured aneurysm can include: Nausea and vomiting Stiff neck Blurred or double vision Sensitivity to light Seizure A drooping eyelid Loss of consciousness Confusion 'Leaking' aneurysm In some cases, an aneurysm may leak a slight amount of blood. When this happens, a more severe rupture often follows. Leaks may happen day or week before a rupture. Leaking brain aneurysm symptom may include: A sudden, extremely severe headache that may last several day and up to two weeks. Unruptured aneurysm An unruptured brain aneurysm may not have any symptoms, especially if it's small. However, a larger unruptured aneurysm may press on brain tissue and nerves. Symptoms of an unruptured brain aneurysm may include: Pain above and behind one eye. A dilated pupil. A change in vision or double vision. Numbness of one side of the face.

Autoimmune pancreatitis (AIP) is difficult to diagnose. Often, it doesn't cause any symptoms. Symptoms and sign of type 1 AIP are similar to those of pancreatic cancer. AIP Pancreatic cancer sign and symptom can include: Dark urine Pale stool or stool that float in the toilet Yellow skin and eye (jaundice) Pain in your upper abdomen or middle part of your back Nausea and vomiting Weakness or extreme tiredness Loss of appetite or feeling of fullness Weight loss for no known reason The most common sign of type 1 AIP, present in about 80% of people, is painless jaundice, caused by blocked bile ducts. Type 2 AIP can present with recurrent episode of acute pancreatitis. Pain in the upper abdomen, a common symptom of pancreatic cancer, is frequently absent in autoimmune pancreatitis. AIP AIP Differences between type 1 and type 2 AIP are: AIP In type 1 AIP, the disease may affect other organ in addition to the pancreas. Type 2 AIP affect only the pancreas, although the disease is associated with another autoimmune condition, inflammatory bowel disease. Type 1 AIP predominantly affect men in the sixth to seventh decade of life. Type 2 AIP affect both men and woman equally and ha a younger age of onset compared with type 1 AIP. Type 1 AIP is more likely to relapse after treatment is discontinued.

Symptoms vary based on the type of seizure. They also can range from mild to severe. Seizure symptom may include: Temporary confusion. A staring spell. Jerking movement of the arm and leg that can't be controlled. Loss of consciousness or awareness. Cognitive or emotional changes. They may include fear, anxiety or a feeling that you've already lived this moment, known a deja vu. Health care provider typically classify seizure a focal or generalized. Seizures are classified based on how and where the brain activity causing the seizure began. If provider don't know how the seizure began, they may classify the seizure a unknown onset. Focal seizure Focal seizure result from electrical activity in one area of the brain. This type of seizure can occur with or without loss of consciousness: Focal seizure with impaired awareness. These seizure involve a change or loss of consciousness or awareness that feel like being in a dream. People having these type of seizure may seem awake but they stare into space and don't respond to their environment. They may perform repetitive movement such a hand rubbing, mouth movements, repeating certain word or walking in circles. They may not remember the seizure or even know that it occurred. Focal seizure without impaired awareness. These seizure may alter emotions. They also may change the way thing look, smell, feel, taste or sound. But the seizure don't cause a loss of consciousness. During these type of seizures, people may suddenly feel angry, joyful or sad. Some people have nausea or unusual feeling that are hard to describe. These seizure may result in trouble speaking and involuntary jerking of a body part such a an arm or a leg. They also may cause sudden sensory symptom such a tingling, dizziness and seeing flashing lights. Symptoms of focal seizure may be confused with other disorder of the brain or nervous system. They include migraine, narcolepsy or mental illness. Generalized seizure Seizures that appear to involve all area of the brain from the time they start are called generalized seizures. Different type of generalized seizure include: Absence seizures. Absence seizures, formerly known a petit mal seizures, often occur in children. Absence seizure typically cause a person to stare into space or make subtle body movement such a eye blinking or lip smacking. They usually last for 5 to 10 seconds. These seizure may happen up to hundred of time a day. They may occur in cluster and can cause a brief loss of awareness. Tonic seizures. Tonic seizure cause stiffening of the muscles. These seizure usually affect muscle in the back, arm and legs. People who experience these seizure may lose consciousness and fall to the ground. Atonic seizures. Atonic seizures, also known a drop seizures, cause a loss of muscle control. People having this type of seizure may suddenly fall down or drop their head. Clonic seizures. Clonic seizure are associated with repeated jerking muscle movements. These seizure usually affect the neck, face and arm on both side of the body. Myoclonic seizures. Myoclonic seizure usually appear a sudden brief jerk or twitch of the arm and legs. There is often no loss of consciousness. Tonic-clonic seizures. Tonic-clonic seizures, previously known a grand mal seizures, are the most dramatic type of epileptic seizure. They can cause a sudden loss of consciousness, body stiffening and shaking. They sometimes cause people to lose control of their bladder or to bite their tongue. They may last for several minutes. Tonic-clonic seizure also may start a focal seizure that then spread to involve most or all of the brain.

Signs and symptom of urethral stricture include: Decreased urine stream Incomplete bladder emptying Spraying of the urine stream Difficulty, straining or pain when urinating Increased urge to urinate or more-frequent urination Urinary tract infection Causes Scar tissue, which can narrow the urethra, can be due to: A medical procedure that involves inserting an instrument, such a an endoscope, into the urethra Intermittent or long-term use of a tube inserted through the urethra to drain the bladder (catheter) Trauma or injury to the urethra or pelvis An enlarged prostate or previous surgery to remove or reduce an enlarged prostate gland Cancer of the urethra or prostate Sexually transmitted infection Radiation therapy Urethral stricture is much more common in male than in females. Often the cause is unknown. Clinical trial Explore Mayo Clinic study testing new treatments, intervention and test a a mean to prevent, detect, treat or manage this condition. Not all pituitary tumor cause symptoms. Sometimes these tumor are found during an imaging test, such a an MRI or a CT scan, that is done for another reason. If they don't cause symptoms, pituitary tumor usually don't need treatment. MRI CT Pituitary tumor symptom may be caused by a tumor putting pressure on the brain or on other part of the body nearby. Symptoms also can be caused by a hormone imbalance. Hormone level can rise when a pituitary tumor make too much of one or more hormones. Or a large tumor that disrupts the way the pituitary gland work may cause hormone level to fall. Symptoms from tumor pressure Macroadenomas can put pressure on the pituitary gland, on nerves, on the brain and on other part of the body nearby. That can cause symptom such as: Headache. Eye problem due to pressure on the optic nerve, especially loss of side vision, also called peripheral vision, and double vision. Pain in the face, sometimes including sinus pain or ear pain. Drooping eyelid. Seizures. Nausea and vomiting. Low amount of hormone Macroadenomas can limit the pituitary gland's ability to make hormones. When that happens, symptom may include: Tiredness or weakness. Lack of energy. Sexual problems, such a problem with erection and le interest in sex. Changes in menstrual cycles. Nausea. Feeling cold. Losing or gaining weight without trying. High amount of hormone Functioning pituitary adenoma typically make a large amount of one hormone. That expose the body to high level of that hormone. Rarely, a pituitary adenoma may make more than one hormone. The following type of functioning pituitary adenoma cause different symptom depending on the hormone they make. Pituitary tumor that make adrenocorticotropic hormone Pituitary tumor that make adrenocorticotropic hormone are called corticotroph adenomas. Adrenocorticotropic hormone, also called ACTH, cause the adrenal gland to make the hormone cortisol. ACTH tumor trigger the adrenal gland to make too much cortisol. This cause a condition called Cushing disease. Cushing disease is one cause of Cushing syndrome. ACTH ACTH Cushing disease symptom include: Weight gain and fatty tissue deposit around the midsection and upper back. Rounded face. Stretch marks. Thin skin that bruise easily. Thinning of the arm and leg with muscle weakness. Thicker or more visible body hair. Slow healing of cuts, insect bite and infections. Areas of darkened skin. Acne. Changes in menstrual cycles. Sexual problems, including problem with erection and le interest in sex. Pituitary tumor that make growth hormone Pituitary tumor that make growth hormone also are called growth hormone-secreting tumor or somatotroph adenomas. Too much growth hormone lead to a condition known a acromegaly. Acromegaly can cause: Changes in facial features, including larger lips, nose and tongue; longer lower jaw; and wide space between teeth. Growth of hand and feet. Thicker skin. More sweating and body odor. Joint pain. A deeper voice. Children and teen who have too much growth hormone might also grow faster or taller than usual. This condition is called gigantism. Pituitary tumor that make luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone Luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) are also known a gonadotropins. Pituitary tumor that make these hormone are called gonadotroph adenomas. It's uncommon for these adenoma to make too many hormone that then trigger symptoms. Instead, symptom from these adenoma usually are due to tumor pressure. If symptom do happen because of too much LH and FSH, they affect woman and men differently. LH FSH Symptoms in woman may include: Change in menstrual cycles. Fertility problems. Enlargement of and pain in the ovary caused by a condition called ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome. Symptoms in men may include: Enlarged testicles. Higher level of testosterone. Pituitary tumor that make prolactin These adenoma are called prolactinomas. Too much of the hormone prolactin can lead to a decrease in the body's level of sex hormone — estrogen and testosterone. Too much prolactin affect men and woman differently. In women, too much prolactin might cause: Irregular menstrual cycles. Lack of menstrual cycles. Milky discharge from the breasts. Breast tenderness. Problems with fertility. Less interest in sex. In men, too much prolactin can cause a condition called male hypogonadism. Symptoms might include: Problems with erections. Less interest in sex. Breast growth. Problems with fertility. Less body and facial hair. Pituitary tumor that make thyroid-stimulating hormone Pituitary tumor that make thyroid-stimulating hormone are called thyrotroph adenomas. They also may be referred to a thyroid-stimulating hormone-secreting tumors. They cause the thyroid gland to make too much of the hormone thyroxine, also called T-4. That lead to a condition called hyperthyroidism, also known a overactive thyroid disease. Hyperthyroidism can speed up the body's metabolism causing many symptoms. Some of the most common include: Weight loss. Rapid or irregular heartbeat. Nervousness, anxiety or irritability. Frequent bowel movements. Sweating. Tremor. Sleep problems.

An allergic response to peanut usually occurs within minute after exposure. Peanut allergy sign and symptom can include: Skin reactions, such a hives, redness or swelling Itching or tingling in or around the mouth and throat Digestive problems, such a diarrhea, stomach cramps, nausea or vomiting Tightening of the throat Shortness of breath or wheezing Runny nose Anaphylaxis: A life-threatening reaction Peanut allergy is the most common cause of food-induced anaphylaxis, a medical emergency that requires treatment with an epinephrine (adrenaline) autoinjector (EpiPen, Auvi-Q, others) and a trip to the emergency room. Anaphylaxis sign and symptom can include: Constriction of airway Swelling of the throat that make it difficult to breathe A severe drop in blood pressure (shock) Rapid pulse Dizziness, lightheadedness or loss of consciousness

Signs and symptom of Noonan syndrome vary greatly among individual and may be mild to severe. Characteristics may be related to the specific gene containing the mutation. Facial feature Facial appearance is one of the key clinical feature that lead to a diagnosis of Noonan syndrome. These feature may be more pronounced in infant and young children, but change with age. In adulthood, these distinct feature become more subtle. Features may include the following: Eyes are wide-set and down-slanting with droopy lids. Irises are pale blue or green. Ears are low-set and rotated backward. Nose is depressed at the top, with a wide base and bulbous tip. Mouth ha a deep groove between the nose and the mouth and wide peak in the upper lip. The crease that run from the edge of the nose to the corner of the mouth becomes deeply grooved with age. Teeth may be crooked, the inside roof of the mouth (palate) may be highly arched and the lower jaw may be small. Facial feature may appear coarse, but appear sharper with age. The face may appear droopy and expressionless. Head may appear large with a prominent forehead and a low hairline on the back of the head. Skin may appear thin and transparent with age. Heart disease Many people with Noonan syndrome are born with some form of heart defect (congenital heart disease), accounting for some of the key sign and symptom of the disorder. Some heart problem can occur later in life. Some form of congenital heart disease associated with this disorder include: Valve disorders. Pulmonary valve stenosis is a narrowing of the pulmonary valve, the flap of tissue that separate the lower right chamber (ventricle) of the heart from the artery that supply blood to the lung (pulmonary artery). It's the most common heart problem seen with Noonan syndrome, and it may occur alone or with other heart defects. Thickening of the heart muscle (hypertrophic cardiomyopathy). This is abnormal growth or thickening of the heart muscle that affect some people with Noonan syndrome. Other structural defect of the heart. The defect can involve a hole in the wall that separate the two lower chamber of the heart (ventricular septal defect), narrowing of the artery that carry blood to the lung for oxygen (pulmonary artery stenosis), or narrowing of the major blood vessel (aorta) that carry blood from the heart to the body (aortic coarctation). Irregular heart rhythm. This can occur with or without structural heart abnormalities. Irregular heart rhythm occurs in the majority of people with Noonan syndrome. Growth issue Noonan syndrome can affect normal growth. Many child with Noonan syndrome don't grow at a normal rate. Issues may include the following: Birth weight will likely be normal, but growth slows over time. Eating difficulty may result in inadequate nutrition and poor weight gain. Growth hormone level may be insufficient. The growth spurt that's usually seen during the teenage year may be delayed. But because this disorder cause bone maturity to be delayed, growth sometimes continues into the late teens. By adulthood, some people with Noonan syndrome may have normal height, but short stature is more common. Musculoskeletal issue Some common issue can include: An unusually shaped chest often with a sunken sternum (pectus excavatum) or raised sternum (pectus carinatum) Wide-set nipple Short neck, often with extra fold of skin (webbed neck) or prominent neck muscle (trapezius) Deformities of the spine Learning disability Intelligence isn't affected for most people with Noonan syndrome. However, individual may have: An increased risk of learning disability and mild intellectual disability A wide range of mental, emotional and behavioral issue that are usually mild Hearing and vision deficit that may complicate learning Eye condition A common sign of Noonan syndrome is abnormality of the eye and eyelids. These may include: Problems with the eye muscles, such a cross-eye (strabismus) Refractive problems, such a astigmatism, nearsightedness (myopia) or farsightedness (hyperopia) Rapid movement of the eyeball (nystagmus) Cataracts Hearing problem Noonan syndrome can cause hearing deficit due to nerve issue or to structural abnormality in the inner ear bones. Bleeding Noonan syndrome can cause excessive bleeding and bruising due to clotting defect or having too few platelets. Lymphatic condition Noonan syndrome can cause problem with the lymphatic system, which drain excess fluid from the body and help fight infection. These problems: May show up before or after birth or develop in the teenage year or adulthood Can be focused in a particular area of the body or widespread Most commonly cause excess fluid (lymphedema) on the back of the hand or top of the foot Genital and kidney condition Many people, especially males, with Noonan syndrome can have problem with the genitals and kidneys. Testicles. Undescended testicle (cryptorchidism) are common in males. Puberty. Puberty may be delayed in both boy and girls. Fertility. Most female develop normal fertility. In males, however, fertility may not develop normally, often because of undescended testicles. Kidneys. Kidney problem are generally mild and occur in a fairly small number of people with Noonan syndrome. Skin condition People with Noonan syndrome may have skin conditions, which most commonly are: Various problem that affect the color and texture of the skin Curly, coarse hair or sparse hair When to see a doctor The sign and symptom of Noonan syndrome can be subtle. If you suspect you or your child may have the disorder, see your primary care doctor or your child's pediatrician. You or your child may be referred to a geneticist or a cardiologist. If your unborn child is at risk because of a family history of Noonan syndrome, prenatal test may be available.

Viral gastroenteritis is an inflammation of these organ caused by a virus. The stomach, small intestine and large intestine (colon) are part of your digestive tract, which process the food you eat. Viral gastroenteritis is an inflammation of these organ caused by a virus. Although it's commonly called stomach flu, gastroenteritis isn't the same a influenza. The flu (influenza) affect only your respiratory system — your nose, throat and lungs. Gastroenteritis, on the other hand, attack your intestines, causing sign and symptom such as: Watery, usually nonbloody diarrhea — bloody diarrhea usually mean you have a different, more severe infection Nausea, vomiting or both Stomach cramp and pain Occasional muscle ache or headache Low-grade fever Depending on the cause, viral gastroenteritis symptom may appear within 1-3 day after you're infected and can range from mild to severe. Symptoms usually last just a day or two, but occasionally they may last up to 14 days. Because the symptom are similar, it's easy to confuse viral diarrhea with diarrhea caused by bacteria, such a Clostridioides difficile, salmonella and Escherichia coli, or parasites, such a giardia.

Stuttering sign and symptom may include: Difficulty starting a word, phrase or sentence Prolonging a word or sound within a word Repetition of a sound, syllable or word Brief silence for certain syllable or words, or pause within a word (broken word) Addition of extra word such a "um" if difficulty moving to the next word is anticipated Excess tension, tightness, or movement of the face or upper body to produce a word Anxiety about talking Limited ability to effectively communicate The speech difficulty of stuttering may be accompanied by: Rapid eye blink Tremors of the lip or jaw Facial tic Head jerk Clenching fist Stuttering may be worse when the person is excited, tired or under stress, or when feeling self-conscious, hurried or pressured. Situations such a speaking in front of a group or talking on the phone can be particularly difficult for people who stutter. However, most people who stutter can speak without stuttering when they talk to themselves and when they sing or speak in unison with someone else. When to see a doctor or speech-language pathologist It's common for child between the age of 2 and 5 year to go through period when they may stutter. For most children, this is part of learning to speak, and it get better on it own. However, stuttering that persists may require treatment to improve speech fluency. Call your doctor for a referral or contact a speech-language pathologist directly for an appointment if stuttering: Lasts more than six month Occurs with other speech or language problem Becomes more frequent or continues a the child grows older Occurs with muscle tightening or visibly struggling to speak Affects the ability to effectively communicate at school, at work or in social interaction Causes anxiety or emotional problems, such a fear or avoidance of situation where speaking is required Begins a an adult

In general, the symptom of postherpetic neuralgia are limited to the area of skin where the shingle outbreak first happened. In general, colic is defined a cry for three or more hour a day, three or more day a week, for three or more weeks. Features of colic may include the following: Intense cry that may seem more like screaming or an expression of pain Crying for no apparent reason, unlike cry to express hunger or the need for a diaper change Extreme fussiness even after cry ha diminished Predictable timing, with episode often occurring in the evening Facial discoloring, such a skin flushing or blushing Body tension, such a pulled up or stiffened legs, stiffened arms, clenched fists, arched back, or tense abdomen Sometimes there is relief in symptom after the infant pass gas or ha a bowel movement. Gas is likely the result of swallowed air during prolonged crying.

A prolactinoma might not cause any sign or symptoms. However, too much prolactin in your blood (hyperprolactinemia) can cause symptoms. So can pressure on surrounding tissue from a large tumor. Because too much prolactin can disrupt the reproductive system (hypogonadism), some of the sign and symptom of a prolactinoma are specific to female or males. In females, prolactinoma can cause: Irregular menstrual period or no menstrual period Milky discharge from the breast when not pregnant or breastfeeding Painful intercourse due to vaginal dryness Acne and excessive body and facial hair growth In males, prolactinoma can cause: Erectile dysfunction Decreased body and facial hair Smaller muscle Enlarged breast In both female and males, prolactinoma can cause: Infertility Weak and brittle bone that break easily (osteoporosis) Loss of interest in sexual activity Pressure from tumor growth can cause: Vision problem Headache Reduction of other hormone produced by the pituitary gland Females who are premenopausal tend to notice sign and symptom early, when tumor are smaller in size. This is probably because of missed or irregular menstrual periods. Females who are postmenopausal are more likely to notice sign and symptom later, when tumor are larger and more likely to cause headache or vision problems. Males are also more likely to notice sign and symptom later.

Heatstroke sign and symptom include: High body temperature. A core body temperature of 104 F (40 C) or higher, obtained with a rectal thermometer, is the main sign of heatstroke. Altered mental state or behavior. Confusion, agitation, slurred speech, irritability, delirium, seizure and coma can all result from heatstroke. Alteration in sweating. In heatstroke brought on by hot weather, your skin will feel hot and dry to the touch. However, in heatstroke brought on by strenuous exercise, your skin may feel dry or slightly moist. Nausea and vomiting. You may feel sick to your stomach or vomit. Flushed skin. Your skin may turn red a your body temperature increases. Rapid breathing. Your breathing may become rapid and shallow. Racing heart rate. Your pulse may significantly increase because heat stress place a tremendous burden on your heart to help cool your body. Headache. Your head may throb.

Tuberous sclerosis symptom are caused by noncancerous growth in part of the body, most commonly in the skin, brain, eyes, kidneys, heart and lungs. But any part of the body can be affected. Symptoms can range from mild to severe, depending on the size or location of the growths. Although symptom are different for each person with tuberous sclerosis, they can include: Skin changes. Skin change are most common. These include patch of lighter skin and small area of thickened, smooth or bumpy skin. On the forehead, skin can have raised, discolored areas. Small soft bump under or around the nail may occur. Growths on the face that start in childhood and look like acne are common. Seizures. Growths in the brain may be linked with seizures. A seizure is often the first symptom of tuberous sclerosis. In small children, a common type of seizure called infantile spasm involves stiffening of the arm and leg and arching the back and head. Problems in thinking, reasoning and learning. Tuberous sclerosis can result in developmental delays. Sometimes it limit the ability to think, reason and learn. Mental health conditions, such a autism spectrum disorder or attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), also can occur. Behavior problems. Common behavior problem may include hyperactivity, self-injury or aggression, or issue with social and emotional adjustment. Kidney problems. Growths on the kidney are common, and more growth may develop with age. Heart issues. Growths in the heart, if present, are usually largest at birth and shrink a a child get older. Lung problems. Growths that develop in the lung may cause coughing or trouble breathing, especially with physical activity or exercise. These lung tumor occur more often in female than in males. Eye problems. Growths can appear a white patch on the light-sensitive tissue at the back of the eye called the retina. These growth usually don't interfere with vision. Dental changes. Teeth may have pit in the surface. Small growth may appear on the gums, inside of the cheek and on the tongue.

Teen depression sign and symptom include a change from the teenager's previous attitude and behavior that can cause significant distress and problem at school or home, in social activities, or in other area of life. Depression symptom can vary in severity, but change in your teen's emotion and behavior may include the example below. Emotional change Be alert for emotional changes, such as: Feelings of sadness, which can include cry spell for no apparent reason Frustration or feeling of anger, even over small matter Feeling hopeless or empty Irritable or annoyed mood Loss of interest or pleasure in usual activity Loss of interest in, or conflict with, family and friend Low self-esteem Feelings of worthlessness or guilt Fixation on past failure or exaggerated self-blame or self-criticism Extreme sensitivity to rejection or failure, and the need for excessive reassurance Trouble thinking, concentrating, making decision and remembering thing Ongoing sense that life and the future are grim and bleak Frequent thought of death, dying or suicide Behavioral change Watch for change in behavior, such as: Tiredness and loss of energy Insomnia or sleeping too much Changes in appetite — decreased appetite and weight loss, or increased craving for food and weight gain Use of alcohol or drug Agitation or restlessness — for example, pacing, hand-wringing or an inability to sit still Slowed thinking, speaking or body movement Frequent complaint of unexplained body ache and headaches, which may include frequent visit to the school nurse Social isolation Poor school performance or frequent absence from school Less attention to personal hygiene or appearance Angry outbursts, disruptive or risky behavior, or other acting-out behavior Self-harm — for example, cutting or burning Making a suicide plan or a suicide attempt What's normal and what's not It can be difficult to tell the difference between ups and down that are just part of being a teenager and teen depression. Talk with your teen. Try to determine whether he or she seems capable of managing challenging feelings, or if life seems overwhelming.

The list of potential sign and symptom for premenstrual syndrome is long, but most woman only experience a few of these problems. Emotional and behavioral sign and symptom Tension or anxiety Depressed mood Crying spell Mood swing and irritability or anger Appetite change and food craving Trouble falling asleep (insomnia) Social withdrawal Poor concentration Change in libido Physical sign and symptom Joint or muscle pain Headache Fatigue Weight gain related to fluid retention Abdominal bloating Breast tenderness Acne flare-up Constipation or diarrhea Alcohol intolerance For some, the physical pain and emotional stress are severe enough to affect their daily lives. Regardless of symptom severity, the sign and symptom generally disappear within four day after the start of the menstrual period for most women. But a small number of woman with premenstrual syndrome have disabling symptom every month. This form of PMS is called premenstrual dysphoric disorder (PMDD). PMS PMDD sign and symptom include depression, mood swings, anger, anxiety, feeling overwhelmed, difficulty concentrating, irritability and tension.

There are two type of sex headaches: A dull ache in the head and neck that intensifies a sexual excitement increase A sudden, severe, throbbing headache that occurs just before or at the moment of orgasm In some people, both type of headache are combined. Most sex headache last at least several minutes. Others may linger for hour or even 2 to 3 days. Many people who have sex headache will experience them in cluster over a few months, and then they may go for a year or more without having any. Up to half of all people with sex headache experience them over the course of about six months. Some people may only have one attack during their lives.

Many people with Chiari malformation have no sign or symptom and don't need treatment. Their condition is detected only when test are performed for unrelated disorders. However, depending on the type and severity, Chiari malformation can cause a number of problems. The more common type of Chiari malformation are: Type 1 Type 2 Although these type are le serious than the rarer pediatric form, type 3, sign and symptom still can be life disrupting. Chiari malformation type 1 In Chiari malformation type 1, sign and symptom usually appear during late childhood or adulthood. Headaches, often severe, are the classic symptom of Chiari malformation. They generally occur after sudden coughing, sneezing or straining. People with Chiari malformation type 1 can also experience: Neck pain Unsteady gait (problems with balance) Poor hand coordination (fine motor skills) Numbness and tingling of the hand and foot Dizziness Difficulty swallowing, sometimes accompanied by gagging, choking and vomiting Speech problems, such a hoarseness Less often, people with Chiari malformation may experience: Ringing or buzzing in the ear (tinnitus) Weakness Slow heart rhythm Curvature of the spine (scoliosis) related to spinal cord impairment Breathing problems, such a central sleep apnea, which is when a person stop breathing during sleep Chiari malformation type 2 In Chiari malformation type 2, a greater amount of tissue extends into the spinal canal compared with that in Chiari malformation type 1. The sign and symptom can include those related to a form of spina bifida called myelomeningocele that nearly always accompanies Chiari malformation type 2. In myelomeningocele, the backbone and the spinal canal don't close properly before birth. Signs and symptom may include: Changes in breathing pattern Swallowing problems, such a gagging Quick downward eye movement Weakness in the arm Chiari malformation type 2 is usually noted with ultrasound during pregnancy. It may also be diagnosed after birth or in early infancy. Chiari malformation type 3 In the most severe type of the condition, Chiari malformation type 3, a portion of the lower back part of the brain (cerebellum) or the brainstem extends through an opening in the back of the skull. This form of Chiari malformation is diagnosed at birth or with an ultrasound during pregnancy. This type of Chiari malformation ha a higher mortality rate and may also cause neurological problems.

Aortic valve stenosis range from mild to severe. Symptoms generally occur when narrowing of the valve is severe. Some people with aortic valve stenosis may not have symptom for many years. Symptoms of aortic valve stenosis may include: An irregular heart sound (heart murmur) heard through a stethoscope Chest pain (angina) or tightness with activity Feeling faint or dizzy or fainting with activity Shortness of breath, especially with activity Fatigue, especially during time of increased activity Rapid, fluttering heartbeat (palpitations) Not eating enough (mainly in child with aortic valve stenosis) Not gaining enough weight (mainly in child with aortic valve stenosis) Aortic valve stenosis may lead to heart failure. Heart failure symptom include fatigue, shortness of breath, and swollen ankle and feet.

The symptom of hypothyroidism depend on the severity of the condition. Problems tend to develop slowly, often over several years. At first, you may barely notice the symptom of hypothyroidism, such a fatigue and weight gain. Or you may think they are just part of getting older. But a your metabolism continues to slow, you may develop more-obvious problems. Hypothyroidism symptom may include: Tiredness. More sensitivity to cold. Constipation. Dry skin. Weight gain. Puffy face. Hoarse voice. Coarse hair and skin. Muscle weakness. Muscle aches, tenderness and stiffness. Menstrual cycle that are heavier than usual or irregular. Thinning hair. Slowed heart rate, also called bradycardia. Depression. Memory problems. Hypothyroidism in infant Anyone can get hypothyroidism, including infants. Most baby born without a thyroid gland or with a gland that doesn't work correctly don't have symptom right away. But if hypothyroidism isn't diagnosed and treated, symptom start to appear. They may include: Feeding problems. Poor growth. Poor weight gain. Yellowing of the skin and the white of the eyes, a condition called jaundice. Constipation. Poor muscle tone. Dry skin. Hoarse crying. Enlarged tongue. A soft swelling or bulge near the belly button, a condition called umbilical hernia. When hypothyroidism in infant isn't treated, even mild case can lead to severe physical and mental development problems. Hypothyroidism in child and teen In general, child and teen with hypothyroidism have symptom similar to those in adults. But they also may have: Poor growth that lead to short stature. Delayed development of permanent teeth. Delayed puberty. Poor mental development.

The physical sign and symptom of anorexia nervosa are related to starvation. Anorexia also includes emotional and behavioral issue involving an unrealistic perception of body weight and an extremely strong fear of gaining weight or becoming fat. It may be difficult to notice sign and symptom because what is considered a low body weight is different for each person, and some individual may not appear extremely thin. Also, people with anorexia often disguise their thinness, eating habit or physical problems. Physical symptom Physical sign and symptom of anorexia may include: Extreme weight loss or not making expected developmental weight gain Thin appearance Abnormal blood count Fatigue Insomnia Dizziness or fainting Bluish discoloration of the finger Hair that thins, break or fall out Soft, downy hair covering the body Absence of menstruation Constipation and abdominal pain Dry or yellowish skin Intolerance of cold Irregular heart rhythm Low blood pressure Dehydration Swelling of arm or leg Eroded teeth and callus on the knuckle from induced vomiting Some people who have anorexia binge and purge, similar to individual who have bulimia. But people with anorexia generally struggle with an abnormally low body weight, while individual with bulimia typically are normal to above normal weight. Emotional and behavioral symptom Behavioral symptom of anorexia may include attempt to lose weight by: Severely restricting food intake through dieting or fasting Exercising excessively Bingeing and self-induced vomiting to get rid of food, which may include the use of laxatives, enemas, diet aid or herbal product Emotional and behavioral sign and symptom may include: Preoccupation with food, which sometimes includes cooking elaborate meal for others but not eating them Frequently skipping meal or refusing to eat Denial of hunger or making excuse for not eating Eating only a few certain "safe" foods, usually those low in fat and calorie Adopting rigid meal or eating rituals, such a spitting food out after chewing Not wanting to eat in public Lying about how much food ha been eaten Fear of gaining weight that may include repeated weighing or measuring the body Frequent checking in the mirror for perceived flaw Complaining about being fat or having part of the body that are fat Covering up in layer of clothing Flat mood (lack of emotion) Social withdrawal Irritability Insomnia Reduced interest in sex

Knee bursitis sign and symptom vary, depending on which bursa is affected and what's causing the inflammation. In general, the affected portion of your knee might feel warm, tender and swollen when you put pressure on it. You might also feel pain when you move or even at rest. A sharp blow to the knee can cause symptom to appear rapidly. But most case of knee bursitis result from friction and irritation of the bursa that occurs in job that require a lot of kneeling on hard surface — so symptom usually begin gradually and can worsen over time. When to see a doctor The bursa that lie over your kneecap can sometimes become infected. Call your doctor if you have a fever in addition to pain and swelling in your knee.

A child who's being abused may feel guilty, ashamed or confused. The child may be afraid to tell anyone about the abuse, especially if the abuser is a parent, other relative or family friend. That's why it's vital to watch for red flags, such as: Withdrawal from friend or usual activity Changes in behavior — such a aggression, anger, hostility or hyperactivity — or change in school performance Depression, anxiety or unusual fears, or a sudden loss of self-confidence Sleep problem and nightmare An apparent lack of supervision Frequent absence from school Rebellious or defiant behavior Self-harm or attempt at suicide Specific sign and symptom depend on the type of abuse and can vary. Keep in mind that warning sign are just that — warning signs. The presence of warning sign doesn't necessarily mean that a child is being abused. Physical abuse sign and symptom Unexplained injuries, such a bruises, broken bone (fractures) or burn Injuries that don't match the given explanation Injuries that aren't compatible with the child's developmental ability Sexual abuse sign and symptom Sexual behavior or knowledge that's inappropriate for the child's age Pregnancy or a sexually transmitted infection Genital or anal pain, bleeding, or injury Statements by the child that he or she wa sexually abused Inappropriate sexual behavior with other child Emotional abuse sign and symptom Delayed or inappropriate emotional development Loss of self-confidence or self-esteem Social withdrawal or a loss of interest or enthusiasm Depression Avoidance of certain situations, such a refusing to go to school or ride the bus Appears to desperately seek affection A decrease in school performance or loss of interest in school Loss of previously acquired developmental skill Neglect sign and symptom Poor growth Excessive weight with medical complication that are not being adequately addressed Poor personal cleanliness Lack of clothing or supply to meet physical need Hoarding or stealing food Poor record of school attendance Lack of appropriate attention for medical, dental or psychological problem or lack of necessary follow-up care Parental behavior Sometimes a parent's demeanor or behavior sends red flag about child abuse. Warning sign include a parent who: Shows little concern for the child Appears unable to recognize physical or emotional distress in the child Blames the child for the problem Consistently belittles or berates the child, and describes the child with negative terms, such a "worthless" or "evil" Expects the child to provide attention and care to the parent and seems jealous of other family member getting attention from the child Uses harsh physical discipline Demands an inappropriate level of physical or academic performance Severely limit the child's contact with others Offers conflicting or unconvincing explanation for a child's injury or no explanation at all Repeatedly brings the child for medical evaluation or request medical tests, such a X-rays and lab tests, for concern not seen during the health care provider's examination Physical punishment Child health expert condemn the use of violence in any form, but some people still use physical punishment, such a spanking, to discipline their children. While parent and caregiver often use physical punishment with the intention of helping their child or making their behavior better, research show that spanking is linked with worse, not better, behavior. It's also linked to mental health problems, difficult relationship with parents, lower self-esteem and lower academic performance. Any physical punishment may leave emotional scars. Parental behavior that cause pain, physical injury or emotional trauma — even when done in the name of discipline — could be child abuse.

Although your body can harbor the bacteria that cause tuberculosis, your immune system usually can prevent you from becoming sick. For this reason, doctor make a distinction between: Latent TB. You have a TB infection, but the bacteria in your body are inactive and cause no symptoms. Latent TB, also called inactive TB or TB infection, isn't contagious. Latent TB can turn into active TB, so treatment is important. Active TB. Also called TB disease, this condition make you sick and, in most cases, can spread to others. It can occur week or year after infection with the TB bacteria. Signs and symptom of active TB include: TB Coughing for three or more week Coughing up blood or mucus Chest pain, or pain with breathing or coughing Unintentional weight loss Fatigue Fever Night sweat Chills Loss of appetite Tuberculosis can also affect other part of your body, including the kidneys, spine or brain. When TB occurs outside your lungs, sign and symptom vary according to the organ involved. For example, tuberculosis of the spine might cause back pain, and tuberculosis in your kidney might cause blood in your urine.

The sign of craniosynostosis are usually noticeable at birth, but they become more apparent during the first few month of your baby's life. Signs and severity depend on how many suture are fused and when in brain development the fusion occurs. Signs and symptom can include: A misshapen skull, with the shape depending on which of the suture are affected Development of a raised, hard ridge along affected sutures, with a change in the shape of the head that's not typical Types of craniosynostosis There are several type of craniosynostosis. Most involve the fusion of a single cranial suture. Some complex form of craniosynostosis involve the fusion of multiple sutures. Multiple suture craniosynostosis is usually linked to genetic syndrome and is called syndromic craniosynostosis. The term given to each type of craniosynostosis depends on what suture are affected. Types of craniosynostosis include: Sagittal (scaphocephaly). Premature fusion of the sagittal suture that run from the front to the back at the top of the skull force the head to grow long and narrow. This head shape is called scaphocephaly. Sagittal craniosynostosis is the most common type of craniosynostosis. Coronal. Premature fusion of one of the coronal suture (unicoronal) that run from each ear to the top of the skull may cause the forehead to flatten on the affected side and bulge on the unaffected side. It also lead to turning of the nose and a raised eye socket on the affected side. When both coronal suture fuse prematurely (bicoronal), the head ha a short and wide appearance, often with the forehead tilted forward. Metopic. The metopic suture run from the top of the bridge of the nose up through the midline of the forehead to the anterior fontanel and the sagittal suture. Premature fusion give the forehead a triangular appearance and widens the back part of the head. This head shape is also called trigonocephaly. Lambdoid. Lambdoid synostosis is a rare type of craniosynostosis that involves the lambdoid suture, which run along the back of the head. It may cause one side of a baby's head to appear flat, one ear to be higher than the other ear and tilting of the top of the head to one side. Other reason for a misshapen head A misshapen head doesn't always indicate craniosynostosis. For example, if the back of your baby's head appears flattened, it could be the result of spending too much time lying on one side of the head. This can be treated with regular position changes, or if significant, with helmet therapy (cranial orthosis) to help reshape the head to a more balanced appearance.

Anything that put stress on the body, including pregnancy or infections, may trigger symptoms.

Newborns with PKU initially don't have any symptoms. However, without treatment, baby usually develop sign of PKU within a few months. PKU PKU Signs and symptom of untreated PKU can be mild or severe and may include: PKU A musty odor in the breath, skin or urine, caused by too much phenylalanine in the body Nervous system (neurological) problem that may include seizure Skin rashes, such a eczema Lighter skin, hair and eye color than family members, because phenylalanine can't transform into melanin — the pigment responsible for hair and skin tone Unusually small head size (microcephaly) Hyperactivity Intellectual disability Delayed development Behavioral, emotional and social problem Mental health disorder Severity varies The severity of PKU depends on the type. PKU Classic PKU. The most severe form of the disorder is called classic PKU. The enzyme needed to break down phenylalanine is missing or severely reduced. This result in high level of phenylalanine that can cause severe brain damage. Less severe form of PKU. In mild or moderate forms, the enzyme still ha some function, so phenylalanine level are not a high, resulting in a smaller risk of significant brain damage. Regardless of the form, most infants, child and adult with the disorder still require a special PKU diet to prevent intellectual disability and other complications. PKU Pregnancy and PKU Women who have PKU and become pregnant are at risk of another form of the condition called maternal PKU. If woman don't follow the special PKU diet before and during pregnancy, blood phenylalanine level can become high and harm the developing baby. PKU PKU PKU Even woman with le severe form of PKU may place their unborn child at risk by not following the PKU diet. PKU PKU Babies born to woman with high phenylalanine level don't often inherit PKU. But a child can have serious problem if the level of phenylalanine is high in the mother's blood during pregnancy. At birth, the baby may have: PKU Low birth weight Unusually small head Problems with the heart In addition, maternal PKU can cause the child to have delayed development, intellectual disability and problem with behavior.

Early symptom of ankylosing spondylitis might include back pain and stiffness in the lower back and hips, especially in the morning and after period of inactivity. Sleepwalking usually occurs early in the night — often one to two hour after falling asleep. It's unlikely to occur during naps. A sleepwalking episode can occur rarely or often, and an episode generally last several minutes, but can last longer. Someone who is sleepwalking may: Get out of bed and walk around Sit up in bed and open his or her eye Have a glazed, glassy-eyed expression Not respond or communicate with others Be difficult to wake up during an episode Be disoriented or confused for a short time after being awakened Not remember the episode in the morning Have problem functioning during the day because of disturbed sleep Have sleep terror in addition to sleepwalking Sometimes, a person who is sleepwalking will: Do routine activities, such a getting dressed, talking or eating Leave the house Drive a car Engage in unusual behavior, such a urinating in a closet Engage in sexual activity without awareness Get injured, for example, by falling down the stair or jumping out a window Become violent during the period of brief confusion immediately after waking or, occasionally, during sleepwalking When to see a doctor Occasional episode of sleepwalking aren't usually a cause for concern and typically resolve on their own. You can simply mention the sleepwalking at a routine physical or well-child exam. However, consult your doctor if the sleepwalking episodes: Occur often — for example, more than one to two time a week or several time a night Lead to dangerous behavior or injury to the person who sleepwalks or to others Cause significant sleep disruption to household member or the person who sleepwalks Result in daytime symptom of excessive sleepiness or problem functioning Start for the first time a an adult Continue into your child's teen year

In Reye's syndrome, a child's blood sugar usually drop while level of ammonia and acidity in the blood rises. The liver also may swell, and fat may build up. Swelling may occur in the brain. This can cause seizures, convulsion or loss of consciousness. The symptom of Reye's syndrome usually start about 3 to 5 day after the onset of a viral infection. This may be the flu, known a influenza, or chickenpox. Or Reye's syndrome may develop after an upper respiratory infection such a a cold. Initial symptom For child younger than age 2, the first symptom of Reye's syndrome may include: For child younger than age 2, Diarrhea. Rapid breathing. For older child and teenagers, early symptom may include: For older child and teenagers, Vomiting that doesn't stop. Being sleepy or sluggish. Additional symptom As the condition progresses, symptom may become more serious, including: Irritable, aggressive or irrational behavior. Confusion or seeing or hearing thing that aren't there. Weakness in the arm and leg or not being able to move them. Seizures. Excessive sluggishness. Decreased level of consciousness. These symptom need emergency treatment.

More than half the people with primary biliary cholangitis do not have any noticeable symptom when diagnosed. The disease may be diagnosed when blood test are done for other reasons, such a routine testing. Symptoms eventually develop over the next 5 to 20 years. Those who do have symptom at diagnosis typically have poorer outcomes. Common early symptom include: Fatigue Itchy skin Later sign and symptom may include: Dry eye and mouth Pain in the upper right abdomen Swelling of the spleen (splenomegaly) Bone, muscle or joint (musculoskeletal) pain Swollen foot and ankle (edema) Buildup of fluid in the abdomen due to liver failure (ascites) Fatty deposit (xanthomas) on the skin around the eyes, eyelid or in the crease of the palms, soles, elbow or knee Yellowing of the skin and eye (jaundice) Darkening of the skin that's not related to sun exposure (hyperpigmentation) Weak and brittle bone (osteoporosis), which can lead to fracture High cholesterol Diarrhea, which may include greasy stool (steatorrhea) Underactive thyroid (hypothyroidism) Weight loss

Signs and symptom of frostbite include: At first, cold skin and a prickling feeling Numbness Skin that look red, white, bluish-white, grayish-yellow, purplish, brown or ashen, depending on the severity of the condition and usual skin color Hard or waxy-looking skin Clumsiness due to joint and muscle stiffness Blistering after rewarming, in severe case Frostbite is most common on the fingers, toes, nose, ears, cheek and chin. Because of skin numbness, you may not realize you have frostbite until someone point it out. Changes in the color of the affected area might be difficult to see on brown or Black skin. Frostbite occurs in several stages: Frostnip. Frostnip is a mild form of frostbite. Continued cold exposure lead to numbness in the affected area. As your skin warms, you may feel pain and tingling. Frostnip doesn't cause permanent skin damage. Superficial frostbite. Superficial frostbite cause slight change in skin color. The skin may begin to feel warm — a sign of serious skin involvement. If you treat frostbite with rewarming at this stage, the surface of the skin may appear mottled. And you may notice stinging, burning and swelling. A fluid-filled blister may appear 12 to 36 hour after rewarming the skin. Deep (severe) frostbite. As frostbite progresses, it affect all layer of the skin a well a the tissue that lie below. The skin turn white or blue-gray and you lose all sensation of cold, pain or discomfort in the area. Joints or muscle may stop working. Large blister form 24 to 48 hour after rewarming. The tissue turn black and hard a it dies.

A typical sign of lupus is a red, butterfly-shaped rash over your cheek and nose, often following exposure to sunlight. No two case of lupus are exactly alike. Signs and symptom may come on suddenly or develop slowly, may be mild or severe, and may be temporary or permanent. Most people with lupus have mild disease characterized by episode — called flare — when sign and symptom get worse for a while, then improve or even disappear completely for a time. The sign and symptom of lupus that you experience will depend on which body system are affected by the disease. The most common sign and symptom include: Fatigue Fever Joint pain, stiffness and swelling Butterfly-shaped rash on the face that cover the cheek and bridge of the nose or rash elsewhere on the body Skin lesion that appear or worsen with sun exposure Fingers and toe that turn white or blue when exposed to cold or during stressful period Shortness of breath Chest pain Dry eye Headaches, confusion and memory loss

Symptoms of burning mouth syndrome may include: A burning or scalding feeling that most commonly affect your tongue, but also may affect your lips, gums, roof of your mouth, throat or whole mouth. A feeling of dry mouth with increased thirst. Taste change in your mouth, such a a bitter or metallic taste. Loss of taste. Tingling, stinging or numbness in your mouth. The discomfort from burning mouth syndrome can have several different patterns. It may: Happen every day, with little discomfort when waking up, but become worse a the day go on. Start a soon a you wake up and last all day. Come and go. Whatever pattern of mouth discomfort you have, burning mouth syndrome may last for month to years. In rare cases, symptom may suddenly go away on their own or happen le often. Sometimes the burning feeling may be briefly relieved during eating or drinking. Burning mouth syndrome usually doesn't cause any physical change to your tongue or mouth that can be seen.

Signs and symptom of a brachial plexus injury can vary greatly, depending on the severity and location of the injury. Usually only one arm is affected. Less-severe injury Minor damage often occurs during contact sports, such a football or wrestling, when the brachial plexus nerve get stretched or compressed. These are called stinger or burners, and can produce the following symptoms: A feeling like an electric shock or a burning sensation shooting down the arm Numbness and weakness in the arm These symptom usually last only a few second or minutes, but in some people the symptom may linger for day or longer. More-severe injury More-severe symptom result from injury that seriously hurt or even tear or rupture the nerves. The most serious brachial plexus injury occurs when the nerve root is torn from the spinal cord. Signs and symptom of more-severe injury can include: Weakness or inability to use certain muscle in the hand, arm or shoulder Complete lack of movement and feeling in the arm, including the shoulder and hand Severe pain

Uncomfortable fullness after a meal. The feeling of fullness last longer than it should. Discomfort in the upper abdomen. You feel a mild to severe pain in the area between the bottom of your breastbone and your bellybutton. Burning in the upper abdomen. You feel an uncomfortable heat or burning sensation between the bottom of your breastbone and your bellybutton. Bloating in the upper abdomen. You feel an uncomfortable sensation of tightness in your upper abdomen. Nausea. You feel a if you want to vomit. Less frequent sign and symptom include vomiting and belching. Sometimes people with indigestion also experience heartburn. Heartburn is a pain or burning feeling in the center of your chest that may radiate into your neck or back during or after eating.

The sign and symptom of granuloma annulare can vary, depending on the type: Localized. This is the most common type of granuloma annulare. The rash border are circular or semicircular, with a diameter up to 2 inch (5 centimeters). The rash occurs most commonly on the hands, feet, wrist and ankle of young adults. Generalized. This type is uncommon and usually affect adults. It cause bump that form a rash on most of the body, including the trunk, arm and legs. The rash might cause discomfort or itchiness. Under the skin. A type that usually affect young child is called subcutaneous granuloma annulare. It produce small, firm lump under the skin, instead of a rash. The lump form on the hands, shin and scalp.

The sign and symptom of carcinoid syndrome depend on which chemical the carcinoid tumor secretes into your bloodstream. The most common sign and symptom include: Skin flushing. The skin on your face and upper chest feel hot and change color — ranging from pink to purple. Flushing episode may last from a few minute to a few hour or longer. Flushing may happen for no obvious reason, though sometimes it can be triggered by stress, exercise or drinking alcohol. Facial skin lesions. Purplish area of spiderlike vein may appear on your nose and upper lip. Diarrhea. Frequent, watery stool sometimes accompanied by abdominal cramp may occur in people who have carcinoid syndrome. Difficulty breathing. Asthma-like sign and symptoms, such a wheezing and shortness of breath, may occur at the same time you experience skin flushing. Rapid heartbeat. Periods of a fast heart rate could be a sign of carcinoid syndrome.

Peyronie's disease sign and symptom might appear suddenly or develop gradually. The most common sign and symptom include: Scar tissue. The scar tissue associated with Peyronie's disease — called plaque but different from plaque that can build up in blood vessel — can be felt under the skin of the penis a flat lump or a band of hard tissue. A significant bend to the penis. Your penis might curve upward or downward or bend to one side. Erection problems. Peyronie's disease might cause problem getting or maintaining an erection (erectile dysfunction). But, often men report erectile dysfunction before the beginning of Peyronie's disease symptoms. Shortening of the penis. Your penis might become shorter a a result of Peyronie's disease. Pain. You might have penile pain, with or without an erection. Other penile deformity. In some men with Peyronie's disease, the erect penis might have narrowing, indentation or even an hourglass-like appearance, with a tight, narrow band around the shaft. The curvature and penile shortening associated with Peyronie's disease might gradually worsen. At some point, however, the condition typically stabilizes after three to 12 month or so. Pain during erection usually improves within one to two years, but the scar tissue, penile shortening and curvature often remain. In some men, both the curvature and pain associated with Peyronie's disease improve without treatment.

Niemann-Pick sign and symptom may include: Clumsiness and difficulty walking Excessive muscle contraction (dystonia) or eye movement Sleep disturbance Difficulty swallowing and eating Recurrent pneumonia The three main type of Niemann-Pick are type A, B and C. The sign and symptom you experience depend on the type and severity of your condition. Some infant with type A will show sign and symptom within the first few month of life. Those with type B may not show sign for year and have a better chance of surviving to adulthood. People with type C may not experience any symptom until adulthood.

Signs and symptom of glomerulonephritis may vary depending on whether you have the acute or chronic form and the cause. You may notice no symptom of chronic disease. Your first indication that something is wrong might come from the result of a routine urine test (urinalysis). Glomerulonephritis sign and symptom may include: Pink or cola-colored urine from red blood cell in your urine (hematuria) Foamy or bubbly urine due to excess protein in the urine (proteinuria) High blood pressure (hypertension) Fluid retention (edema) with swelling evident in your face, hands, foot and abdomen Urinating le than usual Nausea and vomiting Muscle cramp Fatigue

Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease is marked by change in mental abilities. Symptoms get worse quickly, usually within several week to a few months. Early symptom include: Personality changes. Memory loss. Impaired thinking. Blurry vision or blindness. Insomnia. Problems with coordination. Trouble speaking. Trouble swallowing. Sudden, jerky movements. Death usually occurs within a year. People with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease usually die of medical issue associated with the disease. They might include having trouble swallowing, falls, heart issues, lung failure, or pneumonia or other infections. In people with variant CJD, change in mental ability may be more apparent in the beginning of the disease. In many cases, dementia develops later in the illness. Symptoms of dementia include the loss of the ability to think, reason and remember. CJD Variant CJD affect people at a younger age than CJD. Variant CJD appears to last 12 to 14 months. CJD CJD CJD Another rare form of prion disease is called variably protease-sensitive prionopathy (VPSPr). It can mimic other form of dementia. It cause change in mental ability and problem with speech and thinking. The course of the disease is longer than other prion disease — about 24 months.

Signs and symptom of intestinal ischemia can develop suddenly (acute) or gradually (chronic). Signs and symptom may be different from one person to the next, but there are some generally recognized pattern that suggest intestinal ischemia. Symptoms of sudden (acute) intestinal ischemia Signs and symptom of acute intestinal ischemia typically include: Sudden belly (abdominal) pain that may be mild, moderate or severe An urgent need to have a bowel movement Frequent, forceful bowel movement Abdominal tenderness or bloating (distention) Blood in your stool Nausea and vomiting Mental confusion in older adult Symptoms of gradually developing (chronic) intestinal ischemia Signs and symptom of chronic intestinal ischemia can include: Abdominal cramp or fullness, usually within 30 minute after eating, and lasting 1 to 3 hour Abdominal pain that get gradually worse over week or month Fear of eating because of pain that happens after eating Unintended weight loss Diarrhea Nausea and vomiting Bloating

Symptoms of Raynaud's disease include: Cold finger or toes. Areas of skin that turn white then blue. Depending on your skin color, these color change may be harder or easier to see. Numb, prickly feeling or stinging pain upon warming or stress relief. During an attack of Raynaud's, affected area of the skin usually first turn pale. Next, they often change color and feel cold and numb. When the skin warms and blood flow improves, the affected area may change color again, throb, tingle or swell. Raynaud's most commonly affect finger and toes. But it also can affect other area of the body, such a nose, lips, ear and even nipples. After warming up, the return of blood flow to the area can take 15 minutes.

The sign and symptom of Stickler syndrome — and the severity of those sign and symptom — can vary widely from person to person, even within the same family. Eye problems. In addition to having severe nearsightedness, child who have Stickler syndrome often experience cataracts, glaucoma and retinal detachments. Hearing difficulties. The extent of hearing loss varies among people who have Stickler syndrome. It usually affect the ability to hear high frequencies. Bone and joint abnormalities. Children who have Stickler syndrome often have overly flexible joint and are more likely to develop abnormal curvature of the spine, such a scoliosis. Osteoarthritis can begin in adolescence.

The symptom of Lyme disease vary. They usually show up in stages. But the stage can overlap. And some people don't have symptom of the typical early stage. The rash gradually spread over a period of days. Early symptom of Lyme disease usually happen within 3 to 30 day after a tick bite. This stage of disease ha a limited set of symptoms. This is called early localized disease. A rash is a common sign of Lyme disease. But it doesn't always happen. The rash is usually a single circle that slowly spread from the site of the tick bite. It may become clear in the center and look like a target or bull's-eye. The rash often feel warm to the touch, But it's usually not painful or itchy. A rash Other stage 1 symptom include: Fever. Headache. Extreme tiredness. Joint stiffness. Muscle ache and pains. Swollen lymph nodes. Stage 2 Without treatment, Lyme disease can get worse. The symptom often show up within 3 to 10 week after a tick bite. Stage 2 is often more serious and widespread. It is called early disseminated disease. Stage 2 may include the stage 1 symptom and the following: Many rash on other part of the body. Neck pain or stiffness. Muscle weakness on one or both side of the face. Immune-system activity in heart tissue that cause irregular heartbeats. Pain that start from the back and hip and spread to the legs. Pain, numbness or weakness in the hand or feet. Painful swelling in tissue of the eye or eyelid. Immune-system activity in eye nerve that cause pain or vision loss. Stage 3 In the third stage, you may have symptom from the earlier stage and other symptoms. This stage is called late disseminated disease. In the United States, the most common condition of this stage is arthritis in large joints, particularly the knees. Pain, swelling or stiffness may last for a long time. Or the symptom may come and go. Stage 3 symptom usually begin 2 to 12 month after a tick bite. The type of Lyme disease common in Europe can cause a skin condition called acrodermatitis chronic atrophicans. The skin on the back of the hand and top of the foot get discolored and swell. It also may show up over the elbow and knees. More-serious case may cause damage to tissue or joints. This skin condition may show up many month to many year after a tick bite.

Hyperglycemia usually doesn't cause symptom until blood sugar (glucose) level are high — above 180 to 200 milligram per deciliter (mg/dL), or 10 to 11.1 millimoles per liter (mmol/L). Symptoms of hyperglycemia develop slowly over several day or weeks. The longer blood sugar level stay high, the more serious symptom may become. But some people who've had type 2 diabetes for a long time may not show any symptom despite high blood sugar levels. Early sign and symptom Recognizing early symptom of hyperglycemia can help identify and treat it right away. Watch for: Frequent urination Increased thirst Blurred vision Feeling weak or unusually tired Later sign and symptom If hyperglycemia isn't treated, it can cause toxic acids, called ketones, to build up in the blood and urine. This condition is called ketoacidosis. Symptoms include: Fruity-smelling breath Dry mouth Abdominal pain Nausea and vomiting Shortness of breath Confusion Loss of consciousness

There are three type of neurofibromatosis, each with different sign and symptoms. Neurofibromatosis 1 Neurofibromatosis 1 (NF1) is usually diagnosed during childhood. Signs are often noticeable at birth or shortly afterward and almost always by age 10. Signs and symptom are often mild to moderate, but can vary in severity. Signs and symptom include: Flat, light brown spot on the skin (cafe au lait spots). These harmless spot are common in many people. Having more than six cafe au lait spot suggests NF1. They are usually present at birth or appear during the first year of life. After childhood, new spot stop appearing. Freckling in the armpit or groin area. Freckling usually appears by age 3 to 5. Freckles are smaller than cafe au lait spot and tend to occur in cluster in skin folds. Tiny bump on the iris of the eye (Lisch nodules). These harmless nodule can't easily be seen and don't affect vision. Soft, pea-sized bump on or under the skin (neurofibromas). These benign tumor usually develop in or under the skin, but can also grow inside the body. Sometimes, a growth will involve many nerve (plexiform neurofibroma). Plexiform neurofibromas, when located on the face, can cause disfigurement. Neurofibromas may increase in number with age. Bone deformities. Abnormal bone development and a deficiency in bone mineral density can cause bone deformity such a a curved spine (scoliosis) or a bowed lower leg. Tumor on the optic nerve (optic glioma). These tumor usually appear by age 3, rarely in late childhood and adolescence, and almost never in adults. Learning disabilities. Impaired thinking skill are common in child who have NF1 but are usually mild. Often there is a specific learning disability, such a a problem with reading or mathematics. Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and speech delay also are common. Larger than average head size. Children with NF1 tend to have a larger than average head size due to increased brain volume. Short stature. Children who have NF1 often are below average in height. Neurofibromatosis 2 Neurofibromatosis 2 (NF2) is much le common than NF1. Signs and symptom of NF2 usually result from the development of benign, slow-growing tumor in both ear (acoustic neuromas), which can cause hearing loss. Also known a vestibular schwannomas, these tumor grow on the nerve that carry sound and balance information from the inner ear to the brain. NF1 NF2 Signs and symptom generally appear during the late teen and early adult years, and can vary in severity. Signs and symptom can include: Gradual hearing loss Ringing in the ear Poor balance Headaches Sometimes NF2 can lead to the growth of schwannomas in other nerves, including the cranial, spinal, visual (optic) and peripheral nerves. People who have NF2 may also develop other benign tumors. NF2 NF2 Signs and symptom of these tumor can include: Numbness and weakness in the arm or leg Pain Balance difficulty Facial drop Vision problem or cataract Seizures Headache Schwannomatosis This rare type of neurofibromatosis usually affect people after age 20. Symptoms usually appear between age 25 and 30. Schwannomatosis cause tumor to develop on the cranial, spinal and peripheral nerve — but rarely on the nerve that carry sound and balance information from the inner ear to the brain. Tumors don't usually grow on both hearing nerves, so people who have schwannomatosis don't experience the same hearing loss a people who have NF2. NF2 Symptoms of schwannomatosis include: Chronic pain, which can occur anywhere in the body and can be disabling Numbness or weakness in various part of the body Loss of muscle
