At first, the flu may seem like a common cold with a runny nose, sneezing and sore throat. Colds usually develop slowly. But the flu tends to come on suddenly. And while a cold can be miserable, you usually feel much worse with the flu. Common symptom of the flu include: Fever Aching muscle Chills and sweat Headache Dry, persistent cough Shortness of breath Tiredness and weakness Runny or stuffy nose Sore throat Eye pain Vomiting and diarrhea, but this is more common in child than adult Related information COVID-19 vs. flu: Similarities and difference - Related informationCOVID-19 vs. flu: Similarities and differencesCOVID-19, cold, allergy and the flu: What are the differences? - Related informationCOVID-19, cold, allergy and the flu: What are the differences?

Gender dysphoria might cause adolescent and adult to experience a marked difference between inner gender identity and assigned gender that last for at least six months. The difference is shown by at least two of the following: A difference between gender identity and genitals or secondary sex characteristics, such a breast size, voice and facial hair. In young adolescents, a difference between gender identity and anticipated secondary sex characteristics. A strong desire to be rid of these genitals or secondary sex characteristics, or a desire to prevent the development of secondary sex characteristics. A strong desire to have the genitals and secondary sex characteristic of another gender. A strong desire to be or to be treated a another gender. A strong belief of having the typical feeling and reaction of another gender. Gender dysphoria may also cause significant distress that affect how you function in social situations, at work or school, and in other area of life. Gender dysphoria might start in childhood and continue into adolescence and adulthood. Or you might have period in which you no longer experience gender dysphoria. You might also experience gender dysphoria around the time of puberty or much later in life. Complications Gender dysphoria can affect many aspect of life, including daily activities. People experiencing gender dysphoria might have difficulty in school due to pressure to dress in a way that's associated with their sex assigned at birth or out of fear of being harassed or teased. If gender dysphoria impairs the ability to function at school or at work, the result may be school dropout or unemployment. Relationship difficulty are common. Anxiety, depression, self-harm, eating disorders, substance misuse and other problem can occur. People who have gender dysphoria also often experience discrimination, resulting in stress. Accessing health service and mental health service can be difficult due to fear of stigma and a lack of experienced care providers. Adolescents and adult with gender dysphoria without gender-affirming treatment might be at risk of thinking about or attempting suicide. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Gender dysphoria care at Mayo Clinic

Paralysis below the neck, including both arm and legs, is called quadriplegia. Your ability to control your limb after a spinal cord injury depends on two factors: where the injury occurred on your spinal cord and the severity of injury. The lowest part of your spinal cord that remains undamaged after an injury is referred to a the neurological level of your injury. The severity of the injury is often called "the completeness" and is classified a either of the following: Complete. If all feeling (sensory) and all ability to control movement (motor function) are lost below the spinal cord injury, your injury is called complete. Incomplete. If you have some motor or sensory function below the affected area, your injury is called incomplete. There are varying degree of incomplete injury. Additionally, paralysis from a spinal cord injury can be referred to as: Tetraplegia. Also known a quadriplegia, this mean that your arms, hands, trunk, leg and pelvic organ are all affected by your spinal cord injury. Paraplegia. This paralysis affect all or part of the trunk, leg and pelvic organs. Your health care team will perform a series of test to determine the neurological level and completeness of your injury. Spinal cord injury can cause one or more of the following sign and symptoms: Loss of movement Loss of or altered sensation, including the ability to feel heat, cold and touch Loss of bowel or bladder control Exaggerated reflex activity or spasm Changes in sexual function, sexual sensitivity and fertility Pain or an intense stinging sensation caused by damage to the nerve fiber in your spinal cord Difficulty breathing, coughing or clearing secretion from your lung Emergency sign and symptom Emergency sign and symptom of a spinal cord injury after an accident include: Extreme back pain or pressure in your neck, head or back Weakness, incoordination or paralysis in any part of your body Numbness, tingling or loss of sensation in your hands, fingers, foot or toe Loss of bladder or bowel control Difficulty with balance and walking Impaired breathing after injury An oddly positioned or twisted neck or back

Breast cyst may be found in one or both breasts. Signs and symptom of a breast cyst include: A smooth, easily movable round or oval lump that may have smooth edge — which typically, though not always, indicates it's benign Nipple discharge that may be clear, yellow, straw colored or dark brown Breast pain or tenderness in the area of the breast lump An increase in breast lump size and breast tenderness just before your period A decrease in breast lump size and resolution of other symptom after your period Having breast cyst doesn't increase your risk of breast cancer. But having cyst may make it harder to find new breast lump or other change that might need evaluation by your doctor. Your breast may feel lumpy and painful when you're menstruating, so it's important to be familiar with how your breast feel throughout your menstrual cycle so that you'll know if something changes.

Video: How irritable bowel syndrome affect you Video: How irritable bowel syndrome affect you (function () { kWidget.embed({"targetId":"kaltura-video-1_gx18hy28","wid":"_1825021","uiconf_id":44373111,"flashvars":{"IframeCustomPluginCss1":"/-/media/kcms/ux/css/kaltura-player.css","localizationCode":"auto","autoPlay":false},"cache_st":20200805,"entry_id":"1_gx18hy28","readyCallback": function(playerId) {var kdp = document.getElementById(playerId); kdp.addJsListener('doPlay', 'doPlayCallback'); window.inlineReadyCallbackCalled = playerId; }}); })(); Show transcript for video Video: How irritable bowel syndrome affect you IBS is a functional disorder. Even though the digestive tract look normal, it doesn't function a it should. Muscles in the intestine move food from the stomach to the rectum. Normally, they contract and relax in a gentle rhythm that move the food along in a fairly predictable schedule. But with some people, the muscle in the intestine spasm. That mean the contraction are longer and stronger than normal. Those spasm are painful. They also disrupt the movement of food through the intestines. If they slow it down, you become constipated. If they cause it to move through too quickly, you get diarrhea. It's not unusual for people to alternate between the two. Another cause of discomfort for people with IBS result from oversensitive nerve ending in the digestive tract. Small bubble of gas that wouldn't bother most people might be quite painful for you. Your heightened sensitivity can also lead to swelling and bloating.

Symptoms of a heart attack vary. Some people have mild symptoms. Others have severe symptoms. Some people have no symptoms. Common heart attack symptom include: Chest pain that may feel like pressure, tightness, pain, squeezing or aching Pain or discomfort that spread to the shoulder, arm, back, neck, jaw, teeth or sometimes the upper belly Cold sweat Fatigue Heartburn or indigestion Lightheadedness or sudden dizziness Nausea Shortness of breath Women may have atypical symptom such a brief or sharp pain felt in the neck, arm or back. Sometimes, the first symptom sign of a heart attack is sudden cardiac arrest. Some heart attack strike suddenly. But many people have warning sign and symptom hours, day or week in advance. Chest pain or pressure (angina) that keep happening and doesn't go away with rest may be an early warning sign. Angina is caused by a temporary decrease in blood flow to the heart.

Most herniated disk occur in the lower back, but they can also occur in the neck. Signs and symptom depend on where the disk is situated and whether the disk is pressing on a nerve. Herniated disk usually affect one side of the body. Arm or leg pain. If your herniated disk is in your lower back, besides pain in your lower back, you'll typically feel pain in your buttocks, thigh and calf. You might have pain in part of the foot a well. For a herniated disk in your neck, you'll typically feel the most pain in your shoulder and arm. This pain might shoot into your arm or leg when you cough, sneeze or move into certain positions. Pain is often described a sharp or burning. Numbness or tingling. People who have a herniated disk often have radiating numbness or tingling in the body part served by the affected nerves. Weakness. Muscles served by the affected nerve tend to weaken. This can cause you to stumble, or affect your ability to lift or hold items. You can have a herniated disk without symptoms. If the listeria infection spread to your nervous system, sign and symptom can include: Headache Stiff neck Confusion or change in alertness Loss of balance Convulsions Symptoms during pregnancy and in newborn During pregnancy, a listeria infection is likely to cause only mild sign and symptom in the mother. The consequence for the baby, however, can be devastating — the baby can die in the womb or have a life-threatening infection within a few day of being born. Obsessive-compulsive disorder usually includes both obsession and compulsions. But it's also possible to have only obsession symptom or only compulsion symptoms. You may or may not realize that your obsession and compulsion are excessive or unreasonable, but they take up a great deal of time and interfere with your daily routine and social, school or work functioning. Obsession symptom OCD obsession are repeated, persistent and unwanted thoughts, urge or image that are intrusive and cause distress or anxiety. You might try to ignore them or get rid of them by performing a compulsive behavior or ritual. These obsession typically intrude when you're trying to think of or do other things. OCD Obsessions often have theme to them, such as: Fear of contamination or dirt Doubting and having difficulty tolerating uncertainty Needing thing orderly and symmetrical Aggressive or horrific thought about losing control and harming yourself or others Unwanted thoughts, including aggression, or sexual or religious subject Examples of obsession sign and symptom include: Fear of being contaminated by touching object others have touched Doubts that you've locked the door or turned off the stove Intense stress when object aren't orderly or facing a certain way Images of driving your car into a crowd of people Thoughts about shouting obscenity or acting inappropriately in public Unpleasant sexual image Avoidance of situation that can trigger obsessions, such a shaking hand Compulsion symptom OCD compulsion are repetitive behavior that you feel driven to perform. These repetitive behavior or mental act are meant to reduce anxiety related to your obsession or prevent something bad from happening. However, engaging in the compulsion brings no pleasure and may offer only a temporary relief from anxiety. OCD You may make up rule or ritual to follow that help control your anxiety when you're having obsessive thoughts. These compulsion are excessive and often are not realistically related to the problem they're intended to fix. As with obsessions, compulsion typically have themes, such as: Washing and cleaning Checking Counting Orderliness Following a strict routine Demanding reassurance Examples of compulsion sign and symptom include: Hand-washing until your skin becomes raw Checking door repeatedly to make sure they're locked Checking the stove repeatedly to make sure it's off Counting in certain pattern Silently repeating a prayer, word or phrase Arranging your canned good to face the same way Severity varies OCD usually begin in the teen or young adult years, but it can start in childhood. Symptoms usually begin gradually and tend to vary in severity throughout life. The type of obsession and compulsion you experience can also change over time. Symptoms generally worsen when you experience greater stress. OCD, usually considered a lifelong disorder, can have mild to moderate symptom or be so severe and time-consuming that it becomes disabling.

Memory loss is the key symptom of Alzheimer's disease. Early sign include difficulty remembering recent event or conversations. But memory get worse and other symptom develop a the disease progresses. At first, someone with the disease may be aware of having trouble remembering thing and thinking clearly. As symptom get worse, a family member or friend may be more likely to notice the issues. Brain change associated with Alzheimer's disease lead to growing trouble with: Memory Everyone ha memory lapse at times, but the memory loss associated with Alzheimer's disease persists and get worse. Over time, memory loss affect the ability to function at work or at home. People with Alzheimer's disease may: Repeat statement and question over and over. Forget conversations, appointment or events. Misplace items, often putting them in place that don't make sense. Get lost in place they used to know well. Eventually forget the name of family member and everyday objects. Have trouble finding the right word for objects, expressing thought or taking part in conversations. Thinking and reasoning Alzheimer's disease cause difficulty concentrating and thinking, especially about abstract concept such a numbers. Doing more than one task at once is especially difficult. It may be challenging to manage finances, balance checkbook and pay bill on time. Eventually, a person with Alzheimer's disease may be unable to recognize and deal with numbers. Making judgment and decision Alzheimer's disease cause a decline in the ability to make sensible decision and judgment in everyday situations. For example, a person may make poor choice in social setting or wear clothes for the wrong type of weather. It may become harder for someone to respond to everyday problems. For example, the person may not know how to handle food burning on the stove or decision when driving. Planning and performing familiar task Routine activity that require completing step in order become a struggle. This may include planning and cooking a meal or playing a favorite game. Eventually, people with advanced Alzheimer's disease forget how to do basic task such a dressing and bathing. Changes in personality and behavior Brain change that occur in Alzheimer's disease can affect mood and behaviors. Problems may include the following: Depression. Loss of interest in activities. Social withdrawal. Mood swings. Distrust in others. Anger or aggression. Changes in sleeping habits. Wandering. Loss of inhibitions. Delusions, such a believing something ha been stolen. Preserved skill Despite major change to memory and skills, people with Alzheimer's disease are able to hold on to some skill even a symptom get worse. Preserved skill may include reading or listening to books, telling stories, sharing memories, singing, listening to music, dancing, drawing, or doing crafts. These skill may be preserved longer because they're controlled by part of the brain affected later in the course of the disease.
